<1ST_LINE>u i PM-PanamaManeuver     05-04 0710</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama Maneuver,0733</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega May Have Outfoxed United States</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In its confrontation with Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega, the United States seems to have been maneuvered
into an awkward position by the military strongman.
   The U.S. government had pledged to remove the commander of the
Defense Forces, the de facto ruler of this country, from office and
from Panama.
   Now the Reagan administration appears to be offering Noriega a
deal he had hinted at more than a month ago: that he leave power,
but not the country. He also wants his U.S. indictments on drug
trafficking charges invalidated.
   The apparent U.S. policy shift has managed to alienate
opposition leaders. They now privately use the word
``incompetence'' when referring to the way the United States has
handled the general.
   Noriega denied on Saturday that he had reached any agreement
with the United States. But Treasury Secretary James A. Baker said
on Sunday that talks with Noriega continued during the weekend and
that ``progress is being made.''
   Initially, the United States encouraged the opposition as it
demanded both Noriega's ouster and exile. Washington imposed
economic sanctions and froze Panamanian government assets in the
United States, causing a severe economic crisis in this country,
where the dollar is the legal currency.
   The United States recognized as Panama's legitimate president
Eric Arturo Delvalle, a man Noriega himself had picked as president
and whose only merit, opposition leaders say, was that he later
tried to fire the general.
   But Noriega, a military leader with the populist tactics of a
Latin American politician, vowed he would not leave under pressure.
He clung to power in spite of the crisis, whipping up Panamanian
nationalism and the sympathy that Latin American nations feel for
anyone who confronts the United States.
   ``The gringos overestimated the opposition and underestimated
Noriega,'' said Maj. Edgardo Lopez, a spokesman for the general.
   As late as April 16, State Department officials were telling
opposition members the U.S. position had not changed, and that
Noriega had to leave soon.
   ``If they (United States) are now offering a deal that would
enable Noriega to stay in Panama, then it is a serious mistake,''
said Ricardo Arias Calderon of the Christian Democratic Party.
   ``All Panamanians know that allowing Noriega to stay in Panama
is not a solution,'' said Guillermo Endara, spokesman for the
Authentic Panamanian Party, the largest opposition party.
   Concerned about a possible U.S.-Noriega deal that might bypass
them, the opposition parties met on Monday for the first time ``to
discuss the serious crisis we are suffering.''
   The opposition includes the National Civic Crusade, an umbrella
organization of private, professional and labor groups that since
June has mounted demonstrations against Noriega's rule.
   Opposition leaders feel the U.S. government created Noriega by
sustaining his 15,000-member Defense Forces and allowing him to
impose and depose presidents during the past five years.
   ``The change in attitude on the part of the United States to
support democratization in Panama now is not the result of
solidarity with our people,'' said Arias. ``It merely recognizes
that its interests in Panama are more compatible with the struggle
for democracy than with the support of a dictatorial regime.''
   Noriega has insisted that the American decision to topple him
was political because he refused to cooperate with U.S. attempts to
involve Panama in incidents to embarrass the leftist Sandinista
regime in Nicaragua. The Reagan administration supports the
Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras.
   Noriega said on Saturday that he would not leave unless the
``popular forces,'' meaning the Defense Forces and his political
base, ``negotiate their security.''
   ``He will leave on his terms now,'' said an opposition party
leader, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Aides said the general also wants the economic sanctions lifted.
   ``Noriega is more concerned about lifting the economic sanctions
than any discussion about his departure,'' Lopez said.
   ``He is not going to resign under U.S. pressure and he is not
going into exile,'' he said. ``We have learned to be wary of the
United States, a country that historically had been our friend.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Eloy O. Aguilar, as bureau chief for Mexico and
Central America, has been covering the region since 1979.
</TEXT>
