<1ST_LINE>u p AM-DCPrimary 1stLd-Writethru a0875 05-04 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DC Primary, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0875,350</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with 70 percent in; new delegate figures, lists other
Jackson victories.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson scored a runaway victory over
Michael Dukakis in the District of Columbia primary Tuesday,
duplicating his 1984 primary win. It was Jackson's first primary
election victory since he won Puerto Rico in March.
   With about 70 percent of the vote counted, Jackson had 41,694 or
80.2 percent, while Michael Dukakis had 9,215 or 17 percent.
Jackson captured 13 of the district's 16 Democratic convention
delegates with Dukakis winning 3.
   The results maintained Jackson's strong nationwide showing among
black voters; about two-thirds of the district population is black.
   On the Republican side, Vice President George Bush had 3,111 or
88.5 percent; Sen. Bob Dole, 279 or 6.5 percent and Pat Robertson
170 or 3.9 percent.
   Elections director Emmett Fremaux said a light turnout resulted
from a lack of campaigning and the fact that Dukakis and Bush have
all but wrapped up the presidential nominations for their parties.
   In other balloting, Del. Walter Fauntroy, D-D.C., running
unopposed in his party's primary. Seeking his 10th term to
Congress, Fauntroy will face Republican William Reed in November.
Reed also ran unopposed.
   Jackson spent the day in the district, doing radio interviews
and speaking at a local high school.
   Mayor Marion Barry Jr., an active Jackson backer, voted early
and said it would be tough for Jackson to win the Democratic
nomination, but that Jackson would stay in the race all the way to
the Atlanta convention.
   Jackson delivered an anti-drug message to students at Roosevelt
High School and in a WOL radio interview he supported patrols by
Nation of Islam members designed to curb drug traffic at two
apartment complexes.
   In 1984, Jackson won all but three of the delegates on the
primary ballot. The only other primary he won was Louisiana. This
year Jackson has won primary elections in Georgia, Alabama,
Virginia, Louisiana, Mississippi and Puerto Rico. He won caucuses
in Alaska, Delaware, Michigan and South Carolina.
</TEXT>
