<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0308EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MinimumWage     05-04 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Minimum Wage,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Committee Member Says Damaging Data Were Suppressed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ranking Republican on the House labor
committee says the Democratic leadership has tried to quash a
non-partisan report indicating that an increase in the minimum wage
to $5.05 could cost up to 500,000 jobs.
   Rep. Thomas E. Petri, R-Wis., ranking GOP member on the House
labor standards subcommittee that handled the minimum wage
legislation, said Tuesday that the Democratic leadership is not
interested in objective analysis.
   ``They're just interested in ramming their bill through with
brute force _ no matter who gets hurt,'' Petri said in a floor
statement.
   The Congressional Budget Office studied the Democratic-sponsored
legislation, which would raise the minimum wage from $3.35 an hour
to $5.05 an hour over the next four years.
   Petri said that although the CBO found the legislation could
wipe out 500,000 jobs and boost inflation, ``the folks who run the
Labor Committee didn't want that kind of information, and ordered
it removed from the CBO report before the minority could see it.''
   Stanley L. Greigg, a CBO spokesman, said it followed its normal
procedure of sending a copy of the report to both Rep. Augustus F.
Hawkins, D-Calif., labor committee chairman, and Rep. James M.
Jeffords, R-Vt., ranking GOP member.
   ``We followed the same procedure we always do,'' said Greigg.
``A copy went to both of them simultaneously. We were baffled by
the suggestion (of Jeffords) that he made three requests for a copy
of the report.''
   The House is expected to take up the minimum wage bill sometime
this month.
   The CBO, the research arm of Congress, has disputed news reports
that the agency has become politicized in issuing a report on the
cost estimates of the legislation.
   In a letter to the House Education and Labor Committee, CBO
acting chairman James L. Blum said the budget office was ``fully
responsive to the requests made of us by the committee staff and
that nothing has transpired to change the non-partisan,
professional conduct of our office.''
   At the specific request of the staff, Blum said, the CBO
provided the committee with an assessment of the possible impact of
the measure on the economy.
   ``Our cost estimates normally provide information only on the
possible budget impacts for federal, state and local governments,''
Blum said.
   Susan McGuire, committee staff director, sent a letter last
Thursday to all panel members in which she said the staff requested
CBO to provide a second submission ``because the first CBO cost
estimate included an analysis not required by the Budget Act or
House Rules for inclusion in the committee's report.''
   ``This analysis has been available to any member requesting it,
and the staff's action in requesting CBO to conform ... in no way
constituted suppression of the analysis or improper pressure on the
Congressional Budget Office.''
</TEXT>
