<1ST_LINE>u p AM-RothCandidacy     05-04 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Roth Candidacy,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sen. Roth Announces For Re-election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GEORGETOWN, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three-term Republican Sen. William V.
Roth Jr. declared Tuesday he will seek re-election, creating an
uphill battle for the winner of September's Democratic primary
between Lt. Gov. S.B. Woo and civic activist Samuel Beard.
   Roth said he already has raised about $800,000 toward the $1.2
million he estimates he'll need for the campaign, which kicked off
in Georgetown, with similar announcements later in Dover and
Wilmington.
   Roth, 66, said his campaign will focus on issues important to
Delaware families, including the economy, job, affordable child
care, a secure national defense and making sure Social Security is
available for future generations.
   ``It's important that we continue to prepare for tomorrow. And
tomorrow depends on our young people,'' Roth said.
   Roth said he has supported the war on drug abuse and stiffer
penalties for drug dealers, in addition to fighting against child
pornography.
   Roth probably became best-known nationally as co-author, with
Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y., of the Kemp-Roth multiyear tax-reduction
legislation. The measure was eventually endorsed by President
Reagan and enacted in large part by Congress as a prime feature of
Reagan's first-term economic program.
   Roth was a two-term congressman when in 1970, he replaced
retiring incumbent Republican Sen. John J. Williams. Roth was
re-elected in 1976 and 1982.
   Roth's wife, Jane, a Harvard law graduate, was appointed a
federal court judge in Wilmington in 1985 by Reagan. The Roths have
two children, William V. Roth III and Katharine K. Roth.
</TEXT>
