<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--CatDisease     05-04 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Cat Disease,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Residents of Massachusetts County Warned To Keep Cats Indoors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Veterinarians urged cat owners in
Berkshire County to keep their pets indoors after 25 cats became
sickened, apparently by a deadly illness that may be linked to a
wild bird disease.
   The Berkshire Veterinary Hospital in this western Massachusetts
city has been treating cats for the past three weeks for an
infection that evidently hit some animals after they ate wild
songbirds, Barry Kellogg of the hospital said Tuesday. At least
three cats have died, he said.
   Kellogg said humans were not in danger of contracting the
disease and that it did not appear to be communicated from cat to
cat.
   Outbreaks of the disease have been reported in western New York,
Vermont and parts of New Hampshire, said Dr. Fred Scott, director
of the Feline Health Center at the New York State College of
Veterinary Medicine in Ithaca, N.Y.
   He said the illness appeared to be related to a malady killing
wild songbirds in the same areas.
</TEXT>
