<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0325EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ArcticOil     05-04 0636</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arctic Oil,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Environmentalists in House Fight To Stop Refuge Drilling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmentalists are looking to the House
Interior Committee in their efforts to reverse a congressional tide
that is running toward oil development in the Arctic National
Wildlife Refuge.
   The focus of the biggest energy-vs.-environment battle of the
100th Congress shifted to that panel Tuesday after the House
Merchant Marine and Fisheries Committee approved a bill to open the
Alaska preserve to oil rigs.
   Tim Mahoney of the Alaska Coalition of drilling foes said he is
optimistic about stopping the bill in the Interior Committee,
chaired by Rep. Morris Udall, D-Ariz., who opposes developing the
nation's largest refuge.
   ``It's been a friendlier committee to us traditionally,''
Mahoney said. ``The committee is always split 50-50 on tough
developmental issues. ...Our strategy is pretty simple. We believe
in the just-say-no strategy.''
   Mahoney and other anti-drilling lobbyists are trying to slow
down the bill, which is similar to a measure approved narrowly
earlier this year by the Senate Energy and Natural Resources
Committee.
   He said he thinks the chance of a drilling bill getting through
Congress this year are ``very low. There are a lot of people who
prefer not to vote on controversial issues in an election year.''
   Drilling opponents hope to stall final action until 1989 on the
theory that a new administration will be less eager than the Reagan
administration to develop the 1.5 million acre coastal plain of the
19-million-acre refuge.
   Randy Snodgrass of the Wilderness Society said that Democratic
front-runner Michael Dukakis has pledged to make the coastal plain
a no-development wilderness area.
   Drilling advocates, including Interior Secretary Donald Hodel,
say the refuge's potentially rich oil deposits must be tapped as
soon as possible in order to reduce the nation's growing dependence
on imported petroleum.
   The Merchant Marine Committee approved its drilling bill 28-13
after rejecting bipartisan pleas by some members that Congress
postpone a decision on the issue until a new president can study
the matter and formulate a new national energy policy.
   ``This is the first positive energy step we've made since
1973,'' said Rep. Don Young, R-Alaska, a principal proponent of
tapping what the Reagan administration and the oil industry say may
be a major supply of petroleum.
   Young was referring to Congress' approval of the pipeline that
carries Alaskan oil from Prudhoe Bay, the huge field about 70 miles
west of the refuge boundary and the source of about 20 percent of
U.S. oil production.
   An opponent, Rep. Gerry Studds, D-Mass., said the drilling
legislation backed by Young and crafted by chairman Walter Jones,
D-N.C., was ``ill-conceived and ill-timed.''
   ``The resources of the Arctic will wait, and we can await the
arrival of a new president and a new energy secretary,'' said
Studds, predicting a bitter battle if drilling legislation reaches
the House floor.
   ``We will have a donneybrook of such dimensions that it will be
recalled for some time,'' Studds predicted.
   The Jones bill would allow drilling to begin within 21 months of
enactment. It would bar rigs from a caribou calving area and
earmark federal revenue from refuge oil for national wildlife and
conservation programs.
   The closest drilling opponents got to victory was a 23-18 vote
against a plan to allow pre-leasing activities, which would take
two or more years, to be carried out while the National Academy of
Sciences studied the nation's future energy needs and how they
could be filled by conservation and renewable sources of energy.
   The foes also tried to add language to force the administration
to reverse its decision to lower the auto fleet economy standard
from 27.5 mpg to 26 mpg. Rep. Mike Lowry, D-Wash., said that over
the long term oil saved this way could equal what the refuge may
contain.
</TEXT>
