<DATELINE>WELLESLEY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boston Celtics Coach K.C. Jones says
he's decided to retire at the end of the season because he's not
ambitious and wanted to spend more time with his family.
   Jones, who led the Celtics to two National Basketball
Association championships during his previous four seasons as
coach, made the surprise announcement Tuesday, a day before Boston
plays the New York Knicks in the third game of their best-of-five,
first-round playoff series.
   Boston leads 2-0 and can wrap it up with a victory tonight.
   ``It's something I wanted to do. I'd been giving it
consideration since last summer,'' the 56-year-old Jones said of
his retirement.
   Jones said he will be succeeded by assistant coach Jimmy Rodgers.
   The decision had to do with ``not being ambitious and wanting to
... win another nine titles,'' Jones said, adding that wants to
spend more time with his family and play a little more golf and
tennis.
   ``It's good for me, it's good for the family, it's good for
Jimmy,'' said Jones, who said he will become a Celtics vice
president and director of player personnel.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT PIERCE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of Len Bias, the basketball
star who died of a cocaine overdose, told high school students it
takes courage for young people to take a stand against drugs, but
it's worth it.
   In moving appearances at three area high schools Monday, Lonise
Bias told students they must learn not to cave in to peer pressure
when it comes to drugs.
   ``Anyone can go along with the crowd. Who could stand to go
alone?'' she said. ``It takes courage and character. ... You must
stand up for what's right.''
   Ms. Bias told students they needed to put their problems in
proper perspective, and called suicide ``a permanent solution to a
temporary problem.''
   Her son, a University of Maryland basketball star, died in 1986
shortly after being named the Boston Celtics' first-round draft
pick.
</TEXT>
