<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0834EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Drifter'sOdyssey     05-04 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drifter's Odyssey,0645</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supertanker Rescues Man Drifting Out To Sea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE MAY COURT HOUSE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who hoped to float from
Florida to the Bahamas drifted more than 600 miles during his 20
days in a raft, buoyed by his thoughts of hot cereal and strawberry
ice cream while waiting for rescuers.
   Kenneth Maffei, who was rescued Monday, said he survived on rain
for drinking water and tiny shrimp, crab and fish from seaweed he
plucked from the sea.
   ``I have a great desire to learn about cultures on the islands,
and I like to travel in unusual ways,'' said Maffei, who was
rescued by a supertanker off Cape Hatteras, N.C., suffering from
second-degree burns and having lost more than 30 pounds.
   ``I'll be staying on land for a while,'' Maffei said Tuesday
from his hospital bed. ``I won't be heading for any islands.''
   Maffei, 28, of Santa Cruz, Calif., climbed into a tiny
inflatable raft at sunset on April 12 and set out from Fort
Lauderdale. The closest island was Great Isaac Island, about 60
miles away.
   ``I thought I could zig-zag back and forth to get there,'' he
said. ``I felt very strongly that it could be done.''
   Maffei said he studied maps and wind and current patterns at a
library before leaving.
   His equipment included oars and oarlocks and another tiny Army
surplus raft that carried food, water and clothes.
   But Maffei, an odd-job laborer, had taken only a few informal
sailing lessons in California and the tiny raft was too small for
his 6-foot-3, 180-pound frame. He had no motor, no radio
communications, no signal flares, no water desalination unit and no
compass.
   But he did have a strong personal will.
   ``Whenever I thought that this could be it, I would say, `Stop,
you can't think that way,''' Maffei said.
   ``I felt I would make it,'' he said, licking his blistered lips
so he could continue talking.
   Maffei said he caught high winds, heavy rains and swells that
dwarfed and repeatedly overturned his craft. His supply raft
deflated on the second day of his voyage and many of his supplies
sank. He was burned by the sun and saltwater and suffered abrasions
from the raft.
   The rains provided him with drinking water.
   ``I held out my raincoat to catch the water, and I'd scoop it
up,'' he said.
   For food, he caught tiny shrimp and crab and fish from seaweed.
Once he had a hole in the raft, which he quickly patched.
   Maffei said he lost track of time and overcame his fears with
two all-consuming visions.
   ``Strawberry ice cream with Fig Newtons, and Cream of Wheat with
cream,'' he said.
   On Sunday, 650 miles from Fort Lauderdale and 20 days out, he
saw one of the many tankers that had passed him by, and waved the
T-shirt he kept handy. Just like the other tankers, this one kept
going.
   ``About 20 minutes later, I looked back, and they had turned,''
he said. ``I said to myself, `There are no traffic signals out
here, tankers don't just turn. They're coming back.'''
   Korean crew members aboard the 800-foot Bahamian oil tanker Rich
Duchess climbed down a ladder to fetch Maffei, who was too weak to
stand.
   Maffei was in stable condition at Burdette Tomlin Memorial
Hospital after the Coast Guard on Monday used a helicopter to bring
him ashore.
   ``If we had known about this ahead of time, it would have been
classified as an unsafe voyage and would have been stopped,'' Coast
Guard Petty Officer James McHugh said Tuesday from the Cape May
Station.
   ``Sometimes, going through life, you take risks,'' Maffei said.
``You've got to take chances, otherwise you can't reach your
dreams.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
