<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Soviet     05-04 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Soviet,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Soviet Union Has Made Some Progress In Religious
Rights</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top prospects uncertain; no arrangements yet for advance
text; Chicago speech scheduled for 1:55 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan says he sees ``encouraging
signs'' that religious oppression has abated somewhat in the Soviet
Union.
   In a speech Tuesday devoid of the harsh criticism of recent
weeks, the president said Mikhail S. Gorbachev has admitted the
Soviet Union made mistakes dealing with religious believers in
decades past and they would be ``rectified.''
   ``What we hope for ultimately is a willingness to see continued
change, in the spirit of glasnost, when it comes to matters of
religion,'' Reagan told a meeting on religious rights at the White
House.
   Glasnost is the Russian term for the Soviet leader's policy of
bringing openess to Soviet society.
   Reagan was scheduled to address the issue of human rights again
today in the Soviet Union during a speech in Chicago to the
National Strategy Forum, a non-partisan organization that sponsors
educational programs on national security and foreign policy issues.
   The address is another in a series of scene-setters for the
upcoming May 29-June 2 summit in Moscow.
   In Tuesday's speech, Reagan said some dissidents have been
allowed to emigrate from the Soviet Union, some churches have been
allowed to open and organize and the printing of 100,000 Bibles
will be permitted.
   ``These are encouraging signs and we welcome them,'' Reagan said.
   But, Reagan added, many churches have been denied recognition,
religious instruction outside the home is still illegal and the new
Bibles will scarcely serve a nation of 280 million.
   ``So while every positive step taken by the Soviets is welcomed
_ we realize that this is just a beginning,'' Reagan said. ``I
promise you that the witness of faith you brought here today will
not be confined to these four walls or forgotten when this meeting
is ended.
   ``I will carry it in my heart when I travel to the Soviet Union
at the end of this month and I will say that the most fitting way
to mark the millenium of Christianity in Kiev ... would be granting
the rights of all the peoples and all the creeds of the Soviet
Union to worship their god in their own way.''
   While noting the 1,000th anniversary of Christianity in the
Soviet Union, Reagan also said: ``The rights of Soviet Jews have
taken up much of our official time and this is very close to my
heart. Our hope is for doors to open completely to emigration and
to full freedom for all faiths.''
   After the conference, Reagan told a Ukrainian Catholic leader he
would visit an Orthodox monastery in Moscow despite the church
leader's request Reagan cancel the trip in protest of religious
persecution.
   ``He said he already made plans and he has to go,'' Myroslav
Cardinal Lubachivsky told reporters.
   The monastery on the outskirts of Moscow, the central building
of which is more than 700 years old, is being restored with
government financial help.
   The cardinal said he made the request because Ukrainian
Catholics continue to suffer persecution.
   ``Today, we hear so much about glasnost and perestroika,'' he
said. ``But, Mr. Gorbachev's reforms have yet to touch the
Ukrainian Catholic Church. Our priests are punished or fined for
celebrating the liturgy in private homes, and the faithful live in
constant fear of imprisonment. Such violations of basic human
rights simply must not exist.''
</TEXT>
