<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Marcos-Mother 2ndLd-Writethru a0451 05-04 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marcos-Mother, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0451, a0457, a0458,</2ND_LINE>
<TEXT>
   a0460,0585
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Marcos' Mother Dies As Government Weighs Her Request</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines urgent series. No pickup.
^By YASMIN ARQUIZA</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of ousted President
Ferdinand Marcos died Wednesday after appealing to President
Corazon Aquino to allow her son to return from exile in Hawaii as
her dying wish.
   Dr. Sergio Brillantes, director of Veterans Memorial Medical
Center, said 95-year-old Josefa Edralin-Marcos suffered cardiac
arrest at noon (midnight Tuesday) and was pronounced dead 20
minutes later.
   Mrs. Edralin-Marcos had been hospitalized since Sunday suffering
from pneumonia, diabetes and kidney failure. She lapsed into a coma
late Tuesday, Brillantes said.
   She died as Mrs. Aquino convened her Cabinet's crisis committee
to consider a request by Mrs. Edralin-Marcos to allow her son to
return to see her one last time. The request was made in a letter
delivered Tuesday to the presidential palace.
   Mrs. Edralin-Marcos stayed behind in February 1986 when a
military-civilian uprising drove her son into exile after 20 years
in power and lifted Mrs. Aquino to the presidency. Mrs. Aquino
since has refused to allow Marcos to come back.
   The former president's supporters have been linked to several
attempts to topple the Aquino government. On Tuesday, the military
announced that troops had seized 30 rifles and 300 sticks of
dynamite during a raid Monday on a suburban machine shop owned by a
Marcos supporter.
   Military Chief of Staff Gen. Renato de Villa had said it was up
to civilian authorities to decide whether to allow Marcos to
return. But he indicated the military command was wary of such a
request.
   ``We will have to assess ... whether conditions in the past are
still the same,'' he told reporters on Tuesday. ``We still have
certainly a serious threat situation in the country coming from
(communist rebels), and we don't want additional problems.''
   Before Mrs. Edralin-Marcos' death, Justice Secretary Sedfrey
Ordonez told reporters today the decision on allowing Marcos to
return would have to be political and not based solely on legal
considerations.
   Brillantes said Mrs. Edralin-Marcos underwent dialysis Tuesday
for her failing kidneys and was running a high fever. He said she
was comatose, but she showed stable blood pressure and was
``breathing easier.''
   In her letter, Mrs. Edralin-Marcos said she was near the end of
her life. ``My dying wish, the one thing that will put a smile upon
my lips when I leave this world, is to see my Ferdinand by my
bedside as I say goodbye to all of you,'' said the letter, a copy
of which was released by the presidential staff. ``Pray grant me
this wish and this privilege as one mother to another.''
   The letter, apparently drafted by family members, included the
thumb print of Marcos' mother.
   In a separate letter, the former president's brother and sister,
Dr. Pacifico Marcos and Mrs. Fortuna Marcos-Barba, asked Mrs.
Aquino to ``grant our mother's final wish.'' They were at her
bedside when she died.
   Marcos supporters held a candlelight vigil and prayed for Mrs.
Edralin-Marcos' recovery. Dozens of Marcos supporters jammed an
adjacent hospital room to watch her through a small window.
   Mrs. Edralin-Marcos came from a wealthy northern Luzon family of
Filipino and Chinese extraction. Marcos' father, Mariano, was a
politician and lawyer who died in 1944 during the Japanese
occupation.
   Marcos was not allowed to return for the funeral of his sister,
Elizabeth Marcos-Keon, who died in December 1986.
</TEXT>
