<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Trade     05-04 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Move to Junk Trade Bill's Oil Export Curbs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats seeking to head off a presidential
veto of the trade bill or gain enough votes for an override are
wooing Alaska's two senators with a promise to consider more
lenient export rules for that state's oil.
   The move came Tuesday with House introduction of a resolution
authorizing ``technical corrections'' in the trade bill, which
cleared the Senate 63-36 last week. The margin was three votes shy
of what would be needed to override a veto.
   The ``corrections'' would be made in two provisions opposed by
Alaskan oil interests.
   One of the provisions would approve export of 50,000 barrels a
day of Alaskan crude oil to Canada, but would require the oil to be
transported first to a West Coast port in American vessels. The
feature is a favorite of politically influential maritime unions
and lawmakers from states whose ports could benefit.
   The other provision would limit exports from new refineries in
Alaska to 70,000 barrels and day and half of total production.
   The House is expected later this week to take up the resolution
authorizing changes, with senators likely to act next week when
they return from a recess.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, described the resolution as a
last-ditch effort to dissuade President Reagan from his threatened
veto.
   ``We're trying to meet him halfway if we can,'' Wright said.
   But Republicans immediately scoffed that the real reason was to
pick up the two votes from Alaska's senators for an override
attempt.
   Reagan's opposition to the trade bill stems in large part to a
provision to require all but the smallest companies to provide
their employees with 60-day notice of plant closings and
large-scale layoffs. Democrats have been threatening to make that
an issue in fall campaigns.
   More recently the president has reportedly objected to the
Alaska oil provisions. Wright said that was one reason the
Democrats are attempting to remove them and replace them with
funding for a study that would not have any direct impact on
exports.
   ``We're trying in every way to appeal to his better nature,''
Wright said.
   But just before Wright's plan went through the Rules Committee,
Rep. James Quillen, R-Tenn., described it as ``a ploy to change
some votes in the Senate in order to override a possible
presidential veto.''
   House Minority Leader Robert H. Michel, R-Ill., took the floor
and accused Wright of trying to ``win at all costs.''
   ``I am told there is a proposed new rule in the works that will
allow the majority to delete the Alaskan oil provisions in a
last-ditch attempt to manipulate a veto override in the Senate,''
Michel said. ``Is there nothing left of the integrity of our rules
and procedures?''
   Despite the maneuvering, one of the Alaska senators, Ted
Stevens, has said he will not necessarily back the trade bill even
if the export curbs are dropped.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880504-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0836EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AirTax Bjt   05-04 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Air Tax, Bjt,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winooski Tax Heats Up Air War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANICA KIRKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINOOSKI, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This innovative Yankee town, which once
considered building a dome over itself to keep out the harsh
Vermont winter, is trying to tax neighboring Burlington for its
noisy use of Winooski's airspace.
   The western Vermont town of about 6,300 people sits at the end
of Burlington International Airport's runway, and its downtown is
just off the airport's main approach.
   Residents say the noise from helicopters, Vermont National Guard
fighters and jets flying in and out of Vermont's largest city can
be unbearable.
   ``They go right over our building,'' Alice Levesque said
recently. ``It's really an awful thing. They wouldn't do that to a
herd of cows.''
   Winooski officials, saying the planes were invading their
airspace, decided to tax Burlington. Burlington balked.
   Winooski, contending that Burlington hadn't paid the taxes, then
filed suit in Chittenden County Superior Court to collect on a bill
of $90,000, plus interest.
   ``By flying that low, they have essentially confiscated the land
that is below that air,'' said Dominique Casavant, a physics
professor and former Winooski selectman. The airport noise
depresses land values, Casavant said.
   ``Yes, it is unusual ... (but) this is not the first time
Winooski has set precedent,'' Casavant said.
   In 1979, a dome to cover the town was proposed to save energy
and ward off winter. The proposal was the subject of an
international symposium and federal money was requested to study
it, but the project never got out of the planning stages.
   Officials argue that they aren't taxing the planes, but the
space they use when they land and take off.
   ``Property taxes are not novel,'' said Winooski City Manager
Brendan Keleher. ``Property taxes are our business.''
   Burlington has dismissed the airspace tax, although Bernard
Sanders, the city's outspoken Socialist mayor, applauded Winooski
for its imagination.
   ``As somebody who is interested in alternatives to the property
tax, I have to congratulate our friends in the city of Winooksi,''
Sanders said. ``It's an interesting concept, but not terribly
practical. If Winooski could do it, so could Toledo. We would be
evolved to a toll booth in the sky.''
   Landowners have sued over airspace rights in the past, but
experts said they cannot recall a case where one city sued another
to collect taxes for airspace.
   Walter Hellerstein, a University of Georgia law professor and
tax expert, said he had not seen the suit but called the idea
behind it ``bizarre.''
   ``It seems to me, it would be as if the state of Iowa were
trying to tax the city of San Francisco,'' Hellerstein said,
explaining that a plane might fly over the Midwestern state on its
way to the West Coast. ``I've never heard of anything like this.''
   But Peter Teachout, a professor at Vermont Law School in South
Royalton, said the lawsuit is not so far-fetched, even if it
presents some practical problems.
   Teachout said the city faces the difficulty of placing a
monetary value on the airspace. Tax values are normally established
by properties' market values.
   ``How do you figure out what that airspace is worth?'' he asked.
``Nobody is going to pay for it.''
   The lawsuit also has to draw a boundary on the airspace in
question and has to show that Winooski's situation is different
from that of most other communities, where planes overhead fly at
greater altitudes, Teachout said.
   ``That would be the toughest problem _ convincing a court it
isn't going to be opening up the floodgates (to future suits).''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
