<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0401EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HousingNeeds     05-04 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Housing Needs,420</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release 10 a.m. EDT, time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>36 Million New Housing Units to be Needed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country will need to build or renovate 36
million new housing units over the next 15 years to address the
problems faced by Americans living in substandard and overcrowded
conditions, a study reported today.
   The study, prepared by the Urban Institute, said that over 6
percent of housing units in urban areas and 17 percent of units in
rural areas don't meet minimum standards set by the Department of
Housing and Urban Development.
   The study was financed by the National Association of Realtors.
The report said 7.7 million households are living in substandard
units and another 3.2 million are in overcrowded conditions.
   Under the HUD definition, a home is classified as substandard if
it does not have electricity, lacks adequate plumbing or lacks
sewage disposal.
   ``We are reminded daily of the homeless on our streets and
shelters. Less visible, but no better off, are those who live in
inadequate housing or who pay the majority of their incomes just to
stay off these streets,'' Nestor Weigand, president of the Realtors
association, said in presenting the study.
   The study estimated that it would cost $41 billion over the next
15 years to build or upgrade the 36 million units it estimated
would be needed to eliminate substandard housing in the United
States.
   The study also estimated it would take an additional $56 billion
in subsidy payments to insure that households were not paying more
than 30 percent of their income for housing.
   The study said this would break down to an increase of $6.5
billion annually over and above current government subsidy efforts.
   The study did not address the likelihood of getting such
additional funds through Congress at a time of budget constraints
imposed by the high federal deficits. The Reagan administration has
generally opposed any new housing initiatives and scaled back many
of the programs in existence when it came into office in 1981.
   The Realtors association study is the latest of several recent
reports which have looked into the country's housing needs. In
March, the National Housing Task Force issued a report recommending
a 12-year program with a goal of providing livable housing for all
Americans.
   The private task force recommended the program begin with an
initial appropriation of $3 billion to be used as seed money to
stimulate state and local efforts to develop and renovate
low-income housing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880504-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0401EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DefenseSpending     05-04 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Spending,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Adds More Arms Control Resolutions To Spending Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House says the United States ought to keep
at least 20 missile-firing submarines and NATO's non-nuclear forces
should be improved.
   Both proposals were approved Tuesday on voice votes as
non-binding amendments to the Pentagon budget bill now on the floor
of the Democratic-controlled chamber.
   The amendments affect a pair of U.S.-Soviet arms control efforts
_ the Strategic Arms Reduction Talks aimed at cutting each side's
long-range arsenals by 50 percent, and the Intermediate-range
Nuclear Forces pact eliminating medium-range nuclear missiles.
   Both superpowers have long-range arsenals of submarine-launched
missiles, bombers, and land-based missiles, with the submarines
considered to the least vulnerable to attack. The START treaty
would require major changes and restructuring of those stockpiles.
   More than half the U.S. strategic nuclear firepower is now
contained on 36 missile-firing submarines, which include 28 older
Poseidon-class subs and eight Ohio-class subs. Seven more Tridents
are under constructions and a 16th is part of the bill on the House
floor.
   While the future composition of the U.S. arsenal is
undetermined, it should include at least 20 subs, said the
amendment by Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y.
   Solarz said the proposal is designed to ``insure that our
strategic nuclear submarine force is not jeopardized by the START
talks ... we must insure that we have the maximum number of these
submarines possible within the overall framework of the triad.''
   Also approved on a voice vote was an amendment by Rep. Jack
Buechner, R-Mo., urging President Reagan to upgrade conventional
forces in the 16-member North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   Reagan is already urging NATO to improve its non-nuclear forces,
which will assume greater importance in deterring a Warsaw Pact
attack when the American-built medium-range nuclear missiles are
removed.
   As it plowed through the bill, the House also approved, by close
margins, a pair of measures that give federal contractors more
leeway in setting pay scales.
   The first decision, by a 213-195 vote, approved an overhaul of
the Davis-Bacon Act. That is a 1931 law which directs that
employees covered by contracts on federal jobs worth more than
$2,000 be paid prevailing local wage rates, a figure set by the
Labor Department. The rates are usually those paid union employees.
   The proposal passed Tuesday raises the threshold figure from
$2,000 to $50,000.
   Moments later, the House voted 210-204 to reject an amendment
that would have raised the Davis-Bacon threshold even higher, to
$250,000.
   The law was passed during the Great Depression to assuage fears
that construction companies would hire cheap labor. Critics say the
measure has been overtaken by events and should be changed, but
defenders, including organized labor, call it a linchpin of
workers' protection.
   The votes generally split along party lines, with Democrats
backing the $50,000 threshold and Republicans supporting the
$250,000 threshold.
   In other votes Tuesday, the House:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Approved, on a voice vote, an amendment banning deployment of
any Coast Guard vessels to the Persian Gulf. The Pentagon has
already announced that the plan was scuttled in the face of stiff
congressional opposition and backers of the amendment had planned
to drop it as unnecessary. But a procedural snarl made it easier to
simply approve the amendment than to bypass it.
   _Gave voice vote approval to a ban on spending for the Bigeye
bomb, the problem-plagued chemical weapon. The bill provides no new
money for the bomb, which has run into a series of technical
problems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
