<1ST_LINE>r p PM-OhioPrimary     05-04 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ohio Primary,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Metzenbaum, Voinovich Look to General Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Howard Metzenbaum and Cleveland's
Republican Mayor, George Voinovich, predict that their showdown in
November in the U.S. Senate race will be one of the fiercest and
most expensive in state history.
   ``You mark my words, the most focused-on race in the United
States is going to be Metzenbaum-Voinovich, Voinovich said Tuesday
after Metzenbaum's primary victory.
   ``This will be a barn-burner. If Dukakis and Bush don't get them
out, Voinovich and Metzenbaum will,'' the mayor said.
   Metzenbaum agreed there was a tough battle ahead.
   ``There isn't a (political) hit list in America that doesn't
have me at the top of it. I must be doing something right in the
Senate if so many people want to beat me,'' he told reporters in
Cleveland.
   Metzenbaum, seeking a third term at age 70, easily survived a
primary challenge from Ralph Applegate, 56, who runs a small
lawn-care business in Columbus and did no active campaigning. With
96 percent of the vote counted, Metzenbaum had 1,043,624 votes, or
84 percent, to Applegate's 206,184, or 16 percent.
   Voinovich, 51, was unopposed for the GOP nomination.
   In the presidential primaries, Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis easily outpolled Jesse Jackson and claimed most of the 159
Democratic delegates at stake. On the Republican side, George Bush
had no active opposition for 88 delegates.
   With 98 percent of the vote counted, Dukakis had 853,902 votes,
or 63 percent, compared with 373,497 votes, or 28 percent, for
Jackson. Six other counties split the rest of the vote.
   In the race for the state's 159 delegates, Dukakis was leading
for 115, while Jackson was ahead for 41.
   In the 5th Congressional District, Ohio Senate President Paul
Gillmor appeared to have won a razor-thin victory over the son of
the retiring incumbent, U.S. Rep. Delbert Latta, and a third
candidate. Final, unofficial returns showed Gillmor with 28,666
votes to 28,608 for Robert Latta. Rex Damschroder ran a distant
third.
   In the 20th District, Democratic Rep. Mary Rose Oakar easily
defeated former Cleveland Mayor Dennis Kucinich. With 99 percent of
the vote counted, Ms. Oakar had 64,143 votes, or 77 percent, to
19,454, or 23 percent, for Kucinich.
   Ms. Oakar said she was overwhelmed by the margin of victory.
Kucinich was in a joking mood.
   ``I hate to lose when it's close, but this one wasn't close, so
it's not that bad,'' he said. ``The (Cleveland) Indians had a bad
year last year. They came back.''
   In Cincinnati, voters narrowly approved a proposal to increase
the city's 2 percent earnings tax to 2.1 percent to raise money for
repairs of deteriorating streets and bridges. The Hamilton County
Board of Elections said the issue won 50.24 percent to 49.74
percent.
   Voinovich, a popular mayor for 8{ years, has claimed credit for
pulling Cleveland out of the default on bank loans that occurred
during Kucinich's stormy tenure.
   Voinovich has struggled to overcome what he concedes is
Metzenbaum's advantage in name recognition, and already has spent
more than $1 million, much of it on media ads.
   The Metzenbaum campaign has spent more than $800,000 since Jan.
1, and has a campaign warchest of more than $3 million for the fall
election.
</TEXT>
