<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NapaCrush Bjt   05-04 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Napa Crush, Bjt,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moving To Limit Establishment Of More Napa Wineries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time, there are high-level
moves in Napa Valley toward limiting establishment of new wineries
in the nation's top wine-producing region.
   The Napa County Board of Supervisors and the Napa Valley
Vintners Association believe the time may have come to put the
brakes on winery development in the valley north of San Francisco.
   Twenty years ago, the valley had 33 wineries; by 1978 the number
more than doubled, to 74. Today there are about 200 in the valley,
which is only 30 miles long by four miles wide.
   During those years, a Napa wine beat out the best wines of
France in a Paris blind tasting, establishing Napa wines as world
class.
   Since then, buyers from a dozen countries have been purchasing
Napa wineries, and uncounted vineyards up and down the state. Prime
Napa producing vineyard land sells for up to $42,000 an acre.
   ``We must preserve this place,'' said Robert A. Dwyer, executive
director of the vintners association, representing the most
successful U.S. wine producers. ``What's at stake is the quality of
life here.''
   With the growing success of Napa wines, land prices rose, but
that didn't stop buyers. Sapporo brewers of Japan recently paid
more than $35,000 an acre to Abbott Vineyards for producing land in
the prized Carneros area.
   Another section of producing vineyards went to Domaine Mumm of
France for $42,000 an acre. Bare land _ it takes four years for a
new vine to produce mature grapes _ goes for $20,000-$22,000 an
acre. Still, it's a seller's market.
   The mark of Napa Valley is magic. Cabernet sauvignon grapes from
the valley can get a 25 percent higher tonnage price than grapes
grown elsewhere and which might even be of higher quality.
   In mid-March, the vintners' association voted to submit a
proposal to the county Planning Commission barring further winery
construction in Napa County's designated agricultural watershed
districts _ 85 percent of the county.
   The association also wants a winery production zone to
``grandfather'' all the existing wineries in the county. The issue
is to go before the commission in mid-June.
   Dwyer, who spoke of a valley whose traditions go back to 1838,
said the theory is ``to give legitimacy to the wineries that are
here. Anybody who wanted to rezone agricultural preserve land ...
would have to jump through some pretty restrictive hoops.''
   The action came on a note of alarm. The vintners, some of whose
vineyards were planted 125 years ago, had noticed that the Planning
Commission over 18 months had received applications for use permits
for 40 prospective wineries.
   Within two weeks a record 27 applications were received for new
wineries.
   ``We usually get only two, maybe three, applications a month,''
planning director Jim Hickey said.
   ``I think we're reaching the limit, and they (supervisors) want
to examine the density issue,'' he said. ``That has never come up
before. The board wants the department to look into the question,
how many wineries (should be) in a given geographical area. What
would be the criteria?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
