<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     05-04 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Sets Off On Another Campaign Swing Even Though Nomination
Locked Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush was heading West
today after celebrating his lock on the Republican presidential
nomination as a ``first step, a tremendously important step.''
   Bush backers threw an ``Over The Top'' party for him Tuesday
night at a Washington hotel a few blocks from the White House. The
vice president actually secured the 1,139 delegates needed for the
nomination a week earlier, in the Pennsylvania primary.
   Bush was making a three-day campaign trip through California,
Montana and Idaho. Aides said the trip was important to Bush's
effort to position himself for the fall campaign, and to keep his
workers energized.
   At Tuesday night's celebration, which came as Bush rolled up a
trio of primary wins in Ohio, Pennsylvania and the District of
Columbia, the vice president rejoiced in his success, but told
campaign aides and volunteers: ``Now we've got a long way to go.''
   A son, George Bush Jr., had more direct advice: ``Sometimes a
son can say things a father can't. We want you to go out there and
kick some Mike Dukakis, and kick him hard.''
   The reference to the Democratic front-runner by the younger Bush
recalled Bush's off-color remarks to New Jersey longshoremen in
1984 following his debate with Democratic vice presidential
candidate Geraldine Ferraro.
   Bush Jr. told the rally: ``Our dad needs a real job.''
   Bush himself said his mathematical lock on the nomination last
week ``wrapped this thing up sooner than I think any of us thought
might take place.''
   ``It all boiled down to working together,'' he said. ``And yet I
don't feel any finality to what has happened now at all.''
   The vice president said his lock on the nomination was ``a first
step, a tremendously important step'' but he cautioned against
complacency.
   Still, Bush declared to rousing cheers, ``the party is united.''
   ``Let Mike Dukakis go around here talking about pink slips,
despair, pessimism in the United Stats,'' he said. ``I'll be the
guy out there talking about hope and opportunity and challenge.''
   Republican Party Chairman Frank Fahrenkopf told the gathering:
``Tonight we officially celebrate the fact that George Bush will be
our nominee following the convention in New Orleans.''
   Bush planned campaign stops in Sacramento and Los Angeles today.
On Thursday, he was to visit a high school in East Los Angeles and
attend a GOP barbecue near Boise, Idaho.
   On Friday, he campaigns in Montana and Nebraska.
   ``I think that the importance of the West is evident,'' said
campaign spokesman Peter Teeley. ``California ...is extraordinarily
important to the November outcome. As a result, we have to get out
there and begin to build a base of support.''
   Bush planned three separate trips to California and other
Western states between now and the June 7 California primary.
   ``We can't ignore the West,'' Teeley said. ``We've got
organizations in place and people on the ground that have been
working for us. You've got to keep those troops energized.''
   Bush campaigned on Tuesday in West Virginia.
</TEXT>
