<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0438EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-ChinaBeer     05-04 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-China Beer,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese to Get More Beer, Less Pork</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More beer and fewer pork chops are what the
future holds for the average Chinese, the Department of Agriculture
predicts.
   ``During the 1980s, China's beer production increased more than
sevenfold and is expected to have reached 5 billion liters in
1987,'' says David Schoonover, the agricultural counselor at the
U.S. embassy in Beijing.
   ``The goal for the current five-year plan likely will be
fulfilled in 1988, two years early.''
   That figure still allows only a modest gallon or so a year for
the average Chinese, because the country's population is now well
over 1 billion. A liter is slightly larger than a quart.
   That gallon average compares with more than 38 gallons a year
for the average West German and 24 gallons for each man, woman and
child in the United States, according to the latest figures
available from the U.S. Beer Institute.
   When it comes to pork _ the main source of meat for the Chinese
_ the prospect is for a shortage, Schoonover finds.
   His brief report is quoted in the May edition of the
department's ``Foreign Agriculture.''
   It says supplies of pork in China are already short, but gives
no figures on consumption. Over 90 percent of Chinese pigs live
with only one to three other pigs on small family farms, he
calculates. He says it is now being proposed that production be
turned over more to larger units that can take advantage of
economies of scale.
   In economies run by Communist governments, the small plots
permitted to private farmers are generally much more productive
than larger state farms.
   From the U.S. farmers' viewpoint, what pigs and beer have in
common is that both are products of grain, a major U.S. export.
   ``The new policy of concentrating pig production on large state
farms, cooperatives and in `specialized households' is likely to
encourage greater imports of feed grains,'' Schoonover wrote.
   ``Currently, the diets of 90 percent of China's hogs are
comprised mostly of slop,'' he wrote.
   He reports that China's home-grown barley is not up to the
standard required by brewers. He says in 1986, China imported
200,000 to 300,000 metric tons of malting barley, with Canada the
main source of supply.
   He also implies that China may need to import hops, the other
main ingredient of beer. He says the country grows enough hops fr
its own needs in most years and even exports some, depending on the
weather, but adds it does not have the equipment to prepare and
store the crop in surplus years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880504-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0440EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-RahRahRaese     05-04 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rah Rah Raese,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Candidate's Wife Decries His `Party Animal' Image</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican gubernatorial candidate John
Raese's wife says she's tired of seeing her millionaire husband
portrayed as a hot-headed ``party animal'' and calls him a ``man's
man.''
   Liz Raese says her husband is sometimes an impulsive figure who
can be aloof but he gets hot under the collar when he's called
immature.
   ``Sure, John loves fast cars and fast boats. When he gets
stressed out, that's his release,'' Mrs. Raese said in an interview
published in Tuesday's Charleston Daily Mail.
   ``In fact, we have our best love affairs in the middle of the
ocean. There is solitude out there. You're alone.
   ``The press makes an issue about his cigarette boat and portrays
him as a party animal,'' Mrs. Raese said. ``We've always had boats.
The cigarette boat is used as much for fishing as racing. We're
like a lot of people _ we like to fish.''
   Raese is challenging Gov. Arch Moore for the GOP gubernatorial
nomination in next Tuesday's primary. Two years ago, he bucked
Moore and won the state GOP chairmanship, which he resigned earlier
this year in a party dispute, and their relationship remains bitter.
   ``They give John two minutes to speak at most of those Lincoln
Day events, then Governor Moore talks for 20 minutes,'' Mrs. Raese
said. ``He calls John immature and I sit there and watch John's
face get flushed. His temper builds and I keep whispering, `Relax,
honey, don't let him get to you.'''
   The 38-year-old Morgantown millionaire owns steel, coal,
limestone and media companies. But his wife said he is awkward, shy
and searching for a secure family life that eluded him while
growing up.
   ``I have seen him grow tremendously in the 10 years we have been
married,'' said Mrs. Raese, 31. ``I like to mother him. I'll come
up behind him and put my arms around him and squeeze tightly. He
says he doesn't want to be mothered and then his face gets flushed.
   ``He's a man's man. There is no women's lib in our house. I lean
on him. He's the man of our house,'' she said.
   Mrs. Raese said her husband is running for governor because he
wants to ``give something back'' to West Virginia.
   ``I say to him, `Why do you want this job? Our life was so good
before, so easy.' And he says, `Liz, how many suits can we buy? How
many planes can we fly? How many parties can we attend? There must
be something more to life than this.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
