<DOCNO> AP880504-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0429EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ExitPolls     05-04 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Exit Polls,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Exit Polls Indicate Relatively Free Rein for Dukakis on Veep</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Primaries Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic voters in Ohio and Indiana gave Gov.
Michael Dukakis good news on two fronts: broad support as their
presidential nominee and a relatively free rein to pick a vice
presidential running mate.
   Overall, ``The signs don't look bad for November'' for Dukakis
if he wins the presidential nomination, said ABC News poll analyst
Doug Muzzio.
   ``He does well in the horse race against Bush,'' Muzzio said.
``He brings the Reagan Democrats back home. And while he's not
winning the black vote, he shows the ability to get it in the
general election.''
   If there was a downside to Dukakis' landslides in Tuesday's
primaries, it was that a plurality of his Ohio voters had
reservations about the Massachusetts governor, and sizable shares
of voters were unfamiliar with his ideology.
   Dukakis had limited success drawing black voters from Jesse
Jackson, who has enjoyed massive black support. Dukakis won 12
percent of the black vote in Indiana, but only 4 percent in Ohio,
CBS News-New York Times polls said.
   Nonetheless, about 60 percent of Jackson's supporters said they
would vote for Dukakis if he were the nominee against George Bush,
ABC's exit poll said. A third said they would not vote, but the
turnout of black Democrats in past elections indicates otherwise,
Muzzio said.
   One issue for the Democrats is whether Jackson's voters would
accept a ticket that did not include him at least as the vice
presidential nominee, and the ABC poll indicated many would, Muzzio
said.
   While 80 percent of Jackson's voters said they wanted him to be
the vice presidential nominee if Dukakis wins, majorities _ 57
percent in Ohio and 63 percent in Indiana _ said the ultimate
choice should be up to the winner.
   Even greater shares of the Dukakis voters, more than 80 percent,
said the nomination winner should pick his own running mate rather
than being bound to choose the second-place finisher. The finding
jibed with high unfavorable ratings of Jackson among Dukakis
supporters.
   When ABC asked voters if they favored Jackson, Sen. Albert Gore
Jr. or someone else to run for vice president with Dukakis, only
about 15 percent of the Democrats in both states chose Jackson.
Just over 30 percent took Gore and pluralities, about 40 percent,
said someone else.
   In the CBS-Times poll, about 60 percent of Dukakis supporters
said Jackson should not be offered the vice presidential
nomination, and only as many said they would vote for Dukakis in
the fall if Jackson ran with him.
   Without a running mate specified, 77 percent of the Democrats
said they would vote for Dukakis over Bush in November, with 10
percent for Bush and 9 percent saying they wouldn't vote, the
CBS-Times polls said.
   Among the Dukakis backers Tuesday were sizable numbers of
Democrats who voted for President Reagan in 1984, the ABC polls
said. Seventeen percent of the Democrats in Indiana and 16 percent
in Ohio said they backed Reagan in 1984; two-thirds of them in Ohio
and 81 percent in Indiana said they would support Dukakis over Bush
in November.
   ``It indicates they're coming home, in one sense,'' said Muzzio.
``Not only does Dukakis win landslide wins in Ohio and Indiana, but
in the numbers he can see some not bad news for November.''
   One less positive sign for Dukakis was in the strength of his
support in Ohio, where a plurality of his voters, 45 percent, said
in the CBS-Times poll that they backed him with reservations, to 41
percent who supported him strongly. In Indiana, however, 51 percent
of Dukakis' support was strong.
   Also, while 45 percent of Democrats in Ohio and 53 percent in
Indiana said Dukakis was ``just about right'' ideologically as
opposed to too liberal or too conservative, considerable numbers _
34 percent in Ohio and 28 percent in Indiana _ said they didn't
know.
   ``Dukakis is still somewhat of an unknown ideologically,'' said
Muzzio. ``A lot of people still don't have a handle on him, this
late in the primary season.''
   The polls had margins of sampling error of 3 points.
</TEXT>
