<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis     05-04 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Won't Claim Nomination, But Says He's Now Tough To Beat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis edged a bit closer to laying claim
to the Democratic presidential nomination with a pair of landslide
primary victories in Ohio and Indiana.
   Asked Tuesday night whether he thought Democratic rival Jesse
Jackson could take the lead away from him now, Dukakis said: ``It's
going to be difficult.''
   Even so, the Massachusetts governor vowed to campaign
aggressively in the remaining primary states. He said he hoped to
lock up enough delegates to win the nomination, and to broaden his
exposure for a likely fall campaign against Vice President George
Bush.
   ``I want people to get to know me more and more and the way to
do that is to go out and campaign hard,'' said Dukakis.
   Dukakis was spending a day at the Statehouse today and attending
a fund-raiser in New Jersey and a Democratic Party dinner in New
York City tonight.
   Asked if his primary wins on Tuesday night and in recent weeks
were a trend that Jackson should take note of, he said: ``I hope
so.'' Jackson scored a victory in Tuesday's District of Columbia
primary, however.
   ``I feel great about today and the results today,'' Dukakis said.
   Dukakis, who has come under increasing criticism from Jackson
lately, refused to say whether he thought Jackson should tone town
the rhetoric.
   ``He's going to have to make that judgment,'' Dukakis said.
``I'm going to try to keep this as positive as I can.''
   Dukakis was campaigning Thursday in West Virginia and Nebraska.
Both states hold primaries next Tuesday.
   The governor was in a jovial mood following his two primary
victories, joking about the White House admission that Nancy Reagan
sometimes seeks the advice of an astrologist before setting the
president's schedule.
   ``I hope that the nation's decisions beginning in January 1989
will be based on something other than horoscopes,'' he said.
   Later, he referred to Reagan's pending endorsement of Bush as
the ``astrological endorsement.''
</TEXT>
