<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0423EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nielsens     05-04 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Magnum' Leads Way to CBS Ratings Victory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thomas Magnum rescued a girlfriend, got his
personal life in order, rejoined the Navy, confronted Higgins over
the identity of Robin Masters, attended a wedding and gave CBS a
much-needed ratings boost. All in two hours.
   The episode of ``Magnum P.I.'' broadcast Sunday brought the
8-year-old, Hawaiian-based detective show starring Tom Selleck to
an end.
   The show was first in last week's A.C. Nielsen Co. ratings. It
gave CBS its first weekly uncontested claim on first place for the
season, after a tie with NBC for the week ended April 10.
   Its 32.0 rating was the 14th highest-rated made-for-TV movie
ever.
   By comparison, the first chapter of the ABC miniseries ``The
Richest Man in the World: The Story of Aristotle Onassis'' came in
37th for the week that ended Sunday and the NBC movie ``Mad Max:
Beyond Thunderdome'' finished 57th.
   It was an especially sweet victory for CBS, which ended the
season in last place for its first time in its history. The network
was in last place the previous week.
   Last week's second-highest rated show, NBC's ``Cheers,'' was
more than eight points behind, with 23.6. A rating point measures
the percentage of the nation's 88.6 million TV homes.
   An original episode of ``Murder, She Wrote'' came in fifth and
helped CBS win the week.
   ``It goes to show what a couple of hit shows can do for you,''
said Arnold Becker, a CBS vice president. ``They can put you back
on top.''
   The movie special allowed Magnum to get his personal life in
order, find the daughter he thought had been killed and quit his
job as head of security for millionaire author Robin Masters to
return to the Navy as a commander.
   Magnum also confronted Jonathan Higgins, played by John
Hillerman, over his suspicion that Higgins was really Robin
Masters. Higgins at first admitted that he was Masters. But as the
show ended he smirked at fooling Magnum and confessed he had been
lying.
   CBS was first for the week with a rating of 13.9; NBC had 13.4
and ABC 12.1.
   In the May sweeps, CBS took an early lead. The Arbitrons, from
April 27 to May 1, CBS 14.9, NBC 13.7, ABC 10.1. The Nielsens, from
April 28-May 1, CBS 15.8, NBC 13.8, ABC 9.0. The sweeps are periods
in which the audiences of local television stations are measured to
set their advertising rates.
   According to Nielsen, last week's top 10 shows were: CBS Sunday
Movie ``Magnum, P.I.'' NBC's ``Cheers,'' NBC's ``The Cosby Show,''
NBC's ``A Different World,'' CBS' ``Murder, She Wrote,'' NBC's
``Golden Girls,'' ABC's ``Just the 10 of Us,'' CBS' ``60 Minutes,''
ABC movie ``Little Girl Lost,'' and ABC ``Growing Pains'' special.
   The ``Growing Pains'' special was the opening for the new spring
series ``Just the 10 of Us.'' ``Little Girl Lost'' was ABC's
highest-rated movie of the year.
   Three shows on the Fox Broadcasting Co. network got better
ratings than some of the network shows. ``America's Most Wanted''
came in ahead of ``Houston Knights.'' Fox's ``Married With
Children'' and ``21 Jump Street'' came in ahead of ``Max Headroom.''
   ABC was first among the evening news shows, moving ahead of CBS,
while NBC stayed in third place. The ratings: ABC 10.4, CBS 9.6,
NBC 8.6.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
