<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0431EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-DCPrimary     05-04 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-DC Primary,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Scores Overwhelming Win In District Of Columbia Primary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson scored his first primary victory
in six weeks in the District of Columbia, telling cheering
supporters: ``We're making America better every day.''
   Jackson brushed aside primary losses Tuesday night in Indiana
and Ohio, telling backers he would keep his campaign going until
the end of the primary season.
   ``All the way to California and New Jersey!'' he said at a
victory party at a Washington hotel. ``We keep on winning.''
   In final, unofficial returns in the district, Jackson had 67,812
votes, or 80.2 percent, compared with 14,969, or 17.7 percent, for
Massachussetts Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   Paul Simon, who has suspended his campaign, collected 750 votes,
or 0.9 percent.
   Early returns showed Jackson winning in all but one of the
city's eight wards, the predominantly white Ward 3, where Dukakis
had a sizable lead. The city is 67 percent black.
   As a result of Tuesday's voting, Jackson netted 13 delegates, to
three for Dukakis.
   Among the Republicans, Vice President George Bush, who already
has a numerical lock on the GOP nomination, got 5,620 votes or 88.8
percent, followed by Sen. Bob Dole with 445 votes, 7 percent; and
Pat Robertson with 262 votes, 4.1 percent.
   Dole has dropped out of the race, and Robertson technically
remains a candidate although he has only 31 delegate.
   Jackson hadn't won a primary since March 20 in Puerto Rico.
   He had been expected to win by a landslide in Washington, but
the voter turnout was disappointingly low. Elections officials said
91,949 voters went to the polls, about 40 percent of those eligible
to participate in the primary.
   In the 1984 primary, 112,412 people voted.
   Four years ago, Jackson won all but three of the delegates on
the primary ballot. The only other primary he won was Louisiana.
This year Jackson has won primary elections in Georgia, Alabama,
Virginia, Louisiana, Mississippi and Puerto Rico. He won caucuses
in Alaska, Delaware, Michigan and South Carolina.
   In other balloting in the district, Del. Walter Fauntroy,
D-D.C., running unopposed in his party's primary for a 10th term to
Congress, now faces Republican William Reed in November's general
election. Reed also ran unopposed.
</TEXT>
