<DOCNO> AP880504-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0253EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-AmnestyRuling     05-04 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amnesty Ruling,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Rules Against Cutoff of Immigration Amnesty</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Amnesty Rush, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Illegal aliens who left the country
briefly without permission from immigration officials may be
eligible for an extension of today's amnesty deadline, a federal
judge has ruled.
   U.S. District Judge Lawrence K. Karlton on Tuesday declared
invalid a rule that made aliens ineligible for legalization if they
left the United States since November 1986.
   Karlton scheduled a Thursday hearing on a motion to force the
U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service to extend the amnesty
deadline through the end of November 1988 for those affected.
   Aliens who were discouraged from applying because of the rule
would then have an opportunity to gain citizenship, said Ralph
Abascal, an attorney for California Rural Legal Assistance.
   Abascal said late Tuesday that 50,000 to 100,000 illegal aliens
could be affected by Karlton's order, which found the INS had
failed to carry out the intended meaning of the Immigration Reform
and Control Act.
   Thomas Laughlin, chief of the INS' Legalization Office in
Sacramento, said he had not seen the ruling.
   ``I'm not sure how it will affect us or who will be eligible,''
he said.
   The Immigration Reform Act granted amnesty to illegal aliens who
have lived in the United States continuously since Jan. 1, 1982.
The deadline to apply is midnight tonight.
   A Nov. 30 deadline has been set for undocumented farm workers
who have picked perishable crops for at least 90 days in recent
years.
   Karlton's ruling was prompted by a lawsuit by Catholic Social
Services, the rural legal assistance organization and other
immigrant-rights groups. The suit challenged the INS interpretation
of what Congress meant by the phrase ``brief, casual and innocent''
departures.
   That phrase was used to describe those brief trips out of the
United States by illegal aliens that would not break the continuous
residency requirement spelled out in the law.
   INS regulations interpreted ``brief, casual and innocent'' trips
as a departure of not more than 30 days for legitimate emergency or
humanitarian purposes. No trips could be made without INS
permission, it said.
   Abascal said many illegal aliens had gotten terse messages such
as, ```Your father is dying,' and they run across the border.''
   Upon returning, they are afraid they have lost their eligibility
for amnesty and fail to apply, he said. Still others were told
flatly that they didn't qualify for amnesty.
   In a separate order issued earlier in the class action lawsuit,
Karlton said it ``is this court's view that the statute requires a
case-by-case determination of whether an absence is `brief, casual
and innocent.'''
   Karlton said Tuesday his order applies to all obviously eligible
people who departed and re-entered the United States since Nov. 6,
1986 _ the date the immigration reform legislation took effect.
   In his 24-page ruling, Karlton concluded that Congress did not
intend the ``brief, casual and innocent'' absence exceptions to
apply only to absences authorized by the INS, the agency's
interpretation.
   Other sections of the reform act, Karlton said, ``reflect
congressional recognition that the legalization program might fail
because of the illegal alien's natural fear'' of the INS.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
