<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0533EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama     05-04 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Banks To Reopen Next Week For Limited Withdrawals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banks that closed two months ago
following the imposition of U.S. economic sanctions will open on
Monday, but there will be limits on the amount of money customers
can withdraw.
   The announcement was made Tuesday by the president of the
Banking Association, Edgardo Lasso. The association represents 93
of the 117 banks operating in Panama, most of them foreign.
   Political instability brought on by the attempts of Washington
and local opposition leaders to oust Panama's strongman, Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega, has crippled the nation's once-bustling
economy.
   ``We are trying to reactivate the economy,'' Lasso said in a
television interview. But, to prevent a run on accounts, withdrawal
amounts will be restricted as specified by the government's Banking
Commission, he said.
   Also Tuesday, the Roman Catholic Church said it was withdrawing
as mediator in the conflict over Noriega until the civilian
government stops criticizing it publicly. Noriega, head of the
15,000-member Defense Forces, is the power behind the civilian
government in Panama.
   Conditions for reopening the banks limit withdrawals to 25
percent of checking account balances as of March 3, the day the
government closed the banks. A maximum of $10,000 may be withdrawn.
   Withdrawals of up to $50 may be made from savings accounts one
month after banks reopen, while payment of interest is restricted
and subject to cash availability in each bank.
   The Banking Commission has promoted a gradual reopening of the
banks.
   On April 18, it let them begin accepting deposits. But because
of limits on withdrawals, about 75 percent of the checks deposited
bounced, analysts and business people said.
   A week later, about a dozen additional services were resumed,
including handling letters of credit; collecting outstanding loans;
transferring funds within Panama, and making foreign exchange
transfers.
   But business people said the operations were largely on paper
and did little to help resolve their problems of liquidity and
credit.
   Both the March 3 closing and the reopening applied to the 67
banks holding licenses to conduct both local and international
banking business. Others also closed their doors because of the
impact of the crisis.
   Some banks had closed even earlier, after Noriega ousted
President Eric Arturo Delvalle Feb. 26 following the president's
attempt to fire the general.
   A statement from the Catholic church on Tuesday accused the
government of attacking it and Archbishop Marcos Gregorio McGrath.
   ``Since the attacks have proliferated in government news media,
we assume the government rejects the mediation of the church,'' it
said.
   The church had offered to negotiate a way for Noriega to step
down, but the opposition demanded his departure as a condition for
talks.
   The government refused and the church suspended the effort a
week after accepting the role at the end of March.
   The church has held the government responsible for the crisis,
but also blamed the ``economic domination of foreign powers and ...
the corruption in the public and private sectors.''
   Noriega is under federal indictment in the United States on drug
trafficking charges, which he denies.
   After the indictments were issued in February, the Reagan
administration imposed economic sanctions in an effort to pressure
the general to leave.
   Washington froze Panamanian assets in the United States and told
U.S. citizens and companies to stop making payments to the
Panamanian government, except for bills relating to utilities and
services such as garbage collection.
   The United States still recognizes Delvalle, who is in hiding,
as Panama's chief executive.
</TEXT>
