<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     05-04 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,XXX</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Creates Panel to Pick Unneeded Bases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci,
anticipating Congress will pass legislation making it easier to
close unneeded military bases, has set up established a bipartisan
commission to select likely facilities.
   He named Former Sen. Abe Ribicoff, D-Conn., and former Rep. Jack
Edwards, R-Ala., as co-chairman of the commission.
   ``Some have suggested that this may be an exercise in
futility,'' Carlucci wrote on Tuesday in a memo to the service
secretaries and Joint Chiefs of Staff, referring to past efforts to
close military bases.
   ``To the contrary, I am convinced that the commission's efforts
can be fruitful in developing a process and criteria for closing or
realigning bases and proposing candidates by the end of the year.''
   Congress has prevented the Pentagon from closing unneeded
military bases for more than a decade, with individual members
always stepping in to protect facilities in their district.
   Under a plan proposed by Rep. Dick Armey, R-Texas, however,
Congress would approve shutdowns before the doomed bases are
actually named.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Authorities Now Processing Exit Applications `Reasonably Fast'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. official is urging Soviet Jews wishing
to leave to take advantage now of an apparent Soviet effort to
speed up processing emigration applications.
   Richard Schifter, assistant secretary of state for human rights
and humanitarian affairs, said the applications are being handled
``reasonably fast,'' but that they should be submitted soon in case
the situation changes.
   Schifter told the National Conference on Soviet Jewry he
believed a huge percentage of the Soviet Union's two million Jews
would emigrate if given the chance. He said most have not applied,
however, believing they would be subject to discrimination in
employment and other opportunities during the long _ often unending
_ period while waiting for approval.
   But, he said, ``A good many of them also are not fully aware
today of what the possibilities are: that you can indeed fill out
the forms, get them filed and there's a chance within six weeks or
two months perhaps to get your application processed.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Subcommittee Charges Illegal Sale Of Korean-Made M-16 Rifles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional panel is charging a South
Korean company with selling American-designed M-16 rifles to at
least one foreign nation in violation of a 17-year-old agreement
between the United States and South Korea.
   The 1971 pact allowed M-16s to be manufactured in South Korea,
but prohibited sales to third countries without U.S. approval. It
also set a production cap.
   The plant was built by Colt Industries Firearms Division of
Hartford, Conn., the maker of the Army rifle, and run by the South
Korean government. But the South Korean Defense Ministry
transferred the operation and ownership to a private company,
Daewoo Precision Industries, in 1982.
   Following the transfer, Colt began reporting to U.S. officials
suspicions that the Korean company was exceeding the production
cap, according to Warren Nelson, a House Armed Services Committee
aide.
   Later, U.S. government investigators uncovered ``solid''
evidence of unauthorized sales to one country and ``hints'' of
sales to other nations, Nelson said. The names of the countries are
classified, he said.
</TEXT>
