<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     05-04 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some players plunk down their money week after
week and never win at Lotto. Not Francine Katzenbogen.
   She bet $1 on the state lottery.
   Once.
   And won $7 million.
   ``I can't believe how it all happened,'' the unemployed beauty
consultant from Brooklyn said Tuesday when she came to collect her
prize from the April 23 drawing.
   ``My mother said, `Here's a dollar, play Lotto. I have never
won; you choose the numbers, maybe that will bring us luck.'''
   Miss Katzenbogen said she almost tore up the ticket because ``I
was certain that I wasn't going to win, so why bother. But my
mother had paid for the ticket, so I proceeded to play it.''
   She said she'll split the jackpot with her mother, Jeanette
Katzenbogen, also of Brooklyn, ``because she is the one who just
about forced me to play.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HENRY, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some modern-day Pony Express riders will get
a chance to live out a legend Saturday when they make a dash for a
doughnut.
   More than 60 riders will celebrate Scotts Bluff County's
centennial by retracing the Pony Express route of the 1860s from
McGrew to Henry.
   The 43-mile ride will include a doughnut derby as each rider
gets a chance to spear a pastry ring with a finger.
   Legend has it that a young woman sweet on one of the dashing
riders discovered that a doughnut could catch a rushing rider's
finger _ and his fancy, said Virgnia Cassells of Scottsbluff, who
organized the doughnut dash.
   ``This rider was quite a ladies' man,'' Ms. Cassells said. ``All
the ladies were really interested in him and tried to give him
cookies and cakes. But he couldn't get those.''
   A Scottsbluff bakery has come up with a special doughnut for
Saturday's dash.
   ``No glaze, no frosting, no jelly,'' Ms. Cassells said. ``It
probably won't taste as good, but they can catch it better and it
won't be as messy.''
</TEXT>
