<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     05-04 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll: Bush-Dukakis Race Tight in Nebraska</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A presidential race between Republican George
Bush and Democrat Michael Dukakis would be tight in Nebraska, the
site of a primary next week, according to a newspaper poll shows.
   Of the 1,100 registered Nebraska voters interviewed in the Omaha
World-Herald Poll, 42 percent said they would support Bush while 40
percent favored Dukakis and 18 percent were undecided.
   Among the Democratic presidential candidates who will be on
Tuesday's Nebraska primary ballot, Dukakis led Jesse Jackson more
than 3-to-1 in a poll of 424 registered Democrats.
   Dukakis was favored by 54 percent of the Democrats, 15 percent
supported Jackson, 20 percent were undecided and other Democrats
split the rest of the vote.
   The telephone poll, conducted last week by SRI Research Center
Inc. of Lincoln, has a margin of error of plus or minus 3
percentage points on general election questions and 4.8 percentage
points for questions on the Democratic primary.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Blanchard: Nominee Should Be Able to Get Votes On His Own</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic Party's presidential
nominee should be able to win black votes without a black running
mate, says the head of the party's national platform committee.
   Michigan Gov. James Blanchard told reporters Tuesday that if
front-runner Gov. Michael Dukakis secures the nomination, he should
consider Jesse Jackson for the No. 2 job but shouldn't feel locked
in to a Dukakis-Jackson slate.
   But, ``if Gov. Dukakis needs to have Jackson on the ticket to
get the black vote, he shouldn't be the nominee. He shouldn't even
run,'' Blanchard said.
   Jackson, who is running second to the Massachusetts governor in
the party's delegate count, beat Dukakis in Michigan, where
Blanchard was officially neutral because of his platform-writing
post.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis Names Campaign Aide As Convention Manager</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential front-runner Michael
Dukakis has named Marcia Hale, his former Southern field director,
as his manager of operations for the Democratic National Convention.
   Ms. Hale, a veteran of the 1984 vice presidential campaign of
Geraldine Ferraro, will coordinate major events for the
Massachusetts governor during the July 18-21 convention in Atlanta.
</TEXT>
