<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0552EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Poland-StrikeScene     05-04 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Strike Scene,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Much Has Changed Since Walesa Led 1980 Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This time, Lech Walesa arrived at the
strikebound Lenin shipyard in a chauffeured car and was greeted as
an elder statesman with cheers and chants of ``Solidarity'' and
``Lech, Lech.''
   Eight years ago, as a little known labor agitator, he had to
vault the shipyard fence to take charge of a workers' revolt that
eventually led to the founding of the Solidarity labor federation
and brought down a government.
   ``I am not your leader. I'm tired,'' Walesa, 44, told the
striking shipyard workers on Tuesday. ``You need a new Walesa, many
more new Walesas.''
   Much has changed since Solidarity was recognized by the
government in accords signed in this Baltic port that ended the
1980 strike wave.
   Walesa has put on some weight, he won the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize
and Solidarity was banned after a December 1981 martial law
crackdown.
   But his trademark moustache remains and he still works as an
electrician at the shipyard.
   Since 1980, Walesa has taken on bodyguards and a driver as part
of his entourage. Fame has complicated his life, making it busier
and making him the subject of an occasional death threat.
   When he attends a union meeting or travels to see visiting
foreign dignitaries, he more likely will be driven than drive
himself.
   Old people, women and children pressed to shake Walesa's hand as
he stepped out of the car and walked up to the shipyard gate, which
was decorated with Solidarity banners, pictures of Pope John Paul
II, yellow flowers and a sign proclaiming ``Occupation Strike.''
   The strikers shouted his name and patted him on the back as he
approached a makeshift podium to deliver a speech.
   Policemen patrolled nearby, but did not intervene.
   Walesa told the strikers that he wasn't their leader.
   ``I've done what I had to do,'' Walesa told them. ``But I don't
want a past. I only want bread, calm and peace for us all. I want
to help Poland enter a road of reforms.''
   The strikers wore Solidarity badges and armbands on their blue
overalls. Many also wore yellow hardhats as they sipped tea and
smoked in the balmy sunshine.
   Dozens of strikers crowded the rooftops of nearby buildings to
listen to the speech. Outside the plant, people pressed together to
catch a glimpse while others climbed on the iron shipyard gate.
   They joined in occasional ``Solidarity'' chants and chatted with
the strikers, some of whom guarded the entrances to the shipyard
and checked the plastic identity cards of yard workers going in or
out.
   Over a loudspeaker, an announcer read names of workers whose
relatives had come to the gate to bring them food and cigarettes.
   Cheers arose when workers and sympathizers delivered loaves of
bread, cans of sardines and jars of honey and jam in large canvas
bags and wheeelbarrows.
   Just outside the gate, a red-and-white Polish flag with the
Solidarity logo was placed near the three tall, concrete crosses
joined by three anchors. The monument honors scores of Baltic Coast
workers, including at least 27 in Gdansk, killed during the harsh
goverment response to riots against price increases introduced just
before Christmas 1970.
   The monument was dedicated Dec. 16, 1980, fulfilling a pledge
made by Walesa during the early days of the 1980 Solidarity strike.
</TEXT>
