<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Biaggi-Wedtech     05-04 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness: Wedtech Hired CIA Deputy, Israeli in Contracts Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Wedtech Corp. turned to a former deputy
director of the CIA and an Israeli general in attempts to sell arms
overseas, according to testimony in the racketeering trial of Rep.
Mario Biaggi.
   The testimony Tuesday came as part of the defense's attempt to
show that the scandal-plagued South Bronx defense contracting firm
did not need Biaggi's help in obtaining work because it already had
high-level connections in the Reagan administration and elsewhere.
   The Bronx Democrat, his son and five others are on trial in
federal court on charges of turning Wedtech into a racketeering
enterprise that paid public officials millions of dollars to obtain
government contracts.
   Former Wedtech vice president Larry Shorten said the company
approached former CIA official Max Hugel in 1985 for help in
selling a tug barge to Yugoslavia.
   Hugel would have received a commission if the sale went through
but Shorten did not specify the outcome.
   Shorten said the company paid Maj. Gen. Avigdor Ben-Gal of
Israel between $3,000 and $4,000 a month for two years to serve as
a consultant. The company did not get any contracts with Israel
through the general, who retired from the Israeli army in 1982.
</TEXT>
