<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DrugTesting 1stLd-Writethru a0508 05-04 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Testing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0508,590</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf pvs, bgng The drug ..., to correct figure to 42
federal agencies; picks up 3rd graf pvs, Officials at</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plans to require random drug testing of
government employees are meeting strong opposition from a group of
Justice Department attorneys, who plan a legal challenge to the new
program.
   The drug testing would be required for government employees
ranging from White House chief of staff Howard Baker down to
secretaries and butlers under plans unveiled Tuesday by 42 federal
agencies.
   Officials at the Department of Health and Human Services
forwarded employee drug-testing plans from the agencies to
Congress, technically clearing the way for the agencies to begin
testing the workers they have designated.
   Stephen Sachs, a private Washington attorney, said he has met
with a number of Justice Department lawyers who feel the program is
``much more expansive'' than had been anticipated.
   ``Our contention is that they cannot do mandatory, random
drug-testing without some probable cause or some kind of
individualized suspicion,'' he said.
   He said Justice Department officials have said in the past there
is no drug problem at the department.
   As a practical matter, many of the various testing plans already
have been blocked by court suits. Other federal employee
organizations have said they also will sue once their agencies'
attempts to implement testing.
   At the White House, the plan would affect 370 employees,
including Baker, secretaries, butlers, ushers, chefs, maids,
receptionists and tradesmen in the presidential residence.
   Ray Kogut, director of personnel for the Office of
Administration, said about 1,200 of the 1,600 people working in 13
separate agencies under the executive office of the president will
be affected.
   President Reagan and Vice President George Bush will not be
required to submit to random testing. However, they have
voluntarily given specimens in the past, Kogut said.
   Kogut said the 100 percent coverage figure also applies to the
National Security Council staff, the office of the vice president,
the Council of Economic Advisors and its staff, the Office of
Policy Development, office of the U.S. Trade Representative and
Office of Science and Technology Policy.
   The Defense Department said HHS had certified drug-testing plans
that could ultimately cover about 20 percent of its civilian work
force _ or more than 200,000 federal workers. The Army already has
begun testing some of its civilian employees.
   The mandatory, random drug testing at the Justice Department
covers some 4,700 employees in the attorney general's office, U.S.
attorneys' offices nationwide and in the six divisions of the
department: criminal, civil, antitrust, tax, lands and civil rights.
   About 7 percent of the 4,700 would be tested annually under the
Justice Department plan, which will go into effect in several
months.
   In addition, there are 9,300 other Justice Department employees
who could be tested if there was reasonable suspicion to suspect
they were using drugs. Applicants for those posts also would face
drug tests.
   Separate drug testing programs already are under way or are
about to begin for certain employees at four Justice Department
agencies: the FBI, Drug Enforcement Administration, Immigration and
Naturalization Service and the Bureau of Prisons.
   The HHS guidelines _ regarding clinical urine collection
procedures and testing laboratory accuracy _ were first issued more
than a year ago and formally published in final form in the Federal
Register last month.
   The HHS's own internal plan calls for testing for marijuana and
cocaine. It says 8,661 of the agency's approximately 130,000
employees are liable for testing and that it envisions testing 10
percent of the 8,661 in any given year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
