<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged up in light European trading
early today. Gold bullion fell.
   The dollar fluctuated within a tight range in the first hours of
trading, and market participants said they did not expect much
movement throughout the session.
   A trader at a West German bank said the latest, generally
favorable, U.S. economic reports were supporting the dollar. The
recent upward trend in U.S. interest rates also helped, an Italian
trader said.
   Midmorning dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.6820 West German marks, up from 1.6770
   _1.4005 Swiss francs, up from 1.3945
   _5.7120 French francs, up from 5.6935
   _1.8858 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8795
   _1,251.50 Italian lire, up from 1,247.50
   _1.2370 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2294
   The British pound fell to $1.8651 from $1.8715.
   Tokyo markets were closed for a second day for Japanese
holidays. The dollar was quoted at 125.00 yen in London, up from
124.83 yen late Tuesday.
   London's major bullion houses fixed a recommended gold price at
midmorning of $441.95 a troy ounce, down from $445.50 late Tuesday.
A trader said selling from the Middle East was helping to depress
prices.
   Gold was bid at $441.90 in Zurich, down from $446.
   Earlier, the metal closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $444.71, down
from $446.57.
   Silver bullion traded in London at $6.31 a troy ounce, down from
$6.39.
</TEXT>
