<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0659EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Poland     05-04 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Poland,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Media Paint Somber Picture Of Polish Strikes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet media painted a somber picture of the
industrial strikes now under way in Poland, saying the labor unrest
is a menace to economic reforms being pursued by the Warsaw
government.
   The Communist Party daily Pravda today accused ``anti-Polish
centers'' in the West and an ``internal opposition'' in the
Moscow-aligned country of trying to exploit the discontent for
their own ends.
   Pravda said the airwaves were filled with broadcasts from
Western radio stations urging the Poles ``to enlarge the scale of
the protest'' and to increase their demands.
   The Tass news agency said the strikes in Gdansk, Wroclaw and
other areas of the country are harmful to Poland's economy. But it
also quote a Polish government spokesman as saying the strikes did
not threaten the government and it gave a veiled reminder that the
regime in place enjoys Soviet backing.
   ``The strikes that are held now and that are sought to be
organized do not threaten the socialist state as it has durable
internal and external foundations,`` spokesman Jerzy Urban was
quoted as saying in Warsaw on Tuesday.
   ``But strikes threaten the economic reform,'' Urban continued.
``They can put off or undermine it. And the reform is our national
opportunity to overcome the difficulties of life and economic
stagnation.''
   An estimated 7,000 workers were on strike at the Lenin shipyard
in Gdansk and work stoppages also had spread to at least two other
industrial facilities.
   Workers are demanding higher wages to offset government-imposed
price increases on food and consumer goods. Government officials
say the price increases were needed to balance goods with the money
supply.
   ``The heightening of tension, endless demands and the staging of
strikes can only hamper the processes of democratization and
reforms,'' Tass quoted Urban as saying.
   Tass said Urban claimed the latest round of strikes is
dissimilar to the labor crisis which began in Poland in the early
80s. Bad leadership was partially responsible for that crisis, he
said.
   ``Now the strikes have broken out at the very start of the
process of transition to radical reforms, in a situation when there
is no need to stop work in order to speak out loud and be heard,''
Urban said. ``The strikes are groundless and harmful both from the
political and economic viewpoints.''
   Pravda, apparently referring to martial law, said Solidarity had
``played on feelings of Poles'' and ``what came of this is known to
everyone.''
   Solidarity was the first independent union in the Soviet bloc,
but was outlawed after martial law was declared in December 1981.
   Tass reported that Poland's Minister of Industry Erzy Bilip has
rejected demands for wage increases, saying the pay increases would
``contradict the second stage of reform.''
</TEXT>
