<DOCNO> AP880504-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0732EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Plane     05-04 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Plane,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plane That Lost Power In Engines Heads Home For Exam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A United Airlines jumbo jet that landed at Tokyo's
airport with just one of its four engines working took off today
for San Francisco with no passengers aboard, an airline spokesman
said.
   Robert Leu said a team of United Airlines engineers sent from
the United States inspected the Boeing 747 thoroughly and ``found
no defects in the aircraft and deemed the aircraft airworthy.''
   The jetliner will be taken to the company's maintenance
operation center in San Francisco, where it will be examined by the
National Transportation Safety Board, he said.
   Aviation sources in Washington said that the tanks supplying
fuel to the three dead engines were found to be dry when the plane
landed safely on Monday at New Tokyo International Airport.
   But Leu said the aircraft's six tanks are all interconnected and
the fuel supply system had plenty of fuel remaining on arrival at
the airport, better known as Narita.
   ``Each tank can supply fuel to each engine,'' he said. ``And the
aircraft had 23,500 pounds of fuel upon arrival at Narita. This
craft had considerably more than our own requirements,'' he said.
   The Federal Aviation Administration requires 16,000 pounds of
fuel remaining on arrival, while United requires 19,000 pounds, Leu
said.
   The jetliner, en route to Tokyo from Los Angeles, was flying at
39,000 feet with 258 people aboard one hour and 15 minutes from its
destination when the first engine lost power, United announced
Tuesday.
   Half an hour later, a second engine shut down and shortly before
landing, a third engine lost power.
   A Boeing 747 has a maximum fuel capacity of 320,000 pounds and
burns about 23,500 pounds of fuel per hour while cruising with all
four engines operating, according to the manufacturer.
   According to a report in the Yomiuri Shimbun, a Tokyo newspaper,
the gauge that indicates how much fuel is feeding into the engines
showed there was almost no fuel going into engines one and four and
that the No. 3 engine was also malfunctioning.
   Leu declined to comment on the cause of the engine failure,
saying it was still under investigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
