<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Honduras-Guard, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0511,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oklahoma National Guardsman Electrocuted in Honduras</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to restore paragraph marker in 1st graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the Oklahoma National
Guard was killed when he touched a high voltage line while doing
electrical work at Palmerola air base, a U.S. Embassy spokesman
said.
   Oklahoma National Guard Col. Bill Francis identified the victim
as Sgt. David Alvin Brown, 21, of Sperry, Okla.
   Brown was in Honduras with the 245th Aviation Battalion of
Sperry for two weeks of annual training, Francis said Tuesday in
Oklahoma City. The battalion was due back in Oklahoma on May 13, he
said.
   The embassy spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
the victim was died Sunday at the base, about 40 miles north of
Tegucigalpa.
   The United States maintains about 1,100 troops in Honduras.
Additional troops and national guardsmen come on temporary duty for
joint exercises conducted every few months with the Honduran armed
forces.
</TEXT>
