<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0813EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LotteryFix     05-04 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lottery Fix,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Under Scrutiny After Lottery Forgery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID MORRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennsylvania lottery officials are reviewing
security measures in the wake of an insider scam that almost
allowed two men to get away with a $15.2 million jackpot.
   Lottery officials revealed Tuesday that a ticket turned in last
week for the jackpot was bogus and an employee at the company that
runs the lottery computer had been charged, along with a man who
claimed the prize.
   Gov. Robert P. Casey ordered a suspension of the contract
extension for Control Data Corp. ``until the commonwealth is
totally satisfied that all reasonable safeguards against fraud have
been built into the security system.''
   One of the two men charged in the case, Henry Arthur Rich,
worked for Control Data as a troubleshooter for the lottery's
mainframe computer.
   State Attorney General LeRoy S. Zimmerman alleged Rich used a
Control Data computer to identify unclaimed jackpots and to print a
copy of the winning ticket from the July 15 Super 7 drawing.
   Also charged was Mark S. Herbst, who claimed the prize last
Thursday.
   Both men were arraigned on charges of theft by unlawful taking,
theft by deception, criminal conspiracy and forgery, and were held
in the Dauphin County Prison in lieu of $50,000 bail.
   Rich also was charged with unlawful use of a computer and
tampering with public information.
   If convicted, Herbst could be jailed for up to 31 years and
fined $70,000, Zimmerman said. Rich could face 40 years in prison
and $90,000 in fines.
   Zimmerman said officials have no evidence of anyone else
participating in the scam or of any other bogus tickets in
Pennsylvania or Delaware, where Rich also had access to the lottery
computer.
   James Scroggins, the lottery's executive director, said the scam
was discovered last Thursday, shortly after Herbst received the
first $469,989 installment of the prize.
   When Herbst claimed the jackpot, he said he had been using the
ticket as a bookmark and checked the numbers after seeing a
newspaper story about the unclaimed prize.
   But the bogus ticket was printed on a blank from a Scranton
outlet, while a computer check showed the actual winner was sold in
Bucks County. The holder of the ticket bought in Bucks County has
never come forward.
   A spokesman at Control Data said Tuesday the firm had been told
by the state Revenue Department not to comment, although Revenue
officials said no such order had been given.
   A previous insider incident occured in the April 24, 1980,
drawing of Pennsylvania's Daily Number. The drawing was fixed by
altering pingpong balls used to pick the winning digits.
   The so-called 6-6-6 case, named after the winning numbers, also
resulted in tighter security for the televised drawings as well as
the convictions of six participants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
