<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Marcos 1stLd-Writethru a0554 05-04 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marcos, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0554,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marcos Says He'll Try To Negotiate Return to Homeland for Mother's
Funeral</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Marcos statement; adds byline</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Marcos-Mother</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ousted Philippines President Ferdinand Marcos
said he would continue to seek permission to return to his homeland
for his mother's funeral despite the government's refusal.
   Marcos' 95-year-old mother died today in Manila after making a
deathbed request that Marcos be allowed to return so that she could
see him before she died.
   However, Philippines President Corazon Aquino said her
predecessor remained unwelcome in the country as a threat to the
nation's stability.
   Marcos, in a statement, posed his return in political, as well
as personal, terms, saying he wanted to help save the country from
possible civil war or the threat of a communist takeover.
   Marcos and his wife, 20 members of his staff and about 30
supporters gathered this morning to celebrate a Mass in memory of
his mother at the Marcos estate overlooking downtown.
   ``I am completely shocked by the sudden demise of my beloved
mother, Josefa Edralin-Marcos,'' Marcos said in the statement read
by his spokesman, Gemmo Trinidad, to reporters outside the walled
estate.
   ``I am sure that our Lord will take my dear mother into his
kingdom to live the eternal life of heaven. This is indeed a very
tragic personal matter for the entire Marcos family,'' Marcos said.
   ``I will exhaust all possibilities that may still be available
to us to return to our motherland, to help save her from the
threatened communist takeover or a possible civil war,'' he said.
   Trinidad said that when Marcos was informed that he would not be
allowed back in the Philippines for mother's funeral, Marcos said
he would continue to negotiate ``but won't violate any laws to go
back.''
   Trinidad said there has been no contact with the Aquino
government and the only word about Mrs. Aquino's decision came from
news reports.
   Asked about how Marcos and his wife, Imelda, were taking the
death, Trinidad said, ``Both of them are calm but sad.''
</TEXT>
