<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0830EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ColumbiaJournalists     05-04 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Columbia Journalists,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Journalists Say Coverage of Presidential Elections has Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rules for covering presidential elections
have changed and Jesse Jackson has won a place in historyr,
according members of a panel of journalists at a 75th anniversary
dinner for the Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism.
   The panel members were Benjamin Bradlee, executive editor of The
Washington Post, Patrick Buchanan, co-host of Cable News Network's
program ``Crossfire,'' Max Frankel, executive editor of The New
York Times, and Judy Woodruff, an anchor on the MacNeil-Lehrer
NewsHour.
   ``The press now has the power to destroy,'' said Buchanan,
referring to the failure of Gary Hart's candidacy for the
Democratic nomination following revelations he spent a weekend with
a Miami model.
   The panelists noted that the infidelities of President Kennedy
and the polio of President Franklin D. Roosevelt were largely
ignored in coverage of their presidential races.
   Frankel said there has been a maturing of reporting and
analysis, but added that journalists ``have not been cured of the
urge to predict and handicap'' the races.
   Television has made progress, Ms. Woodruff said, but is still
too dependent on ``snappy eight-second sound bites'' and is too
preoccupied with polls.
   Bradlee said the 1988 campaign has become the longest ever and
the length was hindering coverage. However, the character issues
have changed the rules of journalism, he said, and the other
panelists agreed with him.
   ``Jesse Jackson changed the political arena for better and
forever,'' he said. He called Jackson ``the candidate of the
left,'' which he said was still vital and alive in the country.
   ``Jackson went beyond winning a victory or winning the
nomination. He won a place in history,'' said Frankel.
   The panel was moderated by Albert Hunt, Washington bureau chief
of The Wall Street Journal. Almost 300 people attended the dinner
and panel discussion in the Rotunda of Low Memorial Library.
</TEXT>
