<DOCNO> AP880504-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0855EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-MeeseLetter 2ndLd-Writethru a0519 05-04 1144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese Letter, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0519,1170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Ethics Office Probing Letter Sent by Meese for Japan
Conference</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to include reference to regional Bell
source report and LA Times report on Wedtech; picks up 7th graf,
`Meese will...'; SUBS last 4 grafs, bgn, `Swanson said he...' with
6 grafs to give detail.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal ethics officials want to know why
Attorney General Edwin Meese III solicited 30,000 lawyers and
businessmen to pay more than $3,000 apiece to a profit-making
organization to attend a conference.
   The Office of Government Ethics on Tuesday launched an
investigation into Meese's April 26 letter, said Frank Q. Nebeker,
the head of the ethics office.
   Meese's letter _ written on his official stationery and
emblazoned with the Justice Department seal _ was sent to 30,000
people whose names were ``provided by everyone from the American
Bar Association, the advisory committees on both sides, to the
American Chamber of Commerce in Japan,'' said Norm Swanson,
chairman of the Citizen Ambassador Program, the profit-making group
that is a cosponsor of the meeting along with a Japanese federation.
   A presidential order on ethics forbids federal officials from
engaging in conduct that might present the appearance of
favoritism, conflict of interest or loss of objectivity in
governmental decision making. The appearance of such a problem is
enough to trigger an investigation. It also is a crime to use the
Justice Department seal for non-authorized purposes.
   Meanwhile, sources said Tuesday that Meese reversed a Justice
Department position on the breakup of American Telephone &
Telegraph Co. at a time when he owned $14,000 in regional Bell
stock. And the Los Angeles Times reported today that a Senate
subcommittee will report that Meese violated government policy when
he tried to help the Wedtech Corp.
   Meese will be heading a U.S. delegation to the Aug. 29-Sept. 1
legal and economic conference in Japan called ``The U.S.-Japan
Bilateral Session: A New Era in Legal and Economic Relations.''
   Justice Department spokesman Terry Eastland said the department
was unaware that a profit-making organization was involved, but he
contended Meese's involvement might still be justified.
   The U.S. sponsor for the meeting is the Citizen Ambassador
Program of People to People International. The Kansas City,
Mo.,-based People to People International is a non-profit
organization set up originally in the State Department by
then-President Dwight Eisenhower, Swanson said.
   The Citizen Ambassador Program, however, is a profit-making
organization that works exclusively to set up international
exchanges for People to People, Swanson said Tuesday night in a
telephone interview from his home in Spokane, Wash.
   ``Yes, the Citizen Ambassador Program is for-profit, which is
how Eisenhower established the program with the intention of making
it self-supporting,'' Swanson said.
   The cost for participants is listed as $3,240, Swanson said. He
said the amount includes transportation and lodging and an $800
registration fee set by the Japanese organizing committee.
   Swanson acknowledged his company is paying $100 to People to
People International for each person who signs up for the
conference, but he denied that it was a payoff.
   ``Ever since the beginning of the People to People organization,
the relationship has been that the delegates on any project pay a
fee to People to People International to become members,'' Swanson
said. His company collects the fee from participants and pays it to
People to People and the new members ``hopefully become involved in
chapter projects, pen-pal projects, sister city projects and
others.''
   Swanson said he could not say how much profit his company might
earn.
   ``I wish I knew,'' he said. ``It's not large. It depends on the
participation in the conference.''
   Eastland said the Justice Department became involved when
``People to People International came to us and represented
themselves as a non-profit, tax-exempt organization.''
   ``To the extent that they're linked to some group that is
profit-making, that was not known by those making decisions on the
attorney general's participation,'' he said.
   ``It could be argued that the department could engage in a joint
venture so long as it was in the department's interest, and
obviously we have an interest in international legal questions.''
   Meese sent out a similar letter and hosted a U.S. delegation to
a similar conference sponsored by People to People International in
China last summer, Eastland said.
   Justice Department legal and ethics authorities reviewed both
cases to make sure the attorney general's participation was
permissible, he said.
   The department covers Meese's expenses for the trips. This year,
he will be making an official visit at the same time to Japanese
Minister of Justice Yukio Hayashida.
   However, expenses for Meese's wife, Ursula, for last year's trip
were paid by People to People International ``in return for the
frankly exhausting role that she fulfilled in being head of the
women's contingent for the conference,'' Swanson said.
   Eastland said that was permissible under department regulations.
   Swanson said the cost for the China meeting, including
transportation, was about $2,500.
   The two-page letter from Meese says, in part, ``Although
attended and assisted by senior officials of the governments of
both Japan and the United States, the conference is fittingly a
non-governmental one administered on behalf of the Japanese by
Japan's Federation of Economic Organizations (Keidanren) and on the
American side by the Citizen Ambassador Program of the People to
People International organization.''
   ``I invite and encourage your participation. Sincerely Edwin
Meese III, Attorney General.''
   In connection with the AT&T breakup, administration sources told
The Associated Press on Tuesday that Meese was urged by his friend
E. Robert Wallach to get involved, then obtained a White House
waiver letting him make a decision and approved a reversal of the
department's previous position, urging a federal judge to lift
restrictions barring the regional Bell companies from entering
various new types of business.
   Meese, whose telephone stock holdings and meetings with regional
Bell executives have been under criminal investigation, received
Wallach's advice in a memo in mid-December 1986, the sources said.
   Meese's attorney, James Rocap, said Tuesday that he had ``no
knowledge that Mr. Meese ever saw or read the memo,'' and that
Meese's decision to seek a waiver ``was based solely on the advice
of the attorney general's staff.''
   Wallach is under indictment in the Wedtech scandal, in which
Meese remains under criminal investigation.
   The Los Angeles Times reported today that the Senate
Governmental Affairs subcommittee on oversight of government
management will report that Meese, as counsel to President Reagan
in 1981, violated a White House ban on intervening in government
contracts on behalf of friends when he tried to help Wedtech.
   Meese's lawyer, Nathan Lewin, disputed the subcommittee's
findings, saying Meese's actions ``did not give the appearance of
impropriety'' and ``did not fall within the scope of the White
House regulation.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Associated Press writer Michael J. Sniffen also
contributed to this story.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880504-0094 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0901EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PrimariesRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0520 05-04 1126</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Primaries Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0520,820</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: New thruout with comments from Jackson, Nunn, Babbitt and
with latest results from Indiana, Ohio and the District of
Columbia.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, harvesting another pair of landslide primary
victories, sounded ever more confident of his claim to the
Democratic presidential nomination while rival Jesse Jackson vowed
today he's in the race ``all the way'' despite setbacks in Ohio and
Indiana.
   Republican George Bush looked ahead to the fall and cautioned
his supporters, ``We've got a long way to go.''
   Jackson scored an expected victory Tuesday in the District of
Columbia, but found himself slipping an additional 120 delegates
behind Dukakis, who won handily in Ohio and Indiana.
   His latest victories moved Dukakis to fewer than 600 delegates
from the 2,081 he needs to clinch the nomination. He also moved
more than 600 ahead of his only rival.
   But Jackson gave no sign he was ready to end what he called a
struggle ``for the direction of our party and the soul of our
nation.''
   ``We're within striking distance,'' Jackson said on CBS's ``This
Morning'' program. ``It's not over really till it's over. What's
next is West Virginia and Nebraska, Oregon, New Mexico, California,
New Jersey.''
   Asked if he is in the race for the long run, Jackson replied,
``All the way.''
   Jackson was seeking support today among House Democrats and then
holding strategy sessions with aides before flying off to Nebraska,
which holds its primary Tuesday, as does West Virginia.
   Meanwhile, former Democratic candidate Bruce Babbitt said he
would accept the No. 2 spot on the presidential ticket, but would
advise front-runner Dukakis to select a southerner.
   ``Bruce Babbitt is from southern Arizona, that's not enough,''
Babbitt said on the CBS show. ``It's got to be somebody from the
South ... Sam Nunn or Chuck Robb.''
   But Nunn, the Georgia senator frequently mentioned as a vice
presidential candidate, said today he has ``not very much
interest'' in taking the post.
   ``On a scale of one to 10, 10 being the most interest, my
interest is about level one, so I have not very much interest,''
Nunn said on NBC-TV's ``Today'' show.
   The senator said he would discuss the possibility with Dukakis
when the candidate wants to talk.
   ``I've never desired that job, so we'll just have to roll up our
pants when we get to the creek, and we're not to the creek yet,''
he said.
   Democratic Party leaders tempered their euphoria over the latest
signal that their nomination marathon was over with concern that
Jackson's recent attacks on Dukakis could provide campaign
ammunition for the Republicans in the fall.
   ``I would hope he wouldn't say anything that could be used
against Mike in the general election,'' said Gov. Bill Clinton of
Arkansas, who predicted Dukakis would win the Democratic nomination
on the first ballot at the party's convention in July.
   Judy Carnahan, chairman of the Oregon Democratic Party, said
Jackso's recent attacks were ``very disappointing. What he's
managing to do is diminish his own stature.''
   That view was by no means unanimous.
   Lynn Cutler, vice chair of the Democratic National Committee,
said she wasn't concerned about Jackson's rhetoric.
   ``I don't (believe) any of it is stuff we're going to see coming
back at us out of George Bush's mouth,'' she said. ``He's trying to
draw distinctions and I don't blame him for that. I don't think
there is anything there that is problematic.''
   Questioned today about the Democratic leaders' concerns, Jackson
said, ``Well, in this stage, I'm trying to help my chances and
that's the first issue because both of us are running for the
nomination.''
   ``I'm not pushing Dukakis. I'm pulling Dukakis and pulling Bush
into facing issues that will make a difference in this country,''
he said on the CBS program. ``I challenge judgment, distinction and
differences, but not integrity.''
   When Dukakis was asked if he thought Jackson should tone down
his attacks, the Massachusetts governor replied, ``He's got to make
that judgment. I'm going to try to keep this as positive as I can.''
   In recent days, Jackson has repeatedly pressed Dukakis to
provide more details of his plans for improving education and day
care and reducing the federal budget deficit.
   No prominent Democrats were ready to call on Jackson to end his
campaign and Dukakis appeared content to see the contest play out
through the final Democratic primaries on June 7.
   Clinton said there were ``a number of governors who were willing
to endorse him (Dukakis) before this time,'' but were discouraged
by Dukakis.
   ``He just didn't want to be perceived as trying to stop
Jackson,'' said Clinton. ``He wanted to win the votes in the
primaries ahead.''
   Riding high after a streak of primary victories that included
Connecticut, Wisconsin, New York, Pennsylvania, Indiana and Ohio,
Dukakis said Tuesday night he thought it was ``going to be
difficult'' for Jackson to deny him the nomination.
   Bush celebrated his lock on the nomination at a hotel within
walking distance of the White House and urged his supporters not to
let up.
   ``I don't feel any finality to what has happened now at all,''
he told a cheering crowd. ``We've passed the first step, a
tremendously important step. ... But now we've got a long way to
go.''
   The vice president's son, George Bush Jr., urged the partisan
crowd: ``We want you to go out and kick some Mike Dukakis, and kick
him hard.''
   Bush went over the top in his quest for a GOP convention
majority last week in Pennsylvania and at his Washington rally he
offered this preview of the fall campaign:
   ``Let Mike Dukakis go around here talking about pink slips,
despair, pessimism in the United States. I'll be the guy out there
talking about hope and opportunity and challenge.''
   There were 254 delegates at stake in the three primaries.
   The latest Associated Press tally gave Dukakis 1,486 and Jackson
927.
   In Ohio, with 99 percent of the precincts reporting, Dukakis had
860,896 or 63 percent, to 378,315 or 28 percent for Jackson.
   In Indiana, with 98 percent of the precincts reporting, Dukakis
had 436,955 or 70 percent to Jackson's 138,496 or 22 percent.
   In the District of Columbia, final unofficial returns showed
Jackson had 67,812 votes, or 80 percent, while Michael Dukakis had
14,969, or 17 percent. Jackson captured 13 of the district's 16
Democratic convention delegates. Dukakis won 3.
   On the Republican side, Bush had 648,478 or 81 percent of the
Republican vote in Ohio with 99 percent of the precincts reporting;
341,332 or 83 percent in Indiana with 98 percent of the precincts
reporting; and 5,620 for 89 percent in final unofficial returns in
the District of Columbia, where he resides.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
