<DOCNO> AP880504-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0907EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SupernovaElements     05-04 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Supernova Elements,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Balloon Over Antarctic Confirms Gold's Supernova Origins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists say a balloon flight over
Antarctica has given them confirmation that supernovas are the only
origin of gold and other heavier-than-iron elements such as copper
and lead.
   ``The (1987) supernova explosion itself was one of the most
significant events in 20th century astrophysics, and now it's
giving us an opportunity to answer old questions on the origin of
matter in the universe,'' said Carl Rester, director of APEX, the
recently established Laboratory for Astrophysics and Planetary
Exploration at the University of Florida.
   Elements lighter than iron are formed under normal conditions
within stars, but scientists have long theorized it would take the
shock waves and extremely high temperatures of a supernova
explosion to form most elements heavier than iron.
   Supernova explosions are rare and cause a star to suddenly
become 10 million to 100 million times brighter.
   When astronomers spotted supernova 1987a last February, Rester
saw a unique opportunity and quickly mobilized several agencies to
investigate.
   On Jan. 8, researchers at the University of Florida and the NASA
Goddard Space Flight Center launched a balloon, carrying an
instrument called GRAD, for gamma ray advanced detector, from near
McMurdo Station in Antarctica.
   For three days it floated 22 miles above the earth, suspended
from a helium balloon the size of a football field. From that
vantage point, it had a clear view of supernova 1987a unobstructed
by the Earth's atmosphere.
   The balloon-suspended instrument detected gamma rays from the
radioactive decay of cobalt-56 to iron-56, proving that cobalt,
which is heavier than iron, was formed in the supernova.
   National Aeronautics and Space Administration researchers had
detected radiation from cobalt-56 late last year, but Rester says
the GRAD project provided much more detail.
   Color-shift readings also indicate the supernova did not explode
symmetrically as an expanding sphere. Rather, it exploded with
lobes and fingers protruding in several directions, with
significant mixing of its core and mantle.
   Rester said a UCLA scientist is examining the data to try to
further reconstruct the explosion, which occurred 170,000 years
ago, though the light reached the earth only last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880504-0096 </DOCNO>
