<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq, 1st Ld -Writethru, a0595,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Claims Iraqi Planes Downed In Raids On Cities</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs to UPDATE with Iraq confirming air raids.
Picks up 9th graf pvs ``Iran has reported...'' Edits thereafter to
trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqi warplanes bombed an Iranian oil
refinery and a petrochemical complex today and Iran claimed its
anti-aircraft gunners shot down three of the attacking jets.
   The Iraqi raids were the first major attacks on Iranian cities
since the two Persian Gulf war foes halted the latest round of
their so-called ``war of the cities'' April 21. They pounded each
other's cities with more than 300 missiles Feb. 29-April 21.
   The official Iraqi News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, quoted a
military communique as saying one formation of fighter-bombers
attacked and set fire to the refinery in the southwestern city of
Shiraz. The refinery, one of five in Iran, has a capacity of 48,000
barrels a day.
   Other warplanes hit a petrochemical plant in the area, the Iraqi
report said.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, also monitored in
Cyprus, said several people were killed in the raids on Shiraz.
   Two French-built Mirage F-1s were downed in the second raid,
IRNA said.
   The agency reported that one pilot bailed out and was captured.
There was no word on the fate of the other pilot.
   Tehran Radio said a third Iraqi jet was shot down, but did not
say where or give any other details.
   IRNA said an industrial plant in the oil-producing Gachsaran
region, 100 miles west of Shiraz, also was bombed in another Iraqi
raid.
   There was no mention of that raid in the Iraqi communique, which
declared that Iraq would inflict ``further painful blows on the
Iranian regime'' until it complies with the U.N. Security Council
cease-fire resolution passed last July 20.
   Iraq has said it will abide by the resolution if Iran does.
Tehran has said it will not comply until Iraq is branded the
aggressor.
   The Iraqi air force attacks Iran's refineries and other oil
installations to throttle the Iranian economy and force and end to
the 7{-year-old war.
   Oil industry sources have reported that Iran's refining capacity
has been cut by about one-third in recent weeks because of the
bombing. This has forced Iran to import unprecedented amounts of
refined products such as kerosene and jet fuel, the sources said.
They spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Iran has reported Iraqi warplanes repeatedly have flown over its
western cities in the last few days. IRNA said the intruding jets
were driven off by anti-aircraft fire.
   Both countries have claimed their border towns have come under
artillery fire recently.
   Both have reported continued artillery battles and skirmishes
along the 730-mile frontline in the past two weeks. But there has
been no major ground action since April 18, when Iraq recaptured
the southern Faw peninsula. Iran seized control of the peninsula in
February 1986.
   Iran has reported sending tens of thousands of men to the front
in a renewed mobilization following naval clashes with the United
States in the Persian Gulf. The U.S. Navy said it sank or disabled
six Iranian vessels in the April 18 fighting.
</TEXT>
