<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0909EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WarholAuction     05-04 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Warhol Auction,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warhol Auction Brings in $25 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was an auction that publicity-savvy Andy
Warhol would have loved, with enthusiastic buyers shelling out more
than $25 million for the late pop artist's possessions, from
plastic watches to paintings.
   By the time the final gavel fell Tuesday on Sotheby's 10-day
Warhol sale, an estimated 60,000 people had passed through the
auction house's galleries to view his private collection.
   ``We're thrilled,'' said Diana D. Brooks, president of Sotheby's
North America. ``I think that from start to finish, it was one of
the great sales in Sotheby's history.''
   The sale brought in $25.3 million, well above Sotheby's official
pre-auction estimates of $9 million to $13 million but close to
predictions by independent experts.
   ``Our feeling when we figured the estimates was that we wouldn't
add any `Warhol factor,''' said Ms. Brooks. ``I think what we're
seeing today is an indication not only of the `Warhol factor' but
of a very strong art market.''
   But a strong art market does not explain some of the sales, such
as the $2,640 paid for three commercially manufactured, plastic
watches bearing the likenesses of cartoon characters Fred
Flintstone, Judy Jetson and Gumby.
   ``You cannot connect that with the normal art market,'' said
Jeffrey Deitch, a vice president for the Citibank Private Banking
Group who buys art for the bank's clients. ``Warhol had lots of
enthusiastic admirers, and people want something that he chose. It
means something to people.''
   For whatever reason, buyers were willing to pay dearly for just
about anything owned by Warhol, the artist who elevated the
ordinary, like Campbell's soup cans, to art. Warhol died in
February 1987.
   Sales figures included $23,000 for a pair of cookie jars;
$55,000 for a set of Salvador Dali ear clips; and $605,000 for a
Roy Lichtenstein painting, ``Sailboats.''
   Proceeds from the auction go to the Andy Warhol Foundation for
the Visual Arts, which was established by the artist to support
cultural institutions.
   The highest-priced item at the sale was an untitled 1967
painting by Cy Twombley that fetched $990,000, a record for a work
by that artist. It was one of many records set during the sale.
   The enthusiastic bidding, though, was a turn-off to some
professional art dealers.
   ``It's a joke to attempt to buy here,'' complained Geert von der
Veen of Toronto. ``I don't think there are many dealers who could
touch those prices _ or want to. You'd look crazy.''
   Still, he would not say private collectors who claimed their
piece of the Warhol legacy had made a mistake.
   ``Certainly in the past 30 years that I've been in the business,
it really hasn't mattered if someone overpaid _ even grossly
overpaid'' for a work of art, van der Veen said. ``Time proved them
right eventually.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880504-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0917EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater 2ndLd-Writethru a0502 05-04 0762</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0502,0777</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Speed-The-Plow,' A New Play By David Mamet, Opens On Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds four grafs at end, further reviews; No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Speed-The-Plow'' has more on its mind than
Madonna.
   In fact, the Broadway debut of one of rock's biggest stars is
not the reason to see playwright David Mamet's brash, biting and
lewdly funny look at the film industry.
   In ``Speed-The-Plow,'' Mamet examines the art of the movie deal,
which is not to be confused with the art of making a good movie.
The play, in three short acts, skewers Hollywood producers with the
same savage humor that Mamet used to dissect Chicago real estate
salesmen in his Pulitzer Prize-winning ``Glengarry Glen Ross.''
   ``Speed-The-Plow,'' which opened Tuesday at Broadway's Royale
Theater, is a small, narrowly focused evening, but it's absolutely
on target, ambushing the egomaniacs who decide what reaches the
silver screen.
   Mamet has created two wonderful, would-be Hollywood magnates,
the kind of guys who wear expensive, baggy Italian suits _ no ties
_ and talk exclusively in movie industry lingo, dropping such lines
as ``greenlighting a project'' or doing ``a courtesy read'' of a
new book for the head of the studio. They have no ready cash and no
apparent class.
   These two producers are also good friends, and Mamet has some
telling comments about what success does to relationships _ both
male and female. Bobby (Joe Mantegna) is the new head of production
at a major studio and Charlie (Ron Silver) has just wangled the
services of a major star for a prison film. They need each other.
   All systems are go on the prison flick until a temporary
secretary, played by Madonna, suggests a film based on a novel
about the historical effects of nuclear radiation. It's that book
the studio chief wanted Bobby to read. And she's ready to be cut in
on the deal.
   Mantegna and Silver are superb. Mantegna is all oily charm. He's
ready to shake hands and stab backs at the same time. Silver
matches Mantegna's obnoxiousness and has a third-act temper tantrum
that will probably bring him a Tony nomination.
   The play has received an extraordinary amount of attention
because of Madonna, but she is a minor and not very successful part
of ``Speed-The-Plow.'' Her acting is tentative, devoid of any
personality. She has none of the oomph needed to hold her own with
the more flamboyant Mantegna and Silver.
   Director Gregory Mosher, long associated with Mamet's plays,
gives the play a hard-edged, staccato style. The actors machine-gun
their lines to each other.
   The setting, designed by Michael Merritt, is odd. Long, flowing
curtains frame Bobby's new office, a collection of furniture
covered with dropcloths.
   ``Speed-The-Plow'' wins this season's award for most obscure
title. It's a variation on a line in ``The Conspiracy of Charles,
Duke of Byron'' by Elizabethan playwright George Chapman. The
expression means ``do your work well'' or at least ``get on with
it.'' Mamet and two members of his cast have followed that advice.
   In other reviews:
   Frank Rich of The New York Times called the play ``riveting
theater'' and ``a worthwhile, funny evening.'' Mamet, Rich writes,
has ``developed into a more inventive storyteller than most people
working in the movies.''
   He also praised the ``intelligent, scrupulously disciplined
comic acting'' of Madonna, whom he said ``needs only more
confidence to relax a bit and fully command her speaking voice.''
   But Howard Kissel, drama critic for the Daily News, says
Madonna's performance falls short. ``Being vacant on the stage
requires more effort than it does in real life,'' he writes.
   ``Elegantly designed, impeccably directed, `Speed-the-Plow' is
Mamet's clearest, wittiest play,'' he concluded. ``I bet it would
be even funnier with an actress.'
   Clive Barnes' New York Post review said the play ``is crammed
with wonderful, dazzling, brilliant lines'' and it calls the cast
of three ``two-thirds perfect and one-third hopeful.''
   ``Madonna tries hard in a Judy Holliday role, but sounds more as
if she were auditioning than acting, and the audition is scarcely
for the big time,'' said Barnes.
   ``Madonna is OK, sort of, but Mamet's `Speed-the-Plow'...with
the irresistible Joe Mantegna and a riveting breakthrough
performance by Ron Silver, is a vicious, scabrous, hilarious,
mean-spirited joy of a play,'' Linda Winer said in Newsday.
   Madonna's performance was ``a gutsy try,'' but in a scene that
she must carry the play comes ``to a screeching stop while we wait
for her to finish and for the professional actors to regain
control,'' said Winer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
