<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JuarezProtest     05-04 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Juarez Protest,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Boycott High School in Protest Over Library Books</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students here boycotted school for a day and it
was their parents' idea _ they're protesting a lack of library
books and sports equipment.
   ``We are breaking our necks trying to get the kids to school,''
said principal Richard P. Schnettler. ``Having adults tell them not
to go to school, this has an effect on them.''
   The Juarez School Council organized the demonstration to demand
more money for library books _ especially those for computer
science and those in the Spanish language _ and physical education
equipment.
   About 1,500 of the 1,763 students at the predominately Hispanic
Benito Juarez High School stayed away from classes Tuesday.
   A group of some 200 parents who organized the boycott stood
outside the school to turn away all students except seniors, who
need to fulfill class requirements for graduation.
   After spending a couple of hours at the school, the group
marched two miles to Board of Education headquarters and met with
Deputy Superintendent Joseph Lee, who told them of the lack of
funds.
   ``They're getting their fair share,'' said board spokesman Bob
Saigh. ``In fact, they might be getting more than their fair
share.''
   Protest organizers later met with Schnettler, but failed to
resolve anything, the principal said.
   ``The library is first-class,'' he said. ``None of us is denying
the need for more books.''
   At a meeting of 350 parents and school officials Monday night,
Alfredo Garcia, the leader of the parent's group, said the boycott
was necessary as ``a show of power.''
   After the meeting, Garcia encouraged students to return to
classes today, but to prepare for the possibility of another
boycott next week.
</TEXT>
