<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Redford,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Actor-Reford Goes To Soviet Union For Showings of His Films</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor-director Robert Redford is leaving
for the Soviet Union on Saturday for a 10-day trip to discuss two
of his favorite subjects, films and the environment.
   Redford was invited last December by Elem Klimov, president of
the Soviet Filmmakers Union. Seven of his films will be shown in
Leningrad, Moscow and Tbilisi.
   While in Moscow, the actor will co-host discussions on global
environment with the Soviet Academy of Sciences, the University
Corporation for Atmospheric Research, Boulder, Colo., and the
Natural Resources Defense Council, N.Y.
   The two-day meeting was initiated by the Institute for Resource
Management, an organization created by Redford in 1981 that
attempts to find resolutions to environmental conflicts and
controversies.
   Soviet and American scientists and environmental-policy experts
will discuss cooperation on the global warming some scientists
believe is taking place due to ozone depletion in the upper
atmosphere and the buildup of carbon dioxide.
   ``I am honored to be invited at a critical crossroads in the
relationship between our countries,'' said Redford.
   Another workshop in Moscow will focus on Redford's Sundance
Institute for Film and Television in Utah, and on plans for an
exchange between young American and Soviet filmmakers.
   His films to be shown are ``All the President's Men,'' ``The
Sting,'' ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid,'' ``The Natural,''
``Jeremiah Johnson,'' ``The Electric Horseman'' and his latest
directorial effort ``The Milagro Beanfield War.''
   The tour is supported by the U.S. Information Agency's
U.S.-Soviet Exchange Initiative and the American Embassy in Moscow.
</TEXT>
