<DOCNO> AP880504-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0931EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru a0588 05-04 0856</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0588,0879</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Role Reported Planned Between Strikers and Officials
^Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 4th, ``There will...' to UPDATE with
bishops' statement. Pick up 5th pvs, `In Warsaw...'
^LaserPhoto NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist authorities agreed to let
Catholic intellectuals mediate in two major strikes, a Solidarity
activist said today after Lech Walesa warned of ``a bloody
revolution'' if workers don't get a say in reform.
   At the huge Lenin shipyard where Solidarity was born in 1980,
workers in the third day of an occupation strike backed down from a
demand that the outlawed independent labor federation be legalized
nationwide.
   Walesa, a Solidarity founder, said strike leaders decided to
limit the demand to Solidarity's shipyard branch because they felt
they had a greater chance of success.
   ``There will be many different strikes around the country, even
if they crush the shipyard, we will do it,'' Walesa told strikers
after returning to the shipyard today. ``The only reason the entire
country is not on strike is that it is too early.''
   Poland's Roman Catholic bishops declared in a statement today
that Polish society ``has the right to seek to be in charge of its
own fate.'' The statement urged authorities to find common
solutions for Poland by meeting with representative groups.
   It was the first official statement by the church on Poland's
worst wave of labor unrest since 1981.
   In Warsaw, Solidarity activist Henryk Wujec said authorities had
agreed to permit a mediation role for five independent
intellectuals linked with the Catholic Church, which claims 94
percent of Poles as followers.
   He said the five had split into two groups, one leaving for the
Lenin steelworks in the Krakow suburb of Nowa Huta, the other for
the 12,000-worker shipyard in this Baltic port.
   The five included Andrzej Stelmachowski, chairman of the Warsaw
Catholic Intellectuals Club. His wife said he left today at the
request of church authorities for the Nowa Huta steelworks, now in
the ninth day of a strike.
   At church headquarters in Warsaw, a secretary said a meeting was
in progress and no one could comment, but there would be an
announcement later.
   The mood was subdued in Gdansk this morning. There was no heavy
police presence as had been the case Tuesday night.
   About 3,000 workers spent the night in the yard and during the
day their numbers rose to 7,000, said strike committee chairman
Alojzy Szablewski.
   Like the shipyard workers, the 15,000 striking steelworkers in
Nowa Huta are demanding higher wages, an independent union,
reinstatement of fired union activists and release of political
prisoners.
   Chief government spokesman Jerzy Urban told a Warsaw news
conference Tuesday that legalizing Solidarity ``is not a question
that can be an object of negotiations ... It is not negotiable.''
Communist authorities crushed the movement with martial law in
December 1981.
   At the shipyard Tuesday, Walesa told strikers, ``If we don't
achieve a real reform this time, then we will have a bloody
revolution.''
   However, the 44-year-old electrician also said Zdzislaw
Sadowski, the deputy prime minister and architect of the
government's reform program, ``is trying to do something. Let him
talk to us and we can do it together.''
   The government raised prices 42 percent this year as part of an
attempt to overhaul the ailing economy.
   The strikes began April 25 with an 11-hour stoppage by transit
workers in the northwestern city of Bydgoszcz. The strikers won a
60 percent raise.
   The next day, a strike began at Nowa Huta _ the country's
largest steel plant. Workers at the defense-oriented foundry in the
southeastern city of Stalowa Wola won promises of higher pay in a
two-day strike that ended Saturday.
   Walesa today denied a report, which originated with local
Solidarity activist Joanna Wojciechowicz, that 5,000 Gdansk
ship-repair and port workers were idle Tuesday in sympathy with the
Lenin shipyard strike.
   On Tuesday, police in Warsaw dispersed protesters who marched in
support of the strikers while in Krakow, Poznan and Gdansk,
university students staged sympathy strikes, opposition spokesmen
in the four cities said.
   Government and opposition spokesmen confirmed a brief work
stoppage Tuesday at a railroad car plant in Wroclaw, and opposition
spokesmen said about 1,000 miners occupied the Rudna copper mine in
western Poland for eight hours.
   Police have rounded up about a dozen opposition figures and
apparently cut off the telephones of others. Sources said others
went into hiding.
   Walesa told reporters that Bogdan Lis of Gdansk and eight other
regional Solidarity leaders were arrested.
   Urban called the detentions ``preventive.''
   He also reiterated the government position that bowing to
strikers' demands for pay raises of up to 60 percent would upset
economic reform and said strike leaders are ``professional
politicians'' working for Western powers.
   Walesa, who won the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize, led the August 1980
strike in Gdansk that toppled a government and co-signed the
accords that made Solidarity the only free labor movement ever
officially recognized in the Soviet bloc.
   The current labor trouble is the worst in Poland since the
crackdown on Solidarity, led by the country's current leader, Gen.
Wojciech Jaruzelski.
</TEXT>
