<2ND_LINE>PM-State Primary Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0573,0827</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Metzenbaum Nominated In Ohio; Bayh In Indiana; Jordan In North
Carolina</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, `A poll...' to include survey size, date and
error margin of Indiana poll; SUBS 17th graf, `Jordan said...' to
include same information on N.C. poll.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic primary voters nominated Sen. Howard Metzenbaum for a
third term in Ohio and picked Indiana Secretary of State Evan Bayh
and North Carolina Lt. Gov. Bob Jordan as candidates for governor
in states where Republicans now have the job.
   Metzenbaum, 70, swamped a political newcomer in Tuesday's
balloting and will face Cleveland Mayor George Voinovich, the
uncontested GOP nominee who promised ``a barn-burner'' of a fight.
The two have already raised more than $7 million between them.
   ``You mark my words,'' Voinovich, 51, told supporters. ``The
most focused-on race in the United States is going to be
Metzenbaum-Voinovich.''
   Metzenbaum said he was eager to run on his record as one of the
most liberal members of Congress. And in a reference to his
opponent and GOP presidential standard-bearer George Bush, he
added, ``As I've said before: when the votes are counted in
November, I'm confident that 1988 will be a very disappointing year
for Republican candidates named George.''
   Final, unofficial returns showed Metzenbaum had 1,067,138 votes
or 83 percent, and his lone opponent, Ralph Applegate, who runs a
Columbus lawn-care business, had 213,120 votes or 17 percent.
   Also in Ohio, former Cleveland Mayor Dennis Kucinich, who
preceded Voinovich in office and was blamed for much of the city's
fiscal crisis, failed in his latest comeback bid. He lost to Rep.
Mary Rose Oakar by a 3-1 margin in a Democratic congressional
primary.
   Bayh, son of former Sen. Birch Bayh and owner of one of
Indiana's most respected political names, swamped his only rival
and will face Republican Lt. Gov. John M. Mutz, who had no primary
opposition.
   With 93 percent of precincts reporting, Bayh had 450,110 votes
or 83 percent and former Kokomo Mayor Stephen J. Daily had 61,531
votes or 11 percent. Senate Minority Leader Frank L. O'Bannon, who
had 31,580 votes or 6 percent, was put on the ballot by the Bayh
campaign in case Bayh had been disqualified because of a residency
challenge.
   With Gov. Robert Orr barred by state law from seeking a third
term, Democrats see a golden opportunity to end 20 years of GOP
rule, and Bayh said as he claimed victory that his campaign would
be ``as important as any in the history of Indiana.''
   A poll published Sunday by the Fort Wayne Journal-Gazette showed
Bayh with a 45 percent to 32 percent lead over Mutz. The phone poll
of 1,017 registered voters from April 23-28 had an error margin of
3.1 percentage points.
   Mutz wasted no time in renewing his claim that Bayh, at 32 and
after less than two years in statewide office, is too young and
inexperienced to be governor.
   ``This is a comparison of abilities to lead a very large
institution, that being the state of Indiana,'' said Mutz, who has
spent 20 years in state government.
   Introducing his family at a victory gathering, Mutz, 52, looked
at his son, Mark, and said: ``Like another young attorney who's
been practicing law in Indiana for less than two years, he's not
ready to be governor.''
   Indiana also has a Senate race this year, but neither Republican
Sen. Richard G. Lugar nor Democratic attorney Jack Wickes was
opposed for his party's nomination.
   In North Carolina, Jordan easily turned back four opponents for
a chance to face Gov. Jim Martin, who had no primary challengers in
his bid for a second term. Martin is only the state's second
Republican governor this century.
   With 97 percent of the vote in, Jordan had 395,904 votes or 80
percent. Next came Billy Martin, a service-station employee not
related to the governor, with 59,103 votes or 12 percent; then
Carroll W. Crawford of Mount Ulla, a former Ku Klux Klansman, with
21,692 votes or 4 percent; James T. LLoyd of Salisbury with 10,158
votes or 2 percent, and Bruce Friedman, an anti-nuclear activist
from Sylva, with 9,332 votes or 2 percent.
   Jordan said his battle against the governor would be ``a classic
race'' and claimed he was steadily narrowing Martin's lead. The
Greensboro News & Record reported that a recent survey showed
Jordan trailing Martin 47 percent to 39 percent with 14 percent
undecided. The phone poll April 23-26 of 834 voters had an error
margin of 3.5 percentage points.
   Merle Black, political science professor at the University of
North Carolina at Chapel Hill, said Jordan's challenge was ``to
present a positive agenda that will excite Democrats and
independents to vote for him.
   ``But he's also running as an underdog and he's got to give
people reasons why Jim Martin shouldn't be re-elected,'' Black said.
</TEXT>
