<HEAD>Lieutenant Governor Wins Right To Run Against Boss</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf to include survey size, date, error
margin.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Lt. Gov. Bob Jordan has won the
right to challenge his Republican boss, Gov. Jim Martin, easily
defeating four opponents in a primary election.
   ``It's the highest honor and the best opportunity the North
Carolina people have ever given me,'' Jordan said Tuesday in an
interview outside his hotel room after winning.
   Jordan said his general election battle against Martin would be
``a classic race'' and said he was steadily narrowing the
incumbent's lead.
   Jordan had 391,482 votes, or 80 percent, with 96 percent of
unofficial returns in. His closest opponent, Billy Martin, a
service-station employee not related to governor, received 58,150
votes, or 12 percent.
   As lieutenant governor, Jordan, 55, put forward policy
initiatives on economic development and dropout prevention,
including a controversial plan to withhold driver's licenses from
minors who quit school.
   He attacked Martin, 52, as a governor who had done little of
substance while taking credit for Democrats' accomplishments.
   Martin, who had no opposition for the GOP nomination, hopes to
become the first Republican governor in North Carolina to serve
consecutive terms. He was only the state's second GOP governor this
century.
   Martin, a former six-term congressman and Davidson College
chemistry professor, pointed to glowing economic statistics during
his term and questioned Jordan's leadership skills.
   Early in the campaign, newspaper polls showed Martin with leads
ranging from 14 to 30 percentage points. But the Greensboro News &
Record reported last week that a survey it commissioned showed
Jordan trailing by only 47 percent to 39 percent with 14 percent
undecided. The phone poll April 23-26 of 834 voters had an error
margin of 3.5 percentage points.
   Other Democratic candidates running Tuesday were Bruce Friedman,
an anti-nuclear activist from Sylva; Carroll W. Crawford of Mount
Ulla, a former Ku Klux Klansman; and James T. Lloyd of Salisbury.
</TEXT>
