<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Charles     05-04 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Charles,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prince Charles Objects To New Building Near His Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swayed by a complaint from Prince Charles, city
authorities said today they have withheld permission to build a
nine-story apartment house overlooking the Kensington Palace
residence of the heir to the British throne.
   The planning committee for the London boroughs of Kensington and
Chelsea said it deferred its decision after receiving a letter
``from a very eminent neighbor'' just before a Tuesday night
meeting.
   Regalian Property Ltd. wants to put up a building with 45
apartments worth between $4.6 million and $11.2 million each on
two-thirds of an acre near the palace.
   The letter to the council, written on Buckingham Palace
stationery, was signed by David Wright, the prince's deputy private
secretary, said a borough spokesman, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   ``The building seems to us to be an overdevelopment of the
site,'' the spokesman quoted the letter as saying.
   He said the committee would reconsider the application only
after the architect revised the plans.
   Charles' intervention came as no surprise. The prince has
outspokenly criticized modern architects, whom he has accused of
ruining London's skyline and ignoring the opinions of ordinary
people.
   Committee chairman Simon Orr-Ewing said the panel might have
withheld permission regardless of the prince's opinion, because the
new building was ``too tall'' and the architecture ``insensitive.''
   But the letter from the palace ``added some sway _ I certainly
can't deny that,'' he added.
</TEXT>
