<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Gulf     05-04 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Gulf,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Secretary Says Congressional Opposition Scuttled Coast
Guard Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci
acknowledged today the Reagan administration scuttled plans to send
Coast Guard ships to the Persian Gulf because of strong
congressional opposition.
   ``There were considerable objections on the part of the
(Capitol) Hill when we consulted the Hill and we decided it would
be best not to go ahead at this time,'' Carlucci said on CBS's
``This Morning'' program.
   The Pentagon had been considering taking up to six Coast Guard
boats off anti-drug patrols and sending them to the gulf. But the
idea was sharply criticized by Democrats and Republicans alike.
   Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee, said earlier this week that the plan ``was a non-starter
from the beginning and I'm glad Carlucci could understand that.
That idea was going nowhere.''
   Sen. John Warner, R-Va., said the decision came after Carlucci
listened ``carefully to those of us in Congress, including myself,
and the leadership who suggested that this would not be the right
time to take Coast Guard vessels from the United States.''
   The administration is using its naval fleet to protect 11
Kuwaiti-owned but U.S.-flagged tankers. The Navy announced this
week that it will respond to pleas for help from any neutral
merchant ships which are attacked in the war-torn gulf.
   Carlucci said the Coast Guard ships have an advantage over Navy
warships because ``they're shallow-draft ships and therefore less
vulnerable to mines and we looked at it from a military point of
view.''
   Two U.S. ships have struck mines in the gulf in the last year.
</TEXT>
