<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FlaGunControl     05-04 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fla Gun Control,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Committee Approves Proposing Seven-Day Cooling-Off Period to
Voters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After an appeal by Miami's mayor, the
state House Criminal Justice Committee has approved a measure that
would let voters decide whether to impose a seven-day waiting
period for all handgun purchases.
   Miami Mayor Xavier Suarez said the cooling-off period was needed
to help prevent a repeat of shootings like three in the Miami area
aimed at law enforcement officers, one of whom was killed.
   ``I've been on national TV the last few days constantly
answering questons on Miami being Dodge City,'' said Suarez. ``Our
circumstances right now in Miami are not good.''
   If the measure approved by the committee Tuesday is passed by
the full House and Senate, voters will decide in November whether
to add the waiting period to the Florida Constitution.
   Rep. Ron Silver, the measure's sponsor, said he proposed the
waiting period in part to counteract the damage to the state's
image from a 1987 law making it easier for people to carry
concealed weapons.
   ``As a result of the legislation we passed, ... we have
nationally achieved not the reputation I would like,'' said Silver.
``We have achieved bad press.''
   Silver said that if his legislation fails, he would back a
signature drive to place the constitutional amendment on the
November ballot. Signatures from several hundred thousand
registered voters across the state would be needed.
</TEXT>
