<1ST_LINE>r p PM-IndianaPrimary 2ndLd-Writethru a0616 05-04 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Indiana Primary, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0616,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bayh Wins Nomination For Governor; Dukakis Takes Primary</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Bayh, if ...' to correct that others were
younger, not older</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State Evan Bayh overcame
questions about his youth and inexperience, trouncing his opponent
for Indiana's Democratic nomination for governor.
   In the presidential primaries, Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis and Vice President George Bush rolled to easy victories.
   Bayh, the 32-year-old son of former Sen. Birch E. Bayh, piled up
nearly an 8-1 victory margin over former Kokomo Stephen J. Daily,
who had tried to draw attention to Bayh's lack of experience.
   ``He's shown in very dramatic and powerful fashion that the
voters _ at least the Democratic voters _ don't think that's an
issue,'' said Daily, 40.
   With 81 percent of precincts reporting, Bayh had 382,390 votes,
or 83 percent, to 51,146, or 11 percent for Daily. Bayh was beating
Daily in each of Indiana's 92 counties, including Howard County,
Daily's home.
   Bayh will face Lt. Gov. John M. Mutz, 52, who was unopposed for
the Republican nomination. Current GOP Gov. Robert D. Orr, who at
71 is the nation's oldest governor, was barred from seeking a third
straight term.
   Bayh, if elected, would be the state's youngest chief executive
this century. Only Jonathan Jennings, first governor of Indiana
after it became a state in 1816, and James B. Ray, the fourth, were
younger.
   A poll published Sunday by the Fort Wayne Journal-Gazette showed
Bayh with a 45 percent to 32 percent advantage over Mutz in a
preview of the fall race. The telephone poll of 1,017 registered
voters from April 23-28 had an error margin of 3.1 percentage
points.
   In the presidential primary, with 80 percent of the vote
counted, Dukakis had 350,074 votes, or 70 percent, to Jesse
Jackson's 110,507 or 22 percent, with the remainder divided among
candidates who have dropped out of the race.
   In the Republican race, with 80 percent of the precincts
reporting, Bush, who has clinched the GOP nomination, had 292,072
votes, or 84 percent. The remainder went to Kansas Sen. Bob Dole
and former television evangelist Pat Robertson.
   The state will send 79 delegates to the Democratic convention
and 51 to the Republican meeting.
   Bayh, in claiming victory, said, ``This campaign begins tonight
and it will be as important as any in the history of Indiana.''
   He challenged Mutz to a series of debates.
   Mutz said he liked the idea of debating his opponent, saying it
would compare ``abilities to lead a very large institution, that
being the state of Indiana.''
   Mutz, a 20-year veteran of government service, has tried to make
an issue of Bayh's youth and his relative lack of experience after
only two years in statewide office.
   Introducing his son, Mark, at a victory gathering, Mutz said,
``Like another young attorney who's been practicing law in Indiana
for less than two years, he's not ready to be governor.''
   Senate Minority Leader Frank L. O'Bannon, whose name was placed
on the Democratic ballot by Bayh's campaign in case Bayh lost a
challenge to his eligibiity, ran a distant third. The state Supreme
Court said last week that Bayh met the state's five-year residency
requirement, despite a sojourn in Washington.
   Two-term Republican Sen. Richard G. Lugar and Democrat Jack
Wickes, an Indianapolis attorney, were unopposed for Senate
nominations.
</TEXT>
