<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 1038EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Presser     05-04 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presser,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer Says Presser Too Ill To Prepare Defense</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teamsters President Jackie Presser's recurring
health problems have made him incapable of preparing his defense
against federal racketeering and embezzlement charges, according to
a letter filed in federal court.
   The letter, hand-delivered by Presser's lawyer, John R. Climaco,
to U.S. District Judge George W. White, sharply contradicts a
medical report by an endocrinologist hired by the government and
appears to be a prelude to a request to delay the trial, set to
open July 12.
   The doctor hired by federal prosecutors, Dr. John J. Canary,
said on Feb. 26 that Presser could work four hours a day.
   ``He (Presser) has been advised by his treating physicians and a
renowned endocrinologist that Dr. John Canary's findings border on
the preposterous,'' Climaco wrote. ``He is not currently capable of
assisting in his defense.''
   Climaco's letter Tuesday was his first public comment after
published reports that Presser had health problems that required
two recent hospital visits. Presser's medical history includes
open-heart surgery in 1985 and the removal of a malignant lung
tumor in January 1987.
   The letter and a motion filed in federal court Tuesday repeated
Climaco's demands for documents showing the ``symbiotic
relationship'' among Presser, co-defendant Anthony Hughes and the
FBI.
   ``It's time to remove the cloak of secrecy the government has
used to hide the facts of this case from the defendants and this
court,'' the motion states.
   The motion says the government's file is essential to show a
jury ``the importance, length and value of the informant
relationship which existed between cooperating citizens Presser,
Hughes and the FBI.''
   Federal prosecutors asked White on Monday to order Presser's
lawyers to provide them with Presser's latest medical records.
   Presser, Hughes and Harold Friedman are accused of participating
in a payroll-padding scheme at Cleveland Teamsters Local 507.
</TEXT>
