<2ND_LINE>PM-Liberace Trial,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Executor's Secretary Claims Estate Overbilled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former secretary to the executor of
Liberace's estate says she took copies of documents from his files
because she thought he was stealing from the estate and wanted to
expose him.
   Helaine Golding, in testimony Tuesday, admitted she told
acquaintances she was so angry with attorney Joel Strote that she
threatened to sell her story on Liberace to the National Enquirer.
   ``I said everyone should know what this man's done,'' she said.
``I said I will go to the Enquirer so everyone knows.''
   Five Liberace associates have filed a civil lawsuit seeking to
have Strote removed as executor and trustee, claiming Liberace was
too ill to know what he was doing when he signed documents Jan. 22,
1987.
   Ms. Golding claimed Strote billed the estate of the famous
pianist for time he actually spent with other clients, from
professional wrestlers to disc jockeys.
   She also alleged he got Liberace to sign blank documents in the
final weeks before his death from AIDS on Feb. 4, 1987. She said
Strote warned her ``Be careful of these, we can't get another
signature. Don't screw up.''
   Strote drew up Liberace's will and had it signed 13 days before
the entertainer's death. The new will made Strote executor of the
estate and head of two Liberace trusts.
   Ms. Golding said she went to work for Strote Jan. 5, 1987 and
handled most of the correspondence involving Liberace. She said she
sent copies of all correspondence to the entertainer until
mid-January when Strote told her to quit doing so, saying Liberace
could no longer read and understand the material being sent him.
   She said Strote was visibly upset when he returned from a visit
to Liberace's Malibu, Calif. condominium Jan. 15, 1987, the day he
met with the entertainer to draft a new will.
   ``Mr. Strote said `He looks awful. It's all over,''' Ms. Golding
testified.
   Ms. Golding said Strote presented her with copies of quitclaim
deeds that were blank except for Liberace's signature, and told her
to type in legal descriptions of Liberace real estate.
   ``I remember seeing how shaky it was,'' she said. ``It wasn't
the usual flourish.''
</TEXT>
