<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BogusPast     05-04 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bogus Past,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fugitive Who Used Dead Man's Identity for 12 Years Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man has been found out and
arrested 12 years after he skipped out on drug charges and began
living the life of a well-respected, law-abiding citizen under a
dead man's name.
   The new life he had built for himself was shattered Tuesday,
police said, when Florida law agents arrested the man who called
himself Danny Lee Wallen.
   Agents said Wallen, general manager of a seafood restaurant, was
really Paul Henry Haulk, who jumped bail on Hillsborough County
heroin charges in 1976.
   Miste Wallen, the arrested man's wife, was astounded when she
learned her husband and the father of their two preschool boys
really was named Haulk and that he had been arrested.
   ``We've been married for six years. I knew him for three years
before that'' in her hometown of Destin, she said. Mrs. Wallen said
she never had heard the name Haulk. ``He's a wonderful man,'' she
said.
   At an initial appearance before U.S. Magistrate Paul Game Jr. on
Tuesday, Haulk said he had been an addict but was clean under his
assumed name of Wallen.
   Haulk is charged with the federal crime of giving phony Social
Security numbers to get a driver's license and bank loans. Each
count carries a maximum penalty of five years in prison.
   Ruling he was a risk to flee prosecution, Game ordered Haulk
held without bail until a hearing Friday.
   According to court records, Haulk's first arrest came on a
charge of selling LSD in 1969 when he was 19. A series of drug
arrests followed.
   Twice in 1976, on May 13 and 26, Haulk was arrested in Tampa and
charged with heroin possession, according to court records. He was
released on $5,000 bail, but failed to show up and an arrest
warrant was issued.
   Haulk, who assumed the name of Wallen after that man had been
buried for more than a year, recently came to the attention of
Florida Department of Law Enforcement agents while they were
looking for a another fugitive.
   Agent Tom Beach found that the description on Wallen's driver's
license didn't match the man who was carrying it. In tracing
telephone calls, he found that one woman ``Wallen'' frequently
called in Tampa was Haulk's mother.
   Confronted at work Tuesday, Haulk ``did not deny who he was,''
Beach said.
</TEXT>
