<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 1058EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HatterasLighthouse     05-04 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hatteras Lighthouse,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Recommends Relocating Famed Lighthouse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The famed Cape Hatteras lighthouse in North
Carolina could be moved about 500 feet inland to save it from an
eroding seashore, a committee of experts decided in a National
Research Council report.
   The report said that errosion has placed the 208-foot-tall
landmark, which has flashed its warning to mariners for more than
100 years, in danger of being damaged or destroyed by a severe
hurricane.
   Errosion has whittled the beach to within 160 feet of the tower,
according to the report, which was made available this week.
   Moving the lighthouse would be a more practical way of saving it
than trying to protect the site from erosion by the sea, the study
said. Other methods of protecting the lighthouse, such as building
a seawall around it, also were examined.
   The landmark structure is the tallest brick lighthouse in the
United States and weighs about 2,800 tons. The lighthouse was built
in 1870 on a point of the North Carolina barrier islands to warn
sailors of the Diamond Shoals area just outside the islands.
   The National Park Service asked for the study. The National
Research Council is the operating agency of the National Academies
of Sciences and Engineering. The study does not comment on the
advisability of saving the lighthouse, but addresses only the
technical ways of doing so.
</TEXT>
