<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Corbin-Mofford     05-04 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Corbin-Mofford,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney General To Withdraw From Financial-Disclosure
Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state attorney general says that to
avoid the appearance of a conflict he will turn over his
investigation of Gov. Rose Mofford's financial disclosures to a
county attorney's office.
   Former Gov. Evan Mecham criticized Attorney General Bob Corbin
for the Tuesday decision, saying Corbin should have the ``guts'' to
do his duty. Corbin's office is currently prosecuting Mecham for
campaign reporting violations.
   Corbin said Tuesday he decided to withdraw from the
investigation of whether Mrs. Mofford had violated financial
disclosure statutes because he is next in line to become governor.
   ``If I were to bring charges, I would be accused of doing it to
become governor,'' he said. But he said the investigation would be
called ``a whitewash'' if it cleared Mofford.
   Mrs. Mofford succeeded Mecham because she was secretary of
state; her successor as secretary of state cannot become governor
because he was appointed, not elected.
   ``There is no legal conflict,'' Corbin said, ``but there is an
appearance. I decided it would be better if we had somebody else
take a look at it.''
   Mrs. Mofford has acknowledged that she erred in not reporting a
series of loans, land holdings or other deals on her
financial-disclosure statements dating back to 1978. She filed
amended reports last week and made public 150 pages of legal
documents.
   Her news aide, Vada Manager, said Mrs. Mofford feels she will be
exonerated and has no problem with an independent counsel
conducting the investigation.
   Corbin said Tuesday night that he had asked Pima County Attorney
Stephen Neely to conduct the probe. Corbin said Neely would have
the option of bringing in another county attorney if necessary to
assist in the investigation.
   In the past, Corbin has called on Neely, or other county
attorneys, to handle cases when the attorney general's office has
had a conflict.
   Mecham, who is being prosecuted by Corbin for failing to
disclose a $350,000 campaign loan, was critical of the attorney
general for withdrawing from the Mofford probe.
   ``Tell him to have the guts to stand up and do his duty,'' said
Mecham, whose criminal trial begins May 19. ``Don't take a powder.
Don't run out of it. Conflict of interest? When did conflict of
interest have anything to do with him? Don't hide behind a conflict
of interest.''
   Corbin had a conflict of interest when he investigated Mecham,
but ``that didn't dissuade him,'' the former governor said.
</TEXT>
