<HEAD>Iran Says Saudi Arabian Spy Arrested In Tehran</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with Iran saying Saudi Arabian spy
arrested. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said today it arrested a Saudi
Arabian spy in Tehran after he entered the country illegally
carrying $4.5 million.
   Saudi Arabia severed relations with Iran last week. The expelled
Iranian diplomats arrived home today and accused the Saudis of
beating them and of taking documents from their offices _ claims
denied by Saudi Arabia.
   There was no immediate Saudi comment on the Iranian report that
a spy had been arrested.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in
Nicosia, said security officials ``arrested an agent of the Riyadh
regime who had entered the country illegally with 300 million rials
($4.5 million).''
   It quoted an unidentified Information Ministry official as
saying the man, whose name was not disclosed, was planning to
``spread Wahhabi faith and the American brand of Islam.''
   The Saudi ruling family and most other Saudis are Wahhabis, a
conservative Sunni Moslem sect. Saudi Arabia, like the other
Persian Gulf Arab states, is run by Sunnis, while Iran's Islamic
government and most Iranians are Shiite Moslems.
   IRNA did not say when the man was arrested. However, it charged
intelligence reports had confirmed links between Wahhabi groups
inside Iran and Saudi Arabia and U.S. agents.
   It said the man arrested ``will be dealt with as a spy.''
Convicted spies may be sentenced to death under Islamic law.
   IRNA quoted Iranian charge d'affaires Mohammed Hussein Tarani as
saying Saudi security forces raided Iran's embassy in Riyadh and
the Iranian consulate in Jiddah on Tuesday and beat Iranian
staffers.
   The agency reported Tarani said the Saudis took many important
documents and forced the Iranians from their homes. He made the
accusations upon arriving at Tehran airport today, IRNA said.
   Tuesday was the deadline set by Saudi Arabia for Iranian
diplomatic personnel to leave the kingdom.
   Diplomatic sources in Riyadh said the Iranian embassy and
consulate were vacant by dusk Tuesday, with only a few Saudi
policemen patrolling outside each building. They said they believed
the Iranian personnel had left peacefully and there had been no
violence.
   The official Saudi Press Agency today quoted an unidentified
government official as calling the Iranian accusations ``completely
false and totally baseless.
   ``All personnel of the Iranian consulate and embassy, taking
along all their equipment, left in a calm, peaceful manner without
any harm befalling them,'' the official was quoted as saying.
   The official noted the Saudis did not retaliate in August when
an Iranian mob attacked the Saudi Embassy in Tehran following riots
in the holy city of Mecca, ransacking the building and killing a
Saudi diplomat.
   More than 400 pilgrims, most of them Iranians, were killed in
the July 31 riots, which followed Iranian political demonstrations
during the annual pilgrimage. The riots were the main reason cited
by Saudi Arabia for breaking diplomatic ties with Tehran.
   Iran has called for the overthrow of the Saudi rulers and
demanded they be stripped of control of Moslem shrines at Mecca and
Medina. Iran also accuses the Saudis of backing Iraq in the Persian
Gulf war.
</TEXT>
