<HEAD>Court Rules Port Elizabeth Beaches Must Be Open To All Races</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court in Port Elizabeth
ruled today that the city's segregated beaches must be open to
people of all races.
   The Supreme Court said a 1966 city council resolution
proclaiming the beaches segregated was invalid.
   Upon hearing of the ruling, some blacks immediately went to
previously ``whites only'' beaches to celebrate.
   City councilor Graham Richards and a member of Parliament, Mia
Loonat, made the application to have the beaches opened to all
races.
   The measure was opposed by Constitutional Development Minister
Chris Heunis and the administrator of Cape Province, Gene Louw.
   Richards called the decision ``a small victory for those of us
fighting what sometimes seems to be a losing battle against the
continuous inroads made by the government against basic human
rights.''
   Most beaches in the larger coastal cities of Durban and Cape
Town are open to all races. However, many beaches in smaller
communities remain segregated.
