<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Jackson 3rdLd-Writethru a0620 05-04 0803</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0620,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says He's Still In, Despite New Losses</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 10 grafs on Jackson news conference. Picks up 4th
graf pvs, bgng: `The party</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said today he believes he still
can capture the Democratic presidential nomination despite
resounding losses to Michael Dukakis in Ohio and Indiana. Jackson
won the race for the District of Columbia's much smaller delegate
package.
   Jackson told reporters he was concerned about fairness in the
allocation of delegates who will choose the nominee, but did not
say specifically how he might challenge the process.
   ``I can only appeal very openly for fairness,'' he said at a
Washington news conference.
   ``We're within striking distance,'' Jackson said earlier on
CBS-TV. ``It's not over really till it's over. What's next is West
Virginia and Nebraska, Oregon, New Mexico, California, New Jersey.
... We look forward to these remaining contests and we are not only
setting the pace for the campaign but setting the agenda as well.''
   Jackson met early today with about 50 or 60 members of the House
Democratic Caucus. The caucus chairman, Rep. Richard Gephardt of
Missouri, characterized it as a ``very warm and successful
meeting,'' and said ``everyone admires the grace and tone'' with
which Jackson has conducted his campaign.
   At his news conference, Jackson said Dukakis leads him by only 8
percentage points in the popular vote. He said that margin should
be reflected in the voting by super delegates _ those delegates
selected by virtue of holding important party positions or public
office.
   ``The super delegates will do America a super favor by not
interfering in the process. ... I simply want fairness,'' he said.
   Although the super delegate process was set up to enable those
delegates to commit to the candidate of their choosing, Jackson
said they should follow the popular vote, and he suggested they
should not take a bandwagon approach to the nomination before the
primary season is over.
   ``If super delegates wait until after June 8 they are in a
better position as judges to help bring balance'' rather than using
party machinery to parcel out delegates before the primaries end,
Jackson said.
   Jackson said on CBS that he has gained victories despite ``the
party machinery, the pundits and the press.''
   ``The party machinery is saying, in fact, go for Dukakis. The
pundits are saying go for Dukakis. In some sense, the super
delegates are moving in that direction and so against the party,
the pundits, the press. We press on against those odds,'' he said.
``We're not about to turn back.''
   Jackson slid further behind Dukakis in the overall delegate
count, losing in Ohio and Indiana by margins of greater than
2-to-1. In total delegates, Jackson trails Dukakis by more than 500.
   In the District of Columbia, which he also swept in his 1984
presidential race, Jackson picked up 80 percent of the vote to 18
percent for Dukakis.
   Jackson scheduled a strategy pow-wow this afternoon with top
advisers. Aides said the discussion would likely focus on mapping
out the campaign through the remainder of the primaries and on what
the Jackson forces will do at the convention.
   June 7 marks the end of the primary season, with votes in New
Jersey and California.
   Jackson's schedule for the rest of the month includes heavy
concentration on California, which offers the biggest delegate
prize in the nation, with a few days spent in New Jersey and Oregon
and brief forays to the small states remaining on the primary
calendar.
   Today, Jackson met with 13 Democratic members of Congress who
are part of a ``Go West '88'' group that is trying to focus the
presidential contest on Western issues.
   Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., an organizer of the group, said Jackson
discussed issues of concern to them, including trade, drugs,
immigration and energy.
   ``He made it clear trade expansion was something very important
on his agenda,'' said Wyden, who told reporters the sessiom was ``a
very positive kind of discussion.'' The group also hopes to meet
with Dukakis, he said.
   Despite a series of losses to Dukakis, Jackson showed no signs
of giving up his campaign and vowed to continue pressing the issues
he has fought for _ reversal of President Reagan's economic
policies and a war on drugs.
   He said his campaign did not start with the kickoff of the
primary season in Iowa, and will not end with the Democratic
convention this summer in Atlanta.
   ``It began in the back of a bus in Montgomery, Alabama, and now
it's three steps from the White House. We're on our way,'' he said,
as he recalled the civil rights battles a generation ago.
