<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Zaire-Opposition     05-04 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Zaire-Opposition,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Members of Opposition Banished to Northern Province</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KINSHASA, Zaire (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two government opponents have been
banished to northern Zaire, sources said today.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Tshisekedi Es Mulumba and Birindwa Birwashira were sent into exile
in Isiro after Tshisekedi distributed political tracts calling for
a boycott of legislative elections held April 10.
   The two are believed to be the only members of the Union for
Democracy and Social Progress who have continued to demand that
opposition parties be permitted in Zaire.
   President Mobutu Sese Seko's Popular Movement of the Revolution
is the country's only legal political party. All other parties were
outlawed in 1965.
   The Union for Democracy and Social Progress, the country's
largest opposition group, operates clandestinely. More than 200
supporters of group were imprisoned after an unauthorized meeting
in February, the sources said.
   Tshisekedi was arrested in February and was put on trial by a
state security court for attempting to hold an unauthorized
meeting, the sources said. The trial reportedly was suspended after
a medical certificate was presented saying the defendant suffered
from ``chronic delirium.''
</TEXT>
