<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--Drugs-BabyMonitor     05-04 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Drugs-Baby Monitor,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Learn Of Drug Deal On Baby Monitor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRASER, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple who heard what they thought was a
drug deal being described over an electronic monitor they use to
listen for sounds in their baby's room alerted police who later
arrested three men.
   Lt. Carl Smith said police came to the couple's home Friday
night after the parents heard a man's voice setting up a drug deal.
Later the same night, police arrested the men and seized 80 grams
of cocaine.
   The suspects were arrested after they gave their address and
telephone number while ordering a pizza over a cordless telephone,
which transmits radio signals to a base station. The signals can be
intercepted by other electronic equipment on the same frequency,
such as the baby monitor.
   Smith said the conversation heard on the baby monitor may be
used as evidence against the three, Smith said.
   The three suspects, charged with cocaine possession, were
arraigned Saturday. Conviction on the charges carries a maximum
penalty of 20 years in jail.
   Fraser is about 20 miles north of Detroit.
</TEXT>
