<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Jackson-Taxes 1stLd-Writethru a0485 05-04 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Taxes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0485,710</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 6 grafs new, with Watkins comments; edits 6th graf pvs,
bgng, `Jackson also,' to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aide to presidential candidate Jesse
Jackson said today he apparently made a mistake in saying that
Jackson made about $46,000 in consulting wages from entertainer
Bill Cosby last year.
   ``Obviously what I said wasn't quite right ... There obviously
needs to be some clarification. At this point I don't have the
clarification,'' said Frank Watkins, a long-time associate of
Jackson and political director of Jackson's Democratic campaign.
   Watkins said he spoke to Cosby and his wife after their
spokesman disputed Watkins' explanation on Tuesday of Jackson's
income tax returns.
   ``They just said they needed to talk to Jackson,'' about the
matter, Watkins said, adding he was trying to get the matter
cleared up, but had not been able to talk to the accountant who
prepared the taxes.
   Jackson on Tuesday released four years worth of federal income
tax returns. When asked about the Cosby consulting fee, he said he
would provide an accounting to reporters at a later time.
   Jackson and his wife had income of nearly $210,000 in 1987 and
paid about one-fourth of that in federal taxes, they reported in
their federal tax returns.
   The bulk of the income last year, $159,000, came from
Personalities International Inc., a corporation headed by
Jacqueline Jackson that provides management for clients and handles
most of Jackson's earnings from speaking fees and publications.
   Jackson is on contract to the corporation but is not a
shareholder, director or officer, according to his presidential
campaign. He reported the money in the category of wages and
salaries.
   Jackson also reported $46,535 in fees for business services, but
where that money came from quickly became a source of controversy.
Watkins said most of that was in consulting fees from Cosby. ``I
don't know the nature of the work,'' Watkins said on Tuesday.
   But David Brokaw, a Los Angeles public relations agent who works
for Cosby, quoted Cosby as saying, ``That's way off the mark.''
   Brokaw added, ``He did not provide Reverand Jackson with most of
the $46,535 for business services.''
   Asked how much Cosby did pay Jackson, Brokaw said, ``Mr. Cosby
says that's none of your business ... or check with IRS.''
   Cosby is a Jackson supporter and has made a television ad for
the campaign, as well as doing benefit performances.
   Jackson promised reporters Tuesday night he would provide more
details on his finances at a briefing later. His Democratic
presidential campaign released copies of his tax returns for 1984
through 1987.
   Together with dividends, interest and other income, the couple's
1987 joint total income was $209,358, before adjustments. They
reported $3,474 in interest and dividend income. Their tax for the
year was $53,019.
   Jackson, who is a minister, and his wife reported paying $2,145
in unspecified cash contributions during 1987.
   Like many American families, Jackson and his wife took advantage
of the working couple deduction until last year, when that
deduction was lost.
   For 1987, the returns did not distinguish between income
received by Jackson and by his wife, who is president and a
director of Personalities International Inc. Watkins said she also
was paid for speaking engagements.
   On their 1986 returns, $55,000 was reported as income received
by Mrs. Jackson.
   The Jacksons' income rose quickly after 1984, the year of his
first presidential campaign. They reported income that year of
$59,453, including more than $6,000 in interest income. Their
federal taxes that year were $12,103, according to the documents.
   A year later, 1985, their income jumped to $187,839. They paid
$55,809 in federal tax, taking advantage of income averaging.
   In 1986, they reported $186,043 in income, including $13,633 in
dividends from Inner City Broadcasting Co., which Jackson holds
stock in. The Jacksons paid $53,103 in taxes that year.
   The company, headed by New York businessman Percy Sutton, owns
the Apollo Theater in New York and radio stations, and is expanding
into cable television.
   Jackson reported no dividends last year from Inner City
Broadcasting Co. Watkins said Jackson continues to own the stock.
</TEXT>
