<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-JapanBeef     05-04 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Japan Beef,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dispute Going to International Referees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States, with the approval of Japan,
has asked an international trade panel to settle a dispute over
Japanese restrictions on imports of beef and oranges, U.S. Trade
Representative Clayton Yeutter said today.
   Japan, which had blocked a similar move last month, agreed to
the formation of a panel under GATT, the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade, Yeutter told a news conference.
   ``We expect that case to move forward expeditiously in both beef
and citrus,'' Yeutter said.
   A weeklong round of negotiations over increasing U.S. beef and
citrus exports to Japan ended in failure Tuesday night as Japanese
Agriculture Minister Takashi Sato and Yeutter broke off their talks.
   It was the second collapse in the negotiations since late March,
when a four-year agreement on Japanese beef and citrus import
quotas expired.
   Yeutter, who referred to ``Japan's obstructive beef and citrus
import practices,'' said he did not know how quickly the GATT panel
would move on the issue but had indicated to Japan that the United
States expected the panel to move expeditiously.
   ``We will not tolerate stalling of the GATT process by the
government of Japan,'' he said. ``We assurredly will not permit
this case to spill into the next administration. We're going to
resolve this dispute one way or another during this (the Reagan)
administration.''
</TEXT>
