<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 1230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mozambique     05-04 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mozambique,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa Reported Considering Training Mozambican Troops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa is considering
training and equipping Mozambican troops to defend the Cahora Bassa
hydroelectric project that serves both countries, a newspaper
reported Wednesday.
   The pro-government Citizen cited an unidentified spokesman for
South Africa's Department of Foreign Affairs as saying the plans
were under consideration and ``no decision has yet been taken.''
   If South Africa agrees to train Mozambican troops to protect the
Cahora Bassa project, it would mark a significant improvement in
relations between the two countries.
   The Cahora Bassa project is capable of providing cheap
electricity to both countries. However, guerrillas of the
Mozambique National Resistance regularly sabotage power pylons.
   Mozambique accuses South Africa of supporting the rebels in
violation of a 1984 mutual non-agression pact. South Africa denies
the charge and accuses Mozambique of allowing its territory to be
used by guerrillas of the African National Congress, who are
attempting to overthrow the South African government.
   The New York Times reported Tuesday that South Africa was
considering providing training and non-lethal aid to three
Mozambican battalions at an estimated cost of $14 million.
   However, Roland Darroll, a spokesman for the South African
Department of Foreign Affairs, said Wednesday that his country had
no plans to train Mozambican troops.
   He said that South Africa was considering some non-lethal
military aid such as vehicles, radios and uniforms, but that no
decision had been made.
   Mozambique has not officially commented on whether it is
interested in receiving South African military assistance. One
official said privately that Mozambique would not accept training
from South African forces.
   ``They (the South Africans) are always trying to occupy our
country one way or another,'' the Mozambican official said.
   Delegations from South Africa, Mozambique and Portugal are
scheduled to meet in Lisbon later this month for discussions on the
Cahora Bassa project. Portugal has been a major backer of the
project in Mozambique, its former colony.
   Mozambique's cooperation minister, Jacinto Veloso, met with
South African President P.W. Botha last week, and there has been
widespread speculation that Botha will soon meet with President
Joaquim Chissano of Mozambique.
</TEXT>
