<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Belgium-AIDS,0152</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Belgium AIDS Cases Up 68 Percent In One Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health officials Wednesday reported a
68 percent increase in AIDS cases in Belgium in the past year and
announced a new information campaign to combat the deadly disease.
   Belgian Secretary of Health Wivina Demeester said 138 cases of
AIDS were reported among Belgians at the end of March, up 68
percent from a year ago.
   Demeester announced that the new information campaign will start
next month.
   She also said that at the end of March, 3,166 people were
reported to be carriers of the AIDS virus in Belgium, up 11 percent
in three months.
   More than 25 percent of the carriers were heterosexuals,
Demeester said.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is caused by a
virus that damages the body's immune system, leaving victims
susceptible to infections and cancer.

</TEXT>
