<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Britain-Stonehenge     05-04 0121</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Britain-Stonehenge,0124</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More People Allowed to Watch Dawn At Stonehenge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The organization that oversees Stonehenge said
Wednesday it will allow 1,000 people, twice as many as last year,
to watch the summer solstice at the 4,000-year-old monument.
   English Heritage, which manages the archaeological site on
Salisbury Plain about 80 miles southwest of London, said the
decision reflects the good behavior of last year's crowd.
   Each June, modern-day sun worshippers celebrate the summer
solstice _ the longest day of the year _ with a ritual sunrise
ceremony at the prehistoric Stonehenge.
   They gather to celebrate this first day of summer, when the sun
reaches its greatest distance from the equator, at Stonehenge's
double circle of huge standing stones.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
