<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   05-04 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0681</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers
throughout the nation.
   April 28
   The Sun, Westerly R.I., on presidential hopeful Albert Gore's
withdrawal:
   An interesting aspect of Sen. Albert Gore Jr.'s remarks on
quitting the (Democratic presidential) nomination race was his
recital of a litany of former rivals.
   Saying they ``taught me a great deal,'' he praised four of them
by name _ and the two still running, as well.
   From Gary Hart, he said, he ``learned that ideas matter,'' from
Joseph Biden ``the importance of grace under pressure,'' from
Richard Gephardt ``that passion in the service of policy is
powerful indeed,'' from Bruce Babbitt the virtue of caring ``less
about what people thought than about being true to his principles.''
   Gov. Michael Dukakis taught him that ``competence is charisma in
the eyes of Americans hungry for leadership,'' and lastly Gore said
Jesse Jackson showed that ``we are a richer party and a better
nation when we break down barriers and fight for justice.''
   It was a handsome way to bow out after a hard decision.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 3
   St. Louis Post-Dispatch on the sinking of an Iranian gun boat by
U.S. planes with the personal approval of President Reagan:
   Is there such as thing as too much civilian control of the
military?
   That is a question that needs to be asked in the wake of the
Navy's recent engagement in the Persian Gulf. ...
   On one level, this is a remarkable display of the capabilities
of the U.S. military's worldwide communication systems. On another
level, it shows that civilian control of the military is clear-cut
and strong.
   But on reflection, this incident raises the disturbing specter
that American lives could be lost in combat because the White House
starts issuing tactical battle orders on the basis of a political
judgment about an on-going battle.
   The president has the duty to set the national strategy, and
civilian control of the military is an absolute.
   But no president has the wisdom and intelligence resources to
start second-guessing low-level field commanders engaged in combat.
To do so is to court disaster.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 1
   The St. Paul (Minn.) Pioneer Press Dispatch on Star Wars:
   Neither President Reagan nor the Pentagon can dismiss out of
hand the critical analysis of the Star Wars system done by the
congressional Office of Technology Assessment.
   The OTA, a non-partisan scientific group, said in a report yet
to be released formally, that the Strategic Defense Initiative
would suffer a ``catastrophic failure'' the first time _ and the
only time _ it would be needed.
   In short, Soviet nuclear missiles would get through United
States defenses.
   The reason for the failure, according to OTA, is that software
necessary to give computers the detailed instructions needed to
destroy thousands of missiles heading toward targets in the United
States cannot be produced in the foreseeable future.
   Congress should take the report seriously and demand answers to
the questions raised by OTA.
   And there seems good reason for a scaling back in the commitment
to a Star Wars system. There should be enough left in the SDI
funding to ensure that basic research can be conducted, but that it
can be accomplished with far less than $4 billion a year.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 30
   The Burlington (Vt.) Free Press on the omnibus trade bill:
   President Reagan is right; the trade bill ought not to become
law. ...
   Congress, too, must not allow debate over the omnibus bill to
delay ratification of the U.S.-Canada trade bill.
   The accord is the result of hard bargaining on both sides over a
period of 18 months. ...
   It is the spirit of the pact with Canada that should be captured
in the omnibus trade bill: cooperation through competition and a
win-win situation for both countries.
</TEXT>
