<TEXT>
   April 29
   The Tri-City Herald, Kennewick, Wash., on Attorney General Meese:
   Edwin Meese, who has done for the U.S. attorney general's office
what Spiro Agnew did for the vice presidency, can't tell a conflict
of interest from a wheelbarrow.
   His latest difficulty arises from his approval of a $50 million
real estate deal between the Justice Department and a property
owner. The Justice Department had intended to leave the building,
owned in part by Howard M. Bender.
   Meese's wife, Ursula, got a $40,000 a year job with the Multiple
Sclerosis Society, and the money for her salary came from the
tax-exempt Bender Foundation, Howard M. Bender, vice president.
   Immediately thereafter the lease was signed.
   Nothing wrong here, Meese says.
   Meese is finding it difficult to attract replacements to the
Justice Department for resignations he has faced since the reports
of the cascade of conflicts. ...
   Meanwhile, the cause of it all hangs on to his post, seemingly
insensitive to the hurt he is doing the president and the Justice
Department as he was to giving at least the appearance of mixing
public service with private gain.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 29
   Nashville (Tenn.) Banner on Social Security's ``notch baby''
provision:
   Until recently, it appeared that there was no middle ground on
the ``notch baby'' provision of the Social Security law.
   For years, people ... born during the 1917-1921 ``notch'' have
had it impressed on them that they were discriminated against by
the law that changed the formula of benefits for people who were
born after 1916. ...
   A report by the General Accounting Office (GAO) released in late
March gives a much clearer picture of the whole issue. ...
   Michelle M. Murphy of Congressional Quarterly ... reported that
although notch babies get smaller monthly benefits than people who
were born just before them, the GAO found that in most cases they
get more _ and never less _ than similar retirees who are younger.
...
   Several proposals are pending in Congress aimed at correcting
the ``notch'' problem through legislation, but they have one thing
in common. They are tremendously expensive. ...
   It is significant that neither Sen. Claude Pepper, D-Fla.,
longtime advocate for the elderly, nor the American Association of
Retired Persons has pressed for the notch legislation.
   We should heed the suggestion of AARP Chairman Kermit Phelps
that ``it is time to focus attention on more substantive issues
facing older Americans, such as long-term care and reduction of the
federal budget deficit.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   April 29
   The Record, Hackensack, N.J., on Joe Clark's call for vigilante
justice:
   Following a speech ... before the American Newspaper Publishers
Association in Honolulu, Joe Clark, the principal of Paterson,
N.J.'s Eastside High School told an impromptu news conference that
ghetto dwellers who feel besieged by crime should bypass the cops
and the courts and take matters into their own hands.
   Specifically, he advised, ``I think a few lynchings are in
order.''
   On some occasions the lynch mob will be right. The kid they'll
seize really will be a mugger, a dealer, or worse.
   But sometime, the mob will be wrong. ... But will anyone care
that some ghetto kid had been wronged?
   Clark is dangerous not only because he urges people to violence,
but because he teaches that the answer to crime is still more
lawlessness and misdirected anger.
   This man is a demagogue, as his call for ``a few lynchings''
demonstrates.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 2
   Lubbock (Texas) Avalanche-Journal on the war in the Persian Gulf:
   The broadened role of the United States forces in the Persian
Gulf signals a further change in policy in the volatile region
which sends a message to those who thought Washington was ready to
back away from further confrontation with Iran.
   In announcing that the U.S. Navy would now come to the rescue of
so-called neutral shipping under attack in the gulf, the Reagan
Administration has warned both foe and ally that American policy of
maintaining freedom of the seas is not something which can be
compromised.
   Our only regret and reservation about the U.S. role is that more
of our allies aren't more actively involved.
   Although Britain and France have moved to bolster their naval
forces in the area, the whole project should have been a
well-coordinated operation in which the Free World acted in concert.
   For the most part, this government and that of British Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher have demonstrated the willingness to
defend freedom wherever it may be threatened.
   It is far better to stop that threat far from one's shores than
have it eventually rear its head on one's doorstep.
</TEXT>
