<TEXT>
   May 1
   The Journal Times, Racine, Wis., on dial-a-porn:
   It appears the infamous 900-prefix telephone information
services aren't the problem state authorities claim they are.
   According to Wisconsin Bell, less than 1 percent of its
southeastern Wisconsin customers have taken advantage of the free
blocking service. ...
   The service would limit access to 900-prefix telephone numbers
which offer various services, primarily information, for a fee.
   Complaints have been registered with utilities and government
officials about abuse of two of those services.
   Specifically targeted are the so-called ``dial-a-porn'' services
offering pornographic telephone conversations, and the teen
``party-line'' services which put teen-agers throughout the country
in touch with each other. ...
   Wisconsin Bell got permission to offer a free service which
would block access to those services in an effort to answer
complaints. ...
   Wisconsin Bell officials report, however, that of 716,500
customers, only 2,908 have asked for the blocking service.
   One factor may be that the service not only blocks access to
dial-a-porn and teen party lines, but to all other 900-prefix
services as well.
   But we suspect the real explanation is that relatively few
Wisconsin Bell customers use 900-prefix services at all, and of
that number fewer still have problems with it.
</TEXT>
