<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brigitte Nielsen, a former wife of Sylvester
Stallone, is expecting a baby, and she and the father, pro
football's Mark Gastineau, are thrilled.
   But he's not telling when they'll become parents.
   ``You can just say ... that she's pregnant,'' said the New York
Jets' defensive lineman, checking into his team's preseason
minicamp Tuesday.
   The couple, who began dating in January, will marry as soon as
Gastineau's divorce from his wife, Lisa, becomes final, he said.
   ``This is the first time I've ever been in love,'' Gastineau,
31, said. He says his fiance is ``happier than she has ever been
about anything.''
   Gastineau and Nielsen met at a San Diego health club during
Super Bowl week. Nielsen, a statuesque blond who has appeared in
such adventure films as ``Red Sonia,'' was in Rome on Tuesday to
work on a new movie, ``Domino.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Culture Minister Melina Mercouri on
Wednesday announced a gala concert to help finance a new $20
million Acropolis museum.
   ``The Stars Shine For The Acropolis,'' will be held Aug. 3 at
the 2,100-year-old Herod Atticus amphitheater at the foot of the
Acropolis hill to raise money to build ``the best and most modern
museum in the world,'' she said at a news conference.
   The concert will feature dancers from the New York City Ballet,
the American Ballet Theater and the Paris Opera, accompanied by
London's Royal Philharmonic Orchestra. Mercouri said a packed
theater would bring in at least $290,000 for the museum.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cher says she didn't even see Eddie Murphy
backstage after the Academy Awards program, let alone give him a
tongue-lashing. And she is suing The National Enquirer for $15
million for reporting that she did.
   According to the U.S. District Court suit filed Tuesday, the
Enquirer reported that Cher, who received the best actress Oscar at
the April 11 ceremonies, told Murphy he had put a damper on the
evening by accusing the academy of discriminating against blacks.
   The lawsuit said the account was a ``complete falsehood.''
   The complaint charged that Don Monte, in a ``TV-Behind the
Scenes'' column, reported that Cher told Murphy the awards ceremony
was not the place to air grievances.
   The remarks were said to have been made after Murphy and Academy
President Robert Wise argued backstage, with Wise allegedly telling
Murphy he would not be invited to participate in any future Academy
Awards programs.
   Cher's lawsuit says the actress did not see Murphy backstage.
Murphy had presented the best picture award.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviets will get a chance to see some
Robert Redford films and discuss the cinema with him, while the
actor-director will get to talk about the environment during a
10-day trip to their nation.
   Seven of his films will be shown in Leningrad, Moscow and
Tbilisi _ ``All the President's Men,'' ``The Sting,'' ``Butch
Cassidy and the Sundance Kid,'' ``The Natural,'' ``Jeremiah
Johnson,'' ``The Electric Horseman'' and his latest directorial
effort, ``The Milagro Beanfield War.''
   A workshop in Moscow will focus on Redford's Sundance Institute
for Film and Television in Utah, and on plans for an exchange
between young American and Soviet filmmakers.
   While in Moscow, Redford also will discuss the environment with
the Soviet Academy of Sciences; the American groups University
Corporation for Atmospheric Research and the Natural Resources
Defense Council.
   The two-day meeting was initiated by the Institute for Resource
Management, an organization created by Redford in 1981.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican gubernatorial candidate John
Raese loves fast cars and boats, but he's no ``party animal,'' says
his wife.
   ``The press makes an issue about his cigarette boat and portrays
him as a party animal,'' Liz Raese said in an interview published
in Tuesday's Charleston Daily Mail.
   ``We've always had boats. The cigarette boat is used as much for
fishing as racing. We're like a lot of people _ we like to fish,''
she said.
   Raese is challenging Gov. Arch Moore for the GOP gubernatorial
nomination in Tuesday's primary. Two years ago, he won the state
GOP chairmanship, which he resigned earlier this year in a party
dispute, and their relationship remains bitter.
   ``They give John two minutes to speak at most of those Lincoln
Day events, then Governor Moore talks for 20 minutes,'' Mrs. Raese
said. ``He calls John immature and I sit there and watch John's
face get flushed. His temper builds and I keep whispering, `Relax,
honey, don't let him get to you.'''
   The 38-year-old Morgantown millionaire owns steel, coal,
limestone and media companies. But his wife said he is awkward and
shy.
   ``I have seen him grow tremendously in the 10 years we have been
married,'' said Mrs. Raese, 31. ``I like to mother him. I'll come
up behind him and put my arms around him and squeeze tightly. He
says he doesn't want to be mothered and then his face gets flushed.
   ``He's a man's man. There is no women's lib in our house. I lean
on him,'' she said.
   Mrs. Raese said her husband wants to ``give something back'' to
West Virginia.
   ``I say to him, `Why do you want this job? Our life was so good
before, so easy.' And he says, `Liz, how many suits can we buy? How
many planes can we fly? How many parties can we attend? There must
be something more to life than this.'''
</TEXT>
