<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 1250EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-AlohaPassenger     05-04 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Aloha Passenger,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Passenger Says Plane's Wall Buckled During Her Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STRATFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who was a passenger on an Aloha
Airlines jet shortly before a section of its fuselage tore away
over Hawaii said she saw the wall of the plane undulate during
takeoff.
   ``As the plane was going up into the air I was resting my arm on
the armrest and my arm started to slip towards the wall, so I took
it away and I saw that the wall was moving in and out, like swaying
in and out,'' Julie Kovach said Tuesday.
   Mrs. Kovach and her husband, Richard, had been honeymooning in
Hawaii and flew from the island of Kauai to Honolulu on Thursday.
   She said she didn't realize the significance until after she
heard that part of the jet's fuselage had blown away on a later
flight Thursday. A flight attendant was killed and 61 of 89
passengers were injured.
   ``At the time my wife Julie was sitting near the window, I was
sitting in the seat next to her and I had my head back and my eyes
closed relaxing, so I didn't even notice this was happening,''
Richard Kovach said in an interview with television station WFSB-TV.
   The couple said they learned about the accident after they
returned to Connecticut on Friday, but didn't realize they had been
on the same plane until they saw a picture and recognized the name
``Queen Liliuokalani'' on the airliner's nose.
   They said they had been sitting four rows up from the wing in a
section that later ripped away. Mrs. Kovach said she called Aloha
Airlines and the Federal Aviation Administration in Washington to
tell them of her observation.
   Federal safety officials have ordered the oldest models of
Boeing 737 jetliners with more than 55,000 landings, like the Aloha
airplane, not to fly higher than 23,000 feet while the accident is
under investigation.
   Above 24,000 feet the difference between higher cabin pressure
and lower atmospheric pressure could be sufficient to cause a
hazard in aircraft where there could be a structural weakness, FAA
officials have said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880504-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 1253EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Prisons-HairLength     05-04 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prisons-Hair Length,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court: State Can Cut Prisoners' Hair</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State prison administrators can cut an
inmate's hair, even if he objects for religious reasons, because
prison security outweighs an inmate's individual rights, a federal
appeals court says.
   A three-judge panel of the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
unanimously rejected the argument of inmate Mark Lee Pollock, from
Lucas County, that prison officials violated his constitutional
right to exercise his religion when they cut his long hair.
   Gail Finkbeiner, lawyer for Pollock, said Tuesday she had not
seen the ruling and declined to comment or to say whether Pollock
will appeal.
   Pollock's suit argued that his rights were violated because he
adheres to the religion of the Lakota American Indians, who believe
that hair is sacred and should not be cut.
   Pollock, 31, is serving a 17- to 45-year sentence for
convictions of burglary, escape and bad-check offenses. He has been
an inmate since October 1981 at the state's maximum-security
Southern Ohio Correctional Facility in Lucasville. His legal battle
with officials over haircuts has been ongoing since he got into the
prison system.
   Prison officials said they have the right to cut prisoners' hair
for a variety of security and identification reasons. They said
prisoners could hide contraband, including keys and pills, in long
hair, could cut it off after escaping to more easily avoid
detection and could provoke homosexual attacks from other inmates
attracted by the appearance of long hair.
   Prison officials also said long hair could hinder prison
employees in identifying inmates, which could hamper roll calls,
mail calls, issuing visitor passes and finding prisoners who break
rules. Longer hair could also clog prison sink and shower drains
and be more conducive to carrying lice and creating other
sanitation problems, state officials contended.
   U.S. District Judge Carl Rubin ruled in favor of the state, and
Pollock appealed. The appeals court panel upheld Rubin's decision
on Monday.
   Raymond Studer, an assistant Ohio attorney general representing
the state, said the appeals court's ruling indicated that the
courts are starting to defer to concerns of prison administrators
faced with complex security problems in crowded penitentiaries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
