<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 1259EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-FAA-Boeing-737s     05-04 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FAA-Boeing-737s,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Expands Inspections Following Hawaiian Accident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration today
widened its inspections of Boeing 737 jetliners for possible
cracking and corrosion in response to an accident last week in
which a large section of one of the jets tore free during flight.
   The FAA directive requires operators of older Boeing 737s _
those with more than 30,000 flights _ to be visually inspected and
to undergo sophisticated electronic inspections if cracks are found.
   FAA Administrator Allan McArtor said the agency's action stems
from a belief that ``an abundance of caution'' is needed in light
of the recent accident involving Aloha Airlines.
   Last Thursday a 20-foot section of an Aloha Airlines Boeing 737
stretching from just behind the cockpit to near the wing tore loose
as the jet was cruising at 24,000 feet. One flight attendant was
swept from the plane and to her death and 61 people were injured,
although the plane landed safely.
   The new inspection order covers 291 older Boeing 737s _ the
first ones made in the late 1960s and early 1970s _ in which a
``cold bonding'' process was used to splice together sections of
the plane's outer metal skin.
   McArtor said he could not immediately say how many planes
covered by the order were in operation in the United States.
   Last week the FAA ordered many of the older Boeing 737s to fly
no higher than 23,000 feet and said that those with 55,000 landings
should be visually inspected for corrosion or cracking.
   The order today expands the visual inspections to planes with at
least 30,000 landings and requires those with 50,000 landings to
undergo so-called ``eddy current'' inspections using high-frequency
electronic devices.
   McArtor said that despite the increased focus on the older
Boeing 737s the aircraft ``are just as safe as newer models and if
they were not they wouldn't be allowed to fly.''
   He said while the cause of the Aloha accident has yet to be
determined ``it is time for an abundance of caution. And it is out
of an abundance of caution that we take today's action.''
   McArtor said that he does not think the inspection requirements
will disrupt air travel. Under the emergency FAA directive, visual
inspections must be conducted within 250 landings.
   The airlines must report to the FAA within 48 hours on the
result of the inspections.
   The Boeing 737 is widely used for short-haul flights and more
than 1,100 of the 737-200 series, such as the one involved in the
Aloha accident, have been built.
   McArtor could not say which airlines fly the older 737s but said
the planes are scattered across the industry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
