<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 1327EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-AmnestyRush 2ndLd-Writethru a0587 05-04 0906</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amnesty Rush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0587,0932</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yearlong Amnesty Marathon Nears Midnight Finish Line</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 7th, `Applicants who ...,' with New
York court decision</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos LA1, LA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY RYCKMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of illegal aliens hoping to take advantage of their
last chance for U.S. citizenship camped outside immigration offices
around the country early today as the yearlong amnesty program
approached its midnight deadline.
   All 107 offices of the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization
Service will remain open until midnight to handle applicatons from
those seeking legal residency status.
   ``I expect to be here forever, for the rest of my life,'' said a
weary Stanley Davis, chief legalization officer for the INS office
in Tucson, Ariz.
   In Houston, vendors sold tacos and sandwiches to those in line
Tuesday. In Albuquerque, N.M., immigration officials hired a
Mexican band to entertain the 400 people queued up.
   ``I think we burned out two photocopiers in the past two days,''
said Patrice Parilli, director of the legalization program at
Catholic Charities in San Francisco, where more than 25,000 aliens
from 200 countries have applied for amnesty in the past year.
   As of Monday, 1.37 million amnesty applications had been filed
nationwide, and 470,000 people were seeking legal status under a
separate program for seasonal agricultural workers, the INS said.
The deadline for that program is Nov. 30.
   Applicants who file by the deadline also may request up to 60
days for submitting other documents necessary to prove they have
lived in the United States continuously since before Jan. 1, 1982.
   In New York state, the midnight deadline was extended for some
aliens until at least May 16 because of initial confusion about the
program's application to parents of U.S.-born children on welfare.
They were first ruled ineligible, then eligible for amnesty.
   Today's order by the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals applies
only in New York state, and INS spokesman Greg Leo said it would
affect only a few hundred families. He urged all eligible aliens
not to wait, but to apply by midnight anyway.
   In Santa Ana, Calif., 2,000 people applied for amnesty on Monday
and nearly as many applied on Tuesday, said legalization officer
George Newland.
   ``I think many of these people deep down inside thought there
would be an extension, so they waited until the last minute,''
Newland said.
   By Monday, 1.33 million people had applied for some form of
amnesty in the INS western region, said Joyce Leonard, the region's
acting assistant director of immigration reform. The region is
comprised of California, Arizona, Nevada, Hawaii and Guam.
   Thousands of amnesty applications piled up in the Los Angeles
office, the region's busiest, as people camped outside.
   More than 13,000 illegal aliens have applied for amnesty in
Oklahoma, said A.J. Irwin, the INS chief legalization officer in
Oklahoma City. About 1,000 people have applied in the last week,
and about 50 were waiting outside the doors when the office opened
Tuesday.
   ``We just can't handle it,'' Irwin said. ``We were doing an
average of 20 people a day, and now we're doing about 200 a day.''
   ``I asked them (the aliens), `Why did you wait, why did you
wait,' and a lot are saying they were afraid to come in,'' he said.
``Now after a year, they're seeing that it's not a trick.''
   Jose Luis Navarro, 40, was among the skeptics.
   ``I thought I would go to the immigration office to apply and
they would be there waiting to catch us,'' Navarro said.
   ``I didn't have sufficient papers, and I wasn't certain about
the program like I am now,'' said Carlos Ortiz, 37, who came to the
United States from Chihuahua, Mexico. ``And I didn't have the
money.''
   In Hialeah, Fla., Marcos Castellon, 40, said he had been afraid
to apply.
   ``I was afraid they would deport me,'' Castellon said. ``But now
everyone believes in the law, and they accept it in good faith.''
   In Phoenix, Ariz., chief legalization officer Eugene Botts said
he found a block-long line upon opening Tuesday, and 900 people
were processed during the day.
   ``We had another rough one today,'' Botts said, with waits of
about four hours for applicants, ``which before this week was
unheard of.''
   In Houston, the legalization office stayed open during the final
24 hours of the application period. On Tuesday, 5,000 people tried
to apply, said Richard S. Rios, the center's director.
   INS officials rented three portable toilets to accommodate
people camping outside the legalization center, and vendors sold
refreshments.
   ``Some of the applicants are free-enterprising, selling tacos,
Cokes, salad, sandwiches,'' Rios said, joking that the INS approves
of the entrepreneurs ``as long as they are reporting that income.''
   In Florida, officials expected the total number of amnesty
applications to reach 125,000 by tonight, said INS regional
director Perry Rivkind.
   ``I think there may be a last-minute push,'' he said. ``But
we'll take everyone _ even if we have to wake 'em up in line.''
   About 23,000 people have applied for amnesty in New Jersey, with
25 percent coming in the last month, said James M. Gray, director
of the immigration office in Camden.
   ``It's been a very successful program but I am disappointed in
this particular area that there are an awful lot of aliens who have
not taken advantage of this once-in-a-lifetime chance,'' Gray said.
   ``There are no more chances,'' Gray said. ``An awful lot of
people are missing the boat.''
</TEXT>
