<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Dissident     05-04 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Dissident,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dismissed Scientist Attacks Party Line on Modernization, Democracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLENE L. FU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's best-known dissident took issue with the
government's modernization plans during a meeting Wednesday with
university students and said economic reform without democracy is
impossible.
   ``The concept of modernization is independent of nation or local
people,'' Fang Lizhi told the students at Beijing University.
``This is a common concept all over the world. You should not be
able to say `Chinese modernization.' The aim, the target, at least,
is the same everywhere.''
   Chinese leaders use the slogan ``modernization with Chinese
characteristics'' to describe China's policy of economic reform
under party direction.
   Fang, 52, an internationally respected astrophysicist, is an
outspoken critic of the government and was kicked out of the
Communist Party last year. He was accused of inciting pro-democracy
student demonstrations in December 1986 and January 1987.
   His meeting with several hundred students during an observance
of the university's 90th anniversary was believed to be the first
time since his dismissal that Fang was allowed to speak about
politics in public.
   ``We need more democracy in China,'' Fang said after the meeting.
   Developing a modern economy without democracy is impossible, he
said, offering Albania as an example of a nation where ``there is
no democracy and also no economy.''
   He said students hadn't abandoned their hopes for democracy.
   ``The students still are concerned about the situation of
democracy in China now,'' he said. ``After the student movement, of
course, they kept quiet, but in their minds they want quicker
(steps toward democracy).''
   Of the students' thinking, he said: ``No change. Still no
change.'' He said of his own: ``I never change my opinion'' on
China's politics or economy.
   After the student protests, Fang was removed as vice president
of the Science and Technology University in Hefei, Anhui province,
and was transferred to the Beijing Observatory, where he continues
research and writing.
   The official press has featured him in several articles recently
in an attempt to show government leniency in allowing Fang to
continue his academic pursuits. He was allowed to attend a
conference in Italy last June.
   On Monday, the Beijing Review published a lengthy feature saying
the past year, during which Fang published five books, was his most
productive.
   Fang said Wednesday he would admit to error in his thinking only
if the government could prove him wrong.
   His repeated requests to visit the United States have been
refused. Fang said he has received invitations from several
American universities, including Harvard.
   He brushed aside questions about possible trouble for speaking
with the students. ``I'm not concerned. Many times, I speak like
this,'' he said.
   Asked whether he had trouble after an interview with the New
York Times in February, Fang said: ``Not too much.''
   In the animated 90-minute discussion, students voiced views
ranging from support of China's attempts at democracy to harsh
criticism.
   Some said later that the meeting was spontaneous, not organized
by the student government or other official groups. Fang said he
had been invited to a small-group discussion by physics department
students.
</TEXT>
