<HEAD>Arrest Caps Reopened Probe Of Fatal Nursing Home Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCEBURG, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of a nursing home where six
people died in a Christmas Eve fire has been charged with setting
the blaze, police said.
   Bobby Ray Howell, 49, was arrested Tuesday shortly after a
Lawrence County grand jury indicted him on six counts of murder and
one count of aggravated arson.
   ``This is silly,'' Howell told Lawrence County Sheriff Tom
Pyrdum.
   Howell and his wife, Wanda, owned the J.D. Residential Home for
the Aged, which was destroyed in a fire Dec. 24, 1986.
   ``The way I feel, it's like something has been lifted off my
chest,'' said Diana Parker, who with her husband, Jim, was an
administrator at the home. Mrs. Parker has maintained a resident
initially blamed with accidentally starting the fire could not have
done so.
   One of the Parkers' sons, 16-year-old Herbert Kenneth Parker,
died in the fire.
   When the initial investigation was conducted, fire officials
said they believed an elderly, slightly retarded man given to
playing with cigarette lighters started the blaze in his room and
then panicked.
   But the Parkers said the flints had been removed from the man's
lighters as a precaution.
   District Attorney Mike Bottoms refused comment on his
investigation of the fire, citing a past legal relationship with
Howell. He also ordered investigators not to comment.
   Arraignment was scheduled Monday.
   If convicted, he could receive the death penalty.
</TEXT>
