<HEAD>State Department Criticizes House Vote for South African Sanctions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Wednesday criticized
proposed legislation that would ban all U.S. investment in South
Africa.
   ``We don't believe that they (sanctions) have, or will, achieve
their intended purpose and would in many respects be
counterproductive,'' department spokesman Charles Redman said.
   He was reacting to a bill passed Tuesday by the House Foreign
Affairs Committee, which now heads for debate in the full House.
   Redman said the trade sanctions against South Africa legislated
in 1986 by Congress ``have not led to significant positive changes
in South Africa and we don't believe that additional ones are any
more likely to succeed.''
   He said the administration had been lobbying Congress against
the bill and would continue to argue its position.
