<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 1445EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Elections     05-04 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Elections,0691</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conservatives Face Tough Battle In Municipal Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservative
government, hurt in opinion polls by fierce opposition to welfare
shake-ups and a new property tax, faces a tough battle in municipal
elections Thursday.
   The local contests, ranging from the big industrial cities of
the north to town councils in the prosperous south, are the first
electoral test of Mrs. Thatcher's government since she won a third
successive in June.
   The opposition socialist Labor Party ended an upbeat campaign
buoyed by revolts among rank-and-file Tory members of Parliament
against the tax and welfare changes, which critics say will hurt
the poor.
   ``The political contours of Britain are shifting before our
eyes,'' Labor campaign manager Bryan Gould declared as the party
hit a seven-year high of support.
   Labor support has surged from the 30.8 percent in the 1987
general election. The Conservatives won that vote with 42.3 percent
of the vote. This month's Gallup poll indicated 41.5 percent
support for Labor, one point ahead of the Conservatives.
   At stake are one-third of the seats in 158 English and Welsh
districts and the entire councils of all 53 cities and towns of
Scotland. There are no elections this year in London and Northern
Ireland.
   Among the biggest prizes are Birmingham, Britain's second
largest city, Edinburgh, the Scottish capital, and the southwest
England port of Bristol, all narrowly controlled by Labor.
   Twenty million Britons are eligible to vote in the elections to
fill nearly 4,000 seats last contested in 1984. About 10,800
candidates are running.
   In the pre-election battle, opposition parties have attacked the
government's proposed welfare changes, which are aimed at ending
what the Tories call Britain's ``dependency culture'' nurtured by
the welfare state.
   The opposition has also criticized the new property tax
legislation _ the latest Conservative salvo in its battle to clip
high-spending, left-wing local authorities. Under the changed laws,
which are getting a rough ride through Parliament, property taxes
will be levied on every adult in a home, instead of on the building.
   Critics say the so-called ``poll tax'' will double or triple
bills for millions of households.
   A rough calculation shows that a four-adult family in a
middle-class London suburb, which used to pay $930 a year on its
house, will now pay $370 per head for a total of $1,480. But the
figures vary and are disputed.
   Mrs. Thatcher calls the new tax a ``community charge,''
insisting ``poll tax'' is pejorative because it falsely implies
that citizens will have to pay for their voting rights.
   Her 101-seat overall majority in the 650-member House of Commons
was slashed to 25 this month in a vote on the bill.
   Surveys show two-thirds of voters oppose the tax.
   Mrs. Thatcher argues that left-wing councils run costly policies
geared to their own low-income supporters, and finance them by
placing the main tax burden on the Tories' constituency _
businesses and middle-class households.
   When the tax comes into force in 1990, Mrs. Thatcher believes,
it will bring home to everyone, rich and poor, the cost of electing
left-wing councils.
   The councils, which run services ranging from education to
garbage collection, raise half their revenue from property taxes.
The government provides the other half.
   In an added boost for Labor, the elections are also the first
since Britain's two centrist parties merged last March into the new
Social and Liberal Democratic Party.
   The new party, known as the Democrats, and a breakway Social
Democratic Party led by former foreign secretary David Owen, are
fighting each other for about 150 seats.
   The Gallup poll indicated 11 percent support for the Democrats
and 4 percent for Owen's breakaway faction.
   In Scotland, where the Tories suffered humiliation at the last
election when they won only 10 of the 72 Scottish parliamentary
seats, the territory looks even more hostile to Mrs. Thatcher.
   Polls indicated 23 percent support there for the Tories,
compared with Labor's 50 percent and 18 percent for Scottish
nationalists.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880504-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 1446EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PostageRates     05-04 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Postage Rates,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Frank Says Budget Changes Needed To Avoid Faster Rate Boosts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Postmaster General Anthony M. Frank, saying
federal restrictions on Postal Service finances are ``absurd,''
called Wednesday for more control over his budget as one way to
avoid an accelerating pace forreases further,'' said
Frank, who took over the Postal Service just weeks before last
month's postal rate increase. ``I believe that the American people
are not going to be happy forever with an inexorable cycle of rate
increases every third year.''
   Frank testified at a hearing of two House Post Office and Civil
Service subcommittees, at which one congressman said talk of
inevitable rate increases is ``in and of itself negativism.''
   Rep. Frank Horton, R-N.Y., urged the Postal Service to lower
rates instead, saying ``even if it's just one cent, I think it
could be a tremendous step forward.''
   But the postmaster general said that ``over the next several
years, we need to improve our situation just to continue to meet''
the past schedule of rate boosts roughly every three years.
   Frank said the Postal Service needs more control over its
budget, hopes to find new sources of revenue in areas ranging from
transportation to philately and is examining other initiatives to
improve its management of costs.
   Horton said the April rate increase, combined with reduced Post
Office window hours because of budget cuts enacted by Congress,
plays into the hands of those who want to turn mail delivery over
to private business.
   Federal budget director James C. Miller III has called for
ending the government monopoly on mail service, and a presidential
commission in March advocated allowing private companies to go into
the mail business.
   Frank, who is a critic of such proposals, said efforts to
privatize the Postal Service ``can find fertile ground for growth
only in shortcomings and failures of the postal system itself.''
   He pledged to restore full window service as soon as finances
allow, and voiced support for legislation to separate Postal
Service finances from the rest of the federal budget.
   Frank said it was ``absurd for the Postal Service to be
regulated by budgetary `scorekeeping' rules'' designed to bring
about deficit reductions.
</TEXT>
