<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Elliott     05-04 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Elliott,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opinionated Actor Says Speaking His Mind Cost Him Stardom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sam Elliott's first film, ``Lifeguard,''
didn't catapult him to stardom as predicted a dozen years ago, due
mainly, he says, to a penchant for speaking his mind.
   When ``Lifeguard'' was released in 1976, Elliott publicly
attacked the studio that made the film for advertisements
emphasizing an unsavory element that didn't exist in the film.
   ``It was about a guy coming of age and making important
decisions in his life, and they were talking ... beach blanket
bingo,'' he said. ``I know it had an effect on my career. Some
people just don't want to hear the truth.''
   Elliott, who lives in Malibu with his actress-wife Katharine
Ross, is starring in ``Shakedown,'' being released Friday. And he's
still speaking his mind.
   ``I'm probably more outspoken now than I was before,'' the
43-year-old actor said recently. ``But I don't think I put off
people as much now because of my sense of humor.
   ``A lot of what I've said over the years was just kidding
anyway, but people didn't realize it. Being opinionated was all it
was.''
   Elliott confesses his undercover cop role in ``Shakedown'' is a
conscious effort ``to elevate myself in this business.''
   ``I'm trying to ally myself with commercially oriented movies so
that I can become bankable and therefore get better roles,'' he
said. ``I've turned stuff down because I didn't believe in it, and
I don't want to do anything I can't believe in.
   ``If it isn't real for me, it won't be real up on the screen.''
</TEXT>
