<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-Contra     05-04 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran-Contra Judge Cites Lack of Progress in Declassifying
Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in the Iran-Contra trial Wednesday
ordered governent security officials to explain at a closed hearing
the ``apparent lack of progress'' in declassifying key documents
for the trial.
   U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell scheduled the hearing for
Friday morning and ordered the attendance of representatives of
national intelligence agencies who are reviewing some 300,000 pages
of classified documents collected by independent counsel Lawrence
E. Walsh. The hearing will be closed to reporters and the public.
   Gesell issued the order a day after Walsh reported that 82,820
pages of classified documents plus another 22,965 pages of
classified or sensitive non-government papers had been placed in a
security facility for examination by defense lawyers for Marine Lt.
Col. Oliver L. North and three co-defendants.
   Gesell said it apeared ``from this report and other information
available to the court that the interdepartmental review committee
charged with examining classified documents is apparently failing
to meet the requirements of this criminal action.''
   The judge, who last week accused the Reagan administration of
``intentional withholding of documents necessary for the defense,''
said the closed hearing would be convened to consider ``the
apparent lack of progress being made in declassifying essential
papers.''
   Gesell's order indicated impatience with the progress that had
been made in a week. On April 28, Walsh reported that 35,254
classified government documents were ready for defense review.
   At the hearing on Friday, Gesell said he would set deadlines for
``reporting the final results of the declassification process.''
   North and his co-defendants, former national security adviser
John M. Poindexter and arms dealers Albert Hakim and retired Air
Force Maj. Gen. Richard V. Secord also were directed to appear
along with their lawyers and prosecutors.
   Under the Classified Information Procedures Act, secret
documents cannot be introduced into evidence unless they are
declassified by the agency that generated them.
   The interdepartmental task force that is reviewing the material
consists of representatives from the White House, the CIA, the
National Security Council as well as the departments of Defense,
State and Justice.
   Gesell has warned repeatedly that unless the defendants are able
to introduce relevant portions of the secret documents as evidence
he would be forced to dismiss charges they conspired to divert
profits from the U.S.-Iran arms sales to the Nicaraguan Contra
rebels.
   During one hearing last week, Gesell said ``a stone wall is
being built up between this court and the trial.''
   Walsh has described the documents as containing some of the
government's most closely guarded secrets, the disclosure of which
could jeopardize the lives of hostages being held in the Middle
East or compromise U.S. intelligence and military planning.
   Some of this secret material, if disclosed, could ``expose
people in very difficult situations to torture and death'' in the
Middle East, Walsh said.
   Walsh testified last week there were some documents found in
North's office that were so secret even ``he shouldn't have had.''
   Meawhile, the defense has argued that the unprecedented volume
of classified documents will make it impossible for the four
defendants to get a fair trial under procedures imposed by the law
for disclosing government secrets in court.
   The classified procedures statute requires the defense to notify
the prosecution in advance of trial of any secrets it wants to
disclose in court. This requirement, among other things, would
force the defense to tip its hand before trial, the defense lawyers
contended in a motion filed last week to declare the law's
provisions unconstitutional as applied to this case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
