<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Borge     05-04 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Borge,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interior Minister Says Nicaragua Talked to Rebels Because of War's
Cost</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Minister Tomas Borge said the
government agreed to negotiate with Contra rebels because of the
high cost of the war in lives and resources and as a way of holding
indirect talks with the United States.
   But he cautioned that if the cease-fire talks failed, the entire
nation would be called to battle the U.S.-supported rebels.
   The leftist leader, in an interview Tuesday night, described the
almost 9-year-old Sandinista government as ``the Nicaragua we
dreamed of,'' despite opposition from a U.S. ``administration that
is particularly aggressive, visceral, expansionist and
reactionary.''
   The Sandinistas came to power in a 1979 revolution that deposed
the pro-American dictatorship of the late Anastasio Somoza. The
Contras began their fight 1{ years later.
   ``We've paid a high price to defend our national sovereignty and
dignity,'' said Borge, one of nine commanders in the directorate of
the governing Sandinista National Liberation Front.
   More than 26,000 people have been killed in the war, and the
government claims the economy has suffered losses of more than $3
billion.
   Recent talks in Managua with the Contras to work out a lasting
armistice have faltered as the two sides attempt to define a
vaguely worded cease-fire pact signed March 23.
   A fragile 60-day truce remains in effect until the end of this
month. The rebels have refused a Sandinista offer to extend it an
additional 30 days.
   Should the truce end without an agreement to either prolong the
cease-fire or a lasting peace plan, ``we'll mobilize the entire
nation,'' Borge said.
   He said Nicaragua agreed to negotiations with the rebels because
it ``has paid a high cost in blood'' in the war.
   ``But if the Contras were not badly beaten militarily, or held
land, they would never negotiate with us,'' he said.
   The Sandinistas initially refused to hold direct talks with the
Contras or allow them to come to Nicaragua for discussions. Borge
acknowledged the back-pedaling but said, ``We will never discuss
political power'' with the Contras.
   ``We understand the negotiations with the Contras are indirect
(talks) with the United States,'' he said.
   The Sandinistas had long said that any discussions to end the
fighting should be with the Reagan administration because of its
aid to the Contras.
   Borge dismissed rumors that the directorate was split between
his hard-line followers and those of President Daniel Ortega.
   ``The worst enemies of revolutions are the revolutionaries ...
who fight among themselves,'' Borge said. ``We all discuss and
discuss until we're in agreement. There are certain contradictions.
That's natural and helps contribute and move things forward.''
   He said the Sandinistas would give up power if they lost in
elections, but said that would be the end of the Nicaraguan
revolution.
   ``And this is impossible, nothing can kill the revolution,'' he
added.
   Asked if the government was Marxist-Leninist, Borge said the
teachings of those two thinkers was ``a universal science and
anyone who doesn't study it is either mentally retarded or
ignorant.'' He said Marxist-Leninist theory ``was an important
guide in our decisions.''
   He praised the government's ties to the Soviet Union, which
provides most of the country's aid. The Soviet Union, he said,
``helps us and respects us and we appreciate it.''
</TEXT>
