<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Madonna     05-04 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Madonna,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Play Praised But Madonna Gets Mixed Notices In Her Broadway Debut</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The play was praised but the critics were not as
kind to Madonna, making her Broadway debut in ``Speed-The-Plow,''
David Mamet's scathing comedy about two Hollywood producers and a
temporary secretary.
   ``No, She Can't Act'' headlined the New York Daily News. Its
drama critic, Howard Kissel, called ``Speed-The-Plow'' ``Mamet's
clearest, wittest play,'' but added ``I bet it would be even
funnier with an actress.''
   Clive Barnes of the New York Post agreed. He said the rock star
``sounds more as if she were auditioning than acting, and the
audition is scarcely for the big time. There is a genuine, reticent
charm here, but it not yet ready to light the lamps on Broadway.''
   Frank Rich of The New York Times was more positive. He said
Madonna ``serves Mr. Mamet's play much as she did the Susan
Seidelman film `Desperately Seeking Susan,' with intelligent,
scrupulously disciplined comic acting.''
   ``She delivers the shocking transitions essential to the action
and needs only more confidence to relax a bit and fully command her
speaking voice,'' the Times said.
   Madonna's role is the smallest in the three-character play, and
she is on stage less than half the time. The play also stars Joe
Mantegna and Ron Silver.
   But it has been Madonna who sold tickets. ``Speed-The-Plow''
orginally was scheduled to open at the 299-seat Mitzi Newhouse
Theater in Lincoln Center but ticket demand was so great than it
was moved to the 1,058-seat Royale Theater.
   Even so, the Lincoln Center Theater, which produced the play on
Broadway, deliberately downplayed Madonna's role in the production.
It declined all interviews for the star and kept publicity to a
minimum.
   By the time the show opened Tuesday night, it had a good but not
overwhelming advance sale of $500,000. With the favorable reviews,
the box office expected to take in more than $100,000 the day after
the opening, said Merle Debuskey, a spokesman for the show.
   Mantegna and Silver, who play the sleazy Hollywood producers,
were universally lauded. Linda Winer, writing in Newsday, called
Mantegna ``irresistible,'' and she said Silver delivered ``a
riveting breakthrough performance.'' Said Rich, ``The men could not
be better. Mr. Silver gives the performance of his career.''
   ``Speed-The-Plow'' is Mamet's third play to be done on Broadway.
``American Buffalo,'' starring Robert Duvall, has a financially
unsuccessful run in 1977, but later was revived successfully
off-Broadway with Al Pacino. Mamet's ``Glengarry Glen Ross,'' which
opened on Broadway in 1984, won a Pulitzer Prize for drama.
Mantegna won a Tony Award in that play.
   All three stars are committed to appear in the play for six
months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
