<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CandidatesAnnounce     05-04 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Candidates Announce,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simons Announces As Senate Candidate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CASPER, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Superintendent of Public Instruction Lynn
Simons announced Wednesday she will seek the Democratic nomination
for the U.S. Senate seat held by Republican Malcolm Wallop.
   Simons, head of the state's public education system since 1978,
joins Democrats state Sen. John Vinich and University of Wyoming
Professor Peter Maxfield in seeking the office Wallop has held 12
years.
   Simons, a former teacher, said the economic policies of the
Reagan administration have done little for the country or the state.
   ``It certainly has not been good for the state,'' she said. ``I
am the right person at the right time for the right job.''
   Simons said she believed her position would help her address
issues in the Senate. ``If there is a hope, and I believe there is
one, education is exceedingly important in the change to a new
economy,'' she said.
   Simons said she decided Friday to run, and added she did not
consider the announcement late, even though the state Democratic
convention is Saturday.
   ``I had to get through the legislative session and take care of
my court case,'' she said.
   The court case stemmed from Simons' decision in 1987 to seek the
dismissal of employees without regard to state personnel rules. A
federal jury found against Simons and her deputy in a lawsuit filed
against them, but Simons said she did not know if the incident
would hurt her chances for support from state employees.
   Simons said she supported a fee on imported oil and did not
support a tax increase.
   State election officials have said she would have to resign only
if she wins the election.
</TEXT>
