<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SubwayShooting     05-04 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Subway Shooting,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robbery Victim Charged With Assaulting Alleged Assailant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager was charged with assault Wednesday
after he shot one of six youths who robbed him aboard a subway
train, police said.
   The bullet glanced off the young man's chest and he was not
seriously injured, said Transit Authority police spokesman Al
O'Leary.
   Officials denied any similarity between the incident and the
highly publicized Bernhard Goetz shooting. Goetz, who is white,
shot four black young men who surrounded him and demanded money
aboard a subway.
   O'Leary said Decosta Wright, 17, shot Anthony Smith, 22, after
Smith and five others accosted Wright as a train pulled into a
Brooklyn subway station around 12:40 a.m. Wednesday.
   The gang put Wright in a headlock, threw him to the floor of the
subway car and took a gold ring and his wallet, containing $20,
O'Leary said.
   ``At some point, Mr. Wright decided he had enough and he pulls
out a .25-caliber silver Raven automatic pistol and fires one
shot,'' striking Smith, O'Leary said.
   The TA spokesman denied any similarity to the Goetz case,
saying: ``Here a violent felony was committed against the victim
before he fired any shots. In the Goetz case there was a threat or
perception of a crime about to be committed.''
   Goetz, who was acquitted of attempted murder and assault charges
but convicted of weapons possession, said he thought the young men
were trying to rob him. His victims said they were only panhandling.
   In the Brooklyn shooting, the victim and his attackers were all
black.
   The wounded youth stumbled off the train and told a transit
officer he had been shot. After transit police found Wright and
heard his story, they arrested both Smith and Wright.
   Police also eventually arrested four other teen-agers, including
a 14-year-old boy who had Wright's gold ring and a high school pass
in his pockets. Transit police were still looking for the other
youth.
   Wright was charged with second-degree assault, illegal weapons
possession and reckless endangerment, according to O'Leary. In
addition to the attackers, there were several other passengers
aboard the train.
   Smith and the other four were charged with first-degree robbery.
</TEXT>
