<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 1712EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-JapanBeef     05-04 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Japan Beef,560</2ND_LINE>
<TEXT>
   US Accuses Japanese of Protectionism, But Opens Door to Resuming
Talks
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter on
Wednesday sharply accused Japan of protectionism in its dispute
with the United States over beef and orange import quotas. But he
left open the door to restarting negotiations that collapsed here
Tuesday night.
   Yeutter said the Japanese restrictions ``presumably'' will be be
declared illegal by GATT, the General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade, under a complaint process accepted by Japan at a GATT
meeting in Geneva hours after breakdown of the Washington talks.
   Such a finding would open the way to compensation or possible
U.S. trade reprisals or a combination of both, he said.
   ``My patience as a negotiator has come to an end,'' Yeutter told
a news conference, but he still talked of a possible resumption of
talks.
   He accused the Japanese of failing to match U.S. concessions in
the prolonged dispute and of making a beef price-fixing proposal
amounting to ``clearly the antithesis of free and open trade.''
   However, Yeutter said overall trade relations between the two
countries are ``still very good'' and the United States ``would be
happy at any time'' to listen to new Japanese proposals provided
they ``reflect a whole lot more market liberalization than surfaced
in the last few days...
   ``Hopefully they will reappraise their position and come forth
with much more accommodating proposals sometime in the future ...''
Yeutter said. ``If an opportunity arises to resolve the issue
through negotiations in the next two to three months while the GATT
panel is organizing itself, we would be very pleased.''
   Yeutter said during the talks he had offered to waive U.S.
claims for potential compensation for damages to its export trade
if the Japanese would agree to a two-year phaseout of the quotas
``but even that was unacceptable.''
   The Commerce Department has estimated that annual U.S. beef
exports to Japan of about $550 million could grow to about $1
billion under free trade and exports of oranges and orange juice,
now less than $100 million a year, could top $150 million.
   Warning that ``we will not tolerate stalling of the GATT process
by the government of Japan,'' Yeutter said, ``we will be a lot
harder to deal with once we have a decision'' from GATT.
   ``We will not permit this case to spill into the next
administration. We're going to resolve this dispute one way or
another during this (President Ronald Reagan's) administration,''
he said.
   He also accused Japan of delaying action on opening markets to
12 varieties of U.S. processed foods in a case settled by GATT
earlier this year. The United States will pursue this with GATT in
June, he said.
   Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng said in a statement issued
by his Washington office that the United States has insisted
throughout on complete removal of the beef and orange quotas.
   Disclosing new details of his negotiations with Japanese
Agriculture Minister Takashi Sato, however, Yeutter said the United
States would have accepted a proposal for a three-year phaseout of
the beef quota if Japan had not sought to raise new barriers.
   He also said a two-year phaseout of orange and orange juice
import quotas could have been accepted, but Japan insisted on five
years and offered only a 10 percent annual tonnage increase.
</TEXT>
