<1ST_LINE>r p AM-StatePrimaryRdp     05-04 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-State Primary Rdp,0737</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Metzenbaum Ready for Fight in Ohio; Bayh Campaigns for Indiana
Governorship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Sen. Howard Metzenbaum predicted a tough battle
against his GOP challenger, Cleveland Mayor George Voinovich, but
the outspoken liberal added: ``I must be doing something right if
so many people want to beat me.''
   ``There isn't a hit list in America that doesn't have me at the
top of it,'' the 70-year-old Metzenbaum told reporters in Cleveland
after he crushed a little-known primary opponent to win nomination
for a third term.
   Voters in two other primaries Tuesday chose Democratic
candidates for governor in states where Republicans now hold the
top job.
   In Indiana, Secretary of State Evan Bayh swamped his only
primary foe and will face Lt. Gov. John M. Mutz, who was unopposed
for the GOP nomination. With Gov. Robert Orr barred by law from
seeking a third term, Democrats hope to recapture the governor's
mansion for the first time in 20 years.
   In North Carolina, Lt. Gov. Bob Jordan beat four rivals for the
chance to face Gov. Jim Martin, who is only the second Republican
governor in the state this century. Martin, seeking a second term,
was unchallenged in the primary.
   Voinovich, a 51-year-old moderate who was the only Republican in
the race, promised a ``barn-burner'' of a fight and said he had
``never seen people more excited about a senatorial campaign,
whether it's enthusiasm for me, or antagonism toward Metzenbaum.''
   Metzenbaum is among the most liberal members of Congress and as
a member of the Senate Judiciary Committee played a key role in
killing the nomination of Robert Bork to the U.S. Supreme Court.
   The contest is expected to be one of the most expensive in Ohio
history, with the two men having raised more than $7 million
through the end of March.
   In Indiana, Bayh has the benefit of one of the state's most
popular political names as the son of former Sen. Birch Bayh. But
Mutz has been attacking him on the issues of age and experience _
he is 32 and has held statewide office less than two years.
   The Mutz campaign quickly unveiled television advertisements
showing each candidate's photograph atop a resume. Mutz's resume
fills with his record as a successful businessman, 13-year member
of the General Assembly and two-term lieutenant governor presiding
over the state's economic development program.
   The lone entry on Bayh's resume is a reference to 15 months as
secretary of state. After that image appears, the two resumes are
shown side by side and viewers are told Mutz is ready now for
Indiana's toughest job.
   Two-term Republican Sen. Richard G. Lugar and Democrat Jack
Wickes, an Indianapolis attorney, were unopposed for Senate
nominations.
   In North Carolina, Jordan acknowledged his standing as an
underdog against a popular incumbent, but said he counted on help
from a Democratic Party that is ``unified in a way that I have not
seen it before.''
   Merle Black, political science professor at the University of
North Carolina at Chapel Hill, said that to win Jordan must
``present a positive agenda that will excite Democrats and
independents to vote for him.''
   ``But he's also running as an underdog and he's got to give
people reasons why Jim Martin shouldn't be re-elected,''
   Here are the vote totals from the primaries:
   _ In Ohio, final unofficial results showed Metzenbaum with
1,067,138 votes, or 83 percent, to 213,120, or 17 percent, for
Ralph Applegate, who runs a Columbus lawn-care business.
   _ In Indiana, with 98 percent of precincts reporting, Bayh had
482,393 votes, or 83 percent and former Kokomo Mayor Stephen J.
Daily had 66,001 or 11 percent. The rest of the votes went to
Senate Minority Leader Frank O'Bannon, whose name was put on the
ballot as a precaution by the Bayh campaign when it appeared Bayh
might be found in violation of the state's residency requirement.
   _ In North Carolina, with 99 percent of precincts reporting,
Jordan had 404,091 votes or 80 percent to 61,291 votes or 12
percent for Billy Martin, a service-station employee from Carthage
not related to the governor. Ex-Ku Klux Klansman Carroll Crawford
had 22,061 votes or 4 percent, James Lloyd of Salisbury 10,433
votes or 2 percent and anti-nuclear activist Bruce Friedman of
Sylva 9,713 votes or 2 percent.
</TEXT>
