<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Beaches     05-04 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Beaches,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Strikes Down Beach Segregation In Port Elizabeth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court ruled Wednesday that
Port Elizabeth must let all races onto its beaches. Groups of
blacks rushed to the shore, running triumphantly on the previously
``whites only'' sand.
   The regional Supreme Court in the southeastern port supported a
city councilor and a member of Parliament who claimed the city
council acted without proper authority when it passed a resolution
in 1966 segregating the beaches of the nation's fifth-largest city.
   Chris Heunis, the constitutional development minister, and Cape
Province administrator Gene Louw opposed the suit. Their lawyers
said they may appeal.
   Heunis and President P.W. Botha have taken a middle ground
recently on the volatile issue of ``beach apartheid,'' saying some
beaches should be integrated but others reserved for whites. The
extreme-right Conservative Party, whose power is growing, opposes
any integration of beaches.
   Graham Richards, the white city councilor who filed the
challenge, called the court decision ``a small victory for those of
us fighting what sometimes seems to be a losing battle against the
continuous inroads made by the government against basic human
rights.''
   Most beaches are open to all races in the two largest coastal
cities, Durban and Cape Town. One section of Durban's beachfront
remains segregated. blacks are barred from many beaches in smaller
communities.
   In January 1987, Port Elizabeth's beaches were the scene of a
political confrontation between Botha and the Rev. Alan Hendrickse,
leader of the mixed-race chamber of Parliament.
   Hendrickse waded into the surf in well-publicized defiance of
apartheid segregation laws. He later apologized to Botha, which
hurt his credibility with anti-apartheid groups.
   After learning of Wednesday's ruling, Hendrickse said in
Parliament: ``Somebody owes me an apology.''
   Also Wednesday, two African National Congress guerrillas were
sentenced to be hanged for land mine explosions that jolted
northern farming communities in 1985-86. They were convicted of
murder last week in Messina, near the Zimbabwe border.
   Mzondileli Nondula, 25, was convicted of planting a mine that
killed two white women and four white children in December 1985.
Mthetheleli Mncube, 28, was convicted of setting a mine that killed
a black man in November 1985 and of killing two white policemen in
a subsequent escape attempt.
   ``We have lost the battle but not the war,'' Mncube said after
the sentence. ``We shall win.''
   The ANC is the main guerrilla movement fighting white domination
in South Africa.
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok offered to compensate
relatives for the funeral expenses of two boys shot to death in
1985 by policemen who were hiding in crates on a truck to entrap
stone-throwing youngsters in a mixed-race township.
   A judge ruled at an inquest March 3 into what is called the
``Trojan horse'' incident that police acted unreasonably, but on
Tuesday a prosecutor declined to press charges against the officers.
   Vlok said his department would pay the funeral expenses and
legal costs borne by the families of Michael Miranda, 11, and Shaun
Magmoed, 16. The families are expected to get about 900 rand ($425)
each.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
