<DOCNO> AP880504-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 2005EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-SlainCandidate     05-04 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Slain Candidate,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Slain Indian `Wins' Symbolic Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-State Primary Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUMBERTON, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Slain Lumbee Indian candidate Julian T.
Pierce outpolled Joe Freeman Britt in the race for a superior court
judge's seat in Robeson County, but Britt will become judge in
December.
   Even though the vote Tuesday carries no legal power, Pierce
supporters said it has symbolic meaning for minority residents'
struggle to rid their county of discrimination and corruption.
   ``The turnout in the minority precincts was even higher than for
school merger (which was passed by county voters March 8),'' said
Harvey Godwin, Pierce's campaign manager. ``That is people making a
strong statement. The voters believed in what he stood for.''
   Britt, the county's district attorney, was automatically
declared the winner of the Democratic nomination for a new state
superior court judgeship after Pierce was killed in his home March
26 by three shotgun blasts in what authorities say was a domestic
dispute. One man was charged with murder in his death, while
another committed suicide before he could be arrested, authorities
said.
   In unofficial vote totals from 28 of the county's 40 precincts,
Pierce got 7,652 votes to Britt's 5,238 in the judgeship race.
   Elections Board Chairman Murchison ``Bo'' Biggs said state law
prevents election officials from counting or publicizing the
results of the Britt-Pierce race because there was no contest. The
totals were reached by reporters checking codes for the early
unofficial returns. Reporters were not allowed to see codes for the
later returns.
   The Robeson County legislative delegation and Pierce's campaign
committee have agreed to ask the Legislature to create another
Superior Court judgeship for the county, and Gov. Jim Martin said
he would appoint a minority, probably an Indian.
   The county's population of about 100,000 is 37 percent Indian,
37 percent white and 26 percent black.
   On Feb. 1 this year two Lumbee Indians took over the offices of
The Robesonian newspaper to protest alleged discrimination against
minorities in the area. The siege ended when Martin agreed to
appoint a task force to study the matter.
</TEXT>
