<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 2010EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Saudi-Iran     05-04 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Saudi-Iran,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Says Saudi Spy Arrested As Expelled Diplomats Go Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said Wednesday its security men
arrested a Saudi Arabian spy in Tehran. It also claimed the Saudis
beat up Iranian diplomats and seized documents after the rupture in
relations between the two countries.
   The Iranian allegations underscored the growing tension between
the two Persian Gulf neighbors. Saudi Arabia severed diplomatic
relations with Tehran on April 26.
   In a brief statement, the official Islamic Republic News Agency
said security authorities ``arrested an agent of the Riyadh regime
who had entered the country illegally with 300 million rials (4.5
million dollars).''
   ``He will be dealt with as a spy,'' the statement said.
Convicted spies may be sentenced to death under Iran's Islamic law.
   IRNA also quoted an unnamed Information Ministry official as
saying the man was planning to ``spread Wahhabi faith and the
American brand of Islam.''
   The Wahhabis are an ultra-conservative Sunni Moslem sect. Most
Saudis, including Saudi Arabia's ruling family, are Wahhabis. The
majority of Iranians are Shiite Moslems.
   ``The measures that were taken were no more than the normal
procedure in line with diplomatic norms under such circumstances,''
the official was quoted as saying.
   Saudi Arabia made no immediate comment on the arrest of the
alleged spy.
   Diplomats from Tehran's embassy in the Saudi Arabian capital of
Riyadh and a consulate in the Red Sea port city of Jiddah, who were
given one week to leave the country, returned home Wednesday.
   Saudi Arabia called ``totally baselesss'' Iranian claims that
the diplomats were beaten up and that documents were confiscated
from the two missions.
   Saudi-Iranian ties have deteriorated rapidly in recent months
after repeated Iranian charges that the Saudis are helping Iraq in
its war against Iran.
   Last year, Iranians ransacked the Saudi Arabian embassy in
Tehran and killed a Saudi diplomat, saying the action was in
retaliation for the killings of 275 Iranian pilgrims in clashes
last July with Saudi security police in Islam's holy city of Mecca.
   Iran has called for the overthrow of the Saudi regime and said
it must be stripped of control of Islam's holy shrines in Mecca and
Medina.
   The Saudis said they will allow only 45,000 Iranian pilgrims to
enter Saudi Arabia during this year's pilgrimage. The Iranians have
insisted they will send the same number of pilgrims as last year _
150,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
