<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Reagan-NuclearWaste     05-04 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Nuclear Waste,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`You've Got To Put It Someplace,' Reagan Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Wednesday the selection of
a nuclear-waste dump site is sure to spark objections from people
who live nearby but ``you've got to put it someplace.''
   Reagan made the comment in a question-and-answer session after a
speech to the National Strategy Forum, a nonpartisan group that
specializes in foreign policy and national security issues.
   Asked how the United States would dispose of nuclear waste,
Reagan said a number of states had been selected as possible
candidates for depositories.
   ``And then a commission is investigating everyone and then we'll
name what they believe are the correct places and the best places
for the safety of the people and the disposition of that nuclear
waste,'' Reagan said.
   ``I realize that somebody's going to think it's too close to
them when it happens,'' he added, ``but you've got to put it
someplace.'' The audience laughed and applauded.
   Yucca Mountain, Nev., has been selected by Congress as well as
the Energy Department over sites in Texas and Washington state as
the best place to study building a high-level nuclear waste dump.
</TEXT>
