<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 2034EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GrannyKids     05-04 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Granny Kids,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Granny Kids' Forsake Big-City Schools for Quiet Southern Illinois</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNDS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To local folks they're known as ``granny
kids,'' children who leave their homes and big-city schools in the
Chicago area for quiet Southern Illinois towns and their smaller,
friendlier schools.
   They're scattered throughout the area, living with their
``grannies'' and other relatives during the school year and heading
for the urban north in the summer.
   It's hard to determine exactly how many there are because they
list home addresses in the area when they enroll, school officials
say.
   But they're there, and have been for years.
   ``We just have to check to make sure their guardianship is in
the hands of someone in our district,'' said Mike Corzine,
assistant superintendent in the Egyptian School District near Tamms.
   ``There's not a major number of them, though,'' Corzine said in
a recent interview.
   Gang violence, drugs and overcrowding are among the reasons
given for leaving city schools, said Don Shaner, guidance counselor
at Meridian High School in Mounds.
   But such problems are ``societal,'' not school-bred, Chicago
Board of Education spokesman Bob Saigh said Wednesday.
   ``Chicago, like any other big city, it's got its share of
problems,'' he said. But he added that the city's schools are ``100
percent safe. I defy anybody to say they're unsafe.''
   Many of the imported students at local schools are carrying on a
family tradition.
   Jerry Richmond, 15, is attending Meridian like his older sister,
who graduated from there before going on to Northwestern University
at Evanston.
   ``It's a lot friendlier here,'' Richmond said. ``Up there, the
teachers don't even know your name.''
   Richmond began his freshman year last fall at Evanston Township
High School in suburban Chicago, which has 4,000 students, some
gang problems and ``a lot of drug traffic,'' he said.
   At midterm, he transferred to the 320-student Meridian. His
parents sent him south _ more than 350 miles south _ to live with
his grandparents so that he could attend a smaller, quieter high
school.
   ``We do have gangs in the city of Evanston. There is no visible
of gang problems at the school,'' said William Logan, director of
the safety department at Evanston Township High. ``There's no doubt
some kids are using drugs and selling them, but it's not rampant.''
   ``I think it's a safe school for studets to come here and study,
if that's what they want to do,'' Logan said.
   But Richmond's story was not new to school administrators in
Southern Illinois.
   There has been a Chicago-to-Southern Illinois school connection
for at least 20 years, said Terry Rueffer, director of special
programs in the Century School District at Ullin.
   ``A lot of them even start when they are little,'' Shaner said.
   Most granny kids adapt readily to the new environment _ but it
does take some adjustment.
   Richmond's school-year home of Pulaski has a population of 500 _
about one-eighth the student body at his hometown school.
   ``There's not much to do,'' he said of the village just north of
Cairo at the southern tip of the state.
   ``My mom thought this would be a better place for me,'' Richmond
said.
   And with fewer distractions, he said he can concentrate on
another goal.
   ``I just want to get into a good college.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880504-0198 </DOCNO>
