<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia-Kidnap     05-04 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Kidnap,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kidnappers Say They Will Release 14 With Message</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER BAENA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas who kidnapped 14
Colombian, West German, French and Swiss officials and journalists
said they will release the hostages soon with a message, the sister
of one captive reported Wednesday.
   Attorney General Eduardo Serra called the abductions ``a
propaganda operation'' by two guerrilla organizations: the National
Liberation Army, a pro-Castro group; and the Maoist Popular
Liberation Army.
   A National Liberation Army spokesman Tuesday night phoned the
sister of kidnap victim Dario Parra, president of the legislature
of the department of Santander.
   Matilde Parra said the spokesman told her that her brother and
the others were being held at a camp in the country's northeastern
mountains, where the guerrillas are active.
   The guerrillas will release their hostages in the next few days
with a ``document of an international importance,'' she quoted the
spokesman as saying.
   In Bonn, a spokesman for the West German Foreign Ministry
confirmed Wednesday that honorary consuls Sigfried Markert and
Helmut Luecker were kidnapped Tuesday.
   Local police said four armed guerrillas kidnapped Markert, 59,
from his metals company in Bucaramanga, 200 miles from Bogota, as
employees watched.
   Luecker, West Germany's honorary consul in Medellin, also
disappeared Tuesday. Medellin, Colombia's second largest city, is
250 miles from the capital.
   Callers identifying themselves as National Liberation Army
members told Bogota radio stations they had seized Jean Christophe
Rampal, a public information officer at the French Embassy.
   In Paris, a spokesman for the French Foreign Ministry said
French officials had not heard from Rampal since Friday but could
not confirm he had been kidnapped.
   Two Swiss officials, Wilfred Lehner and Richard Aufereggen, were
captured Tuesday by commandos who attacked the office of the
Colombia-Swiss Chamber of Commerce in Bogota and overpowered 10
workers, police said.
   The Colombians are Parra, journalists Augusto Jerez, Guillermo
Vallejo, Luz Marina Giraldo, Raul Numas, Omar Paez, and an
unidentified cameraman working for a Bogota television station. The
others are two regional politicians, Otoniel Gomez and Luiz Lopez.
   Police said the guerrillas also tried to kidnap Luisa Victoria
de Porras, the honorary consul of Panama in Cartagena, and Annette
Exiga, the honorary consul of France in Cali.
   One police officer was killed and another one was wounded in a
shootout when the guerrillas tried to abduct Mrs. Exiga, police
said. Two would-be kidnappers of Mrs. de Porras were arrested.
   Guerrillas bombed Colombia's main pipeline in four different
places on Tuesday, forcing operations to stop.
   The pipeline, which carrries 215,000 barrels a day from Cano
Limon, near the Venezuelan border, to the Caribbean, is partly
owned by Occidental Petroleum of the United States.
   Serra said the National Liberation Army is waging a ``terrorist
campaign'' to force Occidental Petroleum out of Colombia.
</TEXT>
