<HEAD>Simon Steadfastly Holds Delegates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAHOMET, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Paul Simon says he is virtually
certain that one-time presidential rival Michael Dukakis will be
the nominee but he refuses to release his delegates ``in the
unlikely event that Michael Dukakis stubs his toe between now and
the convention.''
   The Illinois senator, who put his presidential campaign on hold
a month ago, said he would not surrender about 180 delegates
committed to his campaign despite pressure to do so by supporters
of Jesse Jackson.
   Chicago Mayor Eugene Sawyer and some black lawmakers have urged
Simon to officially drop out of the presidential race. They contend
his continued presence hurts any chance Jackson has of keeping the
nomination away from Dukakis.
   ``I'm going to hold out until the California and New Jersey
primaries on June 7 and see whether I can still have an influence
on the nomination,'' Simon said Wednesday.
   He said he was ``95 percent certain'' that Dukakis would win the
nomination.
   Simon also ruled out a later bid for the White House and said he
was focusing on a probable Senate re-election bid.
   ``I'm definitely getting back to my job as a senator,'' said
Simon, first elected to the Senate in 1984. ``I took a year of my
life to try and make a difference in this country, and I think I
accomplished that.''
