<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DCStatehood     05-04 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DC Statehood,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Shows Strong Backing for D.C. Statehood, Advocates Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new poll indicates two-thirds of Americans
support making the District of Columbia the nation's 51st state,
leaders of the statehood movement said Wednesday.
   A telephone survey of 1,011 households nationwide conducted in
March by the Opinion Research Corporation of Princeton, N.J.,
indicates that 66 percent of those contacted support making the
nation's capital a state, an increase of 14 percentage points
increase over a similar poll conducted a year ago.
   ``We can proclaim today that the American people overwhelmingly
support statehood for the nation's capital,'' said Del. Walter
Fauntroy, D-D.C., who has introduced in the House of
Representatives a bill to establish the state of New Columbia.
``America now knows, and cares, that we achieve full citizenship.''
   Results from the poll, which carried a margin of error of 3
percentage points, also indicate that 83 percent of those surveyed
believe residents of the district ``should have the same rights as
citizens of the other 50 states.''
   Fauntroy's bill, which was passed by the House District of
Columbia Committee last year, would create a state out of all
non-federal lands in the district, give voting rights to a member
of the House and two senators, and establish a state government.
   Currently, Fauntroy is the only congressional representative for
the 625,000 residents of the nation's capital, and he cannot vote
on the House floor.
   The measure has 197 co-sponsors, and Fauntroy said he was
confident he will secure the 218 votes needed to assure House
approval. He said he hoped to bring the matter up for a vote
``before the Fourth of July.''
   One former opponent, Rep. Roman Mazzoli, D-Ky., said Wednesday
that he has decided to support the bill after Fauntroy agreed to
study the possibility of eliminating the city's federal subsidy.
   The district receives about $500 million of its $2.8 billion
annual operating budget in direct federal subsidies, and Mazzoli
and others have opposed creating a state that would receive federal
money in such a way.
   Fauntroy, who noted that 55 percent of all land in the nation's
capital is federally owned, and thus off the tax rolls, predicted
that congressmen will understand the district's unique position.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
