<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Manhattan Movie,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woody Allen, Francis Coppola and Martin Scorsese Make Movie
Together</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The folks who gave us Mickey, Dumbo and Bambi
have signed on Woody, Franny and Marty.
   That's Woody Allen, Francis Ford Coppola and Martin Scorsese.
The three directors are making a film for Disney's Touchstone
Pictures on life in modern-day Manhattan.
   Production work has started on the trilogy, and since the
project was spearheaded by Allen, it carries its usual Allenesque
cloak of secrecy.
   All a Disney spokesman would say was that Allen will write,
direct and star in his segment but that no other casting has been
confirmed. Coppola is writing his segment with his daughter, Sofia.
Richard Price (``The Color of Money'') is writing Scorsese's part.
   All three filmmakers have used New York as their celluloid
playgrounds. Coppola shot ``The Godfather'' and ``The Cotton Club''
here. Scorsese did ``Raging Bull,'' ``Mean Streets,'' ``Taxi
Driver'' and ``King of Comedy'' on the sidewalks of New York.
   And just about all of Allen's work is Manhattan-bound.
   Disney would not discuss the project's budget, and said the
movie, tentatively titled ``New York Stories,'' will be released in
early next year.
