<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 1653EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0803 05-04 0813</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0803,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says He Won't Quit Democratic Race; Bush Talks Astrology</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Simon on holding delegates, Bush on Deukmejian,
inserting 2 grafs after 12th graf pvs, ``If super, and inserting 1
graf after 14th graf pvs, Bush amassed</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis underscored his standing as Democratic
presidential nominee-in-waiting on Wednesday after his latest
landslide primary victories, even though Jesse Jackson said he
would stay in the race because ``It's not really over till it's
over.''
   Republican George Bush made light of astrology but noted a lot
of voters believe in it.
   ``There are two edges to this sword,'' the vice president said
as Air Force Two carried him to California on a campaign swing.
   At a news conference in Boston, Dukakis said he welcomed
Jackson's continued candidacy, so long as his rival would ``keep it
positive and address issues.''
   The governor's aides expressed irritation in recent days with
Jackson's barbed comments during the Ohio and Indiana campaigns,
although Dukakis himself replied only indirectly.
   Dukakis, savoring Tuesday's lopsided primary victories in
Indiana and Ohio, picked up a handful of fresh Democratic National
Convention delegates and arranged to receive the backing of half a
dozen or more Democratic governors later in the week _ perhaps
including Kentucky Gov. Wallace Wilkinson and Louisiana's Buddy
Roemer, both of whom earlier supported Sen. Albert Gore Jr.
Campaign aides said Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton was rounding up the
support for Dukakis.
   Pointing his attention toward the fall campaign, Dukakis also
signed up veteran Democratic warriors Kirk O'Donnell and Dick Moe
as advisers to his campaign.
   Jackson won support for his decision to stay in the race from
Bruce Babbitt, who dropped out last winter. ``I think he should
because he has something to offer and I think it makes it a little
more interesting,'' the former Arizona governor said.
   Jackson spent the day in Washington, where he met with
Democratic House members and others after winning a landslide
victory in the primary election in the nation's capital.
   In an interview with CBS, he said he would remain a candidate
after the primary season ends on June 7, and added, ``...I know
what the boundaries are and I will respect those boundaries.''
   But he also appealed to party leaders to avoid flocking to
Dukakis' side until after the primary season ends.
   ``If super delegates wait until after June 8 they are in a
better position as judges to help bring balance'' rather than using
party machinery to parcel out delegates before the primaries end,''
he said in a reference to 645 delegates to the Democratic National
Convention who are party leaders and not elected by voters in
primaries and caucuses.
   Campaign dropout Paul Simon said he was ``95 percent certain''
that Dukakis would win the Democratic nomination, but he said he
would hold onto his 184 delegates to wield influence ``in the
unlikely event that Michael Dukakis stubs his toe between now and
the convention.''
   ``I'm going to hold out until the California and New Jersey
primaries on June 7 and see whether I can still have an influence
on the nomination,'' said Simon.
   Dukakis has roughly 1,500 delegatges in The Associated Press
count, out of 2,081 needed to win the nomination. He leads Jackson
by more than 600.
   Bush amassed the delegates needed to assure his Republican
nomination a week ago in Pennsylvania's primary, but he kept up a
heavy schedule of campaigning with his trip to the West Coast.
   He told California reporters he has not yet begun selecting his
vice presidential running mate. He praised California's GOP
governor, George Deukmejian, lavishly, and said he would
``absolutely not'' rule him out for his ticket.
   In a conversation with reporters en route, he was asked about
the reported statement in former White House Chief of Staff Donald
Regan's soon-to-be published book that first lady Nancy Reagan
consulted astrologers about the timing of presidential events. The
president says he has never based any policy or decision on
astrological forecasts, but does not deny consulting the writings
of astrologers.
   Bush referred in a joking manner to the disclosure, telling
reporters he hadn't checked his horoscope before leaving Washington
but then added that he and his wife were ``both Geminis.''
   Asked about the assertion that the Reagans relied on the
position of the sun and moon and stars to make decisions, Bush
said, ``I don't know about that. But I'll tell you one thing: there
are two edges to this sword.
   ``There are a helluva lot of people across this country that
read these columns. Otherwise they wouldn't be in the papers.''
   Bush brushed aside a claim by astrologer Joyce Jillson that she
helped Reagan's aides select his running mate in 1980. He said he
never heard of her, but then joked:
   ``I'll work closely with her. She's brilliant.''
</TEXT>
