<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WayneStreet     05-04 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wayne Street,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds Attend `The Duke's' Birthplace for Street Dedication</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINTERSET, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of children and adults sporting
cowboy boots and hats turned out Wednesday to watch as Winterset's
busiest street was named for John Wayne, the community's most
famous native son.
   Much of the attention focused on Wayne's widow, Pilar, who with
her daughter helped dedicate John Wayne Drive.
   ``I'm thrilled, flabbergasted. I think it's one of the most
wonderful things to have this done,'' said the widow of one of
Hollywood's most famous tough guys.
   ``He was the most admirable human being I ever met,'' she said.
``Truly, he had Iowa stock in him _ and that's a great stock to
come from.''
   Wayne's daughter, Marisa, 22, who attends Mountain College in
Steamboat Springs, Colo., was impressed with the turnout.
   ``This is great, it's bigger than I expected,'' she said. ``It's
very flattering. I think he would've loved this.''
   Wayne was born Marion Robert Morrison on May 26, 1907, and he
spent the first three years of his life in Winterset before his
family moved to Earlham.
   State and Winterset officials have touted Wayne's house as a
national attraction for the past several years.
   ``Tourism in Winterset has doubled because of the interest in
the John Wayne birthplace,'' said Gov. Terry Branstad, who presided
over Wednesday's ceremonies.
   A band from the local high school welcomed Wayne's widow and
daughter as they were driven into town. Hundreds of children
excused from school joined residents and business people along the
curb and holding signs saying, ``We Love You Pilar.''
   After the ceremony, Mrs. Wayne and her daughter toured the
restored one-story, four-room white house on a corner a block from
the newly named street.
   Dozens of people thrust paper and pens at the Duke's wife and
daughter for autographs. Some brought Mrs. Wayne's new book, ``John
Wayne, My Life with the Duke,'' for her to sign, while others
wanted her to sign pictures and sketches of her late husband.
   ``I'm a great fan of his. He was my favorite star, he always has
been, '' said George Henry Blades, 68, of Winterset, who carried a
four-foot high picture showing himself standing in front of a huge
statue of the Duke, taken at the Cowboy Hall of Fame in Oklahoma.
   Laura Skeffington of Stewart also said Wayne was her favorite.
   ``Oh my God, yes. If you could see my home, I've got a six-foot
tapestry,'' she said. Added her daughter-in-law, ``Her bedroom is
done in John Wayne.''
</TEXT>
