<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Unrest 1stLead-Writethru   05-04 0828</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Unrest, 1st Lead-Writethru,a0678,0852</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Troops Kill Two Palestinians; Strike Shuts Down
Territories</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES thruout with two Palestinians reported killed, more
wounded, details on clashes. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers reportedly killed two Arab
protesters and wounded more than a dozen Wednesday, and strikers
paralyzed the West Bank and Gaza Strip in a ``day of
confrontation'' ordered by leaders of the Palestinian uprising.
   The worst incident was reported in the Gaza Strip's Jabalia
refugee camp, where Israeli soldiers opened fire on a crowd of
protesters, killing two and wounding six, Arab reports and Gaza
City's Ahli Arab hospital officials said.
   Hospital officials identified the dead as Jamal Mahmoud El
Madhoun, 20, and Rizik Hussein Abbah, 17.
   The army confirmed the clash. A spokesman said that ``there were
killed and wounded'' but did not give the exact figure.
   The army clamped a curfew on Jabalia, an Arab reporter in Gaza
said. He said troops also declared curfew in the Shati refugee camp
and had to drive residents into their homes with tear gas and
rubber bullets.
   Seven Arabs were wounded as army troops opened fire to disperse
stone-throwing rioters at a village near Ramallah in the occcupied
West Bank and in the Gaza Strip town of Khan Yunis, hospital
officials said.
   A 21-year-old Arab woman was hit with rubber bullets after she
tried to stab an Israeli soldier in the marketplace in the West
Bank city of Nablus, the army said. The soldier was not hurt.
   The army said troops also opened fire on stone-throwing Arab
protesters in the West Bank village of Silwad. Two Palestinians
were wounded in the legs, Ramallah Hospital officials said.
   According to U.N. figures, the fatalities brought to 182 the
number of Arabs killed in the occupied territories since the start
of the Arab uprising last Dec. 8. Two Israelis have been killed.
   Palestinians shuttered their stores and shut down public transit
throughout the occupied territories in response to a leaflet signed
by the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   The leaflet called for a ``day of confrontation'' and ordered
Palestinians to ``cultivate the land and rebuild the houses
demolished by the racist Israeli occupation.''
   In Nablus, even bakeries and street vendors that normally
operate during strikes were reported closed.
   Wednesday's general strike was the latest of dozens of such
protests called by uprising leaders, but some Arabs have started to
complain about the work stoppages.
   ``When you ask people to do the same thing over and over, it
gets to be too much. Merchants are regular people. They have to eat
and feed their children too,'' businessman Farouak Abu Sharekh said
in Gaza City.
   But Zahran Zhran, a businessman from Nablus, said the strikes
were needed to train Palestinians to keep up long-term protests.
``You have to make them ready for the civil disobedience or they
will be shocked and not listen to you,'' he said in an interview.
   Hundreds of Palestinians chanting anti-Israeli slogans marched
in the West Bank village of Bani Naim, 30 miles south of Jerusalem,
to protest the deaths of two villagers killed Tuesday by Israeli
troops.
   Carrying 15 outlawed Palestinian flags and signs reading ``We
prefer to die than to submit,'' about 2,000 villagers marched
through narrow dirt streets to the village cemetery.
   About 30 masked men set up barricades and set tires ablaze as
Israeli soldiers watched from rooftops.
   In London, Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin called for an
Arab-Israeli peace settlement entailing a jointly run
Jordanian-Palestinian state in 60 percent of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
   In an interview published in Jane's Defense Weekly, he said his
Labor Party, which shares power with the right-wing Likud Bloc,
insisted that ``Jerusalem must be united under Israeli sovereignty
and remain its capital.''
   Israeli residents of towns bordering the Gaza Strip submitted a
petition to Foreign Minister Shimon Peres expressing support for a
U.S. peace initiative and urging that Gaza be exchanged for peace
with Israel's Arab neighbors.
   The group said they were willing to remain on the border with an
independent Palestinian state in Gaza, Israel radio said.
   Peres, leader of the Labor Party, supports a U.S. peace plan
that calls for an international conference and exchanging territory
for peace. The initiative is opposed by Peres' governing partner,
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of the Likud bloc.
   Israeli media said police would recommend that an Arab woman be
charged in the slaying of an Israeli teen-ager shot to death by a
Jewish guard in a clash between Arabs and Jewish settlers last
month.
   The slaying in the West Bank village of Beita caused an uproar
in Israel.
   The woman, who was not identified, allegedly hurled a rock that
hit a Jewish settler guard, Romam Aldubi, in the head, prompting
him to fire wildly and kill 15-year-old Tirza Porat, Israel radio
and two newspapers reported.
   Jewish settlers blamed Arabs for the death, but an army
investigation said she was accidentally killed by Aldubi.
</TEXT>
