<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Firearms-Media     05-04 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Firearms-Media,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TV Newsman Runs into Trouble with Story about Felons Buying Guns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents are investigating the actions of a
television newsman who had a convicted robber buy three handguns to
show how easy it is to conceal a criminal record and buy guns.
   The federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms will give
results of its investigation to the U.S. attorney's office, which
will decide whether charges should be filed, said agent Gary Wurm.
   Newsman Tom Martino of KCNC-TV in Denver and a cameraman
accompanied a man identified as Ollace M. Williams, 36, to at least
three gun stores as part of Martino's report.
   Williams filled out federal firearms purchase forms and bought
three revolvers, omitting disclosure of a 1972 robbery conviction.
   Williams bought a .357-caliber Magnum from Checkpoint Firearms
on April 26, another .357-caliber handgun from Scottie's Guns &
Militaria on April 28, and a .38-caliber revolver from the Gun Room.
   All three dealers said Williams stated on the forms that he was
not a convicted felon.
   Federal law bars convicted felons from buying guns, said
Assistant U.S. Attorney Joseph Mackey. It also is a federal
violation to advise someone else to break a federal law.
   On Monday, Martino went back to the Gun Room, returned the
weapon, got a refund and told owner Bill Molnar the purpose of the
purchase. Molnar said Martino then asked him to destroy the federal
firearms purchase form.
   Instead, Molnar called the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms because, he said, destroying the purchase form is a
federal offense.
   ``They set me up, and I don't like that,'' he said.
   Channel 4 ``didn't rush headlong'' into the story, said news
director Marv Rockford. ``We set out to show how easy it is for an
ex-offender _ a convicted felon _ to purchase a firearm.''
   He said the station had checked with lawyers and Police Chief
Ari Zavaras. Rockford said Denver police endorsed the idea, but
Detective John Wyckoff, a spokesman for Zavaras, said the
department ``declined to participate.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
