<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 2115EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Salmon-Reagan     05-04 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salmon-Reagan,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mainer Declines to Give His Salmon to Reagan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARS HILL, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tradition calls for the first Atlantic
salmon hooked in Maine's Penobscot River to be presented to the
president, but Ronald Reagan will have to settle for No. 2 this
year.
   Neil Donnelly refused to give up his catch.
   Donnelly, of Mars Hill, signed papers saying he did not wish to
turn over his salmon to President Reagan, state Inland Fisheries
and Wildlife officials said.
   ``I understand he ate it the very same day'' the salmon was
caught, Sunday, said fisheries spokesman Paul Fournier. ``Now it's
gone.''
   Donnelly could not be immediately reached Wednesday. He does not
have a telephone, and messages seeking comment had not been
returned.
   Instead, an 8-pound, 27-inch Atlantic salmon caught by Charles
A. Caron, 53, of Brewer will go to the White House on Thursday.
Gov. John R. McKernan Jr. is planning to be there, along with
members of Maine's congressional delegation.
   The tradition started in 1912, when a salmon caught at the
Bangor Pool, a fishing area on the Penobscot, was presented to
President William Howard Taft.
   The tradition continued through seven more presidencies, but
pollution and dams put an end to Atlantic salmon runs and forced
the tradition to be suspended during Harry S. Truman's
administration.
   After years of cleanup efforts, the Atlantic sea-run salmon
returned to the Penobscot and the tradition was revived by the
Reagan White House in 1982.
   Not all salmon fishermen vie for the privilege of giving up
their fish. In the Eddington Salmon Club along the Penobscot, a
member posted a sign that says he already paid several thousand
dollars in taxes ``and doesn't want to pay any more,'' said J.
William Peppard, a member.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
