<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vatican-Soviet     05-04 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vatican-Soviet,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Names High-Level Churchmen for Soviet Religious Event</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Wednesday named the
largest delegation of Roman Catholic clergymen ever to visit the
Soviet Union as representatives at a major religious celebration
next month.
   The high-level group of 13 includes 10 cardinals, among them
John O'Connor of New York and Cardinal Agostino Casaroli, the No. 2
man in the Vatican hierarchy after the pope.
   John Paul has often expressed the desire to visit the Soviet
Union, but the Vatican earlier disclosed that the invitation from
the Russian Orthodox Church did not extend to the pope.
   The Vatican officials and bishops from various parts of the
world will be attending the celebrations marking the millenium of
Christianity's arrival in what is now the Soviet Union.
   Although the invitation was in the name of the Orthodox Church,
the naming of such a top-level delegation clearly demonstrates an
attempt by John Paul to improve relations with Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The Vatican, in announcing the names, said John Paul attaches
great importance to the event and hopes it will open ``new paths
toward reconciliation, peace and justice of which humanity has so
much need.``
   In addition to Casaroli, the Vatican delegation includes
Cardinal Johannes Willebrands, a Dutchman who heads the secretariat
for Christian Unity, and Cardinal Roger Etchegaray, the French
president of the Justice and Peace Commission.
   The delegation also includes cardinals Joseph Marie Trinh Van
Can of Hanoi; Jozef Glemp, Roman Catholic primate of Poland;
Julijans Vaivods of Latvia; O'Connor of New York; Friedrich Wetter
of Munich; Franz Koenig, retired archbishop of Vienna, and Carlo
Martini of Milan.
   It also includes Archbishop Laszlo Paskai of Hungary, Bishop
Dario Castrillon Hoyos of Colombia, head of the Latin American
bishops conference; and Bishop Gabriel Gonsum Ganaka of Nigeria,
representing Africa.
   Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro said the delegation was not
only the largest group of Roman Catholic prelates to visit the
Soviet Union but was also the first Vatican delegation ever to get
a formal invitation, although Casaroli and other churchmen have
visited individually in the past.
   Navarro could not recall such a large church delegation ever
attending a single event anywhere.
   The Vatican said that while Casaroli and Etchegary would only
attend the main celebration in Moscow, Willebrands would represent
the Holy See at all events.
   The pope has said often that he would travel to the Soviet Union
only if he could visit his flock throughout the country,
specifically the Ukraine, Lithuania, Latvia, Byelorussia and
Kazakhastan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
