<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Seabrook-License     05-04 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seabrook-License,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NRC Proposing Rules Change That Could Lead To Seabrook Low-Power
License</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission voted 4-0
Wednesday to propose a rules change that would allow the Seabrook,
N.H., reactor to obtain a low-power operating license without a
siren system to warn nearby Massachusetts residents in an emergency.
   The proposal, which will be subject to a 30-day public comment
period before a final NRC vote, would apply to any plants seeking a
5 percent power license, but was aimed at Seabrook.
   In February, the Atomic Safety and Licensing Appeal Board
blocked a low-power permit for Seabrook because there was no siren
system in place for the six Massachusetts communities that fall
within a 10-mile evacuation zone around the southern New Hampshire
plant.
   The rules change would allow Seabrook owners to obtain the
low-power license and go ahead with testing while trying to get
approval of an alternate siren system. An approved warning system
would still be necessary to obtain a full-power license.
   New Hampshire Yankee, the plant's operator, was forced to remove
its Massachusetts sirens last year after a federal appeals court
sided with local officials. State and local officials led by
Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis believe no evacuation system
can adequately protect nearby residents, and are fighting to block
the plant's opening.
   The company's new alert plan includes truck-mounted sirens and
siren-equipped helicopters as a backup.
   Critics say the license issue has grown more critical for
Seabrook owners, fearing the beleaguered reactor will never be
approved if Dukakis is elected president.
   The idle $5.4 billion plant is losing $50 million each month in
maintenance and finance costs, plant officials say.
   Current NRC rules do not specify off-site safety requirements to
obtain a low-power license, but a 1982 commission ``explanation''
of the rules does. The rules have been widely interpreted to
require an off-site alert system such as sirens for low-power
licensing.
   The NRC staff, in recommending the rules change, cited the ``low
risk'' involved in low-power testing.
   But critics led by Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., complain that
the risk has not changed since 1982, and therefore there is no
legitimate reason to change the regulations.
   In New Hampshire, Seabrook spokesman Rob Williams applauded the
NRC decision, saying it ``correctly addresses the very low risk of
low-power operation.''
   Commissioner Fred Bernthal did not vote because he is leaving
the NRC soon for a State Department post, said commission spokesman
Robert Newlin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880504-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 2131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SnakeArrest     05-04 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Snake Arrest,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Queens Man Accused of Illegal Shipment of Boas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who owns a tropical fish business was
arrested Wednesday and accused of smuggling 700 baby boa
constrictors into the United States from Colombia, authorities said.
   The snakes, which are a protected species in Colombia, were
concealed in five boxes that were part of an otherwise-legal
shipment of fish that arrived March 7 at Kennedy International
Airport, U.S. Attorney Andrew J. Maloney said.
   The snakes, 21 inches long, were discovered during an inspection
by agents of the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service at the airport.
   The shipment was addressed to Agremiro Espana, 43, of Queens,
who owns Miro Espana Co., a wholesale tropical fish business. He
was charged with violating the federal Lacey Act, which outlaws the
interstate or foreign transportation of illegally captured wildlife.
   The charge carries a maximum sentence upon conviction of five
years in jail and a $250,000 fine.
   Under Colombian law, it is illegal to export boa constrictors,
said John Meehan, a special agent with the wildlife service.
   The snakes are a protected species under the Convention on
International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora,
a treaty to which the United States is a party.
   All but 38 have been returned to their natural habitat in
Colombia, said Meehan. The rest will be used in the prosecution of
the case and may eventually be given to American zoos.
   The snakes were all newborns, Meehan said.
   He said baby boas can be bought in South America for about $5
and resold in the United States for as much as $200. Adult boa
constrictors, which grow up to 15 feet in length, bring much higher
prices.
   Meehan said boa constrictors are very popular among amateur
herpetologists because of their docile temperament and because they
are increasingly difficult to obtain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
