<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 1729EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reagan 2ndLd-Writethru a0777 05-04 0881</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0777,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Soviet Human Rights Progress Is Slow But Better Than
Nothing</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS 5 grafs with White House official's comment on tone of
Reagan rhetoric</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, abandoning his harsh criticism
of the Kremlin, credited the Soviet Union on Wednesday with making
progress on human rights and said gradual improvements were `better
than no change at all.''
   Striking a conciliatory tone in a pre-summit address, Reagan
readily acknowledged that the United States has its own problems
with homelessness, racial discrimination and unemployment, as
Moscow has charged.
   Reagan's remarks appeared intended to soothe Soviet anger about
his demand for the Kremlin to ``tear down a wall of oppression''
and his claim that the Soviet troop withdrawal from Afghanistan was
being made under pressure.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev told Secretary of State
George P. Shultz in Moscow last month he was tired of Reagan's
sermons. And the Soviet government accused Washington of ``imperial
arrogance.''
   In his remarks to a Chicago group, Reagan went out of his way to
credit Gorbachev with loosening restrictions on religion, freedom
of speech and emigration.
   ``We applaud the changes that have taken place and encourage the
Soviets to go farther,'' Reagan said. ``We recognize that changes
occur slowly but that is better than no change at all.''
   In a brief question and answer session with the audience, Reagan
said he was willing to give Gorbachev ``the benefit of the doubt,
up to a point'' _ that the Soviet leader sincerely wants to achieve
the program of economic and social reforms known as ``glasnost.''
   The president said he believed Gorbachev was pursuing the
reforms because of economic problems in the Soviet Union.
   Reagan said he hoped he could offer Gorbachev at this month's
U.S.-Soviet summit some suggestions as to how he could move ahead
with glasnost.
   ``That, I think, is preferable to staging a kind of contest with
him so that someone looks like a winner or loser,'' Reagan said.
   He also expressed a dream ``to rid the world'' of nuclear
weapons. He compared the danger of nuclear weapons with a
hypothetical situation in which the world was threatened by a power
from outer space.
   ``Wouldn't we all of a sudden find that we didn't have any
differences between us at all, we were all human beings, citizens
of the world, and wouldn't we come together to fight that
particular threat?'' Reagan said.
   Reagan's speech was part of a series of addresses intended to
frame the issues he will highlight at the summit in Moscow with
Gorbachev May 29-June 2. His audience was the National Strategy
Forum, a non-partisan organization that sponsors educational
programs on national security and foreign policy issues.
   The president said the Soviets have had ``limited successes'' in
improving their economy.
   ``I do not bring this up simply for the sake of sounding
critical,'' Reagan said. He said he mentioned it because of a
development ``of tremendous significance'' in recent months, that
the Soviets themselves are beginning to talk about shortages in
their country.
   On human rights, Reagan said some 300 political and religious
prisoners had been released from labor camps over the last three
years, and that the incarceration of dissidents in mental hospitals
and prisons had slowed, and in some cases, stopped.
   ``And while the press remains tightly controlled by the
(Communist) Party and the state, we've seen the publication of
stories on topics that used to be forbidden _ topics like crime,
drug addiction, corruption, even police brutality,'' the president
said.
   ``These changes are limited and the basic standards contained in
the Helsinki Accords still are not being met,'' Reagan added.
   Underscoring his theme, Reagan said, ``We welcome the human
rights progress the Soviets have made and believe there is good
reason to hope for still more.''
   Reagan said there is no guarantee that the progress is
permanent. He said the late Soviet leader Nikita S. Khrushchev
``loosened things up a bit'' but that it was reversed later.
   ``And for the nearly three decades until our own day, oppression
and stagnation once again became the determining characteristics of
Soviet life,'' Reagan said.
   ``And just as previous hopeful moments in Soviet history ended
all too soon, so, too, `glasnost' _ today's new candor _ will
succeed if the Soviets take steps to make it permanent, to
institutionalize it,'' he said.
   Asked by reporters about the softened tone of Reagan's rhetoric,
White House communications director Tom Griscom said the speech was
different because the topic was different, such as human rights
versus regional issues.
   ``Is there anything wrong with saying since 1985 we've seen
things that are positive and we hope to see more?'' he said.
   In an April 21 speech in Springfield, Mass., Reagan said, ``Two
of the most basic rights that we have called on the Soviets to
comply with are the right to emigrate and the right to travel. How
can we help but doubt a government that mistrusts its own people
and holds them against their will? ...
   ``In the new spirit of openness, why doesn't the Soviet
government issue passports to its citizens? I think this would
dramatically improve U.S.-Soviet relations.''
   The speech led to Gorbachev's complaint to Shultz about U.S.
sermonizing.
</TEXT>
