<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SurpriseArrest     05-04 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Surprise Arrest,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Arrested Six Years After Losing Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANAHUAC, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For six years Richard McKeand went on with
his life, thinking an appeals court had cleared him of an armed
robbery conviction.
   But recently an arrest warrant with his name on it surfaced and
now he is in jail, awaiting transfer to serve a five-year prison
term for robbing a convenience store a decade ago.
   As it turns out, the appellate court had rejected his appeal and
the paperwork apparently got lost.
   Part of the confusion likely resulted from the death of his
attorney, former Texas House Speaker Price Daniel Jr., who was shot
and killed a few months after McKeand's trial. Then Daniel's
assistant in the case, Frank Hughes, relocated.
   McKeand, 29, who was arrested last week, had made no attempt to
hide. He had continued to list his number in the telephone book
while working as an oil rigger.
   ``Everybody knows what he did was wrong,'' said his
sister-in-law, Rayleene McKeand, 24. ``But the courts should have
taken care of it right then before he'd built a new life. Everybody
changes after 10 years.''
   ``I remember he was very young and didn't have a record. He
wasn't a big-time bandit,'' said State District Judge Carroll
Wilborn Jr., who prosecuted McKeand.
   McKeand and another teen-ager, Thomas Williard Reeves, used a
shotgun to rob a convenience store of $100 on July 2, 1978. They
were pulled over by police 1{ hours later, confessed and turned
over the money and weapon.
   Reeves, who agreed to a three-year sentence in a plea bargain
and testified against McKeand, was released from prison in 1981
after serving 11 months.
   McKeand's mother, Betty McKeand, said some community business
leaders have offered to write a letter asking that her son be
pardoned or paroled.
   She said her son's attorneys had not told him that the appeal of
the 1979 conviction had been denied in 1982 and a warrant had been
issued for his arrest.
   She said her son now has an acre or so of land with a mobile
home and recently bought a truck. McKeand, married with a
5-year-old son, separated from his wife this year after seven
years. He was looking forward to his son visiting him during the
summer, his mother said.
   Court records show an arrest warrant was issued Oct. 6, 1982.
The warrant was later returned unserved from the sheriff's office.
   ``These things sometimes happen,'' said Sheriff C.E. ``Chuck''
Morris. ``We handle about 100 warrants per month. There's a
horrendous workload. I don't know whether a secretary misplaced it
or what.''
   The appellate court was reviewing its records last month and
noticed it had never been notified about McKeand's arrest. It sent
a letter to the district clerk, the error was discovered and a new
warrant issued.
</TEXT>
