<HEAD>No City Funds If Jackson Heads Cinco de Mayo Parade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Word that city funds will be withheld from
the Cinco de Mayo parade if presidential candidate Jesse Jackson is
its grand marshal has angered a parade organizer.
   Chief Administrative Officer Rudy Nothenberg recently notified
the Mission Economic and Cultural Association that it would not be
reimbursed for parade expenses on grounds that taxpayers' money
shouldn't be used for such explicitly political purposes as an
appearance by Jackson.
   Jackson is a candidate in California's Democratic primary on
June 7.
   Association director Roberto Hernandez said withholding the city
money could cost the group $14,000 and would be hypocritical
because politicians such as Mayor (then Assemblyman) Art Agnos,
former Mayor Dianne Feinstein, state Sen. Milton Marks and other
politicians have participated in the parade _ some as grand marshal.
   But Nothenberg responded that public officials who have joined
the Cinco de Mayo festivities were city or state office-holders at
the time.
   ``They're incumbents,'' he said. ``He (Jackson) is a candidate.
... The issue is very clear. This is a partisan political event. We
do not allow city money to be used for political events.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Idea of North Senate Candidacy Divides Virginia GOP Leaders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver North, indicted for his role in the
Iran-Contra affair, has very little time to decide on a Senate bid
this year, the head of the Virginia Republican Party said Wednesday.
   North, who has been indicted on charges of trying to defraud the
government in the Iran-Contra scheme, has remained silent on a move
to draft him as the state GOP's Senate nominee.
   But if North intends to seek the seat of Republican Sen. Paul S.
Trible Jr., who is not running for re-election, he needs to declare
soon, says state GOP Chairman Donald W. Huffman of Roanoke.
   ``It'll be tough unless they actually get North to say, `I'm
running,''' Huffman said of the draft effort. Even then, he said,
North's indictment would pose a major obstacle to winning the
nomination.
   Tim Phares, an organizer of the draft-North movement, said North
may have sent a signal about political plans in a commencement
speech Monday at the Rev. Jerry Falwell's Liberty University when
he talked about finding good candidates for office.
   ``Obviously, we can't read his mind. But that's how we interpret
it,'' said Phares.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Jackson Meets With 13 Western Lawmakers To Discuss Western Issues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest lawmakers came away from a 40-minute
meeting with Jesse Jackson on Wednesday impressed with the
Democratic presidential candidate and his committment to Western
issues.
   ``He was obviously very tired, but made an effort to sell his
program and respond thoughtfully to our concerns,'' said Oregon
Democratic Rep. Peter DeFazio. ``Just by coming he showed his
understanding of the importance of the West.''
   Thirteen lawmakers from seven Western states attended the
meeting to discuss a ``Go West '88'' strategy as the campaign trail
heads to Oregon and California over the next month.
   ``We don't think that any recent candidate, including the
incumbent president, has realized the needs and concerns of the
West,'' said DeFazio. ``We are left out of the debate.''
   Oregon Democratic Rep. Ron Wyden said he thought Jackson
addressed the ``key issues very well. He laid out a specific agenda
addressing our concerns and seemed to understand that a Western
strategy may be a key to winning in November.''
   Wyden was one of the organizers of the campaign by more than 40
Western representatives and senators to impress on Jackson and
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis the importance of Democrats
winning the West if they want to claim the White House.
   The group expects to meet with Dukakis later.
