<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Lorenzo-Eastern     05-04 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lorenzo-Eastern,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Air Chief Sees Eastern Losses Continuing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Texas Air Corp.,
said Wednesday the turmoil surrounding Eastern Airlines ``continues
to ravage'' the financial performance of the air carrier, with
losses expected through the first half of this year.
   Lorenzo in remarks to the International Aviation Club said
Eastern, a Texas Air subsidiary, will post continuing losses during
the second quarter.
   He blamed it in part on the airline unions' campaign against
Eastern, the refusal by the Machinists union to agree to
concessions and the series of government investigations of the
Miami-based airline, which has been in the center of labor turmoil
for years.
   ``The present environment is having a serious impact on Eastern.
It continues to ravage the financial results and the future of this
great airline,'' Lorenzo said.
   ``Currently we are looking at very sizable and continuing losses
in the second quarter because of all the activities that are taking
place and their impact on travelers.''
   Eastern has not made public its financial results for the first
quarter of 1988, although Texas Air officials have made clear that
the carrier lost money. Last year Eastern lost $181.6 million,
including a staggering $143 million in losses during the fourth
quarter.
   Eastern's president, Philip Bakes, several weeks ago
acknowledged that the airline was losing some bookings because of
the recently announced Federal Aviation Administration
investigations into the carrier's safety procedures and its labor
battles.
   Lorenzo said Wednesday that he welcomed the FAA investigation
and said he anticipates it ``will put into perspective the
misinformation and nonsense that's been peddled to the media, the
FAA and Congress'' by Eastern's unions.
   Last month, the FAA announced it was seeking $823,000 in
penalties from Eastern for past safety violations and that it was
beginning a plane-by-plane inspection of the carrier.
   FAA Administrator Allan McArtor told reporters Wednesday that
the Eastern inspections are expected to be complete in about a
week. He said inspectors continue to uncover some infractions
requiring corrective action in 7 percent to 8 percent of the planes
checked.
   McArtor said that while in many of those cases the planes had to
be taken out of service briefly, he did not consider the percentage
of infractions unusually high.
   Lorenzo characterized the problems found by the FAA inspectors
so far as minor and said they likely would have been discovered by
airline employees had the government inspectors not been present.
</TEXT>
