<DOCNO> AP880504-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 1750EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-AIDSPamphlet-Reax     05-04 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Pamphlet-Reax,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Pamphlet Wins Widespread Praise</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-AIDS-Pamphlet Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Medical, health and education groups hailed
the government's new AIDS booklet Wednesday as clear, direct and
compassionate, and said it should be required reading for all
Americans.
   The pamphlet, ``Understanding AIDS,'' was developed by the
Public Health Service under orders from Congress and will be sent
to every household with a mailing address on May 26.
   Despite some grumbling over the length of time it took to
produce the eight-page pamphlet, there was almost unanimous praise
for its content.
   ``This pamphlet should be required reading for every American
citizen,'' the American Hospital Association said in a statement.
   ``Everyone who reads this mailer will understand the disease
better, and I hope this understanding will lead to urgency and
compassion, and replace panic and fear,'' Rep. Henry Waxman,
D-Calif., said in a statement headlined ``At long last,
information.''
   Waxman, chairman of the House Energy and Commerce health
subcommittee, said the booklet comes ``years after any reasonable
American would have expected it'' and two years later than similar
efforts by other nations such as Britain.
   He said it took two acts of Congress to pry the information
loose from what he termed ``White House censors.'' Congress
expressly prohibited the booklet receiving clearance from anyone
outside HHS.
   The pamphlet says people cannot get AIDS from casual contact
such as kisses, mosquito bites, sweat, tears, clothes, telephones
or toilet seats. It also describes explicitly how the AIDS virus
enters the body and what can be done to minimize risk, including
instructions on the correct use of condoms.
   Amid the chorus of approval, Rep. William Dannemeyer, R-Calif.,
disputed the booklet's assertions and said it would mislead the
public.
   ``You get the impression that none of us have anything to fear
from associating with people who have the virus, ARC (AIDS-related
complex) or AIDS. Nothing could be further from the truth,''
Dannemeyer said. ``The report should not go out to the American
people.''
   Asked why Americans should listen to him rather than the battery
of scientists, doctors and others endorsing the pamphlet,
Dannemeyer said public health officials have exercised questionable
judgment so far in handling the AIDS crisis. He said they haven't
shut down homosexual bathhouses or required that infected
individuals be reported to authorities by name, among other things,
and said President Reagan had been poorly served by his health
appointees.
   But Dannemeyer was a lonely voice of protest. The pamphlet won
praise from a diverse range of interest groups ranging from gay
organizations to the American Medical Association, labor unions to
the American Red Cross.
   Jeff Levi, executive director of the National Gay and Lesbian
Task Force, called the booklet long overdue and ``generally a very
positive step. It is compassionate, accurate, straightforward and
non-judgmental. The strong statements about casual contact are
particularly important.''
   Scott D. Thomson, executive director of the National Association
of Secondary School Principals, said the booklet is ``highly
readable for youth'' and will help families discuss AIDS ``in a
candid yet friendly framework.''
   The material is specific and may offend some people, said
Elizabeth Whelan, executive director of the American Council on
Science and Health. ``But in dealing with matters of life and
death, sensibilities should not dictate educational efforts aimed
at prevention,'' she said.
   In addition to being mailed to all American households, the AIDS
booklet will be available at Planned Parenthood clinics and other
facilities.
   Faye Wattleton, president of Planned Parenthood, called the
pamphlet a ``frank and thorough guide'' that her group is happy to
distribute. ``We are pleased and relieved that this nation is
finally acknowledging that the AIDS epidemic is a health issue, not
a moral issue,'' she said in a statement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
