<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 2150EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-LyndaCarter-Mammograms     05-04 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lynda Carter-Mammograms,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Actress Calls For Medicare Coverage Of Mammogram Tests For Breast
Cancer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Lynda Carter teamed up with medical
experts Wednesday to call for Medicare coverage of mammogram
screening tests to detect breast cancer in older women.
   ``Although I am a professional actress and entertainer, I speak
to you today not as a public figure but as a private person _ a
woman who has many female family members and friends for whom
breast cancer remains an ever-present threat and concern,'' Ms.
Carter told a House Appropriations subcommittee.
   ``Mammography can pick up many breast cancers when they're very
small, even before they can be felt,'' Ms. Carter said. ``But for
economic reasons, mammography isn't accessible to many of the women
who need it.''
   She said that making the tests more readily available ``makes
sense for financial as well as humanitarian reasons,'' because
early detection of breast cancers avoids the high costs to treat
cancers discovered later.
   ``All of us can help in our own way to bring about this needed
change,'' she said. ``All of us have a stake in making it happen _
because we are women, or because the lives of women important to us
are affected by the issue.''
   Ms. Carter appeared alongside Dr. Marvin A. Rich, president and
director of AMC Research Center in Denver, before the subcommittee
on labor, health and human services and education and related
agencies.
   Rich said Medicare, most Medicaid programs, and the majority of
private insurers do not pay for routine screening mammograms, only
for tests that are performed after symptoms of breast cancer have
appeared.
   He said the cost of the test, averaging at least $100, is ``a
significant deterrent to utilization of mammography by many of the
women who need it.''
   Because 40 percent of all breast cancers occur in women over age
65 and the risk of breast cancer climbs 15 percent for every five
years of age after 65, ``it is essential that women in the
Medicare-age population receive annual screening mammograms to
detect tumors in the early, most treatable stage,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
