<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SeatBelts     05-04 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seat Belts,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dingell Vows Continued Probe of Federal Seat-Belt Regulations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agencies that fail to require
seat-belt use on roads running through U.S. parks and other lands
will be called before Congress to explain why, a House committee
chairman said. Wednesday.
   ``Obviously, this administration has not been willing to show
the best example when it comes to federal areas and belt use,''
Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., said in a speech to the Society of
Automotive Engineers.
   Dingell, chairman of the House Energy and Commerce Committee,
vowed to use his subcommittee on oversight and investigation to
force greater seat-belt use in government. He said he would call in
representatives of federal agencies to explain the rule-making
process.
   ``If the example won't come from the administration, perhaps the
example will come from the oversight committee,'' Dingell said.
   He said the Defense Department has cooperated in his campaign to
require seat-belt use, but civilian agencies ``are more
recalcitrant.''
   The National Park Service proposed ``a seat-belt use requirement
as part of a revamping of its safety rules,'' Dingell said.
``However, when the rules were finalized, this requirement was
quietly dropped.''
   The Park Service in a letter said the proposed rule was removed
because of adverse public comment, Dingell said. Further
investigation showed ``that all but one of those comments came from
the Park Service employees,'' he said.
   A Park Service spokesman, Andrew Ringgold, said the agency
follows state law in determining seat-belt use. Where states
require seat belts, the parks also require them; where states have
no such requirement, neither does the Park Service.
   ``Our philosophy ... was that states were the appropriate
authorities to regulate traffic and that National Park Service
traffic regulations should be limited to situations that are either
unique to park areas or that are not consistently addressed by
state traffic regulations,'' Ringgold said.
   Also, the public would be confused by mandatory seat-belt use in
parks situated in states lacking such a requirement, Ringgold said.
   More than half the parks administered by the service require
seat belts be worn, Ringgold said. About 8,000 miles of public road
run through Park Service land, he said.
   Thirty-three states and the District of Columbia have enacted
laws requiring seat-belt use, ``but the public has been lukewarm to
the use of seat belts, despite their known and obvious benefits,''
Dingell said.
</TEXT>
