<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Dyson     05-04 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dyson,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dyson Denies Homosexual Rumors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM STUCKEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUGHESVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Roy Dyson on Wednesday openly
confronted rumors that have spread since the apparent suicide
Sunday of his top aide, firmly denying that either he or the aide,
Tom Pappas, was homosexual.
   ``Tom and I were very, very good friends. He was like a brother.
We had a personal and professional relationship,'' the Maryland
Democrat said at a news conference three days after Pappas
apparently jumped to his death from the 24th floor of a New York
hotel.
   ``Was he (Pappas) a homosexual?'' Dyson was asked.
   ``No, he was not,'' Dyson replied.
   To the same question about himself, he responded firmly and
without emotion, ``No, I am not.''
   Dyson said he thinks Pappas jumped to his death because he could
see his reputation being ruined by a story in Sunday's Washington
Post that Pappas forced young male staffers to attend social
functions he arranged, fired one staffer who refused to stay at a
staff party and asked another male staffer to perform a strip-tease
at an office retreat.
   Dyson complained that the story was based on interviews with a
few disgruntled former staffers and gave only one side of the story.
   He said he doesn't think publicity about Pappas, including
earlier stories that he failed to properly report payments he
received from campaign funds, will hurt his chances of beating a
little-known Republican opponent, Wayne Gilchrest, in November.
   ``I am ready to go. I love campaigning,'' he said.
   He said he could not answer questions about the campaign funds
because Repubicans have lodged a complaint with the Federal
Election Commission.
   Until the news conference, Dyson, 39, had been in seclusion
since the 46-year-old Pappas died. The two men, and a third
staffer, Todd Skipper, were in New York for the weekend.
   Dyson said he talked with Pappas after the story was read to him
Sunday and that ``he seemed to be holding up very well.'' He said
Pappas denied the allegations in the story, but knew that ``the
damage had been done.''
   Dyson said Pappas was totally devoted to him and the 1st
Congressional District. ``I think he sensed he was losing it,'' he
said.
   A note left in the hotel room by Pappas ``did not seem like a
suicide note to me,'' Dyson said. The note was not addressed to
anyone and did not mention any names, he said.
   Addressing specific incidents in the Post story, Dyson said he
has discussed them with other staffers since Sunday and ``they have
shed a distinctly different light'' on them.
   He said he does not remember Pappas ordering an aide to perform
a strip tease although he was present at the retreat where the
incident allegedly happened.
   Other staffers told him there is a different explanation for
that incident, he said, but he refused to discuss it, saying ``in
time we'll get to that.''
   Dyson also discussed the firing of aide Andy Hira when he
refused to remain at a party at an Annapolis hotel earlier this
year. He said he was present and that Pappas told Hira he had to
attend because it was a party for constituents who had come to hear
the congressman announce he would run for another term.
   ``He (Hira) said he was not going to stay in the room with those
old bags,'' Dyson said.
   ``At that point, I think Tom told him he was no longer on the
staff,'' Dyson said.
   He said he did think it was improper for Pappas to advertise in
a Missouri newspaper for young men to fill staff positions and to
require them to send Pappas a photograph. He would have put a stop
to that had he known it, he said.
   Dyson said Pappas made some mistakes, but called him ``a man of
integrity, of compassion.''
</TEXT>
