<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 2156EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SuperCollider     05-04 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Super Collider,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Subcommittee OKs $100 Million For Super Collider</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House Appropriations subcommittee on
Wednesday recommended spending $100 million next year on the
proposed superconducting super collider research project.
   The amount approved by the energy subcommittee was $40 million
more than it had originally recommended, but was less than
one-third the $363 million asked by President Reagan.
   ``This is the first hurdle for funding,'' said Rep. Carl
Pursell, R-Mich., the only subcommittee member whose state is a
candidate for the project. ``To survive, it is important that the
project receive adequate support at this stage.''
   Rep. Tom Bevill, D-Ala., chairman of the subcommittee, said the
legislation limits spending to research and development leading to
the $4.4 billion physics research project, which will include a
53-mile-round particle accelerator.
   ``We feel like the $100 million is adequate to hold the team
together, the scientists, and also to go ahead with the necessary
reserch and all the preliminaries ... getting ready for
construction,'' Bevill said.
   But he added that ``this money is not to be used for purchsing
equipment or starting construction.''
   Bevill said the subcommittee increased its recommendation with
the backing of the House Democratic and Republican leadership.
   The Senate Budget Committee has recommended $200 million for the
super collider and other high-energy and nuclear-physics projects
but has not recommended an appropriations amount.
   Bevill said he and other subcommittee members would support
legislation authorizing the super collider project, ``but I think
every one of the panel feels as I do that we've got to have some
extra revenue before we commit this government to a project that is
going to cost somewhere between $5.3 billion and $9 billion.''
   The $5.3 billion estimate includes anticipated inflation. The $9
million estimate was produced by Bevill's staff.
   The super collider would fire subatomic particles against each
other at high speeds for research into the nature of matter.
   Seven states _ Arizona, Colorado, Illinois, Michigan, North
Carolina, Tennessee and Texas _ have been selected as potential
sites for the project, which is expected to create 4,000 permanent
jobs and have an annual budget of $280 million.
   Supporters argue that the super collider is needed to keep the
United States competitive in the next century. Opponents say the
project would siphon much-needed money from other scientific
research.
   Meanwhile, a group of Arizona business, education and labor
leaders presented the Energy Department with a plan to pay for the
super collider without immediate outlays by the federal government.
   Ian Macpherson, assistant attorney general and Arizona's super
collider coordinator, and Robbie Aiken, Washington representative
of Phoenix-based Pinnacle West Corp., said the plan would create a
state agency to issue bonds for construction of the project, which
would be leased to the federal government.
</TEXT>
