<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Fed-EconomicOutlook     05-04 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fed-Economic Outlook,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Improvement Widespread Throughout US Economy, Fed Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. economy has enjoyed healthy growth so
far this year, with even such depressed sectors as energy and
farming showing improvement, according to an economic assessment
released Wednesday by the Federal Reserve.
   The central bank said ``continued moderate growth of the
nation's economy'' was confirmed by the reports received from the
Fed's 12 regional banks.
   Economists at the regional banks survey economic conditions in
their districts and the reports are compiled for use by Fed
policymakers when they meet every eight weeks to review monetary
policy. The next meeting of the Federal Open Market Committee will
be on May 17.
   The government reported last week that the overall economy, as
measured by the gross national product, expanded at an annual rate
of 2.3 percent from January through March. It was a far better
performance than the recession that many analysts had feared
immediately following the Oct. 19 stock market collapse.
   This better-than-expected growth has led to expectations that
the central bank may soon begin tightening up on credit conditions
and boosting interest rates as a way of fighting inflationary
pressures.
   Such an action would seem to be consistent with the generally
upbeat economic assessments contained in the Fed report Wednesday.
   The report said manufacturing activity remained strong,
primarily because of strong growth of U.S. exports. It said housing
activity has shown some improvement following the slump at the end
of last year caused by high interst rates and consumer jitters
caused by the stock market collapse.
   The Atlanta Federal Reserve bank, which covers Georgia,
Tennessee, Alabama, Florida and part of Mississippi, reported that
textile mills in the region were running at near capacity, in part
because of rising export sales.
   Several regional banks in the West reported a pickup in oil
drilling activity. The Dallas region said oil-drilling had
rebounded sharply with the number of rigs in use growing for the
first time in six months.
   In agriculture, the report said farm incomes were expected to be
high this year, but down slightly from the 1987 level because of
smaller government payments and smaller profits in the livestock
sector.
   ``Farmland values are generally rising in most areas and farm
financial conditions appear to be strengthening,'' the report said.
   The Dallas bank found that the number of farmers and ranchers
leaving agriculture had slowed considerably, while the Atlanta and
the St. Louis districts predicted that cotton acreage should be up
substantially this year.
</TEXT>
