<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 2054EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TasteShow     05-04 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taste Show,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taste Show Is A `Glutton's Fantasy'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   How can anyone resist a bite of
Arthur Gutkin's spinach rolls when he is deliberately pulling them
apart in front of passers-by, letting the hot mozzarella ooze out?
   And who would walk by meatballs bubbling in sauce, or a pizza
laden with pepperoni, when samples are there for the taking?
   The public doesn't get to walk through this particular valley of
temptation: The two-day Taste Show at the Convention Hall is
designed for potential customers from the food service and retail
food industries.
   But for the lucky convention-goers, it was a golden opportunity
to try Robert Zitin's honey ham, or maybe Stuart Schnurman's mango
nectar. They could chew on rope cheese, nibble at the chocolate
cake, sample some shrimp or munch some macaroni salad.
   But above all _ Eat! Eat! Eat! That's what this convention is
all about. There were 200 representatives of food product
manufacturers on hand.
   ``This show is a glutton's fantasy,'' said Michael Villari, vice
president of the Tri-State Dairy-Deli Association, the show's
sponsor.
   On Tuesday, Peter Meyer handed out paper-thin slices of
soppressata, a spicy luncheon meat made by a company in Ontario,
Canada.
   Across the aisle, Zitin was promoting ``Made In the U.S.A.''
honey ham that he says has only 25 calories per serving.
   ``Ham has a bad reputation because people perceive it as
fatty,'' he said. ``We have a hard time showing it off _ it's just
a big wrapped loaf in the deli cooler.''
   If Zitin thought he had a hard time marketing his meat, consider
Jeff Groezinger, who was pushing ``headcheese'' made of pork
tongues and pork snouts. ``People love it _ really,'' he said.
   The battle of the pizzas at The Taste Show was intense. Sam
Sheaffer said his family company is the ``largest manufacturer of
crusts in the country.''
   But Henry Hips touted his ``gourmet pizza'' as fresh, not
frozen. Unlike frozen pies, the melted mozzarella cheese pulls away
from the crust when bitten into.
   ``This is wall-to-wall cheese,'' Hips said proudly. ``Women want
fresh, you know?''
   Schnurman, meanwhile, had a catalog with more than 2,000
products ranging from pita crisps to preserves to spicy sauces for
ribs. He was attracting a variety of nibblers to his table.
   Vic Loperfido, on the other hand, was attracting some skeptics.
People peered at his ``Sea Legs'' selection _ processed fish formed
to look like shrimp and lobster tails.
   ``We sell these everywhere, from four-star restaurants to
mom-and-pop delis to the local prison,'' he said. ``Why should
people have to deal with shells and other inconsistencies in real
shellfish?''
   Jim Johnston had no problems with promoting his product, as
eager tasters lined up for Ben & Jerry's ice cream. Business is so
great, he said, that ``we're not going into new markets right now,
but just trying to consolidate business in the states we're now
in.''
   Conventions in this seaside resort normally hand out tote bags
with freebies _ key chains, rulers and posters. But at The Taste
Show, no shopping bags are allowed. Only stomachs are allowed to
leave full.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
