<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Pyatt-Wedtech     05-04 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pyatt-Wedtech,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Official's Wedtech Testimony Referred for Criminal
Investigation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Meese Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate subcommittee said Wednesday it had
referred to the Justice Department for criminal investigation a
Navy official's testimony about his lobbying contacts on a $130
million pontoon contract for scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp.
   Testimony of Everett Pyatt, assistant Navy secretary for
shipbuilding, about his reasons for agreeing to set aside the
pontoon contract for Wedtech ``contains serious inconsistencies and
contradicts relevant documents warranting further investigation,''
the Senate subcommittee on oversight of government management
concluded in a report on Wedtech and its involvement with Attorney
General Edwin Meese III.
   Pyatt's testimony before the subcommittee last year was sent to
the Justice Department last December and has been under review,
said Senate subcommittee aides, who spoke only on condition of
anonymity.
   Pyatt, who was instrumental in awarding the pontoon contract to
Wedtech, denied at the hearings that he spoke to Wedtech lobbyists
Lyn Nofziger and Mark Bragg before the contract was awarded in
April 1984.
   Nofziger, convicted earlier this year of illegal lobbying on
behalf of Wedtech and other clients, was President Reagan's White
House political director until January 1982.
   The Senate subcommittee's report said the evidence includes
statements by former Wedtech executive Mario Moreno, former Wedtech
consultant E. Robert Wallach and a calendar of Pyatt's secretary
showing that Pyatt met at least three times with Nofziger in
September and October 1983.
   The calendar also shows Pyatt accepted an invitation to an
anniversary celebration of the Nofziger-Bragg firm on Feb. 2, 1984.
   Pyatt also ``failed to disclose the full scope'' of his
relationship with Nofziger and Bragg, said the report by the Senate
subcommittee on oversight of government management.
   It wasn't until after last year's hearings that Pyatt supplied
the subcommittee with office calendars indicating that he spoke to
Nofziger and Bragg on the phone ``on at least 60 other occasions in
1984, 1985 and 1986.''
   The post-hearing documents supplied by Pyatt showed he had a
breakfast and two other meetings with Nofziger in 1983; seven
meetings with Bragg in 1984 and 1985; at least two lunches with
Nofziger in 1985 and 1986; and that he attended three anniversary
celebrations of Nofziger and Bragg's lobbying firm.
   Pyatt supplied the information after testifying that he last
talked to Bragg about Wedtech in early 1984. Wedtech officials have
said Bragg claimed to have discussed the pontoon contract
extensively with Pyatt in this period.
   Subcommittee chairman Carl Levin, D-Mich., said in a statement
that the Defense Department's inspector general found Pyatt had
violated department ethics policy and Navy regulations when he
attended the events.
   A Navy spokesman, Lt. Brian Cullin, said Pyatt's office stands
on the testimony that the assistant secretary gave earlier to
Levin's subcommittee and that he would not comment further.
   Wallach and two other men are under indictment for racketeering
charges for allegedly extracting payments from the Wedtech in a
scheme to influence Meese and other public officials.
</TEXT>
