<2ND_LINE>AM-Politics-Quotes,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quotes From the Presidential Campaign Trail,</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some comments Wednesday from the
presidential campaign trail:
   
   JESSE JACKSON, vowing to continue his campaign despite his
fading delegate count: ``We're within striking distance. It's not
over really till it's over.''
   
   MICHAEL DUKAKIS, countering Jackson's recent criticism that he's
a manager rather than a leader. ``People who know me know I'm a
leader as well as a manager. One of the ways you demonstrate that
you can lead is you go out and win elections.''
   
   BRUCE BABBIT, who dropped out of the Democratic field last
winter, supporting Jackson's decision to stay in the race: ``I
think he should because he has something to offer and I think it
makes it a little more interesting.''
   
   PAUL SIMON, saying he will hold onto his 184 delegates in case
Dukakis ``stubs his toe'' before the Democratic National Convention
in July: ``I'm going to hold out until the California and New
Jersey primaries on June 7 and see whether I can still have an
influence on the nomination.''
   
   GEORGE BUSH, asked about assertions that the Reagans consulted
astrologers about the timing of presidential events: ``I don't know
about that. But I'll tell you one thing: there are two edges to
this sword. There are a helluva lot of people across this country
that read these columns. Otherwise they wouldn't be in the papers.''
