<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Amnesty-Family     05-04 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amnesty-Family,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family of Eight Gave Up On Immigration Attorneys and Applied For
Amnesty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Amnesty Rush, Bjt
^By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARLINGEN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After spending more than $2,000 and
eight years seeking help from attorneys, illegal immigrants
Santiago and Beatriz Casares took their six children and applied
for amnesty on their own Wednesday, the last day of the program.
   They said they gave up on one lawyer last week after it took him
a year to tell them their papers were no good.
   ``He wanted to charge us $1,750 more to arrange the amnesty,''
said Casares, who says he has lived in Edinburg with his wife since
1979.
   They borrowed the $420 family application fee from relatives in
time to spend Tuesday night and early Wednesday wrapped in blankets
outside the Immigration and Naturalization Service's legalization
center here.
   The couple and their children were among about 1,000 people in
line when the center serving the Lower Rio Grande Valley opened
Wednesday.
   Mrs. Casares came to the United States legally from Reynosa,
Mexico, with a border crossing card in 1979 and never returned, her
husband said. Casares said he swam the Rio Grande, a river that
forms the border between Texas and Mexico.
   They have worked various construction, yard mowing and migrant
farm labor jobs since then.
   Mrs. Casares said many employers paid them in cash because they
did not have Social Security numbers, but whenever they were given
a check, she saved receipts.
   She also held on to rent receipts from the four-room house they
have rented for eight years. ``I thought we might need them
someday,'' Mrs. Casares said.
   All the while, they put their faith in people representing
themselves as immigration attorneys, in an effort to become legal
residents.
   Most of the more than $2,000 they spent on the lawyers was for
``identification letters'' they would have to renew monthly,
usually for $40, they said.
   Such letters have little value, said Charles Perez, chief
legalization officer at the Harlingen INS center.
   ``All that is is a letter saying they are clients of an attorney
and that the authorities have to call the attorney before deporting
them,'' Perez said, adding he has heard of similar fraud schemes
throughout his 33-year career with the agency.
   ``There are lawyers who thrive on that,'' he said. Or, the
``attorneys'' may have been notaries public who prey on Mexicans
who think the title means the same as ``notario publico,'' a term
for lawyer in Mexico, Perez added.
   Casares, 42, said the first attorney took $1,600 of their money
over seven years then told them he could not do anything for them.
   The second man took $600 in a year before the Casares family
decided a week ago they were wasting their money and their quickly
expiring time.
   They said they would use their rent receipts, check stubs and
other papers to show they have lived in this country since before
Jan. 1, 1982, as called for in the 1986 amnesty law.
   On Wednesday, the couple and their older children born in Mexico
received slips of paper telling them to report to the center Nov. 3
for legalization interviews.
   Mrs. Casares said she is confident their applications will be
accepted and that their landlady will vouch for them if necessary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880504-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 2204EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CrackRaid     05-04 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crack Raid,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crack Raid Involves 100 Police Officers Taking Over One Block</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100 police officers, their guns drawn,
briefly took over a one-block area of a residential neighborhood
intending to wrest control of a cluster of suspected ``crack''
houses.
   ``A lot of people were dealing out of multiple locations,''
Deputy Police Chief John Laux said after Tuesday night's raid.
``They are taking over a block and saying, `This is our block.'
We're saying ... it's a block and we're going to take the block
back.''
   Seven persons were arrested in the raids on seven suspected drug
houses, which police said was the department's largest single
police criminal action in recent memory. There was no shooting
during the raid.
   One man faces possible felony charges was carrying 13 doses of
crack, $600 and a handgun when police broke into one of the
suspected crack houses, Laux said.
   The sweep only turned up two other small amounts of the drug and
one shotgun, Laux said. If any charges are filed against the
remaining suspects, they would be misdemeanor charges, Laux said.
   ``In that respect it was disappointing,'' Laux said. ``It
certainly is nicer if somebody is there holding a large amount (of
drugs.) But the message still goes out to the neighborhood that we
will not let them take over city blocks and ply their illegal
trade.''
   The raids were prompted, in part, by hundreds of calls from
residents to police and to City Council member Sharon Sayles
Belton, who accompanied officers on the operation.
   ``The calls have been coming in every day of the week, whenever
you're in the office,'' she said. ``People are frustrated that the
narcotics unit can't come immediately. But concrete information has
to be pulled together first. People don't understand that. They see
it at all hours on the street.''
   In fact, police said, most of the houses raided by special
assault teams Tuesday had been raided at least once in the past few
months.
   In addition to making undercover purchases in the crack houses
in recent weeks, surveillance officers witnessed drug deals taking
place in front of several of the houses, said Sgt. Doug Smith, who
organized the entry teams.
   Neighbors said drug dealing has been prevalent not only on their
block, but on surrounding blocks as well.
   ``You can bust 'em, and bust 'em and bust 'em, but that doesn't
mean they're going to go away,'' said a man drinking beer on his
steps next to one of the houses that was raided. ``This has been
going on for months. It's gotten real bad. There's little kids here
and everything.''
</TEXT>
