<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DefenseSpending 1stLd-Writethru a0856 05-04 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Spending, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0856,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Votes Deep Reduction in `Star Wars' Spending</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 7th graf pvs bgng, `The SDI,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with later vote and edit for transition</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ignoring a veto threat, the House voted
Wednesday for a deep reduction in spending for President Reagan's
``Star Wars'' anti-missile defense program.
   After a long series of votes, the Democratic-controlled chamber
ended up approving $3.5 billion for the Strategic Defense
Initiative, as Star Wars is formally known.
   The decisions came as the House worked on a huge bill
authorizing Pentagon spending for the fiscal year which begins Oct.
1.
   Reagan had sought $4.8 billion for Star Wars, compared with the
current $3.9 billion budgeted for the five-year-old program.
   The Star Wars budget was approved Wednesday on a 223-195 vote,
after three earlier votes which rejected both total elimination of
all Star Wars money and granting Reagan his entire request, along
with another proposal to provide $4.1 billion.
   First, the House voted 312-105 to reject an amendment that would
have granted Reagan's entire $4.8 billion request. Then it turned
down, 299-118, another proposal to eliminate the entire SDI budget.
After that, a 227-190 voted turned back the $4.1 billion budget
recommended by the Armed Services Committee.
   Later, the House voted 244-174 to limit spending on the
so-called ``phase one'' of SDI to 40 percent of the total Star Wars
budget. ``Phase one'' is aimed at developing an early version of
the missile defense and current plans called for raising the level
of ``Phase One'' spending within the SDI program from 40 percent to
50 percent.
   Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci said the $3.5 billion SDI
figure in the House bill isn't enough and warned that he will
recommend a Reagan veto unless Star Wars spending is increased.
   ``If the Congress sends the president a defense bill that
contains a funding level for SDI that is in my view inadequate, I
would have no choice but to recommend a veto of that bill,''
Carlucci said in a letter read during the debate.
   The votes were part of the complicated congressional budget
process and the $3.5 billion spending level means the final
congressional SDI figure is likely to be around $4.1 billion.
   That's because the Pentagon budget bill that will be considered
by the Senate starting next week proposes $4.6 billion for Star
Wars. Reagan's SDI program traditionally has fared better in the
more conservative Senate, even though that chamber also is
controlled by Democrats.
   Differences between the two bills, including the SDI budget,
will eventually be reconciled by a House-Senate conference
committee. If the Senate votes $4.6 billion and the House figure
remains at $3.5 billion, the likely compromise will be around $4.0
billion, said Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed
Services Committee.
   During four hours of debate, SDI critics and supporters repeated
their past statements. Critics contended the program won't work
because it is technologically unfeasible, while supporters argued
that SDI scientists have made a number of breakthroughs and U.S.
advances worry the Soviet Union.
   Rep. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., called Star Wars ``an astrological
dream our president decided to pursue,'' a reference to reports
that Reagan and his wife, Nancy, follow astrology.
   But Rep. John R. Kasich, R-Ohio, said, ``The debate no longer is
whether we ought to have an SDI ... the experts on both sides all
support it.''
   Rep. Norman Dicks, D-Wash., said ``It makes no sense to spend
billions on long-shot futuristic dreams'' when the budgets for
non-nuclear weapons such as tanks and planes are being reduced.
   Rep. Charles Bennett, D-Fla., said SDI is full of ``half-baked
proposals'' and he urged the House to ``prevent a rush to deploy
inadequate and destabilizing weapons in space.''
   For Rep. William Dickinson, R-Ala., the House was being
``reckless, counterproductive'' to reduce the SDI budget below the
current figure.
   Rep. Duncan Hunter, R-Calif., urged increases in SDI spending
because he said, ``We're asking a question with this research and
... we have to devote resources to answer this question.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
