<2ND_LINE>AM-Mystery Boy,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Identify `Little Kenny'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKELAND, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Little Kenny, a toddler found wandering in
traffic almost six weeks ago, has been identified, police said
Wednesday.
   But the boy's father, who came forward last week after hearing
news accounts of the child's odyssey, has dropped out of sight
again now that police have discovered warrants against him.
   The 20-month-old boy is Theodore Kenneth Shirley Jr., the son of
Ted and Mary Shirley of Zephyrhills, said Detective Miles Watson.
   ``The father gave me a lot of information that matched with what
I had,'' Watson said. Police decided late Tuesday that Shirley's
information was accurate after checking birth records and
footprints.
   The thin, fair-haired boy with brown eyes had been unidentified
since he was found in the street, dirty and hungry. Police said he
may have been wandering for two days.
   Shirley, 21, told police when he first contacted them Friday
that his wife and Kenny left with a man named Lucky Skaggs in
August while Shirley was in jail on spouse abuse and bad check
charges.
   After Shirley gave police Kenny's birth certificate, officials
at the Pasco County Medical Center compared Kenny's footprints with
birth records on file at the hospital. The records show that Kenny
was born on Aug. 19, 1986.
   Shortly after the boy was found, a drunken man reported to
police he had lost ``little Kenny,'' and told a hard-to-follow
story about being given the boy at a skid-row bar.
   Skaggs, in the company of a woman named Mary, according to the
report, left the child in a Lakeland bar and went to Washington
state on a borrowed motorcycle. Police say the owner of the
motorcycle has since filed a report on the bike because it has not
been returned.
   Lakeland police say there is no new information in their effort
to locate the child's mother or Skaggs.
   ``I'd be interested in speaking to the mother,'' said Watson,
but added there have been no charges filed against her.
   Pasco County deputies tried on Monday and Tuesday to arrest
Shirley on outstanding warrants related to driving while
intoxicated and failure to complete more than 30 days in jail.
   Deputies have been unable to contact him at home. He works out
of town as a carpenter, they said.
   A woman who showed up in Bartow on Thursday asking for custody,
claiming to be the child's maternal grandmother, was arrested
Friday in Naples on Washington state grand theft and fraud charges
involving about $110,000 in cash and merchandise.
   Diane Pierce, a child protection supervisor for the state's
Health and Rehabilitative Services in Bartow, said she can't say
how the arrests will affect the child's future.
   Besides Shirley, his parents and his mother-in-law, a maternal
aunt in Texas have asked for custody. Home studies will be made to
consider all custody requests by relatives, Ms. Pierce said.
   The boy continues to live with a family licensed by the state
agency as an emergency shelter.
</TEXT>
