<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChemicalSpill     05-04 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chemical Spill,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Phosphoric Acid Spill Kills Thousands Of Fish</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GIBSONTON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spill of 28,000 gallons of acid into a
Gulf Coast shipping channel has killed thousands of fish and left
environmental officials threatening to shut the plant responsible.
   The phosphoric acid that spilled into the 30-foot-deep mouth of
the Alafia River was a 54 percent concentration, according to
Gardinier Inc., which reported the spill soon after it occurred
Sunday.
   ``That's real strong. It would burn you badly,'' said Roger
Stewart, Hillsborough County Environmental Protection Commission
director.
   Gardinier, a subsidiary of Cargill Inc. of Minnesota that makes
fertilizer from the acid, reported the spill from a storage tank
Sunday by leaving a message on the commission's telephone answering
machine.
   ``The company said there's nothing wrong,'' Stewart said. But
Tuesday, thousands of fish and other wildlife, including blue
crabs, flounder and ray, were floating dead on the water.
   ``The time has come for that plant to shut down. I've got an
attorney working on that,'' said Stewart, adding that Environmental
Protection Agency officials were en route to the scene from Atlanta
on Wednesday.
   Stewart said experts had not decided whether to let the acid
dissolve or churn up the brackish, 3,000-foot-wide mouth of the
river to dilute the acid with seawater.
   The acid overflowed Sunday from one of Gardinier's 5,500-ton
tanks, said Gray Gordon, the plant's vice president for industrial
relations. Company engineers estimated 200 tons of the acid spilled
into the river, he said.
   Gordon said a plant operator was trying to pump the liquid from
a tank to another area where it would be mixed with phosphate rock.
Instead, an open valve that the operator thought was closed allowed
the liquid to flow into another tank, causing it to spill over,
Gordon said.
   Company officials at first thought the acid was trapped in a
retention pond around the tank, Gordon said.
   Residents fishing near the plant Monday and Tuesday said they
noticed milky-colored water and dead fish and crabs in the river
and called the commission.
   The county recently cited Gardinier after a cloud of sulfur
dioxide and ammonia sickened residents and diners in a restaurant
across the river April 7. The company, which was cited for not
notifying the county, blamed the leak on an improperly programmed
computer that opens and closes valves.
   After heavy rains in 1987, storm-water retention ponds
overflowed and Gardinier dumped 13.7 million gallons of acidic
waste into Hillsborough Bay. The spill resulted in a massive fish
kill, and the state fined Gardinier $200,000.
</TEXT>
