<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CollegeSalaries     05-04 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-College Salaries,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Average Full Professor Now Earns $47,400</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The average full professor at an American
college or university now earns $47,400, a faculty organization
said Wednesday.
   The American Association of University Professors said that
campus salaries rose by 4.9 percent in 1987-88, compared to 5.9
percent the year before.
   Across all faculty ranks, the average salary was $37,000.
   The association, which conducts collective bargaining on some
campuses, said that after inflation, faculty salaries rose in real
terms by just 0.9 percent.
   Based on figures compiled from more than 1,900 institutions with
300,000 full-time faculty members, it said the average salaries
were:
   _$47,400 for full professors;
   _$35,300 for associate professors;
   _$29,200 for assistant professors;
   _$25,470 for lecturers;
   _$22,090 for instructors.
   It was the third consecutive year that the rate of increase fell
below the previous year's increase.
   The association said that faculty salaries vary widely by
region, with full professors averaging $52,510 on the West Coast
and Hawaii, and less than $42,000 in some Southern and Central
states.
   Across all faculty ranks, the average salary ranged from a high
of $43,590 on the West Coast and Hawaii to a low of $32,720 in
Alabama, Kentucky, Mississippi and Tennessee.
   Salaries rose 5.6 percent at private, independent colleges and
universities, compared with 4.7 percent at public and
church-related campuses.
</TEXT>
