<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crowe Calls on Officials, New Mine Scare</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shipping executives said Wednesday that
U.S. and British warships were investigating reports of Iranian
vessels sowing mines off the United Arab Emirates, but there was no
confirmation any were found.
   Adm. William J. Crowe Jr., chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of
Staff, met with senior Bahrain government officials on the second
day of a visit to the Persian Gulf, where Iran and Iraq have been
at war since September 1980.
   Iran claimed its anti-aircraft batteries shot down three Iraqi
warplanes during air raids, the first reported since an informal
truce halted attacks on cities two weeks ago.
   Shipping executives said a civilian helicopter pilot reported
Tuesday seeing two ships thought to be Iranian between Das island,
an oil terminal off the Emirates, and the Iran-owned Sassan
platform that U.S. forces destroyed April 18.
   His report raised fears the ships were sowing mines.
   Das Island, 80 miles offshore and 30 miles from Sassan, is run
by British Petroleum and connects with pipelines from two offshore
Emirates fields, Umm al-Shaif and Zakum.
   The executives, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
pilot described one ship as a ``landing craft'' and the other as
resembling a frigate, but could identify neither.
   A reported mine sighting in the same area a week ago turned out
to be dead sheep floating with hooves in the air, a fairly common
sight in the gulf.
   Crowe met with Bahrain's prime minister, Sheik Khalifa Bin
Salman Khalifa, about ``bilateral relations, current developments
and issues of mutual interest,'' the Gulf News Agency reported.
   Also present were the foreign, defense and interior ministers
and Bahrain's military commander. Crowe was accompanied by U.S.
Ambassador Sam H. Zakhem.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency said two
French-built Mirage F-1s were shot down during one of two Iraqi
raids on Shiraz, southwestern Iran. It said several people were
killed.
   Tehran radio said a third Iraqi jet was shot down, but gave no
details.
