<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Afghanistan     05-04 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Afghanistan,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghanistan Asks for Aid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghanistan has asked the world to help it
repair the damage of war and resettle millions of refugees.
Neighboring Pakistan, where most of the refugees live, called the
request a propaganda tactic.
   Pakistan and the United States armed and supported Moslem rebels
who have fought Soviet-supported governments since a Communist coup
in April 1978.
   The Kremlin has had military forces in Afghanistan since
December 1979, but has agreed to withdraw its estimated 115,000
soldiers in nine months beginning May 15.
   ``Pakistan will support aid for the people of Afghanistan at the
proper time but this is not the appropriate time, while Soviet
troops have not started to withdraw,'' Mansoor Suhail, press
spokesman for the Pakistani U.N. mission, said Wednesday.
   He called the Afghan request ``a propaganda tactic to seek
legitimacy of the Kabul regime which was installed by the Soviet
Union ... a regime which is not acceptable to the people of
Afghanistan.''
   More than 5 million Afghans, about one-third of the population,
have fled their country since the civil war began. At least 3
million live in border camps and cities in Pakistan that serve as
bases and supply points for the guerrillas.
   Afghanistan's ambassador, Shah Mohammad Dost, asked the Economic
and Social Council for urgent consideration of the request for
assistance after the Soviets leave, but did not name a figure.
   The council, which held its first meeting of 1988 on Tuesday,
will consider next week whether to put the question on its agenda.
   Dost said in a letter to the secretary-general and council that
the withdrawal agreement, mediated by the United Nations and signed
April 14 in Geneva, paved the way for normalizing the situation in
and around Afghanistan.
   ``This enables the government of Afghanistan to embark upon a
huge reconstruction effort to undo the enormous damage inflicted by
the war and to resettle the Afghan refugees returning to their
country,'' he said.
   ``Such an effort is beyond the domestic means available to
Afghanistan and requires the assistance of this world body.''
   The 18-member Economic and Social Council makes recommendations
to the General Assembly, which has voted overwhelmingly every year
for withdrawal of Soviet troops from Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
