<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 1942EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DwarfStar     05-04 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dwarf Star,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Astronomers Find Lightest Weight Star Yet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A star that may be the least massive ever
found has been located by three Princeton University
astrophysicists at a point 3,000 light years across the Milky Way.
   The star was discovered when it repeatedly eclipsed a heavier,
rapidly spinning companion pulsar star, the National Science
Foundation announced Wednesday.
   Discoverers of the pair of stars were Andrew S. Fruchter, Daniel
R. Stinebring and Joseph H. Taylor, all of the physics department
at Princeton.
   The astronomers said the dwarf star interrupts or eclipses the
radio signals from the pulsar star at regular intervals as the two
stars circle each other every nine hours and 10 minutes.
Measurements of this interval helped determine the size of the two
stars.
   ``The dwarf star is possibly the smallest star ever seen,''
Stinebring said in the NSF announcement. ``It's also unlike typical
stars in that it does not shine by its own nuclear reactions. Nor
is it anything like a planet.''
   He said the pulsar star, which is much heavier though smaller in
circumference than the dwarf star, is spinning at the rate of 622
times per second. This is the second-fastest spin of the 440 known
pulsars. The fastest rotates at 642 times per second.
   Pulsars are small, dense stars thought to be remnants of
exploded stars, or supernovas. Pulsars emit radio signals that are
pulsed by their rotation.
   The pair of unusual stars was discovered using the world's most
powerful radio telescope at the Arecibo Observatory in Puerto Rico.
   The pulsar was first seen March 3 by Fruchter. Two weeks later,
the Princeton team discovered that the pulsar signal was
interrupted for 50 minutes during each pulsar orbit.
   By carefully measuring the eclipse, the team discovered that the
dwarf star is about 50 percent larger in circumference than the
sun, but has only about 2 per cent of the sun's mass.
   Stinebring said this means that the dwarf star is only 25 times
more massive than Jupiter, the largest of the sun's planets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
