<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0885 05-04 0772</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0885,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Looking Ahead to Next Races</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS grafs 9-10 pvs with 4 grafs to UPDATE with new Watkins
comment on finances</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson on Wednesday met with advisers,
liberal activists and congrssional Democrats as he vowed to
continue his campaign for the presidential nomination despite his
fading delegate count.
   Turning his attention to the West and the delegate-rich
California contest on June 7, Jackson held meetings with a group of
Congress members from western states and with some 50 or 60 members
of the House Democratic Caucus, with his advisers and with a group
of representatives from liberal organizations.
   Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., said Jackson gave ``pep talks'' and
heard reports about what's going on with various interest groups,
including consumer and peace organizations, as he headed down the
home stretch of the primary campaign.
   Rangel said there is no intention to ``work any less'' in the
face of Gov. Michael Dukakis' widening lead. He said the Jackson
camp sees no reason to ease up on criticism of Dukakis in the
interest of party unity, and that Jackson supporters will be ready
to make their wishes known at the convention.
   ``There's no marriage unless we get to the wedding,'' he said.
   Jackson's heavy losses to Dukakis in Ohio and Indiana on
Tuesday, and his runaway victory in the District of Columbia left
the delegate count at 927 for Jackson to 1,500 for Dukakis.
   The seven states remaining on the primary calendar hold 577
delegates, including 314 in California and 109 in New Jersey.
   Meanwhile, Jackson aide Frank Watkins said Wednesday that he
apparently made a mistake in saying that Jackson received about
$46,000 in consulting wages from entertainer Bill Cosby last year.
   ``That was my mistake. They have not paid him any money. They
(Cosby, through his production company) have paid money to
Personalities International. I don't know the details of that,''
Watkins said in a telephone interview on Wednesday.
   Personalities International, Inc., a company headed by Jackson's
wife, received payments for his other speaking engagements and
publications. The company paid Jackson $159,000 as an employee and
consultant last year, according to the tax forms.
   Watkins said he did not know how much Cosby's production company
gave the firm or what the payment was for, and said any details
would have to come in writing from Jackson's lawyer John Bustamante
or his accounting firm, Washington, Pittman and McKeever. Neither
Bustamante nor the accounting firm immediately returned messages
left at their Chicago offices Wednesday evening.
   The discrepancy arose when Cosby, through a spokesman, disputed
Watkins' explanation Tuesday of the $46,535 business services
income reported on Jackson's 1987 tax return. Watkins said then it
was mainly consulting fees paid by Cosby.
   Meanwhile, Jackson, who has made a point of stressing party
unity, said at a news conference that he is not happy with the
delegate-selection process in some states, but did not specifically
say he would challenge it.
   He said Dukakis leads him by only 8 percentage points in the
popular vote, and that margin should be reflected in the voting by
super delegates _ those delegates selected by virtue of holding
important party positions or public office.
   ``The super delegates will do America a super favor by not
interfering in the process. ... I simply want fairness,'' he said.
   The super delegate system allows those delegates to back the
candidate of their choosing, but Jackson said they should follow
the popular vote, suggesting they should not try to settle the
nomination before the primary season is over.
   ``We're within striking distance,'' Jackson said. ``It's not
over really till it's over.''
   ``The party machinery is saying, in fact, go for Dukakis. The
pundits are saying go for Dukakis. In some sense, the super
delegates are moving in that direction and so against the party,
the pundits, the press. We press on against those odds,'' he said.
``We're not about to turn back.''
   The Democratic Caucus chairman, former presidential candidate
Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri, said ``everyone admires the
grace and tone'' with which Jackson has conducted his campaign, and
characterized the morning meeting as `'warm and successful.''
   In his meeting with 13 Democratic members of Congress who are
part of a ``Go West '88'' group, Jackson discussed issues of
concern to western states.
   Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., an organizer of the group, said they
talked about trade, drugs, immigration and energy.
   ``He made it clear trade expansion was something very important
on his agenda,'' said Wyden, who told reporters the sessiom was ``a
very positive kind of discussion.''
</TEXT>
