<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PlantBlast 2ndLd-Writethru a0897 05-04 0864</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plant Blast, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0897,0884</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blast Rocks Vast Area of Nevada; More than 150 Injured</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with conflicting reports of casualties,
injuries now at more than 150, comments, Richter scale
measurements, details from scene.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos VG1,2,3; LaserGraphic NY49</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HENDERSON, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three thunderous explosions destroyed a
space shuttle fuel plnt and a candy factory Wednesday, generating a
five-square-mile toxic cloud, injuring more than 150 people and
leaving others unaccounted for, authorities said.
   Because of toxic smoke and flames, it was not immediately known
whether all the workers at the plants escaped. Authorities
initially said one person had died, and there were unconfirmed
reports nine people had died, said Mike Cool, assistant Clark
County manager. Gov. Richard Bryan later said there were no
confirmed deaths, although two people were missing.
   Flames and orange smoke rose into the sky, and buildings shook
10 miles away in Las Vegas after the midday explosions at the
Pacific Engineering & Production Co. in the southern Nevada
community of Henderson.
   ``It flipped cars over, knocked pedestrians to the ground and
windows in the whole town shattered,'' said Susan Russo, 37, of
Henderson, who was getting gasoline when the blasts occurred.
   ``We have tried to count noses. We're uncertain whether we've
accounted for everyone. What we see is pretty much total
devastation,'' said Fred Gibson, Pacific spokesman.
   All roads to Henderson, a town of 54,590 people midway between
Las Vegas and Hoover Dam, were closed. Residents were told to keep
windows closed against the toxic cloud.
   Two of the blasts, which leveled the fuel plant and the Kidd &
Co. marshmallow factory next door, registered on earthquake
seismographs 200 miles away at the California Institute of
Technology in Pasadena, Calif., said spokesman Bob Finn.
   The first blast, at 11:53 a.m., measured about 3.0 on the
Richter scale of ground motion; the second at 11:57 a.m. had a
magnitude of 3.5. ``I find that absolutely amazing. That is
extremely powerful,'' said Finn.
   The fuel plant manufactures ammonium perchlorate, an oxidizer
used in fuel for the shuttle's solid rocket boosters, but NASA said
the accident was not expected to delay resumption of shuttle
flights.
   The explosions followed a fire that began when ``one of our
pieces of equipment malfunctioned,'' Gibson said. ``The fire spread
quickly and there was an explosion.'' At least two blasts followed
shortly.
   More than 150 people were injured at the plants and in
surrounding neighborhoods, according to tallies from hospitals.
Most had cuts and bruises from flying glass and debris. Others
suffered burns, broken bones or shock.
   Firefighters were unable to enter the site for nearly three
hours after the explosions because of the threat of additional
blasts and the toxic cloud.
   Two hundred people were believed to be at the fuel plant at the
time of the blasts, said Clark County spokeswoman Lisa Godwin. The
candy plant employed 85 people, but few employees of either plant
had been seen at hospitals, authorities said.
   ``There are people out there who are probably dying,'' said
Janet Smith, a spokeswoman for Mercy Ambulance in Las Vegas, which
sent ambulances to the site. ``People are out there on the desert
wandering aimlessly'' if they escaped, she said.
   The toxic cloud, five miles square and moving to the northeast,
contained hydrochloric acid and ``it is very important that no one
be within five miles of the smoke or fire,'' said Doug Bradford, a
spokesman for the city of Las Vegas. ``The strategy is to let it
(the plant fire) burn.''
   Hospitals reported treating at least 154 people, and at least
four were in critical condition.
   More than 70 residents of the Glen Halla Nursing Home, two miles
from the blast, were evacuated to the Las Vegas Convention Center,
after the explosion damaged their building, officials said.
   Emergency workers warned residents away from the area as smoke
billowed across the entire Las Vegas Valley. All area schools were
evacuated, and United Blood Services of Las Vegas appealed for
emergency contributions.
   ``Our windows blew out. It blew the frame off the door. We are
probably five or six miles away,'' said Lee Hall, secretary at the
Henderson Convalescent Hospital.
   NASA said in Washington that Pacific Engineering provides the
ammonium perchlorate to Morton Thiokol, NASA's prime contractor for
the motors, as well as to some Department of Defense programs.
   Don Amitor, a spokesman for NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center
in Huntsville, Ala., said Morton-Thiokol had enough ammonium
perchlorate in supply for the next five shuttle launches. Under the
present schedule, the fifth launch would be in mid-1989.
   Pacific is one of two companies that supply ammonium perchlorate
for all U.S. solid fuel rocket engines, including the space
shuttle, Minuteman and Titan projects. The other is Kerr-McGee,
also near Las Vegas.
   The Pentagon said Pacific received no Department of Defense
contracts in fiscal 1988, although they had two in 1987, totaling
$675,000.
   ``Currently, we have no information that Department of Defense
work is in any way related to the fire,'' the Pentagon said in a
statment.
   Kidd, based in Ligonier, Ind., expanded to the Gibson Business
Park and opened its 36,500-square-foot plant about two years ago.
</TEXT>
