<1ST_LINE>u w AM-SpaceFactory     05-04 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Factory,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Forbids NASA from Leasing Private Space Factory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress refused to go along Wednesday with a
Reagan administration plan to negotiate with a private firm for
lease on a space factory that would be put in orbit by the space
shuttle and serviced periodically by astronauts.
   The House space science subcommittee, in an action approved by a
voice vote, said the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
may call for bids on a so-called Commercially Developed Space
Facility, but that it cannot award contracts without the express
permission of Congress.
   The committee's instructions are part of a bill that would
authorize $11.5 billion to be spent by NASA in the fiscal year
beginning Oct. 1. It requires NASA to submit the results of its
request for proposals to Congress before the next presidential
budget message next January or February.
   President Reagan's new space policy, announced in February,
included ``an intent for the federal government to lease space as
an anchor tenant in an orbiting space facility ... that is
financed, constructed and operated by the private sector.''
   NASA, which had strongly opposed such a facility until that
time, came to Congress and said it would lease 70 percent of the
factory for five years at $140 million a year. The agency declared
its intent to issue requests for proposals within two months,
saying the facility was needed to bridge the time span until a
space station is in orbit in the mid-1990s.
   A Houston firm, Space Industries, Inc., has designed such a
robot space factory, but the House subcommittee specified that
proposals must be submitted by more than one company.
   Some critics see any government agreement for the Commercially
Developed Space Facility as usurping funds and thus killing the
space station, and the space subcommittee specified in its bill
that the money for the facility must not come out of funds for
other projects.
   Last Friday, four influential members of the Senate Commerce
Committee sent a letter to NASA administrator James C. Fletcher
saying they will not permit NASA to enter into a lease in the next
fiscal year and that they object to even a request for a proposal.
   Their argument _ that the idea had not been studied sufficiently
and its need had not been established _ was carried on in the House
subcommittee hearing. The subcommittee, however, voted 18-8 against
a proposal that would have shelved the idea completely until next
year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
