<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bolivia     05-04 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bolivia,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Trying To End Hunger Strike By Thousands Before Pope's
Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MC FARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic leaders are trying to
negotiate an end to a hunger strike by at least 5,000 workers and
students before Pope John Paul arrives next Monday on his first
visit to Bolivia.
   The hunger strikers, who began their fast last week, oppose
government economic programs and demand higher wages. Hundreds of
students and workers have marched through the streets of La Paz
almost daily in anti-government protests.
   Interior Minister Juan Carlos Duran said extreme leftist groups
organized the hunger strike and the protest marches to create ``a
climate of social unrest that will show a distorted image of
Bolivia when the pope arrives.''
   On Pope Paul's five-day visit here next week, he will travel
from the 13,000-foot-high city of La Paz to the lowlands and will
meet miners, farmers, and Indians as well as church and government
officials.
   Church officials here are also trying to soft-pedal a letter
sent by a group of Bolivian priests to the Vatican last month
protesting the appointment of foreign bishops.
   ``It seems strange to us that after nearly half a century of
evangelization in America, we must still import the ecclesiastical
hierarchy to teach, santify and rule Christians in Bolivia,'' said
the letter.
   The protests originated after three foreign bishops were named
in April to run dioceses in La Paz.
   According to figures released by the church, 634 of the 834
priests working in Bolivia are foreigners, as are 17 of the 29
bishops.
   Church officials have been meeting with leaders of the Bolivian
Workers Central trying to resolve the hunger strike.
   The Workers Central represents most workers in Bolivia. Its
secretary-general, Simon Reyes, says, ``The situation of hunger and
misery can no longer be supported and for this reason the protests
will continue until our demands are met. We cannot hide the
dramatic reality, economic and social reality, from the eyes of the
pope.''
   The Workers Central demands a wage increase higher than the 10
to 20 percent given by the government last month. With the increase
the minimum monthly wage is $35. The Workers Central says a worker
needs 10 times that amount to subsist.
   The Workers Central also demands bigger budgets for health and
education. The Vatican ambassador to Bolivia, the Rev. Santos Abril
y Castello, said ``the Roman Catholic Church sees with great
preoccupation how the social situation in Bolivia could tarnish the
visit of the Holy Father.''
</TEXT>
