<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PlantBlast-Casinos     05-04 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plant Blast-Casinos,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gamblers Stick to Tables During Blasts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Plant Blast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HENDERSON, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the explosions at a fuel plant
jolted nearby casinos Wednesday, some gamblers packing roulette and
card tables rushed to cash in their chips before evacuating,
officials said.
   After the first blast, ``people still played, they didn't want
to leave, but after the second blast, everybody took it
seriously,'' said shift manager Paul Naujokas at El Dorado casino
in Henderson.
   The building rattled, the glass front door shattered, and
ceiling tiles were knocked down, he said.
   Some of the 60 to 70 card players and slot machine users cashed
in their chips before evacuating the building, which is about two
miles from the plant, Naujokas said.
   The casino closed for about three hours.
   ``The place (Rainbow casino) across the street never closed,''
Naujokas added.
   Hundreds of people were routed from their tables for about 15
minutes at Sam's Town, a casino-hotel-restaurant complex about
seven miles northwest of Henderson, said Shelley Roberts, acting
director of advertising.
   An estimated 2,000 to 3,000 people were at the complex when the
building shook slightly. Fire alarms ushered them outside.
   ``No one quite understood what was going on until they got
outside, and then it was obvious, you could just look at the
skyline,'' Ms. Roberts said. ``I never heard one person complain
that it interrupted their bingo and their Keno.''
   The gamblers, mostly local residents, returned to their games
after the evacuation.
   ``It doesn't seem to bother them. It was like a thunderstorm
that just came and went,'' said employee Beverly Armengo.
</TEXT>
