<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 2212EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AngolaTalks     05-04 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola Talks,0601</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa, Cuba and Angola In Peace ``Step,'' Says U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa, Cuba and Angola made progress in
U.S.-sponsored negotiations on ending the civil war in Angola and
will meet again in Africa within weeks, the United States announced
Wednesday.
   Chester Crocker, U.S. assistant secretary of state for African
affairs, said the agreement to meet again was ``an important step''
toward getting Cuban and South African troops to withdraw from
Angola and securing independence for South African-controlled
Namibia, or South-West Africa.
   ``We were impressed by the tone of the discussions, by the
absence of polemics and the iterations of seriousness,'' Crocker
said of the unprecedented meeting between South Africa's white
generals and the Cuban and Angolan leaders.
   Crocker also raised the prospect of the United States and Soviet
Union guaranteeing an eventual settlement similar to the deal for
the withdrawal of Soviet troops from Afghanistan.
   ``But it is fair to be skeptical,'' Crocker told a news
conference at the U.S. Embassy at the end of the two-day talks.
``There are big, tough issues that lie ahead. Gaps need to be
bridged. We do not think they should be unbridgeable.''
   The place and date for the talks in Africa has not been decided,
Crocker said.
   He said the talks at a London hotel focused on an Angolan
proposal put forward in March for about 40,000 Cuban troops to
leave Angola in a phased withdrawal, while South Africa pulled its
forces out of Angola and Namibia. No specific timetable for the
withdrawal was described.
   The Cubans went to Angola in 1975 to defend the Marxist
government against pro-Western rebels of UNITA, the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola. The United States aids UNITA.
   South African troops are in southern Angola to back UNITA and
attack bases of the South-West African People's Organization, or
SWAPO, which is fighting for Namibian independence.
   In past months, fighting has intensified around the strategic
southern city of Cuito Cuanvale, where Angolan and Cuban forces are
apparently hanging on under attack from UNITA and South Africans.
   South Africa, which has acknowledged 50 servicemen killed in
Angola in recent months, says it has up to 3,000 troops in the
country. Angola says 9,000 South Africans are there with heavy
artillery.
   Crocker said the talks reflected improved U.S.-Soviet relations.
   ``There may be a mutual recognition that it could be useful if
the difficulties in these negotiations are addressed periodically .
.. between us and the Soviets and some effort made to explore how
it might be possible for our two countries to support a
settlement,'' he said.
   The talks took place after Crocker conferred in London last week
with Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister Anatoly Adamishin.
   UNITA and SWAPO were not invited to the discussions which
Crocker described as confined to ``sovereign governments.'' He
added that U.S. support for UNITA continued and was not part of the
negotiations.
   The United States has been trying for eight years to get the
Cubans out of Angola. Cuba and Angola, backed by the Soviets, have
demanded a South African withdrawal Angola and independence for
Namibia.
   Previous settlements have foundered partly on U.S. support for
South Africa's argument that it cannot accede to United Nations
demands for pre-independence elections in Namibia while Cuban
troops remain in neighboring Angola.
   Earlier, the United States, South Africa, Cuba and Angola issued
a joint statement saying: ``The meeting took place in a
constructive atmosphere and progress was made.''
</TEXT>
