<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-04 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Produce Rain, Hail In South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain drenched parts of the Ohio Valley and Southeast on
Wednesday, while much of the rest of the nation enjoyed pretty
spring weather.
   Thunderstorms ranged across Kentucky and Tennessee and produced
small hail at Somerset, Ky. Thunderstorms also developed over
Alabama and Georgia Wednesday morning and across the Carolinas in
the afternoon. Marble-size hail was reported west of Raleigh, N.C.
   Elsewhere along the East Coast, showers and a few thunderstorms
were found in southeast Florida, from eastern Maryland to southern
New Jersey and central New England.
   Showers were widely scattered from Idaho across Washington and
Oregon to Northern California. Small hail was reported with a
thunderstorm at Burney, Calif. Snow fell at Klamath Falls, Ore.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included an inch at Louisville, seven-tenths of an inch at
Knoxville, Tenn., and London, Ky., and about a half-inch at
Lexington, Ky.; Charleston, W.Va.; and Atlanta.
   Gusty wind developed in parts of the Southwest. Around midday
Wednesday, gusts to 43 mph were clocked at Ely, Nev., and 35 to 40
mph at Desert Rock, Nev.; Milford, Utah; San Nicolas Naval Air
Station, Calif., and San Francisco.
   Much of the nation, including the Midwest and Great Lakes
region, had sunshine and mild temperatures. Early-afternoon
temperatures approached 80 in central Minnesota, while the northern
and central Plains had 40s and 50s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT Wednesday ranged
from 40 degrees at Klamath Falls, Ore., to 89 degrees at Gila Bend,
Ariz., and Harlingen, Texas. The nation's morning low was 20
degrees at Yellowstone, Wyo.
   Thursday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
the Carolinas to New York and across the central Appalachians to
the upper Ohio Valley. Showers and a few thunderstorms were
forecast from eastern Montana across the northern Rockies to Idaho
and along the West Coast, with scattered snow showers in northern
Nevada.
   Temperatures were predicted to rise into the 50s along the
northern Pacific Coast, upper 40s and 50s from northern Nevada
across parts of Utah to northern Arizona, 80s and some 90s in the
southernmost states and 60s or 70s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
