<1ST_LINE>r w AM-RifleProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0887 05-04 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rifle Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0887,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No US Protest Over Alleged Korean Violation Of M-16 Pact, GAO Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, bgng, ``State Department... with two grafs
of State Department comment, picks up 7th graf pvs, bgng, ``Colt
sued...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department has never filed an
official protest with the South Korean government over evidence
that American-designed M-16 rifles built in Korea have been sold to
foreign countries in violation of a U.S.-Korean agreement,
according to a General Accounting Office report.
   GAO found that there was little U.S. oversight of the program
and confusion over which government agency should be in charge of
the 1971 pact, which banned sales to foreign nations without U.S.
permission and placed a cap on the number of rifles Korea could
produce.
   When presented with evidence of illegal foreign sales, U.S.
officials usually instructed embassy officials to remind Korea of
the ``seriousness'' of such sales. A strong, official government
protest was never lodged, GAO said.
   The agreement included Colt Industries Firearms Division of
Hartford, Conn., which set up the Korean rifle plant in exchange
for per-weapon royalties.
   Government officials told GAO investigators that the program's
management ``was left largely to Colt.''
   A State Department official close to the M-16 program agreed
there was some confusion over ``who was supposed to be watching
every element of implementation and how much day-to-day watching
was appropriate.'' The official said a ``more meticulous accounting
arrangement'' may be necessary in the future.
   But the official, who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
defended the government's actions in following up on illegal sale
evidence, saying an official government protest was not necessary
and that reminding Korean officials of the agreement had been
successful.
   Colt sued Korea after the Connecticut company stopped receiving
royalties in 1982. That was the year the Korean government, which
operated the plant, turned over ownership to Daewoo Precision
Instruments, a private company.
   The GAO report, a copy of which was obtained Wednesday by The
Associated Press, said records show that Korea produced more M-16
rifles and spare parts than allowed under the agreement. It also
found that M-16s and parts were sold to third parties without U.S.
permission, a violation of the agreement.
   The third-party nations were not mentioned in the report, which
was declassified. A Colt official said Tuesday that the company had
evidence of M-16 sales to Indonesia.
   Sukhan Kim, a Washington attorney representing the Korean
Defense Ministry in the Colt suit, said Korean officials have told
him neither the government nor Daewoo has sold M-16s or parts to
other countries or violated the production cap.
   He declined further comment, citing the pending litigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
