<DOCNO> AP880504-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 2231EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PlantBlast-Investigation     05-04 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plant Blast-Investigation,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Officials Say Plant Had Good Record</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Plant Blast Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pacific Engineering and Production Co.
had a good safety record, a state official said Wednesday, after a
series of explosions leveled the plant and a factory next door.
   Mike Tyler, administrator of the state Occupational Safety and
Health Division, said his division will investigate the explosion,
which plant officials said followed a fire.
   ``We investigate any catastrophe,'' said Tyler. ``We would be
looking for safety and health violations. If there were any
violations, we would cite them.''
   The division's maximum penalty is a fine of $10,000 and up to
six months in jail for each violation. A final decision on fines is
made by Tyler's boss, state Industrial Relations Director Jim
Barnes.
   Tyler and Barnes said they are barred by law from discussing
safety problems of companies. But Laury Lewis, general manager of
the State Industrial Insurance System, said his records indicate
Pacific Engineering ``has always been a pretty good risk.''
   Pacific Engineering, owned by state Sen. Jim Gibson and his
brother Fred Gibson, has been in business ``a long time and they
have had no previous multiple injury problems or explosions at all,
as far as I know,'' Lewis said.
   The space shuttle fuel plant was established in 1959. It
manufactures ammonium perchlorate, an oxidizer used in fuel for the
shuttle's solid rocket boosters, but NASA said the accident was not
expected to delay resumption of shuttle flights.
   SIIS handles claims for insurance benefits from workers injured
at work.
   Gov. Dick Bryan said he has dispatched all state agencies for
immediate response, including the Employment Security Department
which must process applications for jobless relief from workers who
had been employed at Pacific and at a nearby marshmallow factory
also destroyed in the blast.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
