<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 2214EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Mecham     05-04 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Governor Refuses to Return Fund To State</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Evan Mecham on Wednesday
refused to relinquish the $92,000 protocol fund that figured
prominently in his impeachment trial, and his successor said she
will sue to get it back.
   ``The people who put it in (the fund) said it belongs to me,''
said the former Republican governor. ``If we go by the intent of
the giver, well, it's mine.''
   On April 4, the Senate convicted Mecham of misusing $80,000 from
the fund by loaning it to his auto dealership. He also was
convicted of trying to thwart an investigation of an alleged death
threat. Upon conviction he was removed from office.
   On Tuesday, Attorney General Bob Corbin released a letter in
which he gave Mecham until 5 p.m. Wednesday to return the money to
the office of Gov. Rose Mofford. The deadline passed without action
by Mecham.
   Mrs. Mofford and Corbin both said the Senate essentially
determined the protocol fund was state money when it convicted
Mecham if misusing it.
   Mrs. Mofford said before the deadline that she will sue to get
the money back. She said she will put the money in the state
general fund.
   The former governor said in a telephone interview he was looking
forward to a lawsuit to determine whether he or the state owns the
money.
   The fund was created with receipts from Mecham's inaugural ball
in 1987.
   After it was determined under state law that the money could not
be used to pay off campaign debts, the Maricopa County attorney and
the inaugural reached an agreement to put the money into a fund to
finance things like receptions and gifts for visiting dignitaries.
   Mecham said Wednesday some of the money was spent, but he would
not say how much of the $92,000 was left.
   The former governor also faces a May 19 trial on felony charges
of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
