<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CrashHoax     05-04 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash Hoax,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Convicted of Making False Report of Downed Plane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA ENGLERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An amateur radio buff was convicted
Wednesday of sending a false distress report that prompted an
all-out search for a downed plane Jan. 8 at the height of one of
the worst snowstorms of the year.
   A U.S. District Court jury deliberated two hours before finding
Mark Blair guilty of making a false report to the government.
Blair, 29, could receive up to five years in prison at sentencing
July 1.
   ``Imagine the power he felt making this Navy plane run east to
west and north to south,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney Peter Papps
said, referring to a Navy plane that for nearly four hours flew low
over risky terrain searching for a small downed jet with a badly
injured pilot and three dead passengers.
   The report of the downed plane sparked a search that cost about
$50,000 and involved up to 100 people, 20 aircraft and six police
agencies.
   Defense lawyer Paul Twomey said he will appeal on grounds of
insufficient evidence. ``This case is garbage, absolute garbage,''
Twomey said.
   Blair testified he couldn't have committed the hoax because he
was asleep and wasn't aware that a plane was reported down until he
woke and turned on a police scanner.
   Blair said he then overheard the pilot tell the Navy plane that
he believed passengers were dead, that he had lost a lot of blood,
was having trouble staying conscious, and could see and hear the
Navy plane overhead.
   That recollection conflicted with times given by David Webster,
the Navy reservist who piloted the Navy plane. Other critical
testimony came from Timothy Dinan, 24, who lived in Blair's
apartment building.
   Dinan said he heard the scratchy sound of a two-way radio
through an open window in Blair's apartment and a clear voice
saying, ``I am in trouble. I am losing blood.''
   When police searched Blair's apartment and a storage shed, they
seized radio equipment and printed material that included the name
Dale, the name given to searchers by the man who said he was the
injured pilot.
   The materials also contained highlighted references to radio
frequency used that night and information about police emergency
codes.
</TEXT>
