<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama     05-04 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds of Civilians Trained For Combat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of volunteers were graduated
from military exercises Wednesday and declared ready to fight any
invasion by the United States.
   The nation's military strongman, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega,
attended the ceremony for the men and women of the so-called
Dignity Battalion, and reiterated he was willing to meet with
opposition leaders to bring an end to the nation's political crisis.
   ``We are willing to talk (with the opposition) if and when there
is respect,'' he told reporters at the end of the ceremony.
   The Dignity Battalion was established last month as the
government began to whip up nationalistic sentiment against the
U.S. government. The volunteers have been training two to three
hours a day for five weeks.
   The United States imposed sweeping economic sanctions on Panama
in an effort to force the ouster of Noriega, the commander of the
15,000-member Panamanian Defense Forces and power behind the
civilian government. He is under indictment in the United States on
federal drug trafficking charges, which he denies.
   Noriega arrived two hours late for the ceremony as unconfirmed
reports circulated that U.S. officials had arrived for new talks
about his departure.
   Opposition sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said two
State Department officials were in the country. A military
spokesman said he did not know if the reports were true.
   Although Noriega's late arrival was unusual, no explanation was
given for the delay.
   Noriega has acknowledged meeting with a State Department envoy
last week but denied reports from Washington that he had agreed to
leave his military post.
   During Wednesday's ceremony, the battalion members carried old
M-2 carbines and M-16 rifles. They wore red-and-white caps with
tiny Panamanian flags and white T-shirts with ``Dignity Battalion''
stamped on them.
   Noriega, who watched from the stands as two of the platoons
demonstrated a mock assault, waved and smiled.
   ``Don't run when you see this,'' an instructor told some of the
women before the mock attack, showing them a smoke grenade. ``This
is smoke, not tear gas.''
   ``They have shown a great deal of enthusiasm,'' said Maj. Cesar
Dominguez, commander of the battalion, who said its members had
been trained in light weapons.
   ``We are here to say `No' to intervention and `No' to
aggression,'' said Alba Iris Castro, a battalion member.
   At the end of the ceremony, Noriega stood, called the battalion
to attention and shouted, ``One whole territory,'' a reference to
the year 2000 when the last of the U.S. military bases here will be
turned over to Panama.
   Meanwhile, the National Banking Commission confirmed the banks
will reopen next week but with restrictions on the amount of cash
depositors can withdraw.
   The banks were closed March 3 by government order.
   Banks were allowed to accept deposits on April 18 and resume
other services, such as handling letters of credit, a week later.
   The commission said depositors will be allowed to withdraw 25
percent of the cash that was in their checking accounts as of March
3.
   The association represents 93 of the 117 banks operating in
Panama, most of them foreign.
</TEXT>
