<HEAD>Najib, Gandhi Hold `Friendly' Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Najib, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan President Najib met with Indian
leaders on Wednesday and discussed the future of Afghanistan after
the planned withdrawal of Soviet troops.
   Najib met privately with Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi for two
hours while Indian and Afghan delegations held talks, said Foreign
Ministry spokesman D.K. Maitra.
   ``The talks were warm, friendly and cordial,'' Maitra said.
``The talks pertained to recent developments in the region
including the signing of the historic Geneva accord and the
developments that have taken place after the signing.''
   He declined to give further details.
   Earlier, Najib met President Ramaswamy Venkataraman and spoke of
the Afghan government's efforts to increase development.
   The India visit is Najib's first trip overseas since the Geneva
accord was signed on April 14. Under the United Nations-sponsored
accord, the estimated 115,000 Soviet troops in Afghanistan are to
begin pulling out on May 15 and complete the withdrawal by Feb. 15,
1989.
   Later, at an official banquet, Najib said that the signing of
the accord represented ``the solving of one of the most complicated
regional crises'' in the world.
   ``The successful conclusion of the Geneva agreement ...
testifies to the prevalence of common sense,'' he said.
   Najib said he was ``profoundly grateful for the selfless and
consistent assistance'' of the Soviet Union and the support of
India during difficult moments.
   India has maintained close ties with successive governments in
Kabul since the Soviet military intervention in 1979. Indian
newspapers said Wednesday that New Delhi may offer financial
assistance to Afghanistan for rebuilding the country after nearly a
decade of fighting between Moslem guerrillas and the government.
   Najib returns to Kabul on Friday.
