<1ST_LINE>r i AM-WHO     05-04 0155</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-WHO,0158</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Director General of WHO Elected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Hiroshi Nakajima of Japan was elected
director-general of the World Health Organization on Wednesday to
succeed Dr. Halfdan Mahler of Denmark, who held the post for 15
years.
   Nakajima's appointment was approved unanimously by
representatives of the 157 member nations attending the annual
general assembly, the organization said. The voting took place
behind closed doors. WHO has 166 members.
   Nakajima, 59, is a specialist in psychopharmacology, the study
of the effects of drugs on the mind. He begins his five-year term
on July 21.
   In his acceptance speech, Nakajima cited health problems facing
the world including AIDS, the burden of aging, lack of safe
drinking water and sanitation in many parts of the world, and
pollution.
   Nakajima headed WHO's Manila-based regional office for the
Western Pacific since 1979. He was nominated for director general
at a WHO executive board meeting in January.
