<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ChildSwap     05-04 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Swap,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two 9-Year-Old Boys Traded After Birth Switch Discovered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two families swapped their 9-year-old
boys Wednesday after a court ruled that the children were switched
by mistake at birth, a newspaper reported.
   The Joongang Daily News said Park Jong-tae, 44, of Seoul,
tearfully said good-bye to a boy he had believed to be his son.
   At about the same time, Kim Hyung-shin, 35, in Anyang south of
Seoul, said goodbye to Jong-suk, the boy he thought was his eldest
son, the report said.
   ``I am glad to have my real son back, but it's a real pain to
bid farewell to a boy whom I have raised with all care,'' Joongang
quoted Park as saying.
   The paper said the switch was discovered in 1985 when the boy
raised by Park, Jung-soo, had his blood type tested at school.
Jung-soo's blood type was A but his parents' blood types were both
O.
   Joongang said Park's wife feared her husband would think she had
committed adultery so she went to the hospital where she gave birth
Sept. 4, 1978.
   With the help of doctors, she went through records of all
children born at the hospital that day, the paper said.
   A suspected accidental switch was discovered and the hospital
arranged a meeting for the two families, the paper said. There was
no doubt the children were switched because they were strikingly
similar to each other's parents, it said.
   After discussions, the families agreed to get a formal court
order to swap their children, it said.
</TEXT>
