<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AutoTalks 2ndLd-Writethru a0942 05-04 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Talks, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0942,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler, UAW Complete Negotiations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with details of pact. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Auto Workers and Chrysler
Corp. reached tentative agreement Wednesday on a job-protecting
contract covering 66,000 employees in 15 states.
   The two-year agreement was reached after about 40 hours of
non-stop bargaining. It would replace a three-year contract that
runs out Sept. 14.
   The new pact would expire on the same date in 1990, putting
Chrysler's contract in sync with the rest of the Big Three
automakers for the first time in a decade.
   Negotiators adapted to the No. 3 automaker the so-called pattern
contract established last fall at Ford Motor Co. and General Motors
Corp.
   The agreement will be presented Friday to the UAW's 140-member
national Chrysler council for approval before it is put to a
ratification vote next week.
   The pattern contract protects jobs by requiring companies to
keep on the payroll workers whose jobs are eliminated for any
reason except slow sales. It also requires hiring of one worker for
every two who leave the company.
   The pattern forbids plant closings except for those announced
before negotiations began.
   In addition, the agreement includes $1,000 signing bonuses and
lump-sum payments of 3 percent in 1989 and 1990, and provides
profit-sharing for the first time. Profit-sharing will follow the
formula in place at Ford and GM.
   The Chrysler agreement also includes the union leadership's
commitment to encourage its local unions to consider accepting
so-called Modern Operating Agreements _ Japanese-style practices in
which workers are organized into teams.
   Talks began April 18, two to three months earlier than normal,
in an effort to mend three months of discord between the company
and its workers over various job security and retirement issues.
   ``We achieved the full pattern settlement we set out to achieve,
and we accepted no deviations from what we have in effect today at
GM and Ford,'' union President Owen Bieber and Vice President Marc
Stepp said in a statement.
   Anthony St. John, Chrysler's chief bargainer and vice president
for human resources, called the agreement ``affordable and
equitable'' and said the bonus is ``in recognition of the UAW's
contribution to Chrysler's productivity and profits during the past
few years.''
   Unlike the GM or Ford contract, the Chrysler contract also
includes the company's commitment that executives will receive
neither cash nor stock bonuses in years when the profit-sharing
formula produces no payout for workers.
   The two sides negotiated through the weekend to settle separate
but related contracts covering about 7,000 former American Motors
Corp. workers in Wisconsin.
   The national contract will cover workers left on the job after a
former AMC plant employing 5,500 in Kenosha, Wis., closes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880504-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 2253EDT</FILEID>
