<HEAD>Lawyer For AIDS Victim Says Blood Bank Was Negligent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs, `The defendants' ...' with five grafs to
UPDATE with defendants' statements.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BURKHART</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney for a woman who got AIDS during a 1983
transfusion charged Wednesday that the blood bank that supplied the
tainted blood neglected to take adequate precautions against the
deadly disease.
   Susie Quintana's lawsuit against a blood bank and two doctors
opened Wednesday before a six-person jury in Denver District Court.
   Similar suits have been filed, but lawyers said this may be the
first case in the nation in which a jury will decide an AIDS
victim's claim against a blood bank. In a 1986 California case, a
jury was chosen but the lawsuit was settled out of court before the
trial ended.
   ``It was just like a time bomb, waiting to send an AIDS virus
into a person's body. That person turned out to be Susie
Quintana,'' A. Bruce Jones said of the plasma supplied to his
client after she was injured in a gun accident.
   Jones said in his opening statement Wednesday that testimony
would show the doctor who treated Quintana used the blood bank's
plasma despite offers by family members to share their blood
because of their concern about AIDS.
   Quintana, 50, of Dolores, is suing United Blood Services, whose
blood bank in Albuquerque, N.M., supplied the contaminated blood;
Dr. Edward G. Merritt, Quintana's doctor; and Dr. Donald Kearns, a
Denver infectious disease expert who first tested Quintana for
exposure to AIDS.
   UBS attorney Douglas Irish told the jurors they will have to
base their decision on scientific knowledge at the time and the
judgment that was used.
   ``You will hear from doctors ... that there is a risk ... that
any blood transfusion can carry some disease,'' Irish said.
   The blood bank's lawyers earlier said tests for detecting AIDS
in blood were not available until two years after the woman was
infected.
   Susan Fisher, an attorney for Merritt, said Merritt was not even
in charge the night the woman was treated.
   Kearns' attorney, Joseph Jaudon, said Kearns was called in as a
consultant and ``saw the patient on frequent visits, spent time
with her, answered her questions and talked with her.''
   Judge John W. Coughlin is presiding over the case, which began
with jury selection on Monday.
   Chris Quintana, 53, also a plaintiff in the lawsuit, claims his
wife's illness affected the couple's sex life and potentially
exposed him to AIDS as well. The Quintanas seek ``substantial
damages,'' but their lawsuit does not name an amount, Jones said
Wednesday.
   Quintana has had full-blown AIDS since September 1987, but her
husband's tests have been negative, said Jones.
   ``Chris has not had an easy time since Susie was told she has
AIDS,'' Jones said Wednesday. ``Thank goodness he's not infected,
but they didn't know that at the time'' they had sexual relations
after the transfusion.
   Quintana was brought to Southwest Memorial Hospital in Cortez in
May 1983 for treatment of an accidentally self-inflicted gunshot
wound, Jones said. Merritt was the doctor who treated her, he said.
   ``One hour later, that unit of frozen plasma was put into
Susie's body,'' said Jones. ``You are going to hear evidence that
over that one-hour period that Ron (Quintana's eldest son) could
have given blood, Chris (Quintana's husband) could have given
blood.''
   Jones claimed that the Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta
was aware as early as January 1983 of the need to make blood safe
from AIDS, identifying male homosexuals and intravenous drug
abusers as high-risk groups.
   United Blood Services, he said, issued a joint statement with
the Red Cross and other organizations following a CDC meeting that
January that recommended ways for the public to avoid contaminated
blood. But he said the statement failed to call for blood donors to
be asked about their sexual preference.
   Jones said Kearns initially tested Quintana for exposure to AIDS
and told her the tests were negative, and Merritt also told Chris
Quintana that his wife did not have AIDS exposure.
   Biopsy tests performed in fall 1985 confirmed that Quintana had
been exposed to the AIDS virus, said Jones.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
