<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 2340EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-North-SouthYemen     05-04 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-North-South Yemen,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North, South Yemen Settle Border Oil Field Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN'A, North Yemen (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Yemen and Marxist South Yemen
eased restrictions on North-South travel and settled a bitter
dispute over an oil field that straddles their border, a South
Yemen news report said Wednesday.
   Aden radio said the agreements were reached during the night at
a meeting that included President Ali Abdullah Saleh of North Yemen
and South Yemen's Ali Salem Al-Baidh, secretary-general of the
Yemeni Socialist Party.
   Diplomatic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
South Yemeni representatives also told their counterparts they may
be willing to consider a merger with the larger North Yemen in five
years.
   The agreements were seen as a significant step toward easing
tensions between the two nations. Both command the strategic Bab
al-Mandab straits, gateway to the Red Sea and a crucial Arab oil
shipping route.
   Aden radio said details would be released later. But the sources
said people traveling from one country to the other no longer have
to change buses at the border.
   Buses now can travel directly to and from the capital cities of
Aden and San'a, they said.
   Aden radio said an agreement also was reached on the border oil
field. Oil was discovered in commercial quantities in both
countries relatively recently, and the largest fields are near the
border.
   South Yemen is the only Marxist state in the Arab world. North
Yemen is a republic and home to many South Yemeni opposition
leaders.
</TEXT>
