<DOCNO> AP880504-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 2300EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Namibia     05-04 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Namibia,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Crush Protests Marking Anniversary Of South African Attack</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WINDHOEK, South-West Africa (AP) _ Police fired rubber bullets
Wednesday at thousands of black youths marching to commemorate
hundreds of their countrymen killed in a South African military
strike a decade ago.
   Inspector Kierie du Rand, a police spokesman, said the ranks of
marchers swelled from an initial 400 schoolchildren to about 3,000
as the procession moved through the black township of Katutura,
outside the capital of Windhoek.
   He said police used rubber bullets when the marchers reached the
township police station.
   The Namibia Communications Center estimated the number of
marchers at 6,000 and said police used tear gas and truncheons as
well as rubber bullets. The communications center is a news agency
that works with churches opposed to South African rule of
South-West Africa, also known as Namibia.
   The center said one youth was shot in the leg by the bodyguard
of a pro-government tribal chief. Police reported no injuries or
arrests.
   Wednesday was the 10th anniversary of a South African military
strike on Cassinga, an Angola town about 150 miles north of the
border with Namibia.
   The South-West African People's Organization, which has been
waging a guerrilla war for independence for 20 years, says 582
Namibian refugees camped at Cassinga were killed in the attack by
370 South African paratroopers. Among the dead refugees were 120
children, the rebel group says.
   South African military officials contend that Cassinga was the
guerrilla group's main operational base and that the attack was
necessary to pre-empt guerrilla strikes in Namibia. They say 800
guerrillas and six South African soldiers died in the battle.
   A military parade celebrating the Cassinga strike was held
Wednesday at Oshakati, a major South African army base in northern
Namibia.
   Lt. Gen. Ian Gleeson, South Africa's army chief of staff, said
the raid had dealt the guerrilla group a blow from which it had
never fully recovered, forcing it to concentrate on non-military
targets.
</TEXT>
