<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ecuador     05-04 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ecuador,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two More Shooting Deaths Linked to Presidential Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUAYAQUIL, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two supporters of rival presidential
candidates were shot to death during campaign rallies, officials
said Wednesday.
   A runoff election will be held Sunday to replace conservative
President Leon Febres Cordero, whose four-year term ends in August.
   At a news conference, Interior Minister Heinz Moeller condemned
the Tuesday night killings and said police security would be
increased at campaign events and candidates' offices.
   The violence came as backers of Rodrigo Borja, candidate of the
Democratic Left Party, and of populist Abdala Bucaram, candidate of
the Roldosista Party, held marches in this port city 180 miles
southwest of Quito, police said.
   Police declined to give details. Earlier campaign violence
killed at least two other people dead and injured several.
   Borja spokesman Kenneth Carrera said the Borja adherent was
killed by Bucaram backers. Guayaquil Mayor Elsa Bucaram, sister of
the populist candidate, accused Borja supporters of killing the
Roldosista supporter.
   Rumors of a military coup have surfaced frequently since Borja
and Bucaram won a first-round election in January because of
uncertainty over what the winning candidate will do once in office.
   Sunday's vote will mark the third presidential election since
this small Andean nation returned to democracy in 1979 after a
decade of military governments.
</TEXT>
