<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 2307EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hostages-Diplomacy 1stLd-Writethru a0905 05-04 0723</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostages-Diplomacy, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0905,0740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Intense Diplomatic Activity Preceded Release</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 15th graf, ``Interviewed on ... with 1 graf to CORRECT
first name of Marchiani to Jean-Charles sted Jean-Paul.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages Freed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The release of three French hostages by pro-Iranian
kidnappers in Lebanon follows reports of intense diplomatic
activity on their behalf by Premier Jacques Chirac's government.
   There was no immediate indication whether France made
concessions in talks with representatives of Iran. Chirac and other
French officials refused to answer questions about the negotiations.
   There were unconfirmed reports in Beirut in recent days that
France had agreed to pay Iran $670 million, the amount owed to Iran
on a billion-dollar loan made by the late Shah Mohammad Reza
Pahlavi. Payments were frozen by the French government after the
1979 Islamic revolution in Iran.
   Ten French hostages have been freed since the conservative
premier took office in March 1986. The government says an 11th
hostage was killed.
   Although Chirac's government has denied making deals, releases
often coincided with expulsions of Iranian exiles, cash payments to
Iran on a disputed loan or other apparent concessions.
   The final releases occurred four days before Chirac faces
President Francois Mitterrand, a Socialist, in the presidential
runoff election.
   Chirac trails in opinion polls and commentaries have said
release of the hostages could give him the boost he needs.
   Politicians on both sides saluted the release of journalist
Jean-Paul Kauffmann and diplomats Marcel Fontaine and Marcel
Carton, and denied that there would be political ramifications.
   ``The first politician who declares that this liberation was
obtained for the electoral calendar, that politician will dishonor
himself,'' said Alain Juppe, spokesman for the Chirac campaign.
   ``I don't want to make it an electoral game, but you have to
have the courage to say it. ... When Jacques Chirac came to power
there were 10 Frenchmen held hostage in Lebanon. Today there are
none.''
   Charles Hernu, a former Socialist defense minister, said: ``We
must not mix up these two things. Frenchmen and Frenchwomen know
that in a liberation of this kind, no partisan exploitation is
possible.''
   After Chirac announced the release at a campaign rally in
Strasbourg, however, the audience began chanting: ``We're going to
win! We're going to win!''
   Families of the freed hostages reacted with joy undiluted by
considerations of secret dealing or politics.
   Joelle Kauffmann told The Associated Press her husband's release
was ``a great present.''
   Interviewed on French television as she drank champagne with
friends and relatives, Mrs. Kauffmann said she got the first word
by telephone from the wife of French special envoy Jean-Charles
Marchiani, but thought the call a hoax.
   ``I'm sorry; I took it badly,'' Mrs. Kauffmann said. ``I told
her, `I've had enough with jokes this past month.' She was very
disappointed. She said, `You can believe me or not, but I am
Marchiani's wife. They called me from there (Lebanon) and told me
to tell you this, so there.'''
   Among the mysteries of the sudden release was a possible
connection with France's expulsion Tuesday of Syrian businessman
Omran Adham under procedures of ``absolute urgency.'' He was
involved in previous efforts to free the hostages.
   Le Monde said, without giving sources, that the expulsion was
prompted by an article in the pro-Syrian Beirut newspaper Al Haqiqa
saying France had sent negotiators to Beirut and Tehran. Iran asked
for arms in exchange and ``Chirac responded favorably,'' Al Haqiqa
reported.
   The French paper said Adham ``inspired'' the article.
   Al Haqiqa said France paid 50 million francs ($9 million) for
the release last November of French hostages Roger Auque and
Jean-Louis Normandin.
   French officials have denied paying ransom and insist they have
not dealt directly with terrorists, only with governments like
Iran's that might have influence with the captors.
   Iran had offered to help win the release of French hostages in
Lebanon if France repaid the $1 billion loan made before the
Islamic revolution, cracked down on Iranian exiles and stopped
selling arms to Iraq, which has been at war with Iran since
September 1980.
   French officials said privately Iran also sought its own
supplies of French arms and freedom for five men convicted in a
1980 attempt to assassinate Shapour Bakhtiar, the last prime
minister before Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi was overthrown in
February 1979.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
