<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Mofford     05-04 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mofford,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney General Withdraws From Financial-Disclosure Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arizona's attorney general withdrew from
an investigation of Gov. Rose Mofford's financial-disclosure forms
Wednesday, citing a possible conflict of interest in his being next
in line to succeed her.
   Maricopa County Attorney Tom Collins agreed to take over the
investigation from Attorney General Bob Corbin, who is prosecuting
former Gov. Evan Mecham on charges of omitting a $350,000 loan from
his disclosure forms.
   Mrs. Mofford said she saw no conflict to having Corbin
investigate her and Mecham said he believed Corbin should handle
the probe for the sake of consistency, but Corbin said he
considered it inappropriate because he might be accused of
benefiting from Mrs. Mofford's ouster or of having partisan motives.
   Corbin, Collins and Mecham are Republicans while Neely and Mrs.
Mofford are Democrats.
   Collins said he had agreed to take the case because he felt he
could probably ``do it well, quicker than anybody else and at a
lower cost than if they had to appoint a special prosecutor.''
   ``This is clearly a damned if you do and damned if you don't
case,'' Collins added, predicting that Mrs. Mofford's supporters
would accuse him of partisanship if he brought charges against her
and that Mecham's supporters would accuse him of throwing the case
if he declined to press charges against her while Corbin proceeds
with the case against Mecham.
   ``Since I am not running for re-election, I feel that I am
perfectly positioned,'' he said.
   Collins accepted after Pima County Attorney Steve Neely declined
to take the case, said Corbin.
   Neely did not return calls to his office Wednesday, and a
spokeswoman, Kathi Barber, said he would not explain why he had
decided against taking the case.
   ``I didn't ask him,'' Corbin said. ``I assume he had his
reasons.''
   Mrs. Mofford, elected as secretary of state, succeeded Mecham
upon his impeachment and removal last month.
   Her replacement as secretary of state cannot become governor
because he was appointed rather than elected, and Corbin is the
next highest elected official.
   As secretary of state for 10 years, Mrs. Mofford was in charge
of explaining disclosure requirements for state officials.
   The Associated Press disclosed on April 22 that she had not
reported loans, land holdings and partnerships dating back to 1978,
and Mrs. Mofford, saying she had made ``an honest mistake,'' filed
amended reports a week later.
   Mecham has said that his legal troubles also stem from ``an
honest mistake,'' and he accused Corbin on Wednesday of ``ducking
the issue'' by delegating the job instead of taking the case to a
grand jury.
   ``I think he needs to be man enough to stand up and do his
duty,'' Mecham said.
   Mrs. Mofford had no immediate reaction to Collins taking over
the case, press secretary Vada Manager said.
</TEXT>
