<BYLINE>William Speidel</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William ``Bill'' C. Speidel, author and founder
of Seattle's Underground Tours died Tuesday at age 76.
   During the Depression, Speidel went to work as a reporter for
The Seattle Times and wrote a column for the defunct Seattle Star.
He bought Seattle Guide Inc., which published a weekly
entertainment-tourist guide, and established Nettle Creek
Publishing Co. to publish his books.
   Speidel was best known for starting Seattle's Underground Tours
in 1955. About 120,000 people annually take the tours beneath
Pioneer Square to see Seattle as it existed before the Great Fire
of 1889 destroyed much of the downtown area.
