<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0257EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-XeroxCopiers     05-04 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Xerox Copiers,0561</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Xerox Introduces Japanese-Made Personal Copier As Part Of New Line</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY29 of May 3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Xerox Corp. expects to continue nudging its
share of the world copier market higher with a new generation of
copiers offering more features at higher prices.
   The new 50 Series unveiled Tuesday is named in honor of the 50th
anniversary of the 1938 invention of plain-paper copying. It
includes Xerox's first personal copier, a model made for it by
Sharp Corp. of Japan.
   The new copiers are the successors to the 10 Series, which
helped the company begin to regain market share from Japanese
rivals after its inception in 1982.
   Wayland Hicks, a Xerox executive vice president, said Xerox
should continue recapturing market share from the Japanese with the
new machines, although the recovery will come more slowly than did
the rapid decline of the 1970s and early 1980s.
   ``Overall, I would say they're pretty impressive,'' said Eugene
Glazer, who follows Xerox for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Xerox long had resisted introducing a personal copier, saying it
could not justify the investment necessary to compete with Japanese
companies such as Sharp, Canon Inc. and Ricoh Ltd. that dominate
the low end of the market.
   Glazer said that even now the company's new personal copier ``is
not key to the company's strategy.'' It required only a small
investment by Xerox, because it is being manufactured by Sharp.
   The Xerox personal copier is a close cousin of Sharp's Z-55
except for the exterior casing, a small change in the paper-feeding
mechanism and alterations in the cartridges that make it impossible
for Sharp cartridges to be used in Xerox copiers and vice versa.
   The list price of $1,295 for the basic model is about the same
as the list price of $1,299 charged by Sharp for its Z-55. Actual
retail prices for both could be substantially lower.
   Xerox makes the other new copiers itself. The machines range in
size up to the 5090 duplicator, which starts at $145,000, makes up
to 135 copies a minute and can bind pages automatically.
   Chester Carlson, the inventor of the dry copying process,
created the first xerographic image on Oct. 22, 1938. His efforts
to market the invention were met with an ``enthusiastic lack of
interest,'' he later recalled, until the former Haloid Co. of
Rochester, N.Y., picked it up in the late 1950s. Haloid became
Xerox Corp.
   While the new Xerox copiers can not be compared directly with
their predecessors because they have more features, the prices are
about 5 to 10 percent higher than 10 Series machines with similar
copying speeds, said Roy Haythorn, a vice president for marketing.
   Haythorn said the strength of the Japanese yen made it possible
for Xerox to raise prices while remaining competitive with Japanese
rivals. Xerox recently announced price increases on its 10 Series
copiers.
   The personal copier will be sold mainly through retail stores
and office products dealers and will be available to resellers and
agents later this month. Order-taking for the big 5090 duplicator
will begin in major cities in the second half of the year.
   The rest of the line will be rolled out starting in major
Midwestern cities, beginning this month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880504-0303 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0834EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Texaco-Icahn Bjt   05-04 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texaco-Icahn, Bjt,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texaco Asks Federal Court to Block Alleged Icahn Securities
Violations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN C. GIVEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. is counter-attacking takeover
strategist Carl Icahn, its largest shareholder and most threatening
potential antagonist.
   Alleging that Icahn has violated securities laws, Texaco asked a
federal court Tuesday to thwart his ability to use his Texaco stock
in moves against the oil giant.
   The suit filed at U.S. District Court in White Plains, N.Y.,
asked the court for an order blocking Icahn from soliciting
proxies, acquiring additional Texaco stock or voting the shares he
already holds, representing a 14.8 percent stake in the company.
   The nation's third-largest oil company also asked the court to
void Icahn's nomination of five candidates _ including himself _
for Texaco's 14-member board in elections to be held at the
company's June 7 annual meeting in Tulsa, Okla.
   Texaco said the purpose of Icahn's activities was either to
force the company to buy back his shares at a premium, to force its
acquisition by a third party or to acquire Texaco and liquidate its
assets _ in each case netting large profits.
   In seeking that goal, Texaco claimed, Icahn attempted to
``deceive investors and manipulate the market for Texaco stock''
with false and misleading statements. The company said Icahn's
group also had an illegal secret agreement to coordinate its stock
purchases with those of another ``substantial buyer,'' who was not
named in the suit.
   Icahn repsponded with a one-sentence statement issued at his New
York office, saying: ``We believe the lawsuit is without merit, and
will vigorously defend our right to communicate with other Texaco
shareholders.''
   Since last fall, when he began buying Texaco shares at prices
between $29 and $34 per share, Icahn has been an outspoken critic
of the company's management. He has offered to withdraw his slate
of directors if the company puts itself up for sale for $55 a share
or more, which Texaco officals have refused to do.
   Texaco stock fell 62{ cents to $49 a share Tuesday in New York
Stock Exchange composite trading.
   Federal Judge Gerard Goettel scheduled a hearing for all parties
at 10 a.m. Thursday.
   Icahn's involvement with Texaco began in the last months of its
multibillion-dollar legal battle with Pennzoil Co. In 1985 a
Houston court ruled that Texaco, before buying Getty Oil Co., had
improperly interfered with Pennzoil's bid to acquire part of Getty.
   It awarded Pennzoil a judgment that stood at $10.3 billion in
April 1987, when Texaco filed for federal bankruptcy court
protection to avoid having to post a similar amount while appealing
the Houston judgment.
   Late last year, Icahn interjected himself as a mediator between
the two companies. In December, without his participation, the
companies agreed on a $3 billion settlement that formed the
keystone of Texaco's bankruptcy reorganization plan.
   Texaco emerged from bankruptcy last month and paid the $3
billion to Pennzoil. It subsequently expanded its original plan to
sell $3 billion of assets to $5 billion, mindful of the threat that
Icahn might attempt to take over the company in order to sell it
off piecemeal to raise the value of his shares.
   Among other things, Texaco's suit alleged that Icahn said ``he
did not intend to dispose of his stock or seek control of the
company, when in fact his true purpose was to force the sale of the
company, acquire the company himself and liquidate it or to extract
`greenmail' from the company.''
   Texaco also contended that:
   _Icahn illegally exploited confidential information he acquired
concerning the status of the settlement talks with Pennzoil in
order to acquire part of his Texaco stake.
   _Icahn's proxy for the slate of directors he plans to run
``fails to disclose important information about both Icahn and his
nominees,'' including previous SEC charges of ``serious violations
of federal proxy rules,'' and ``material arrangements or
understandings he had made with members of his proxy slate.''
</TEXT>
