<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MangledMemos     05-04 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mangled Memos,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appended Hereunto Is A Mess Of Lousy Writing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Misspellings are cq in grafs 5-6.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stern message about proofreading that wasn't
proofread won one of the first annual Percy Awards given by a
private writing consultant for what he deems ugly business writing.
   ``There's a lot of bad writing out there,'' New York-based
consultant Gary Blake said Tuesday in announcing his personal
selections from more than 500 submitted letters, memos and
directives.
   The name Percy comes from ``pursuant to your request,'' a phrase
that he says weighs down the top of many memos.
   Blake _ who believes bad writing costs American businesses
millions of dollars a year _ said the most common business writing
mistakes were poor organization, wordiness, antiquated or overblown
phrases and sloppiness.
   The Percy-winning proofreading memo, submitted by a Pacific
Palisades, Calif. print shop employee, began this way: ``When asked
to `proof' something whether it is a letter, a bulletin, something
we are printing the follwoing should be the usual procedure.''
   Once readers got past ``follwoing,'' they still had to cope with
``prodedure'' for ``procedure'' and ``a rpoof'' for ``approve.''
   Dishonors also went to a U.S. Navy memo in Camp Hill, Pa., that
spent eight paragraphs explaining how to look for defects in
plastic office chairs; an unintelligible letter from an assistant
branch manager of a Seattle bank; a puzzlingly vague memo from a
Washington, D.C., magazine publisher regarding staff meetings; and
a scolding memo at a Des Moines, Iowa company that threatened the
removal of bathroom stall doors if employees didn't stop smoking in
there.
   Blake said his clients have included Hughes Aircraft Co.,
General Dynamics Corp., Chase Manhattan Bank and the Navy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
