<DOCNO> AP880504-0305 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0307EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MexicoOil     05-04 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico Oil,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexico Will Maintain Oil Production Levels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico will maintain its current level of
crude production until OPEC agrees to cut its own production,
according to the government newspaper.
   Energy Secretary Fernando Hiriart was quoted Tuesday in the
newspaper, El Nacional, as saying Mexico would maintain its export
target of 1.36 million barrels a day until the 13-member cartel
reaches agreement on a production cut.
   Mexico, the world's sixth largest oil producer, was one of
several non-OPEC producers that last week held talks with the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries about reducing output
in a joint effort to bolster sagging world prices.
   Hiriart said OPEC had not rejected the proposal, and would
reconsider it in the coming months.
   OPEC wound up several days of meetings Monday in Vienna,
Austria, without reaching agreement on the production cutback
proposal.
   The cuts were to be made in conjunction with Mexico and five
other non-OPEC producers, which offered to lower their output by 5
percent or about 200,000 barrels a day if OPEC members did the same.
   Other non-cartel producers involved in the talks were Egypt,
China, Malaysia, Oman and Angola.
   While not an OPEC member, Mexico carefully monitors its
decisions and often follows its lead on pricing and production
policies.
   The nation's economy is heavily dependent on its oil industry,
which is the No. 1 source of foreign revenue needed to service its
foreign debt of about $100 billion, the second highest in the
developing world after Brazil.
   In an effort to ease the oil dependence, President Miguel de la
Madrid has pushed in recent years to expand sales of non-oil goods
to foreign buyers.
   A recent report from the National Institute of Statistics said
the nation earned $1.8 billion in petroleum sales in the first
three months of this year, compared to $3.5 billion in non-oil
exports.
   In all of last year, the nation gained $7.9 billion from crude
sales, a 41.2 percent increase over 1986 when oil prices plummeted
on the world market.
   The United States bought nearly 47 percent of Mexico's oil
exports last year, followed by Spain with 15.2 percent and Japan
with 13.9 percent, according to Pemex, the state-run oil company.
   Last July, the government boosted its export volume to 1.36
million barrels a day after maintaining an export target of 1.32
million barrels a day in the first half of 1987.
   Prior to the 1986 collapse in oil prices, the daily export
platform had been 1.5 million barrels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
