<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ContinentalTrial Bjt   05-04 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Continental Trial, Bjt,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Can't Reach Verdict On Main Defendants In Continental Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX10 of May 3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury's failure to reach a verdict on charges
that two former bank executives defrauded Continental Illinois
National Bank & Trust Co. shouldn't deter other probes of such
white-collar crime, federal prosecutors say.
   ``We sent up the best trial lawyer to try an extraordinarily
complex case. They did a good job,'' U.S. Attorney Anton Valukas
said Tuesday. ``The verdict is not going to deter us in any of our
bank-fraud cases.''
   After a 6{-week trial, the jury was ``hopelessly deadlocked''
and could not reach a consensus Tuesday in the cases of former
Continental executive John Lytle and William Patterson, former
executive of the now-defunct Penn Square Bank, of Oklahoma City.
   The jury acquitted co-defendant Jere Sturgis, an oil contractor
from Tulsa, Okla., of wire fraud.
   The government maintained that Patterson manipulated his
debt-plagued co-defendants in schemes to save his own failing bank
by defrauding Continental.
   Continental nearly collapsed in 1984 following a run on deposits
sparked partly by revelations of bad energy loans, and survived
mainly because of a $4.5 billion government bailout.
   Patterson was a Penn Square vice president until the bank's July
1982 collapse, and Lytle headed Continental Illinois'
energy-lending division.
   The government charged that Lytle, caught in spiraling personal
debt to finance a luxurious lifestyle, accepted kickbacks from
Patterson in exchange for financing high-risk energy loans for Penn
Square customers in 1981 and 1982.
   The indictment cited Lytle's involvement in $44 million in loans
made by Continental to 12 Penn Square customers, many without any
documentation.
   ``I am very disappointed,'' Lytle said after U.S. District Judge
Milton Shadur declared a mistrial after a week of deliberations.
``I had hoped for a resolution.''
   Valukas said he would huddle for a few days with assistant
prosecutors before deciding whether to seek another trial.
   Outside the courtroom, Patterson and his attorney, Warren
Bickford, had nothing to say to reporters. But in Oklahoma City,
another Patterson attorney, Burck Bailey, said he was disappointed.
   ``We were hopeful that the jury would return a verdict of not
guilty, but of course we're pleased on the other hand that there
was no guilty verdict returned,'' Bailey said.
   Sturgis was jubilant after the jury found him innocent.
   ``What can I say? The dream came true,'' he said.
   Attorneys for Lytle and Patterson contended Continental was
saddled with the troublesome energy loans because of an aggressive
lending policy, not because of a fraud scheme.
   Lytle and Sturgis were accused of engaging in a related
``buyback'' investment scheme that began with Lytle buying into
Sturgis' oil operations in May 1981.
   Sturgis allegedly bought Lytle out less than a year later at
triple the original investment to improve his chances of getting a
Continental loan through Lytle, prosecutors said.
   The buyback scheme was devised as a way for Lytle to clear much
of his personal debt and for Sturgis, who was being pursued by
creditors over $100 million in business loans, to find a new
lending source, prosecutors said in closing arguments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880504-0307 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0909EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-USG-MerrillLynch     05-04 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-USG-Merrill Lynch,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USG Sues Merrill Lynch Over Desert Partners Link</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USG Corp. has filed a lawsuit accusing Merrill
Lynch & Co. of illegally using confidential information to help a
Texas partnership launch a takeover bid for the company.
   The suit, filed Tuesday in U.S. District Court, charges the
investment house provided Desert Partners L.P. with information
acquired while Merrill Lynch served as USG's financial adviser in
prior business deals.
   Merrill Lynch spokesman Fred Yager said, ``Although we have not
yet seen the lawsuit, we have reviewed the situation and Merrill
Lynch believes that no conflict exists in its involvement with
Desert Partners.''
   USG, a leading producer of gypsum and building materials, has
been fighting Desert Partners' hostile takeover attempts since last
October.
   This week, USG announced a restructuring plan to counter a $2.32
billion buyout offer from the partnership, which is headed by
oilmen Cyril Wagner Jr. and Jack E. Brown of Midland, Texas.
   USG's lawsuit seeks unspecified damages for what it called a
misuse of confidential information in addition to the profits
Merrill Lynch will receive from ``the exploitation of USG's
confidential business information.''
   Merrill Lynch served as USG's financial adviser when it acquired
DAP Inc. last year and as its selling agent for the $59 million in
notes USG issued to acquire Masonite Corp. in 1984, the lawsuit
said.
   From both transactions, Merrill Lynch ``obtained confidential,
valuable and proprietary information about USG's financial
condition and long-term business prospects,'' the suit said.
   Desert Partners announced last week that Merrill Lynch is one of
its financial advisers and has committed $200 million of its own
money to assist the proposed takeover of USG.
   Merrill Lynch has agreed to be an equity partner with Desert
Partners throughout the transaction, obtaining 13.33 percent of
Desert Partners' profit if the takeover is not consummated and
gaining a 14.7 percent stake in USG if the deal goes through,
according to the lawsuit.
   USG said Desert Partners has paid Merrill Lynch $3 million in
fees and that the investment house will receive an additional $4
million when the takeover is completed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
