<DOCNO> AP880504-0308 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 0918EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-USAToday-HongKong     05-04 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-USA Today-Hong Kong,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USA Today Opens New Printing Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USA Today on Wednesday opened a printing plant
here, its third outside the United States, in the paper's latest
move to reach readers overseas.
   The newspaper will be transmitted by satellite from USA Today's
Washington headquarters for printing here by Consolidated
Newspapers Ltd., which is associated with Sing Tao Ltd., a
publisher of English and Chinese newspapers in the British
territory.
   USA Today, owned by Gannett Co., has a daily readership
estimated at more that 5.5 million at home and abroad.
   The paper's expansion into Hong Kong is intended to ``meet the
rising demand for the newspaper in the region and exemplifies our
commitment to better serve our readers abroad,'' said David
Mazzarella, president of USA Today International.
   USA Today also has printing plants in Singapore and near
Lucerne, Switzerland, in addition to 31 plants in the United States.
   The Hong Kong plant's opening coincided with a visit here by
members of the Gannett board headed by chairman Allen Neuharth, who
founded USA Today in 1982.
   Neuharth also is heading a Gannett news team on a global
newsgathering assignment dubbed JetCapade. The team has already
visited Central and South America, Africa, the Middle East and
India, and after China and other Asian countries will visit Europe
and the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
