<1ST_LINE>u f PM-AutoTalks 1stLd-Writethru f0014 05-04 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0014,0569</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS style in 6th graf; picks up 7th graf pvs bg'ng, The
two ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bargainers for Chrysler Corp. and
the United Auto Workers met through the night in attempting to
smooth out by today some last-minute snags in a proposed labor
contract covering 66,000 autoworkers.
   Negotiators, who stopped only for meals from Tuesday morning on,
had hoped to wrap up the contract by Tuesday night. But by evening,
UAW President Owen Bieber and Chrysler Vice President Anthony St.
John said they still had to resolve several, unspecified major
issues.
   ``We've got some issues we're both having some difficulties
with,'' St. John said late Tuesday. ``We're sort of in a holding
pattern.''
   Nevertheless, union officials said they still expected a
settlement today.
   Bieber said the last-minute snags were a normal part of the
bargaining process and would not keep negotiators from working
until they reach a settlement.
   Bieber and UAW Vice President Marc Stepp spent much of Tuesday
meeting with St. John and other Chrysler officials at the so-called
``little big table,'' where they use their authority to settle
issues, including contract economics, that can't be resolved at
lower-level negotiations.
   The two sides were working to fit an industry-pattern contract
established last fall at Ford Motor Co. and General Motors Corp. to
the much-smaller Chrysler.
   The pattern contract already includes 3 percent lump-sum bonus
payments instead of wage increases in 1989 and 1990. But
negotiators must settle on the amount of funding for a crucial
job-protection program.
   That program requires the company to continue paying workers it
otherwise would lay off for any reason other than slow sales, until
funding runs out.
   Workers also were expecting a so-called signing bonus similar to
the $2,120 they each received for ratifying a three-year agreement
in 1985.
   ``If it doesn't include an upfront bonus, that would make
ratification difficult at my plant,'' said John Danski, president
of Local 1264 at Chrysler's Sterling Heights stamping plant.
   ``There's all this money flowing out of Chrysler right now, like
Lee (Iacocca)'s $17.9 million'' in 1987 earnings, Danski said. ``I
feel that our workers should get a piece too.''
   Under the pattern profit-sharing formula, Chrysler workers would
have received an average of $1,800 to $2,000 each, union officials
said. But unless the money is presented as a signing bonus,
Chrysler workers won't get 1987 profit-sharing.
   Both sides have withdrawn several demands that didn't fit the
Ford-GM pattern.
   Chrysler's current three-year contract expires Sept. 14 but
would be replaced by a two-year pact as soon as members ratify one.
   Once the two sides reach a settlement, it must be approved by
the 140-member national Chrysler council before it can be submitted
to the rank-and-file for a vote. The council meeting could occur as
soon as Friday if a settlement is reached today.
   On Monday, the UAW announced tentative settlements covering
about 7,000 Wisconsin workers who were employed by AMC when
Chrysler bought it in August and a local agreement covering 6,500
of them, who work at plants in Kenosha, Wis.
   The settlements cleared the way for a final push toward
agreement on the national Chrysler contract, which will cover about
1,200 Wisconsin workers after a 5,500-worker assembly in Kenosha
closes at year's end.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
