<HEAD>Aeromexico Resumes Service After Bankruptcy Filing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's bankrupt Aeromexico airline
resumed service Tuesday to major Mexican cities with 10 planes, the
news agency Notimex said.
   The airline's 45 planes had been grounded since April 12, when
technical employees struck to protest planned cutbacks. Aeromexico
filed for bankruptcy four days later.
   Jose Castillo Arreaga, a spokesman for the Airline Pilots Union,
said the company's 765 pilots will rotate flying the limited
service.
   Of the company's 1,485 flight attendants, 94 have been
contracted for the service, arranged for a 90-day period, an
official of the flight attendants union said.
   Regional airlines and Mexicana, the country's other major
airline, have taken over some of Aeromexico's 233 daily flights.
</TEXT>
