<HEAD>Corn, Soybean Futures Open Lower; Wheat Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices opened lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade while wheat futures gained
slightly.
   Weather forecasts continue to dominate price movement as soybean
planting begins, corn planting advances and the winter wheat crop
approaches maturity.
   Forecasts issued today predicted generally good planting and
growing conditions in most crop areas, which tended to depress
futures prices, said Walter Spilka, an analyst in New York with
Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   ``We're seeing a fairly typical spring situation _ scattered
showers, a little cooler, generally good conditions for crops that
are planted and dry enough for soybean planting,'' he said.
   Spilka attributed the light, early gains in wheat prices to a
technical rebound after some fairly significant recent declines.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent to } cent higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $2.98{ a bushel; corn was { cent to
1 cent lower with May at $2.04\ a bushel; oats were } cent to 1\
cents lower with May at $1.56{ a bushel; soybeans were 1} cents to
3\ cents lower with May at $6.86 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly lower and pork futures were mostly
higher in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .30 cent lower to .08 cent higher with June at
71.65 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .15 cent
higher with May at 79.30 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent lower to
.20 cent higher with June at 49.60 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were unchanged to .18 cent higher with May at 51.25 cents a
pound.
   Livestock futures settled mostly higher on Tuesday while pork
bellies retreated.
