<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 1204EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-IndustrialAccidents     05-04 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Industrial Accidents,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Most EEC States Comply With Industrial Accident Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community
Commission said Wednesday that most EEC states have made
``signficant progress'' in adopting EEC law designed to prevent
major industrial accidents.
   EEC Environment Commissioner Stanley Clinton Davis, while
calling this ``encouraging,'' said there was a ``need for a better
inspection service in many member states.''
   The EEC Commission has pressed the 12 EEC states to adopt its
safety regulations after the November 1986, accident at Sandoz,
Switzerland, when large quantities of poisonous chemicals were
discharged into the Rhine River.
   EEC law forces industries that store or use dangerous chemicals
to reduce chances of an accident through strict safety measures and
public information campaigns. It also compels member states to
ensure their industries apply the law and provide regular
information about accidents to the Commission.
   Most member nations have amended their laws to comply with the
EEC regulations, Clinton Davis said in a statement.
   The only countries that have not taken any action are Italy and
Greece, according to the Commission.
</TEXT>
