<1ST_LINE>u f PM-LTV-Bankruptcy 2ndLd-Writethru f0078 05-04 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LTV-Bankruptcy, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0078,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LTV Discloses Bankruptcy Reorganization Plan</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS new 10th graf with number of employees; picks up 10th
graf pvs bg'ng, The reorganization ...; ADDS new final graf with
quote on pension plans</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAY JORDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LTV Corp. today announced a bankruptcy
reorganization plan that calls for no further layoffs or plant
closings but includes scaling back steel operations and
restructuring the company around existing business units.
   Dallas-based LTV's board of directors has already approved the
plan, which will be submitted to creditors of the
steel-and-aerospace giant for consideration, said Raymond A. Hay,
chairman and chief executive officer.
   LTV's bankruptcy, filed in July 1986, is one of the largest in
corporate history. Liabilities total about $6 billion and include a
$2 billion liability to the government-run Pension Benefit Guaranty
Corp. _ LTV's largest creditor.
   Principal components of the reorganized LTV will be a smaller
but major steel company concentrating on flat-rolled products, two
aerospace-defense operating groups and a streamlined energy
products company sized for today's market place, Hay said.
   ``Today's action reflects our commitment to emerge from Chapter
11 as quickly as possible with a strong, reorganized company that
will be competitive in each of the industries we serve,'' Hay said.
   ``The settlement of claims and the financial restructuring of
the company, as proposed in the plan, are major steps in
fulfillment of that commitment,'' Hay said.
   Hay said he doubted the company would emerge from Chapter 11
this year because all creditors would have to agree on the
reorganization plan, which would then be submitted to bankruptcy
court.
   Bankruptcy-court protection under Chapter 11 of the federal
bankruptcy laws gives a beleaguered company a reprieve from
creditors while it devises a plan to stay in business and pay its
debts.
   While Hay said he anticipated no additional layoffs or plant
closings, he noted that the company is studying several
cost-cutting options and does not plan to reopen any plant it has
already closed.
   LTV has 48,115 employees worldwide.
   The reorganization plan also includes improving the bar segment
of LTV's steel business, which Hay said has been consistently
unprofitable.
   ``This is the most difficult part of the plan since we cannot
come out of Chapter 11 with any unprofitable businesses,'' he said.
   Since 1986, more than 35,000 claims have been filed against LTV,
although some were thrown out or discovered to be duplicates. That
leaves about 32,000 claims to be addressed in the reorganization
plan.
   LTV has also been feuding with the Pension Benefit Guarantee
Corp. over steel pension plans. The agency took over the plans in
1987 but then turned them back to LTV, arguing that the company
should have to fund them.
   LTV has argued it can't afford to do that, and the matter is in
court. Hay said the three LTV pension plans involved will remain
terminated in the interim, although he expects the PBGC to see a
``substantial recovery'' of the money LTV owes it.
   ``The cost associated with these pension plans was one of the
major factors that put LTV into Chapter 11,'' Hay said. ``The
reduction of costs resulting from their termination is crucial to
the company's successful reorganization.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880504-0320 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 1229EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-BigChains Adv08   05-04 1129</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Big Chains, Adv 08,1173</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday May 8 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Big Retail Chains At Crossroads</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Penney and Montgomery Ward. The names
once dominated American retailing, but growing competition from
specialty retailers and discount stores keeps challenging the
giants to rethink the business they helped create.
   The way they used to do business _ known as general
merchandising _ isn't working anymore.
   ``It's a very mature industry,'' said Joseph Ronning, a retail
industry analyst with the investment firm Brown Brothers Harriman
Inc. ``Mature'' means there is little opportunity for growth.
   As a result, Sears, Roebuck and Co., the nation's largest
retailer, is retooling its sales strategy and revamping its
management structure.
   J.C. Penney Co. Inc., the fourth-largest retailer, already
enjoying some success from its shift to apparel, is moving its
headquarters from New York to Texas to cut costs.
   And Montgomery Ward & Co., the 11th-largest retailer, is going
private just three years after many observers expected it to go out
of business.
   At their height, Sears, Penney and Montgomery Ward stores
numbered in the thousands. Where they had no branches, consumers
could buy from their catalogs.
   But changes in American society affected the way consumers
shopped and the way these companies did business.
   ``The '70s was an era where people went to shopping malls and
had more time,'' said Barbara Loren, a consultant with Loren-Snyder
Marketing Inc. in Troy, Mich.
   In the 1980s, Ms. Loren said, working women have less time to
shop and when they need an item, they go to the store where they
are most likely to find it. Increasingly, specialty retailers are
the place they turn.
   Ms. Loren cited Toys R Us as a specialty retailer that has taken
away business from general merchandisers.
   ``I know Toys R Us will have the best selection and the price is
right,'' she said. ``I know I am going to come out with what I
want.''
   Home improvement stores such as Home Depot and electronics
stores such as Circuit City also drained business away.
   ``The specialists were clearly becoming the leaders in the
industry,'' said Bernard F. Brennan, chairman of Montgomery Ward.
``If we didn't begin to specialize, we didn't have much of a chance
to survive.''
   A further toll was exacted by discount store chains such as K
mart and Wal-Mart, which offered name brands at lower prices while
general merchandisers sold goods under their own labels.
   Penney was the first to change. In 1983, the company began to
move toward specialty retailing by focusing on its clothing lines.
It discontinued hardware and automotive items and closed
unprofitable stores.
   The strategy worked. Penney, in business for 86 years, has seen
its profitability improve dramatically.
   It was do-or-die at Montgomery Ward. In 1985, after years of
losses, the retailer closed its catalog operation and weakest
stores and eliminated money-losing lines.
   ``We clearly went to certain categories in which we had consumer
acceptance already,'' Brennan said in an interview.
   The 116-year-old Montgomery Ward is now a specialty retailer,
concentrating on appliances, apparel, automotive items and home
furnishings.
   But Sears _ headed by Edward A. Brennan, brother of Montgomery
Ward's chairman _ has been slow to catch on to new trends and has
become a follower instead of the industry leader it once was.
   ``They were the biggest and most powerful, the mostly likely to
be bound by tradition than anyone else,'' said Monroe H.
Greenstein, an analyst with Bear Stearns & Co.
   The attitude at Sears was, ``This is what Sears is, what we've
always been and what we'll continue to be,'' he said. As a result,
the 102-year-old Sears stagnated.
   The company tried to capitalize on its strong points, starting a
chain of paint and hardware stores in 1983. But not until 1987 did
Sears begin a push into specialty retailing.
   Its first steps were through acquiring other retailers, such as
Western Auto stores. Now it is experimenting with ``neighborhood
stores,'' outlets focusing on specific merchandise lines such as
home fashions.
   In its full-line stores, the company is trying to jazz up its
image, teaming with McDonald's Corp. and Walt Disney Co. to market
clothing, toys and other merchandise. And while it has sold
appliances only under its own Kenmore label, Sears will now offer
brand names, a strategy working for Montgomery Ward.
   Sears also recognizes its internal structure must change. In
March, the company announced it would overhaul its staff, reducing
the number of management levels and making each part of the
business more independent. It also wants to cut its costs, which
some analysts call the highest in the business.
   Sears Merchandise Group Chairman Michael C. Bozic indicated
Sears has become a giant bureaucracy that has to be more
manageable. ``We want to measure everything in a smaller arena,''
he said in an interview.
   Some analysts are cautiously optimistic Sears can do it.
   Greenstein said Sears' plans should increase their market share,
but just how sucessful the company will be is ``anybody's guess.''
   Walter Loeb, an analyst with Morgan Stanley & Co., predicted the
restructuring would be a difficult process that ``has to go slowly
to be careful not to step on any toes'' but that should pay off.
   More important, Loeb said, Sears ``has to be more responsive to
what the consumer wants.''
   Ronning, of Brown Brothers Harriman, was skeptical, noting
Sears' continuing growth in financial services through its Coldwell
Bankers real estate, Allstate insurance and Dean Witter Reynolds
investment operations.
   ``Sears is a company shifting from a retailer to a financial
services company,'' Ronning said. ``That is pretty much what the
thrust of the company is.''
   Montgomery Ward, however, is a proven success story. Before
Brennan became chairman in 1985, the retailer, owned by Mobil
Corp., was losing money. By transforming itself into a chain of
what Montgomery Ward calls ``value-driven specialty stores,'' it
became a profitable and attractive property that found the
financial backing to go private.
   Brennan said his company will continue to develop its specialty
format, but he doesn't see it branching into other directions.
   ``We are very comfortable with our structure,'' he said.
   Penney is hoping to reduce its overhead by moving to Texas. The
company won't say how many managers will relocate, but some reports
put the number as low as 15 percent.
   ``They've done a very expeditious job of replacing (management)
with qualified people,'' said Loeb. ``It may be disruptive, but
won't hurt them long term.''
   Penney won't fall behind retail trends by being in Texas,
because today's technology, including teleconferencing and
satellites, will ease the way, Ms. Loren said, adding, ``You don't
have to be living in New York to accomplish their goals.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday May 8</NOTE>
</DOC>
