<HEAD>Desert Partners Increases Proposal for USG</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Desert Partners L.P. today unveiled new
proposals in its pursuit to acquire USG Corp. that value the
company at about $2.58 billion in an attempt to top USG's own
restructuring plan.
   Under one scenario proposed to USG's board, Desert Partners
would pay $39 in cash, $9 in bonds and offer stock in a new company
for each of the Chicago-based company's outstanding shares. Wall
Street sources have valued the offer at about $50 a share, giving
the deal an indicated value of $2.58 billion.
   Under another scenario, Desert Partners would pay $50-a-share in
cash for 72 percent of USG's 51.5 million outstanding shares. The
remaining shares would be exchanged for bonds and stock in the new
company ``for the same aggregate amount,'' Desert Partners said in
a statement.
   USG has been fighting a takeover for months. On Monday the
building products manufacturer proposed a $2.2 billion
recapitalization plan that would pay shareholders cash and notes.
The company noted that it would have to sell off its Msonite Corp.
and Kinkead businesses to finance the restructuring.
   John L. Reed, Desert Partners' chief financial officer, called
his company's proposals ``clearly superior'' to the recapitlization
plan.
   The new proposals come less than a week after Desert Partners
said it would pay $45 a share if the two companies could negotiate
a friendly deal.
   Desert Partners, led by Texas oilmen Cyril Wagner Jr. and Jack
E. Brown, is offering $42 a share in a hostile tender offer. That
bid, including debt securities and warrants valued at $42 each, has
a value of about $2.2 billion and remains in effect.
   Desert Partners owns about 9.9 percent of USG's shares and said
that as of last Friday about 19.3 million shares, or 37.5 percent,
had been tendered under its $42-a-share offer.
</TEXT>
