<HEAD>London Shares Off</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites thruout with closing figures</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices declined Wednesday after the
government said it would refer the Kuwaiti government's acquisition
of a British Petroleum Co. PLC stake to the monopolies commission.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index finished down
12.5 The index's best level was 2 points up, hit as the trading day
began.
   Volume was a moderate 427.4 million shares, compared with
Tuesday's 335 million shares.
   Wall Street's lower opening added fuel to an already declining
London market, dealers said.
   Traders said the bearish tone was set early in the session when
the Department of Trade and Industry announced that it would refer
the Kuwait government's purchase of a 22 percent stake in BP to the
Mergers and Monopolies Commission to determine whether it is in the
public interest.
   The referral ``completely depressed market sentiment and that
was it for the rest of the day,'' said Mark Kane, a trader with
Kitkat and Aitken Ltd.
</TEXT>
