<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Gold Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose Wednesday against all major
currencies in listless European trading, bolstered by expectations
of higher U.S. interest rates. Gold prices fell.
   Dealers said trading was subdued because Tokyo markets were
closed for a second day for Japanese holidays.
   They said the dollar was boosted by indications that American
interest rates could rise, making the dollar more attractive to
investors.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.8650 from $1.8715.
   The dollar also rose to 124.95 Japanese yen from 124.83 yen in
London late Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday:
1.6796 West German marks, up from 1.6770; 1.4000 Swiss francs, up
from 1.3945; 5.7075 French francs, up from 5.6935; 1.8840 Dutch
guilders, up from 1.8795; 1,250.50 Italian lire, up from 1,247.50;
and 1.2353 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2294.
   Gold bullion fell in active trading, partly pushed down by a
large Middle East sale, dealers said.
   In London, gold fell to a late bid price of $444 a troy ounce,
down from $445.50 bid late Tuesday. In Zurich, it dropped to
$443.50 an ounce bid from $446 late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell to a closing bid of $444.71 an
ounce from 446.57 dollars.
   Silver bullion fell in London to $6.35 a troy ounce, down from
$6.39.
</TEXT>
