<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   05-04 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain Futures Close Mostly Higher; Soybeans Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain futures prices closed mostly higher
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade while soybeans posted
modest losses.
   Activity in both soybeans and corn, which showed only the
slightest improvement, was primarily influenced by forecasts for
favorable planting and growing weather, analysts said.
   ``We saw the effects of a fairly normal seasonal forecast with
some showers, possibly into the weekend, then generally good
conditions for planting the rest of the corn,'' said Walter Spilka,
an analyst in New York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   Longer-range forecasts indicated conditions also would favor the
beginning of soybean planting next week, Spilka said.
   Wheat and oat prices rebounded after four straight days of
losses as traders hunted for bargains, Spilka said.
   But with the winter wheat crop nearing maturity, wheat prices
are expected to continue their seasonal decline, he said.
   At the close, wheat was 1 cent to 3} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.01{ a bushel; corn was unchanged
to \ cent higher with May at $2.04} a bushel; oats were 1{ cents to
3 cents higher with May at $1.60\ a bushel; soybeans were 1} cents
to 5\ cents lower with May at $6.84 a bushel.
</TEXT>
