<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 1746EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CandyBarWars     05-04 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Candy Bar Wars,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cadbury Exec Asks Government to Halt Raids on Candy Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of takeover target Cadbury Schweppes
PLC on Wednesday called on the government to block foreign raids of
Britain's confectionery companies, which have been dubbed the candy
bar wars.
   Cadbury Chairman Sir Adrian Cadbury told shareholders at the
company's annual meeting that the British confectionery industry
has been in turmoil since U.S.-based General Cinema Corp. announced
last week it planned to increase its 17.7 percent stake in Cadbury,
possibly through a tender offer.
   In the same week, Swiss-based Nestle SA launched a hostile $3.9
billion bid for British confectioner Rowntree PLC.
   Nestle said Wednesday it increased to 6.7 percent its holding in
Rowntree, which makes the Kit Kat candy bar. But Switzerland's
Jacobs Suchard SA, Nestle's rival in the battle for Rowntree, said
its stake in the British candy maker has been boosted to 23.5
percent.
   The raids on Cadbury and Rowntree, both major players in the
world confection market, have sparked an uproar in Britain.
   Cadbury said the government should not allow the stock market to
decide the fate of the companies.
   ``There are a number of public interest issues involved, which
it is for the government rather than the market to take into
account,'' he said.
   He stressed that the two Swiss companies were protected from
hostile bids in their own country while they were free to try to
acquire British companies.
   Both Cadbury and Rowntree represent ``generations of patient
British investment, and they are appreciating assets. So where the
returns from them are to flow in the future is an issue of national
significance,'' he added.
   Rowntree has not directly appealed to the government for
intervention but is discussing the matter with ``one or two
people,'' said a company spokesman who asked not to be identified.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
