<DOCNO> AP880504-0338 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 2013EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-FCA     05-04 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-FCA,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FCA Posts $63.2 Million First-Quarter Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IRVINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financial Corp. of America, the troubled
savings and loan company that federal regulators are trying to
rescue, reported Wednesday it lost $63.2 million in the first
quarter.
   That compares to a profit of $9.2 million, or 17 cents a share,
in the year-ago quarter. The first-quarter deficit follows a $224.6
million loss posted in the previous quarter by the nation's
second-largest thrift holding company and parent of American
Savings of Stockton, Calif.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which is negotiating a
possible sale of FCA to the Bass Group of Texas, has pledged to
protect depositors and general creditors of American Savings, which
has 208 offices in California.
   American's net worth stood at a negative $212 million at the end
of the quarter, in contrast to $496.7 million a year earlier.
Assets totaled $30.6 billion as of March 31.
   FCA Chairman William Popejoy said he welcomed the Bass Group's
interes. Bass recently edged out Ford Motor Co. to secure a bank
board promise of exclusive negotiations for 75 days.
   ``I believe this recently announced agreement ... has tremendous
potential for American Savings,'' Popejoy said. ``We have
consistently stated that strengthening the capital base is our top
priority. We respect the Robert M. Bass Group's reputation as
first-class business people.''
   A drain on deposits, which FCA had blamed on publicity about its
problems, apparently eased at the end of the quarter. As of March
31, the net deposit decrease for the quarter stood at $319.5
million, an improvement from the $493 million decrease the company
said it suffered in the first two months of the year.
   Deposits totaled $16.4 billion as of March 31, down from $17.7
billion a year earlier.
   In the first quarter, FCA added $107 million to its reserve for
bad loans, bringing the total reserve to $1.2 billion.
   FCA lost $468 million in 1987. The company posted profits of
$95.4 million in 1986 and $53.2 million in 1985 after losing $512
million in 1984, when its troubles began.
   The thrift has been plagued by bad loans on real estate in
economically troubled areas of California and Texas.
</TEXT>
