<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 2027EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-ControlData     05-04 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Control Data,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Control Data Chief Says Company Will Fight To Stay Independent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be led with closing stock price.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While declining to say whether Control Data
Corp. has become a possible takeover target, the company's chairman
told shareholders Wednesday that management will fight to keep the
computer maker independent.
   ``I have great confidence in Control Data management to pursue
the vital task of enhancing shareholder value,'' said Robert Price,
chairman, president and chief executive officer of
Bloomington-based Control Data. ``We will fight to remain an
independent company.''
   Price met with shareholders Wednesday for the company's annual
meeting.
   On Tuesday, the Wall Street Journal reported that the Belzberg
family of Canada had bought a stake in the company and may be
considering a bid for it.
   At a news conference after the shareholders' meeting, Price
refused comment on whether a takeover attempt of Control Data is
under way.
   ``We don't comment on speculation and rumors,'' Price said.
   Control Data's stock rose $1.75 a share on Tuesday and was up
another 50 cents a share at $27.12{ a share shortly before the
close of trading on the New York Stock Exchange on Wednesday.
   The report of a possible takeover bid by the Belzberg family is
the latest in a series of takeover and break-up rumors that have
come since Control Data reported total losses of $832 million in
1985 and 1986. Net earnings in 1987 were $19.3 million, or 45 cents
a share, and Price said the company is still in the midst of a
turnaround.
   Despite a projection in Control Data's 1987 annual report that
the company will have a negative cash flow through most of 1988,
Price said Wednesday ``there is some good news in each of our major
areas.''
   He said the company continues to see profit margin improvements
in its data storage division, where new disk drive products were
introduced in 1987. The division suffered serious setbacks in 1985
and 1986.
   Cash flow will be held down in 1988 because the company needs to
keep spending money on improvements in data storage and other
divisions, including supercomputer subsidiary ETA Systems, Price
said.
   ``You can't do these things without spending money,'' Price
said. ``We have to be able to invest in the businesses we have
pursued.''
   Price also said he is comfortable with the size of the company's
debt load, which is between $450 million and $500 million.
   John Buckner, the company's chief financial officer, said the
terms on the debt could be better. But he said the company's
debt-to-equity ratio improved to 42 percent at the end of 1987 from
56 percent the year before.
</TEXT>
