<FILEID>AP-NR-05-04-88 2046EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ComputerStandards     05-04 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Computer Standards,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dozen Major Companies Endorse Computer Communication Standards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dozen companies that represent more than 80
percent of the nation's computer and communications sales joined
Wednesday to endorse a set of standards that will some day allow
effortless communication between computers of different designs.
   The companies committed themselves to following Open Systems
Interconnect standards because of strong pressure from customers,
who are tired of computers that can't easily talk to each other.
   The federal government, the nation's biggest computer customer,
has warned computer makers that starting two years from now it will
not buy any equipment that does not follow the Open Systems
Interconnect standard, except by special waiver.
   Many big computer makers have been cautious about embracing
standards, fearing they will lose their loyal customers once it
becomes easy to mix and match computers from different suppliers.
   Wednesday's new conference in New York was a demonstration that
the companies feel they have more to lose by rejecting standards
than by embracing them.
   ``This is an epochal event, and it's all customer-driven. That's
what's so extraordinary,'' said Jonathan Fram, an analyst for Bear,
Stearns & Co.
   The 12 companies will demonstrate products that follow the Open
Systems Interconnect standard at a trade show in June in Baltimore.
   Showcased will be products for electronic mail and file
transfer. All major computer makers already offer ways to do those
jobs, but at the show they will demonstrate how they can do them in
compatible ways.
   ``OSI has left the drawing boards,'' said Lincoln Faurer,
president and chief executive of the McLean, Va.-based Corporation
for Open Systems, which brought the companies together.
   The dozen companies represented were International Business
Machines Corp., American Telephone & Telegraph Co., Control Data
Corp., Data General Corp., Digital Equipment Corp., Hewlett-Packard
Co., Honeywell Bull Inc., Sun Microsystems Inc., Unisys Corp., Wang
Laboratories Inc., Xerox Corp., NCR Corp., and Telenet
Communications Corp., part of US Sprint Communications Co., the
joint venture of GTE Corp. and United Telecommunications Inc.
   Standards save money, said Murray Weidenbaum, a former chairman
of President Reagan's Council of Economic Advisers, who was invited
to speak at the news conference.
   General Motors Corp. cut the frequency of downtime in half and
the length of downtime episodes to 5 minutes from 15 minutes when
it put a standards-based manufacturing system into its truck and
bus plant in Pontiac, Mich., said Weidenbaum, who is at Washington
University in St. Louis.
   The Defense Department expects to save 15 to 80 percent off the
cost of its antiquated, $800 million-a-year communications system
when it builds a new one that is based on Open Systems Interconnect
standards, said Michael Corrigan, a Defense Department computer
expert.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
