<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Prices, 1st Ld - Writethru,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Slip Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBs 5th graf pvs Both figures...to CORRECT spelling of
Drexel Burnham. Picks up 6th graf, The figures...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices slipped lower Wednesday,
pressured by a continuing negative mood in the market and a report
that showed larger-than-expected domestic inventories in gasoline
and crude.
   June contracts for West Texas Intermediate, the U.S. benchmark
crude, fell 17 cents per 42-gallon barrel to close at $17.20 on the
New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Among refined products for June delivery, wholesale unleaded
gasoline lost 0.56 cent per gallon, settling at 49.72 cents, while
wholesale heating oil dropped 0.57 cent to 46.20 cents per gallon.
   In a weekly report issued after the market's close Tuesday, the
American Petroleum Institute, a Washington-based trade
organization, said gasoline supplies jumped 5.9 million barrels in
the week ended April 29, while crude stocks were down by 700,000
barrels.
   Both figures left ``more inventory than was expected,'' said
Mary L. Haskins, an analyst at the Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
securities firm.
   The figures put downward pressure on prices because they
indicated continuing abundant supplies for existing demand.
   Ms. Haskins also said the market remained depressed by a
perception that the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
will be unable to agree on a way tighten up its production, even
when it meets next month in Vienna.
   In addition, she said technical factors contributed to the day's
slumping prices.
</TEXT>
