<HEAD>Volkswagen First-Quarter Profit Up 2 Percent; U.S. Market Posts
Losses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WOLFSBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Volkswagen AG said Wednesday its
first-quarter net profit rose 2 percent over a year ago, aided by
improvement in its Spanish and South American operations.
   West Germany's largest automaker said quarterly net income
increased to 144 million marks, or about $84 million, from 141
million marks in the same period in 1987.
   Sales also rose 2 percent, to 13.7 billion marks, or $8 billion,
from 13 billion marks last year.
   Volkswagen Chief Financial Officer Dieter Ullsperger said he
expected positive results for the rest of the year.
   Company officials said the company's U.S. operations will post
another loss in 1988 because the underused plant in Westmoreland,
Pa., will not be shut down until July. But he said the loss will be
smaller than the one in 1987.
   Volkswagen has also spent a total of 2.6 billion marks, about
$1.5 billion, on the development of its new mid-size sedan, the
Passat.
   Officials said the Passat will be sold in the United States
beginning next year and they expressed hopes of selling 25,000
Passats in the United States in 1989.
</TEXT>
