<HEAD>Auto Companies Report April Monthly Sales Slide</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBs grafs 6th graf pvs, Among import... to include figures
for domestically-made cars. Picks up 7th graf, Honda import...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of domestically made cars fell 6.7 percent
in late April, with Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. posting sales
gains and General Motors Corp. reporting a decline, the companies
reported Wednesday.
   GM said its car sales for the April 21-30 period trailed 19.7
percent behind unusually strong sales in the same period last year.
   Chrysler posted a 10.3 percent gain for the period and Ford's
car sales were up 8.7 percent.
   Domestic truck sales showed a 6.5 percent increase, but combined
car and truck sales were still down 2.6 percent from the year-ago
late April period.
   For the month, GM's car sales were down 14.2 percent to a
314,671 total, Ford's car sales were down 1.4 percent to 186,175
and Chrysler up 8.8 percent to 95,170.
   Among import carmakers, Toyota's April sales of domestically
made cars rose by 4.5 percent to 4,115, while sales of its imported
cars rose 0.6 percent from the previous April to 43,605. Volkswagen
domestic auto sales fell 11 percent to 4,625 while its import sales
fell 25 percent to 11,922.
   Honda import sales dropped 3.6 percent to 19,702, but sales of
domestically made Hondas were up 7.5 percent to 17,512.
   David Healy, analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New
York, said a GM surge due to sales incentives last April skewed the
figures. ``They were 55 percent of the market, so the comparison
will be kind of distorted. GM will look poor,'' he said.
</TEXT>
