<2ND_LINE>AM-Jeep Settlement,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AMC In $11.5 Million Settlement With Woman Injured in Jeep
Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Motors Corp. agreed
Wednesday to pay $11.5 million to a Fort Pierce woman left a
quadriplegic after a 1984 rollover accident involving a Jeep.
   In return for the settlement, Elizabeth Walker, 34, agreed not
to pursue her claim for punitive damages.
   The settlement included $9.5 million awarded by a jury in Fort
Pierce on April 1, 1986, plus interest. The same jury awarded Ms.
Walker $10 million in punitive damages, but that amount was reduced
to $1 by the state Court of Appeals.
   However, the appellate jury recommended that the Florida Supreme
Court review the punitive award, said Joe Reiter, one of Ms.
Walker's lawyers. Reiter said he had intended to seek the original
$10 million in punitive damages before the Supreme Court.
   Ms. Walker, who now is a nursing home patient, was riding in a
Jeep CJ7 on May 4, 1984, when it was struck by a car. She was
thrown from the Jeep, which then rolled onto her, and suffered a
broken neck.
   The driver of the car, Donald Robinson, earlier had agreed to a
$600,000 settlement with Ms. Walker.
   Reiter said experts convinced the jury that the Jeep's center of
gravity was too high, making it susceptible to rollover accidents.
</TEXT>
